<html><head><title>Dead-rat politics</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Pressure groups</b></p>
<h1>Dead-rat politics</h1>

<p>NO DOUBT the House of Commons Home Affairs Committee listened to many different voices when considering the question of whether to advocate a ban on handguns. But it cannot have harmed the opponents of a ban (on whose side the committee came down) that the <font size=-1>MP</font>s' only expert adviser was Colin Greenwood, the editor of <i>Guns Review</i> magazine, a voice of the gun lobby which regards the police as "malicious" and the media as "sick" for campaigning for gun control.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is rarely the case that the "expert" (expert witness, expert adviser, expert being interviewed on a hastily-put-together news item) is the disinterested sage that the word implies. Usually, he or she comes from a lobby group and is spinning a line.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;William Waldegrave, chief secretary to the Treasury, expresses his alarm at the growing power of pressure groups in a collection of papers published this week by the Social Market Foundation, a centre-right think-tank ("Pressure Group Politics in Modern Britain", &#163;10). The problem, he maintains, is not so much that pressure groups are increasing in number or in strength. His main concern is the declining effectiveness of the institutions that are supposed to protect the common good against vested interests: principally, Parliament and the media. They, contend Mr Waldegrave, are not doing their job.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Waldegrave has a point. Admittedly, if the media promote lobbies, they also sometimes puncture them. Mr Greenwood's exposure, for instance, undermined the authority of the select committee's report. And special interests have always pressed, or obstructed, the government. For example, Lord Robert Cecil, later prime minister, wrote in 1858 of: "the utter impotence of Parliament to raise its hand against the attorneys and the licensed victuallers, or the extreme difficulty with which even so small a body as the ecclesiastical lawyers have been dealt with." And yet today the growth of lobbies seems inexorable. Their clout in Britain is still dwarfed by that of American lobby groups, but Britain seems headed in America's direction.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Pressure groups normally want government to spend more money. Parliament came into existence in part to stop the executive from spending too much, a point which Mr Waldegrave says <font size=-1>MP</font>s are in danger of forgetting. Almost every report from a select committee demands that more money be spent on something. Few politicians have much interest in arguing that less be spent--except the beleaguered chief secretary to the Treasury.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not surprisingly, given the Tories' record and funding sources, Mr Waldegrave's concern is less with business lobbies than with campaigns with more momentum than sense. In one typical case an <font size=-1>MP</font>'s constituent was killed by a piece of machinery. The <font size=-1>MP</font> sounded off in the local newspaper; national newspapers took up the story, as did the opposition; there was a debate; a minister made a conciliatory speech; the bureaucracy started to draft plans to set up an inspectorate. At this stage, somebody asked what the real risk of sudden death from this sort of machinery was. Four times less than that from being struck dead by lightning, it turned out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The media's failure to challenge pressure groups' claims is well illustrated by a paper in Mr Waldegrave's collection by Peter Bazalgette who is, er, a food expert. He tells the story of Alar, a spray used on red apples to delay their maturation so they become bigger and redder before picking. A <font size=-1>TV</font> documentary reported that, in large quantities, Alar could cause cancer in mice (though not in hamsters or dogs). Since children eat more apples than adults do, the risk to them seemed higher. A group called "Parents for Safe Food" was formed, and the actress Meryl Streep appeared on commercials in America demanding that Alar be banned.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ms Streep later recanted, after the risks had been properly explained to her. The carcinogen in Alar, it turned out, exists naturally in mushrooms at 1,000 times the strength. Mr Bazalgette blames such scares on the "dead-rat syndrome", whereby a researcher somewhere feeds huge quantities of some substance to a rat which eventually keels over. He writes up the experiment, describes it in primary-school English in a press release, and bingo.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such stories get space in the papers because journalists are lazy and credulous. It makes a much better story to cry "something must be done" than to argue that, even if the possibility of minutely increased risk to health exists, it would be better if the government did not expensively stick its nose into yet another area of life.


