<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>It's a gas</b> &nbsp;Police forces were given permission to issue their officers with hand-held <font size=-1>CS</font> gas sprays for self-defence. Civil-rights groups and some police forces said they were worried about possible long-term health risks.</p>
<p><b>Testing</b> &nbsp;Schools were accused of discouraging weaker pupils from sitting exams after the number of <font size=-1>GCSE</font>s taken failed to keep pace with the rise in the number of 16-year-olds, and pass rates rose for the seventh year in a row.</p>
<p><b>Meat on trial</b> &nbsp;A coroner in Durham decided that a man who died from Creutzfeld-Jakob disease, the human equivalent of mad-cow disease, probably contracted it by eating contaminated beef. Farmers reacted angrily to a warning by the German government that British lamb may also not be safe.</p>
<p><b>Lords of evil</b> &nbsp;Labour protested at the decision to give a peerage to Maurice Saatchi, an advertising executive, and Peter Gummer, a public-relations executive. Both were involved in a Conservative Party poster campaign which depicted Tony Blair, Labour's leader, with demonic eyes.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Standing down</b> &nbsp;Tobias Bernstein resigned as head of Sage, an anti-gun charity supported by the families of victims of the Dunblane massacre; but he denied newspaper allegations about his past financial dealings.</p>
<p><b>Inside</b> &nbsp;Jimmy Smyth, convicted of the attempted murder of a prison officer and his wife, was extradited from America and returned to the Maze prison in Belfast<b>,</b> 13 years after escaping from it.</p>
<p><b>Flagged up</b> &nbsp;After a dispute between ministers, the government announced that a new, voluntary national identity card would contain both the royal crest and the Union Jack.</p>
<p><b>Flagged down</b> &nbsp;A man sailing a pleasure boat on the Norfolk Broads was stopped by river police who told him he was breaking the laws of the sea: the toy flag his grand-daughter had stuck on to the prow of the boat was a Union Jack, instead of a Red Ensign.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
