<html><head><title>China looming</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>

<h1><center>China looming</center></h1>

SEVENTY years ago, scare-mongering westerners called it "the yellow peril". Today it is called the People's Republic of China. The rise of a nation so huge is certainly a world event. Is it also a reason for the world to shake in its shoes?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;China is not only the world's most populous country; for the past 20 years, it has had the world's fastest-growing economy. Project current growth rates into the future and you find that the Chinese economy will overtake that of the United States in less than 20 years. (Measure output a different way, and it will take China a bit longer to become the world's biggest economy.) True, projecting current trends is an ancient fallacy. True, even when China's economy is bigger than America's the average Chinese citizen will still be far poorer than the average American. "China as number one" may still be a distant prospect--but the reality of a China that will demand and command a growing share of the world's resources is already here. A richer China presents enormous commercial opportunities for outsiders. It also raises political and military concerns.

</p><p><b>A panda as big as the Ritz</b>
<br>Those worries are rarely discussed in public by western elites. But to many ordinary people it seems obvious that the rise of China has to be a bad thing. Any country with more than a billion people must concern the rest of the world; and this is one with traditions of inherent superiority that go back centuries before the peoples of the West came--and at that only for a time--to similar ideas. Today's China is also a one-party state that has clashed several times with its neighbours and recently turned tanks on its own people. Such a chain of thought leads logically to the notion that maybe the West should try to hinder, not help, the rise of China, perhaps by cutting back on commercial ties. It is not enough to say, as most western policymakers do, that China's rise is unstoppable and the West just has to learn to live with it. Given the importance of trade and foreign investment to China, outsiders could slow its growth, albeit not stop it. Should they try?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Western diplomats, businessmen and politicians are largely united in saying No. China's rise should be welcomed, they say, and helped. That view is often advanced for short-term reasons, such as a desire not to antagonise China's leaders, or to win a contract. It is correct for long-term ones.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The orthodox argument for thinking that a stronger China will be easier to live with can be called "liberal internationalism"--the notion that as economic ties between nations grow, so political conflicts will fade. Tie China to the world with trade and investment, the argument goes, and you will inevitably make it not just stronger, but friendlier.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Humph. That was the argument in the first decade of this century that suggested a European war was unthinkable. War broke out, nonetheless, in 1914. One reason was that Germany was led at the time by a group of militarists suspicious of the rest of Europe, anxious to ward off their own people's demands for political liberalisation and uninterested in the pacific virtues of European commerce. Little as others understood it, Germans then--and later--saw themselves as encircled by a hostile world. The parallel with today's China is striking. You will not find many liberal internationalists in the Chinese leadership. On the contrary, they--and many other Chinese--have long memories of being preyed upon by western and then Japanese imperialism, and they draw from their history a grim notion of the way countries deal with each other. They think it is natural for the strong to prey upon the weak. So, next time round, let China be the strong one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And, they might add, if it does a bit of its own preying, well that is just tit-for-tat. Of course, they add no such thought; oh no, a strong China will never behave like the western imperialists of old. China, they say, has always been peaceful. Rubbish. China forcibly colonised Tibet in the 1950s, attacked India in 1962 and Vietnam in 1979 and within the past year has grabbed a reef in the South China Sea and threatened violence against Taiwan. All with solid justification, in the Chinese view--which is yet another reason why a strong China is likely to be increasingly assertive.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The real reason to believe that growth in China will prove to the West's political as well as commercial advantage is that, in time, it is likely to lead to political liberalisation. And history suggests that, by and large, democracies are less aggressive than dictatorships: even the fiercest critics of the United States have to admit that it is 150 years since it was at war with Mexico or Canada, neighbours that it could have defeated within a month. Western politicians are not going to say this to the current Chinese leadership, but it must be the basis of their long-term strategy on China.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As yet, admittedly, there is little sign that China's boom has led to much political loosening. Indeed, there is less scope for political organisation now than a decade ago. But while political freedom has diminished, personal freedom has increased markedly. Students are no longer routinely assigned to jobs by the government; peasants flood into the cities to find work. And the experience of the Asian tigers such as South Korea or Taiwan suggests that, in time, greater personal and economic freedom does lead to political loosening.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is possible that China may resist that trend. Its sheer size, its Communist legacy, its relative poverty compared with the other tigers and the relative lack of American influence over its political leadership all suggest that China's transition to a looser political system will be even more fraught and less predictable than in other Asian countries (see <a href="sf1.html">page</a>). Such fears, as well as a general worry that political change in China could lead not to democracy but to chaos or civil war, incline some westerners to accept the official Chinese line that a China led by "strong" leaders is actually in the West's best interests. But the history of this century hardly suggests that putting your faith in dictators to keep the peace is a safe bet. The demise of Communist oligarchy in China is overwhelmingly in the West's interests, as it is in the interests of ordinary Chinese themselves.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The implications for Western policymakers are threefold. First, they should welcome Chinese economic growth in the hope, albeit not the certainty, that this will lead to political liberalisation. Second, they should accept that they have little direct influence over internal Chinese politics and so should not cede points of principle in the hope of bolstering moderates there. Last, so long as China retains the habits of one-party oligarchy, westerners must not be shy of demanding that it accept international norms of conduct (eg, over Taiwan) and meet its international commitments (eg, over Hong Kong). The panda may be larger and fiercer than the tigers. But, with luck, time and wealth will tame it.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?840236400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
