<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p>
<p>

<p><h2>Budget-busters</h2>
<p><p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>The Bundesbank said Germany's budget deficit is likely to rise to more than 3.5% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> this year, above the Maastricht limit of 3% for Europe's economic and monetary union. The gloomy message comes with the realisation that <b>growth in Europe</b>, and especially in Germany and France, is still weak. This will make it harder for countries to meet the Maastricht targets in 1997. Consequent doubts about <font size=-1>EMU</font>'s chances weakened the French franc.
<p>Germany's <b>Volkswagen</b> defied sluggish growth in Europe to report global sales up 13% and a net profit that soared in the first half to DM282m ($189m), up from DM113m a year earlier.
<p>The world's biggest reinsurance group, Germany's <b>Munich Re</b>, is to take over America's third-largest, <b>American Re</b>, for around $3.3 billion. The move may herald further consolidations in the world reinsurance industry.</p>
<p><h2>Bondage</h2></p>
<p><p>The federal government scored a big victory in its attempts to clean up America's <b>municipal-bond market</b>, when a former partner at Lazard Fr&egrave;res was found guilty of fraud and corruption. Retained by municipal clients to offer independent financial advice, Mark Ferber, who will appeal, recommended underwriting work to Merrill Lynch without disclosing that Merrill Lynch was paying his firm a $1m annual retainer.
<p>Continuing a wave of good results from Swiss banks, <b>Swiss Bank Corp</b> overcame a rise in bad-debt provisions and a depressed Swiss economy to report profits sharply up in the first half of 1996. Boosted also by the bank's takeover of S.G. Warburg, a British investment bank, net profits rose to SFr722m ($593m), up from SFr540m a year ago.
<p>Martin Ebner's <font size=-1>BK</font> Vision investment group lost a battle against <b>Union Bank of Switzerland </b>but said its war with the bank would continue. <font size=-1>BK</font> Vision, the bank's biggest shareholder, said it would not fight a court decision to reject a special investigation into share dealings by the bank before its annual general meeting in 1994.
<p><b>Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan </b>was fined $1m by regulators for unauthorised bond trading at its New York branch, the latest in a string of Japanese institutions to run into trouble in America.
<p>Meanwhile, <b>Daiwa Bank</b>, which was kicked out of America and fined $340m for covering up a $1.1 billion trading loss, has asked the Japanese tax authorities if it can set the fine against tax. Tax officials say a loophole may force them to allow the request.</p></p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><p>
<p><h2>Burnt</h2>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>) </b><br>Tobacco shares were battered after a Florida jury awarded $750,000 to a lung-cancer victim and his wife. The jury decided that Brown &amp; Williamson, whose parent, <font size=-1>B.A.T</font>, is the second-largest tobacco company in the world, had misled smokers about the dangers of cigarettes. As in the only previous case in which an award was made, in 1988, Brown &amp; Williamson hopes to overturn the verdict on appeal and continue the industry's record of no payouts so far despite numerous lawsuits.
<p><b>Thyssen</b>, a German engineering group, described the arrest of ten of its top managers, including Dieter Vogel, its chief executive, on fraud charges as "monstrous". It said it would bring charges against the Berlin public prosecutors for unlawful arrest. The executives are accused of misappropriating DM37.8m ($25.6m) during the privatisation of a former East German metals company.
<p>There were two big <b>energy and utility</b> mergers in America. Houston Industries, one of the biggest, is buying NorAm Energy, a natural-gas company, for $2.4 billion. Delmarva Power &amp; Light and Atlantic Energy, two East Coast utilities, are to merge in a $830m share swap.
<p><b>General Mills</b>, an American food group, is to buy the Chex Cereal line from Ralcorp Holdings for $570m. The deal confirms General Mills's position as America's second-biggest breakfast-cereal maker.
<p><b>British Petroleum </b>said it wanted to hurry through a $5 billion deal with <b>Mobil </b>to combine European downstream assets, raising speculation about a merger between the oil majors.
<p>In the latest of a string of acquisitions, <b>Softbank</b>, a Japanese software and publishing company, is to pay $1.4 billion for 80% of <b>Kingston Technology</b>, a California-based firm that is the world's largest memory-board maker.
<p>Shares in <b>Flextech</b>, a loss-making firm that has interests in 13 European cable and satellite <font size=-1>TV</font> stations, soared after it confirmed that it was talking to the <b>BBC</b> about a joint venture to launch six new channels. The attraction for the <font size=-1>BBC</font> would be access to America through Flextech's parent, Tele-Communications Inc, America's biggest cable operator. For <font size=-1>TCI</font> and Flextech, the lure is the British broadcaster's archive.
<p>A jump in the number of rough diamonds from Russia slipping past the informal cartel arrangement it has with <b>De Beers</b>, which controls most of the world market, has depressed De Beers's shares. But De Beers, which declared net profits up 18% to $482m in the half year, reckoned Russia would soon sign a firm contract--though whether it will slow the leaks is questionable.
<p><p>
</p>
