<html><head><title>Trigger happy</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>

</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<h1>Trigger happy</h1>



<p>IT TOOK Thomas Hamilton, a 43-year-old former scout leader with a grudge, only four minutes to fire 105 rounds from two 9mm Browning pistols, killing 16 little children and their teacher in Dunblane on March 13th. The government's response was admirably balanced and deliberate. Rather than rushing into ill-conceived legislation, it established an inquiry under Lord Cullen, a Scottish judge, who is expected to report next month, and promised legislation soon after his report. But now a group of the government's own backbenchers have landed it in trouble by rushing to their own judgment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The six-strong Tory majority on the House of Commons Home Affairs Committee rejected a ban on the private possession of handguns in a report published on August 13th, a move which has been almost universally condemned. Instead of winning credit for the sensible and delicate handling of the gun issue in the wake of Dunblane, the Tories were made to look as if they were insensitive blunderers. Senior ministers quickly moved to distance themselves from the report. David Maclean, a Home Office minister, desperately pointed out that the committee's view was neither Conservative nor government policy. Indeed, the outcry over the committee's report has made it all but certain that John Major will have little choice but to endorse a total ban on the private ownership of handguns, a policy already adopted by the Labour Party, even if Lord Cullen recommends something less draconian.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are three theories as to why the Tory members of the committee, chaired by Sir Ivan Lawrence, a veteran backbencher, should have put their names to a report which was bound to infuriate the public as well as present opposition <font size=-1>MP</font>s with an open goal. The first is that they were simply nobbled by the gun lobby which has extensive links to the party. A second is that Sir Ivan, who is close to Michael Howard, the home secretary, was persuaded to float a trial balloon. Mr Howard is sceptical about the practicalities of banning the private ownership of handguns, in contrast to Mr Major and Michael Forsyth, the Scottish secretary, who both believe that tough action has to be taken. The final theory is that the Tories on the committee simply took leave of their political senses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The committee's report provides few clues as to how the Tory majority reached its conclusion. The report's chief argument--that banning the private use of handguns would be ineffective because most of the handguns used in crime are unlicensed--is less than persuasive. Both Thomas Hamilton and Michael Ryan, the madman who killed 16 at Hungerford in 1987, used legally held weapons for their massacres.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The committee's claim that the practical problems of banning the private possession of handguns are virtually insuperable is equally unconvincing. To claim, as the report does, that requiring all handguns to be used and kept at licensed gun clubs would cause difficulties for starters at athletic races is to invite derision.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of course, there would be obstacles to be overcome and a total ban on handguns at home would restrict the freedom of some perfectly sane and reasonable gun owners. But the public seems in the mood to accept nothing less. And the size of the gun lobby is easy to overestimate. Shooting is reputed to be the third most widely pursued sport after fishing and walking, with more than a million people taking part. But the vast majority are shotgun and rifle owners. Only 57,000 people have handgun licences compared to 723,000 shotgun-licence holders.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many gun-club members are off-duty policemen and women. Most of these would probably favour much tighter controls. The Association of Chief Police Officers has called for a ban on any handgun with a calibre above .22-inch capable of firing more than one shot without reloading. This would eliminate about 90% of the 200,000 handguns held legally in Britain. The Police Federation, which represents junior officers, renewed its call for a ban on the private possession of all handguns on August 14th after a 22-year-old man was convicted of a murder committed with a handgun bought through the post.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Evidence submitted to the Cullen inquiry shows a close international correlation between gun ownership and gun crime. For example, 150 times as many handgun murders are committed in the United States as in England and Wales. Japan, which has fewer than half the number of gun murders than Britain, has the most restrictive gun laws in the world. No Japanese is allowed to keep a handgun at home and illegal possession of a firearm is punishable by 15 years in prison.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?840236400,iss">Search</a>
