<html><head><title>A conundrum</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Social housing</b></p>
<h1>A conundrum</h1>


<p>IT SEEMED to make good sense. Switching housing subsidies from bricks and mortar to those in need, combined with the policy of allowing council-house tenants to buy their homes, was supposed to save money by getting millions of employed people to pay their own housing costs, and to target spending on those who really required help. The policy achieved these goals. But it has also had unforeseen consequences and landed the government in something of a hole.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The point has now been reached where savings from reducing government housing grants are offset by resulting increases in housing-benefit payments and, because higher rents increase the retail-prices index, in other government benefits which are linked to the index.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the past 17 years, council-house and housing-association rents have more than doubled in real terms as the government has almost halved capital grants to them. Since 1990, the proportion of costs of building new housing-association properties borne by government has declined from 79% to 58%. Another 2% cut in grant has just been announced for next year by David Curry, the housing minister. Spending on housing grants declined from &#163;12.5 billion in the fiscal year 1979-80 to &#163;4.9 billion in 1994-95. Raising rents to nearer market levels also enabled housing associations to attract &#163;10 billion of private finance and build many more homes for rent. But much of this saving has been offset by a rise in benefit payments. In the past five years, housing benefit, used to pay for these higher rents, has more than doubled in real terms to more than &#163;10 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The disadvantages of this rapid switch are now becoming apparent. New housing-association properties have to be let at such high prices--&#163;85 a week--that many poor families cannot afford them, unless they qualify for housing benefit. The result is a welfare trap. The perverse inter-reaction between housing and other benefits, which can involve withdrawal of benefit at rates as high as 97p for every pound earned, means that for many it makes little sense to work. A family with two children in a high-rent property might have to earn as much as &#163;250 a week to be significantly better off. Even then, the family would probably have to move to cheaper accommodation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dependence on housing benefit has also helped create a culture in which fraud, both by individuals cheating the system and by landlords milking it, has become endemic. A report by the House of Commons Social Security Committee, published earlier this year, estimated that a fifth of the housing-benefit budget, ie, &#163;2 billion annually, was being swallowed up in bogus payments.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The fact that an increasing number of council and housing-association estates are occupied almost exclusively by those on benefit is having a devastating effect on the social cohesion of many of these places. Research commissioned in 1993 by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation, an independent charity, found that the average income on large new housing-association estates is a third of the national average. One in two of the households surveyed was headed by a lone parent, three-quarters of the tenants had no job and child densities were three to six times the officially recommended level.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The case for digging no further into this particular welfare hole may be overwhelming. But there is no obvious way to get out. Ministers privately accept that rapid rent increases have now become counter-productive. And yet an increase in capital grants is not currently an attractive option for either government or opposition, who have both pledged spending restraint. Modifying earnings ceilings before benefits are withdrawn and smoothing benefit withdrawal rates makes sense, but any such overhaul drastic enough to matter much would also be extremely expensive.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One way to lower rents on new housing, and thus housing-benefit payments and the poverty trap for new renters, would be to make housing associations pool rents across the whole of their housing stock. But this would raise rents for those in older properties, limiting the savings and the effect on the poverty trap. Building new housing to a lower standard, and so more cheaply, would also lower rents. But this threatens to produce the slums of the future and may be more costly in the long term.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
