<html><head><title>At last, the real race begins</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<h1><center>At last, the real race begins</center></h1>


PRESIDENTIAL elections have a habit of tempting candidates to perform somersaults. As the 1996 campaign gets properly under way, with the Republican Party convention in San Diego on August 12th-15th, followed by the Democrats' convention in Chicago a fortnight later, the displays of gymnastic and other forms of virtuosity are proving more spectacular than anything seen in Atlanta this past month. And the task for voters is coming down to this: to decide which of the displays reflects genuine abilities, and which might be the temporary result of performance-enhancing substances.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A few months ago the race looked straightforward, the likely outcome even more so. It has always been foolhardy to predict the outcome and still is, even with Bill Clinton retaining a big lead in the opinion polls. But it is in the race itself that the surprises are coming. As the conventions open, the prevailing fashion is for role-reversal. The energetic incumbent, whose 50th birthday is on August 19th, is approaching November as the conservative, standing for moderation, for caution and for a safe pair of hands. Meanwhile his 73-year-old opponent, Bob Dole, who until recently had claimed that his greatest virtues were his experience, his track record, his steadiness, has suddenly started to present himself as the optimistic radical, eager to slash taxes and transform the American economy. A third-party candidate, whether Richard Lamm for the Reform Party or more likely the party's founder, Ross Perot, may yet manage to confuse the two-party picture. No matter: it is already confused enough.
</p><p><b>Bob Dole's political economics</b>
<br>If <i>The Economist</i> were an American voter seeking to make sense of the campaign, between now and November 5th it would be seeking evidence to help choose between two hopes: the hope that Bob Dole is lying; and the hope that Bill Clinton is telling the truth.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To a Republican tactician, to hope that Bob Dole is lying will sound bizarre. This week Mr Dole released an economic plan called "Restoring the American Dream" which is designed to unite the fissiparous Republican Party (see <a href="sf1.html">page</a>) and to act as the centre-piece of his campaign. In it, he says the American economy is growing much too slowly; if he is elected he will press on the accelerator by lowering personal income taxes, removing regulations, reforming the tax system and, while he's at it, balancing the federal budget. The middle classes are worried about high taxes and stagnant wages, so Mr Dole promises to deal with both. Since it is middle-class votes that win elections, this ought surely to be a winner.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It would be, if it made sense. It may do, in political terms. But in economic terms it is dubious, to say the least. Mr Dole's measures look attractive when each is viewed in isolation. In combination, the result looks ugly. Mr Dole proposes no serious cuts in federal spending, and has promised to leave Medicare, Social Security and defence, which together account for the bulk of the budget, untouched. That leaves his promise both to cut taxes and balance the budget dependent on magic. And it is better to save your tax-cuts until tax reform is well under way, for reform creates losers as well as winners, and some spare change is essential if the losers are to be persuaded to accept it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Finally, the claim that tax cuts will boost the economy also invites scepticism: with unemployment already down to 5.3% of the workforce, growth is unlikely to accelerate for long without igniting inflation, the fear of which will lead the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates. Tax and regulatory reform might eventually help the economy to grow faster without boosting inflation, by encouraging investment and productivity, but a true budget-balancer would not count on it. He would wait, as the old Bob Dole used to say, to get his dividend before he spent it.
</p><p><b>Bill Clinton's political zig-zags</b>
<br>That is why the hope must be that the old Bob Dole is the real one, that decades of senatorial prudence have not suddenly been ditched. It is an awkward hope for voters, for you cannot expect a candidate willingly to offer evidence for the proposition that he is lying. But the other hope--that Mr Clinton is telling the truth--will also be hard to prove.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reason why this hope matters is that Mr Clinton's greatest talent is self-transformation. More even than other politicians, he follows the polls and shapes himself accordingly. In his first two years of office he was an activist president, seeking to extend federal responsibilities in all sorts of ways. Since the mid-term congressional elections of 1994 he has taken a different stance, seeking to "triangulate" himself midway between old Democrats and rabid Republicans, trying to trim government back rather than extend it. His latest move, agreeing last week to sign a welfare bill that will end a federal guarantee of welfare benefits to poor families that was established in 1935, was his most dramatic yet.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In one sense, this was merely a belated implementation of a promise he made in the 1992 campaign "to end welfare as we know it". Even on that level it was significant, as for three-and-a-half years he appeared to have changed his mind. Even more than that, however, it looked like a statement of future intent, a demonstration that the new Bill Clinton really does mean to cut government, to eliminate the deficit and to devolve responsibilities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the difficulty, with Mr Clinton, will be to judge whether he will mean this as much in 1997 as he does in the run-up to November 5th. The Democrats' convention may offer some clues, through his manner of dealing with intra-party opposition. Mr Clinton's stance, as an experienced president who admits to his mistakes and learns from them, is an appealing one, as the opinion polls show. Yet after November a re-elected Bill Clinton would be in what for him is uncharted territory: the chance to govern, without worrying about the next election. How will he behave then? That is what voters must decide.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
