<html><head><title>The first extra-terrestrials</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>



<h1><center>The first extra-terrestrials</center></h1>
<p><b>The discovery of even provisional evidence of life on Mars is an historic event. But it is still a long way from the discovery of alien intelligence</b></p>


YOU are not alone--maybe. The search for extra-terrestrial life is the most compelling of all scientific quests. If life were found elsewhere, it would change humanity's view of itself forever. No longer the lone, brave experiment on a little planet, but a cosmic commonplace--and the ultimate knockdown. Copernicus told people they were not at the centre of the universe. Darwin told them they were not a divine creation. Now the risen apes are hearing that the same evolutionary process that created them may have gone on elsewhere. Analysis of a meteorite from the Allan Hills of Antarctica (see <a href="st1.html">page</a>) suggests that it may have happened on Mars.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The evidence is not water-tight. But it is the best that could be hoped for from such a source. The rock in question was blasted from Mars's surface by an asteroid impact, wandered in the vacuum of space for 15m years, where it would have been bombarded by powerful radiation, and then came screaming through the earth's atmosphere at breakneck speed, banging into Antarctica, where it sat through 13,000 consecutive winters. Rough handling of this sort is not conducive to the preservation of delicate biological features.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet such features still seem, according to the scientists, to be there. They have found what they believe is evidence that the rock in question was once inhabited by Martians. Not, to be sure, the malign, tentacled geniuses invented by H. G. Wells, but things a bit closer to terrestrial bacteria. But even bacteria would qualify as a scientific bombshell.
</p><p><b>The measure of mankind</b>
<br>True, Wells may have caught the public mood better. What most people want, and want to measure themselves against, are not bugs, but bug-eyed monsters. A couple of times, astronomers have thought they have heard them. When Jocelyn Bell first noticed a regularly pulsing radio signal coming from the sky in 1967, she nicknamed it "<font size=-1>LGM-1</font>" after the ubiquitous Little Green Men of <font size=-1>B</font>-movie science-fiction. The discovery a few weeks later of <font size=-1>LGM-2</font> somewhat dampened the idea that a first contact with extra-terrestrial intelligence had at last been made (the signals turned out to be coming from a new class of star now known as pulsars). A second radio emission, known as the "Wow Signal", also attracted fans of extra-terrestrial intelligence. The signal was heard in 1977 by astronomers at Ohio State University. It looked, to the faithful, like a radio beacon. Unfortunately, when they looked again, it had vanished.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And that, so far, is it. No reliable radio signal from an alien civilisation has been detected. Short of a visitation from such a civilisation's ambassadors, radio is the only way any such contact can be made.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For those who still believe in the uniqueness of Man, therefore, there remains a slim hope. If the evidence from the Allan Hills meteorite stands up in the court of world scientific opinion--and it will be vigorously contested over the coming months--it may mean that primitive life can evolve quite easily. That says nothing, though, about how easy it is to arrive at intelligence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What is known of the history of the solar system suggests that the earth and Mars are probably the only bodies that have experienced the sort of conditions (moderate temperature, tolerable atmosphere, water and so on) that are needed to support life, at least as the term is understood by terrestrial biologists. If life originated separately on each of these planets--and there is a slim chance that one could have "infected" the other through a meteorite--this suggests that evolving life from non-living ingredients could be quite common.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But there remains a large gap between bacteria and intelligence. Even on earth, a dispassionate history of life would, save for a brief appendix, be a history of bacteria. The oldest terrestrial fossils date back over 3 billion years. Multicellular animals have been around for barely a sixth of this time; modern human intelligence for a mere 200,000 years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On earth, the evolution of intelligence involved at least four giant leaps. The first, and in many ways hardest, was from bacteria to the more complex cells of which animals and plants are composed. The second came when these cells formed viable colonies (ie, bodies). This meant some cells giving up the sacred right of reproduction in order to specialise in other functions, something that goes strongly against the evolutionary grain. The third was for animals to become complex enough, and to develop sufficiently sophisticated nervous systems, to allow for intelligence. Even when this had happened, at the beginning of the period known as the Triassic, it still took around 250m years before the fourth leap, when man's ancestors started to develop a brain big enough to support such intelligence. It is quite possible, therefore, that the galaxy is teeming with primitive life, but that none of it, other than that on earth, is intelligent.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The message of the Allan Hills meteorite could, therefore, be somewhat paradoxical. If it does indeed contain the first evidence of extra-terrestrial life, that is tremendously exciting. But it may also suggest that the history of life is not one of automatic progress from primeval soup to potent primate. That is a somewhat different conclusion from the one the extra-terrestrial enthusiasts have been urging. Rather than telling us we are not alone, the Allan Hills meteorite may emphasise how utterly alone we are.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839631600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
