</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>.&#160;.&#160;.&#160;to the grave?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif"  alt="Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>.&#160;.&#160;.&#160;to the grave?</h1>

<p><b>The Republican Party is in a mess. The Republican philosophy is healthy</b></p>


<p>A LITTLE over a year ago, America's Republicans were ecstatic. In the mid-term election of November 1994 they had won control of both House and Senate, ending 40 years of Democratic dominance of Congress. Once in power, they had defied predictions that they would squabble among themselves, remaining united behind their campaign manifesto, the Contract with America. Their leaders talked grandly of a rising Republican tide, of a new Republican age to match the six-decade-long "liberal ascendancy" that began with the New Deal in the 1930s (liberal in the American sense of social-democratic). There was little question in Republican minds that, come 1996, their presidential candidate would campaign on the merits of the Contract--and emerge victorious.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now a very different kind of tide is lapping round the Republicans as they gather for their party convention in San Diego on August 12th-15th. This tide is threatening to drown them. Their presidential candidate, Bob Dole, lags behind Bill Clinton in opinion polls; some Republicans fear that they might even lose control of the House this November. In May Mr Dole announced his resignation from the Senate to distance himself from his congressional colleagues, who had earned a bad name for themselves by pushing their campaign for spending cuts to the point of closing down the federal government for days on end. And over the next three months he turned the Contract's tactics upside down: rather than offer a list of clear promises, as the Contract did, he mumbled his way through a series of speeches that committed him to as little as possible.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Mr Dole finally broke this pattern, on August 5th, he repudiated much of last year's Republican programme. He unveiled a proposed series of tax cuts, which may give his campaign a boost. But he abandoned the pledge, trumpeted loudly by congressional Republicans last year, to pay for these cuts by controlling the cost of defence and big entitlement schemes (health care for the elderly; pensions). Instead, he reverted to the old Reaganite line: that tax cuts to some extent pay for themselves by stimulating growth and revenues, while spending cuts to balance the budget need not be specified. Balancing the budget without such leaps of faith had been a big part of the Contract.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tensions within party ranks are bound to be visible through the cheerful fa&ccedil;ade of the Republican convention. Over the past few months the party has been riven by arguments over abortion which threaten to spill on to the convention floor. Colin Powell, whom Mr Dole wanted as his running mate, may use his speech in San Diego to defend affirmative-action plans to help blacks; if he does, opponents of racial preferences may stage a walk-out. Pat Buchanan, who challenged Mr Dole's nomination from the right, issues veiled threats of secession from the party.
</p><p><b>Triumph or tragedy?</b></b>
<br>Was this humiliating fall inevitable? Optimistic Republicans put their recent setbacks down to superficial mistakes, representing mere hiccups on the way to an era of Republican dominance. If Mr Dole were a better campaigner, they think, if he would stick to his message and smile just a little bit, he would stand an excellent chance against the tele-friendly Mr Clinton. Equally, if the congressional Republicans had played their hand more skilfully over the past year, if they had not alienated voters by bringing the government to a close, the entire party would be more popular. Republican believers still maintain that, by 2001, and perhaps even by next year, their party will control both the White House and Congress, and will be radically changing the way America is governed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sceptics, on the other hand, see last year's Republican unity, not this year's disarray, as the real anomaly. They see the party as a muddled alliance of libertarians and moralists, tax-cutters and spending hawks, technocratic visionaries and anti-Internet reactionaries. On their view, Mr Dole's unfocused campaign reflects more than his personal flaws; it reflects the confusion within his party. The sceptics predict that over the next decade or so the Republicans will shamble along, unable to bring about big change. American government will continue to hand out favours to interest groups; it will remain highly indebted and increasingly unpopular.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The sceptics' case starts by emphasising the most obvious split in Republican ranks, that between social moderates and conservatives. Exit polls taken after the 1994 landslide showed that the Republicans had made their biggest gains among two intensely conservative groups, Southern whites and born-again Christians. White evangelicals cast one in three Republican votes; two in five came from religious conservatives, a group that includes members of mainstream churches as well as evangelical ones. These voters had little in common with the libertarians and socially tolerant business elites who had earlier made their home in the Republican Party.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The resulting split made itself felt in the Republican primaries this spring. Then, Mr Buchanan carried the banner of the religious right to victory in the New Hampshire primary election, promising to protect the right to life of "the innocent unborn", attacking gay marriage and calling for prayer in government schools. At the opposite end of the spectrum was Steve Forbes, a tolerant billionaire: he refused to support an abortion ban, avoided most social issues and was criticised for owning a photograph by Robert Mapplethorpe, a gay artist. Mr Dole himself acknowledged the seriousness of this split when he declared the primaries "a struggle for the heart and soul of the Republican Party".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He won the nomination by steering a middle course, and Republicans hoped for a quick healing of party wounds. They did not get one. When Mr Dole proposed that the party's anti-abortion plank be tempered with a passage emphasising tolerance of dissenting views, the religious right rebelled. When Mr Dole then backed down, Governors William Weld of Massachusetts and Pete Wilson of California, who both oppose an abortion ban, mounted their own protest. On the eve of the convention, the religious right seem to have won this battle: they reckon the party will run on a strict anti-abortion policy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If so, the Republicans will find themselves in a trap that can cripple parties for years: a zealous minority has won control of policy, alienating the majority whose support is needed for electoral victory. The best that moderate Republicans can hope for is that abortion will not sway many votes. Those who care about abortion generally oppose it, and so will like the Republican platform; other voters pay little attention to the issue. The trouble with this defence is that, on other issues, the Republicans may not be much more united.
</p><p><b>Moral militants</b></b>
<br>The fight over abortion reflects a wider split in Republican ranks between libertarians and moralists. In this struggle, the moralists include not only the religious right, but a group of intellectuals who worry about the corrosive power of "liberal relativism"-- ie, Americans' reluctance to pass judgment on socially destructive forms of personal behaviour. Divorce, illegitimacy and other sorts of family collapse, they argue, have been allowed to spread unchecked; these have in turn brought about a rise in poverty and teenage delinquency. Gang leaders in the ghettos have no sense of right and wrong. Even middle-class children have been depraved by the diet of sex and violence served up by Hollywood.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In defiance of their party's libertarian, anti-government wing, the moralists conclude that too much freedom has proved dangerous. To restore discipline among children, they support the curfews imposed in several cities. To curb family disintegration, they argue that divorce should be made more difficult. They oppose gay marriage, a practice which they fear will undermine the traditional family still more. They favour strict censorship of pornography and regard the anarchy of cyberspace with despair. Even though many are not practising Christians themselves, they favour school prayer and government support for Christian social work, on the argument that religion instils moral values.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some moralists espouse a distinctive view of foreign policy as well. In a recent issue of <i>Foreign Affairs</i>*, two eminent Republicans attack the isolationists and tepid internationalists who dominate their party, and urge Republicans to throw their weight behind a crusading foreign policy. Mr Buchanan, they point out, wants American troops withdrawn from Europe; the congressional Republicans have cut the foreign-policy budget to its bare bones; Mr Dole and some of his advisers are uncomfortable with this but do not dare propose a return to the foreign policy of the cold war. The moralists are not so shy. The defence budget should be boosted by a quarter, they declare, and America should loudly proclaim its commitment to spreading democracy abroad. If democracy is a moral good, they say, there can be no justification for doing otherwise.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such policy prescriptions may be controversial but at least the boundaries of debate are relatively well defined. The much larger discord that the moralists have stirred up concerns the party's view of human behaviour. During the 1980s Ronald Reagan preached that liberty was both an economic and a moral good: in an atmosphere of free competition untrammelled by the state, people would be thrifty, disciplined and diligent. This 1980s Republicanism represented a backlash against the social policy of earlier years, which was based on the idea that human beings could be improved by enlightened government activism. But now the moralists are reviving a variant of that old view. Freedom does not breed virtue, they insist: this can be done only by social institutions such as the family and church, backed up by a sympathetic government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In short, the party that attacked social policy a decade ago is now reinventing it. The party that celebrated the swash-buckling individualism of American myth now emphasises the need for stable communities. The party that worshipped Mr Reagan's cowboy style is now led by Mr Dole, who invokes the neighbourly values of rural Kansas. This confusion has frustrated Republican attempts to articulate a consistent view of the world, and so to rise above the squabbles on censorship, school prayer and abortion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many Republicans openly concede their divisions on social and moral issues. But they claim that opposition to economic statism unites them. The essence of Republicanism, they contend, is hostility to the expansion of the welfare state wrought by Democrats in the 1930s and the 1960s. So long as Republicans can remember this, their other divisions will not matter.
</p><p><b>Enemies of the state?</b>
<br>This claim is based on an edited version of history. Although it is true that Franklin Roosevelt and Lyndon Johnson, Democrats both, presided over the legislation of the New Deal and the Great Society, it is also true that Republican presidents have done their bit to expand the state. Between 1901 and 1909 Theodore Roosevelt created the Commerce Department and the National Park Service, quadrupled the federal government's land holdings, and brought the railways under federal regulation. In the 1950s Dwight Eisenhower backed federal aid for education, housing projects and interstate highways. Richard Nixon created the Environmental Protection Agency and new safety rules for workers. Most recently, George Bush raised taxes, promoted a new public-education effort called Head Start, and presided over a massive increase in regulation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Anti-statism, meanwhile, has often been just an undercurrent in the Republican Party. Robert Taft, an anti-statist, failed to secure his party's presidential nomination repeatedly from 1940 until 1952. Barry Goldwater, a Republican of similar beliefs, won the nomination in 1964 but lost the election so heavily that anti-statism was buried for a decade.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The only Republican to attack the state and do well was Ronald Reagan. In 1976 he campaigned for the nomination on a Goldwaterite platform and was rebuffed; but in 1980 and 1984 he was resoundingly victorious. Why this change? Because, between 1976 and 1980, Mr Reagan's anti-statism had been transformed. Instead of promising to scrap government spending programmes, Mr Reagan was promising to cut taxes. Anti-statism had become code for letting people keep more of what they earned: hence its popularity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In office, Mr Reagan was true to his word. Taxes were cut, but government spending grew--and Mr Reagan was a hero. On a state level, other Republicans have since repeated the same trick. In New Jersey Christine Todd Whitman spouts anti-statist rhetoric of which Mr Reagan might be proud; she has cut state income taxes by 30%--but has done little to cut spending.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Seen in this light, Republican fortunes over the past year hardly come as a surprise. For a brief period, the party tried to rein in government: like Taft, Goldwater and the Reagan of 1976, it soon found that this destroyed its popularity. Learning from the experience, Mr Dole has shifted to anti-statism of the more electable sort. He lays out promised tax cuts in loving detail. There will be a 15% cut in income tax, a 50% cut in capital-gains tax, and a $500-per-child tax credit; overall, a family of four making $35,000 a year would see a 56% drop in its federal tax bill. At the same time, Mr Dole assures voters that he will not cut popular government programmes to pay for all this. More than half of the spending cuts that his plan entails are not spelled out at all; the rest are alluded to in vague, soothing terms. The biggest proposed cut, purportedly worth $90 billion over six years, will come from "non-defence administrative costs". Nice to hear that it's so easy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In short, the anti-statism that supposedly binds Republicans together is not really anti-statism at all; it is anti-tax populism. This can work wonders, as Mr Reagan's record shows. It may revive Mr Dole's hopes too; together with the publicity gained from his announcement of a running mate and a good speech in San Diego next week, it might, just possibly, make him electable. But, as a mechanism to unite Republicans over the long term, anti-tax rhetoric will hardly do. America's budget deficit, though shrinking now because of steady economic growth, will expand again when the economy turns down. As baby boomers retire in vast numbers a decade or so hence, the deficit could balloon. America can ill afford tax cuts, so Republicans can hope for only short-term gains by pushing them.
</p><p><b>The Eisenhower principle</b>
<br>In sum, the Republicans' critics are mostly right: the party is fundamentally divided. The unpopularity of the Republican Congress reflects the political unsellability of its radical anti-statist creed. Mr Dole's lacklustre campaign reflects the dearth of binding Republican ideas, not just his limited skills as a campaigner.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And yet, in another sense, the critics go too far. The Republicans may well hold on to Congress despite their internal splits, just as the Democrats held on for decades despite equally profound divisions: the advantage of incumbency is formidable. Although Mr Dole's prospects look poor in this election, future Republican contenders may prove charismatic enough to overcome the party's lack of a common philosophy. After all, Eisenhower made the White House Republican for eight years without, it seemed, standing for any kind of Republicanism at all; until he announced his candidacy in 1952, nobody knew which party he belonged to. Equally, the Republicans could have been riding high this year had another anti-ideological ex-general, Colin Powell, sought the party's nomination.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Besides, even if Mr Dole and his party bicker their way to defeat this year, a Republican era may still be at hand. Mr Clinton's strong showing in the polls reflects his adoption of various Republican ideas, from fiscal conservatism to a crack-down on crime, from welfare reform to rhetorical attacks on Hollywood. Though Republican moralists may push the point too far for most Americans, many think that their country's infatuation with freedom needs to be tempered by some mix of private and public authority. Although there is little support for a radical pruning of the state, even Mr Clinton accepts that the reach of government cannot be blatantly extended.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the height of the liberal era, Dwight Eisenhower managed to hold the White House for the Republicans because he was free of Republican ideas. Equally, Mr Clinton may govern in a Republican era because he has ditched (for the campaign season, at least) traditional Democratic opinions. In each case, the battle of ideas may matter more than the battle among men. Let that console the Republicans as they fight it out in San Diego.

<br><hr><br>
<i>* </i>"A Foreign Policy for Candidate Dole" , by William Kristol and Robert Kagan. <i>Foreign Affairs. </i>July/August 1996<i>.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
