<html><head><title>New York's finest</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width=224 height=26  alt="International">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>South Africa</b></p>
<h1>New York's finest</h1>

<font size=-1>JOHANNESBURG</font>
<p>WHEN William Bratton, former head of the New York Police Department, landed in Johannesburg this week, he was invited to a dinner party with the top official responsible for security. The daughter of the woman he sat next to had just had her car hijacked, at 8 o'clock on a weekday morning, as she drove with her two-year-old daughter (you keep the baby, said the hijackers, we'll keep the car--which, by South African standards, was better than she might have feared). "Everybody around that table seemed to be a victim of crime, or know one," he says. No wonder South Africans greeted Mr Bratton, under whom New York's murder rate fell by 40% in two years, with such enthusiasm.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Crime has become an obsession in the new South Africa. Johannesburgers telephone local radio shows to advise others to aim between the eyes of an armed attacker and kill him first shot. Residents of leafy suburbs advise newcomers not to stop if their car gets an "accidental" shunt from the one behind--indeed even to ignore red traffic lights, if they want to be sure of avoiding a hijack. Houses are hidden behind high perimeter walls, topped with razor spikes, their alarms electronically linked to alert private armed guards.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This dread of crime is not unwarranted. The annual murder rate--about 50-55 per 100,000 people (there are statistical problems)--is one of the highest in the world, and, by any estimate, about five or six times that of the United States. South Africans own over 3m licensed guns, and many more illegally; at Johannesburg airport, passengers routinely turn up with guns, though the bullets must be taken out and the gun checked in. Nor does crime, or the fear of it, hit whites only. Rich blacks are no less afraid of housebreakers than rich whites and, of Johannesburg's 8,500 carjackings last year, around one in seven happened in Soweto. Rape is common there. In a survey of readers by <i>The Sowetan</i>, 80% claimed they had been victims of crime last year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In May, the government did launch a "national crime prevention strategy", followed by a police blitz. George Fivaz, the police commissioner, said he would hunt down South Africa's "most wanted criminals" within 30 days. Things did not look too hopeful: his list stretched to 10,000 names. But, lo, Mr Fivaz felt able in due time to declared that, after 30 days, his force had arrested no fewer than 7,099 of them. Which begs two questions. If it was that easy, why were they not caught earlier? Or could it just be that they weren't caught at all? Even the justice minister, Dullah Omar, cast doubt on the figures, remarking that there had been no noticeable increase in cases brought to court.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Enter Mr Bratton. He left his New York post in April, and now runs a security consultancy. He has had no firm offers from South Africa yet, and its police chiefs and politicians can be stubbornly proud about taking advice from outsiders. But South Africans, desperate for crime-fighting ideas, have hailed him.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In New York, Mr Bratton worked on two principles. In the office, he managed the police force like a business. He delegated responsibility to his "business units" (local police precincts), set them "profit" targets (reductions in crime), and changed a slow, bureaucratic culture into a snappy, entrepreneurial one in which policemen can take their own initiative.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the streets, he applied the doctrine of "zero tolerance". If policemen make arrests for petty offences, goes the logic, such as urinating on the street or drinking alcohol in public, it reinforces the idea that no crime is tolerated; and this, in turn, helps reduce more serious crime. Could it work in South Africa too? Yes, Mr Bratton claims: "Systems of policing are transferable and replicable."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some of his ideas make common sense. South Africa's police force was structured to control and crush political enemies, not common criminals; over two-thirds of its time was spent undermining or hunting those who challenged apartheid. It is rare, for example, to see policemen simply patrolling the streets in Johannesburg. "I've never been to a city where policing is so invisible," comments Mr Bratton. To make it less so would help both to curb fear and to deter opportunists.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps the prickliest obstacle for Mr Bratton, as he tip-toes across South Africa's political sensitivities, is the authoritarian tone of his tactics. Were South Africa's policemen to apply zero tolerance, they would be cracking down on small but precious liberties that blacks have only recently won. Pavement peddlers or the enterprising, if not always welcome, young men who wash windscreens in traffic jams might be swept away. And one idea--to introduce identity cards, to facilitate random street checks--has a very nasty smell in South Africa. To many blacks, it recalls the days when they had to carry pass books, and were banned from white areas at night, under the laws of apartheid.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839631600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
