These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>Dial 'S' for snitch</b> &nbsp;On the first day of operation of a confidential telephone line set up by the government for people to report neighbours they suspect of making false claims for benefits, more than 1,600 people called.</p>
<p><b>Short fuse</b> &nbsp;Clare Short, the Labour Party's overseas development spokesman, gave an interview denouncing "dark forces" among Tony Blair's advisers. Mr Blair made it clear that he would not sack Miss Short.
<b>Double</b> <b>jeopardy</b><br>
Anti-abortionists won an injunction to stop an unmarried mother having one of her healthy twins aborted on the ground that she could not cope with two more babies. It later emerged that the abortion had already taken place.</p>
<p><b>No surrender</b> &nbsp;Protestant Apprentice Boys were banned from marching along part of the walls of Londonderry overlooking a Catholic area, and from marching along the Lower Ormeau Road in Belfast, another Catholic area.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>No future</b> &nbsp;The Ulster Volunteer Force, an outlawed loyalist paramilitary group, disbanded one of its units in Portadown, County Armagh, following the murder of a Catholic man last month. The unit had opposed the loyalist ceasefire.</p>
<p><b>Not so mad</b> &nbsp;The Bank of England said the crisis over mad-cow disease cut the growth of Britain's <font size=-1>GDP</font> by just 0.1 percentage points, and increased inflation by the same amount, in the second quarter of this year--much smaller figures than were originally expected. The fall in beef prices was outweighed by rising prices of other types of meat.</p>
<p><b>In the news</b> &nbsp;Pearson, part-owner of <i>The Economist</i>, sold Westminster Press, its chain of 60 regional newspapers, for &#163;305m to Newsquest, a consortium of American and British investors.</p>
<p><b>Elvis spotted</b> &nbsp;Police investigating reports of a body seen under a bridge near Settle, North Yorkshire, found a life-size papier-m&#226;ch&#233; model of Elvis Presley, minus the blue suede shoes.</p>
