<html><head><title>Taking Europe off-line</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>On-line services</b></p>
<h1>Taking Europe off-line</h1>

<p>BEFORE it had really got going, Europe Online, a Luxembourg-based Internet provider, has gone bust. On August 2nd a Luxembourg court wound up the company, a month after Burda, its largest single shareholder, withdrew from the venture. The firm, which had a paltry 25,000 subscribers in France, Germany, Luxembourg and Britain, racked up bills of around LFr 1.4 billion ($45m) in less than six months of full service.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is the second such failure of a European Internet provider in four months: in April, the owners of Italy's Video On Line, an Internet service that operated in dozens of languages, from English to Chokwa, agreed to sell the loss-making venture to Telecom Italia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Does this mean that a pan-European consumer on-line service is always destined to fail? Not necessarily. CompuServe, an Ohio-based on-line service that has operated in Europe for ten years, boasts 800,000 European members. <font size=-1>AOL</font>, a joint venture between Bertelsmann, a German media firm, and America Online, the world's largest on-line service, has notched up 200,000 subscribers in less than a year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But these firms are in a different league from Europe Online. They have considerable experience, well-known brands and oodles of content--much of it tailored for each country. Europe Online at least avoided the mistake of treating Europe as one homogeneous market: each member country could gain access to its service (and content) in its own language. But it did little else right. Access was slow: in Britain, for example, the service used yesteryear's slow modems, when its rivals were already offering much faster Internet access.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Worst of all, Europe Online's owners did not really understand their own business model. Until November last year, the company planned to launch on <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s soon-to-be-defunct Interchange service, rather than on the Internet. A few weeks before its launch, Europe Online decided to switch to the Internet, with massive technical and, even more importantly, financial ramifications.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All its short life, Europe Online was plagued with boardroom squabbles. An offer from CompuServe to acquire the company was turned down in July; a rival plan that <font size=-1>ITT</font>, an American technology giant, should take a stake in the business and float it, also got nowhere. But the company, though clinically dead, is still on life support: as of August 8th, its subscribers could still get full access to the Internet, and the Luxembourg government is paying the firm's employees. (The Luxembourg State Savings Bank and the Luxembourg State Investment Bank both had stakes in the failed venture.)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The game is not yet over. The company is still talking to Deutsche Telekom, Germany's main telephone company. But why should Deutsche Telekom, which already runs T-Online, a German on-line service with 1.2m members, be interested in a small, failed on-line service? The answer lies in politics.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Luxembourg government is proud of the country's role as the home of <font size=-1>SES</font>, which owns the Astra satellites from which much of Europe's pay-television is beamed; it is keen to be similarly central to Europe's on-line future. Deutsche Telekom has a sizeable stake in <font size=-1>SES</font>. And Christian Schwarz-Schilling, until a couple of weeks ago the chairman of Europe Online, was Germany's minister for post and telecommunications until December 1992 and is still a senior member of the governing Christian Democratic party.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With so much national pride at stake, Europe Online could yet return expensively from the grave. How its resurrection makes sense on any other grounds is hard to see.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839631600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="fn1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
