<html><head><title>Sacred hearths</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width=360 height=26  alt="Finance And Economics">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>Sacred hearths</h1>

<p>AS ANY theologian will tell you, the best measure of a person's well-being is the sense of closeness that he feels to his divine creator. Unfortunately for economists, this is a tricky thing to measure. Instead, they may settle for a proxy: the value of one's personal property. As it turns out, these two measures may be more closely related than you might expect. For among a handful of academic economists, a debate has been raging over how proximity to a church affects the price of one's home.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The protagonists split into two camps. The first group argue that churches are a nuisance for nearby homeowners because they tend to introduce noise and bother into their immediate surroundings: clanging bells, lots of traffic, overly helpful neighbours and so forth. According to this school of thought, building a church in an area ought to have roughly the same effect as opening a landfill--giving new meaning, as one economist puts it, to the term "moral hazard".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other economists, however, believe that churches, like playgrounds or parks, bestow all sorts of positive externalities on those who live nearby, and should therefore help to raise local house prices. Who is right?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a while, the antis appeared to have the weight of evidence on their side. For example, one prominent study, published in the <i>Journal of Real Estate Finance and Economics</i> in 1994, found that houses in Chula Vista, a small town in California, tended to sell at a bigger discount the closer they were to a church.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The devil, however, is in the details. In a new study in the same journal*, three economists from the University of Las Vegas examined house prices in Green Valley, Nevada. The good news: contrary to the previous study's conclusions, prices of houses tended to fall the farther away they were from a church.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How to reconcile these apparently contradictory results? The authors of the latest study offer a tempting explanation: that the value of a church depends on its location. In godly Chula Vista, which has 15 churches per square mile, normal folk cannot get far enough away. But in godforsaken Green Valley, which is close to Las Vegas, or "sin city", it would appear that every house needs a firm foundation.

<br><hr><br>
* "Living Next to Godliness" . By Thomas Carroll, Terrence Clauretie and Jeff Jensen. May 1996.</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839631600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="st1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
