<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><h2>Feeling buoyant</h2>
<p><p>
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>In America, second quarter <b>growth</b> was faster than expected: 4.2% at an annual rate. Annual wage inflation was 3.2% in the quarter. Consumer confidence rose in July to its highest level for six years. The latest monthly survey by the Conference Board, a business coalition, found that consumers were "clearly confident about current economic conditions and anticipate further economic growth in the months ahead".
<p>The central bank of Australia cut half a percentage point off the official <b>interest rate</b>, reducing it to 7%.
<p>The German state of Saxony refused to withdraw a subsidy to <b>Volkswagen</b>, even though the European Commission had ruled that the payment was illegal and is now threatening to go to the European Court unless the German car maker repays DM90.7m ($61.6m) immediately. Saxony says it is determined to save the thousands of jobs the state would lose if the car maker moved production elsewhere.
<p>In response to America's <b>Helms-Burton act</b>, which penalises foreign companies that do business with Cuba, the European Commission proposed legislation to make it illegal for European companies to comply with the act. Any similar bill would also be covered by the commission's proposed legislation.</p>
<p><h2>Cashing in</h2></p>
<p><p>Europe continues to struggle with its ailing state-owned banks. The European Commission's competition officials are investigating the rescue of <b>Banco di Napoli</b>, just as its shareholders approved a 2.28 trillion lire ($1.5 billion) bail-out by the Italian government. In France, meanwhile, the finance ministry denied reports that it would sell up to 25% of <b>Cr&eacute;dit Lyonnais</b> by the end of the year.
<p>The recovery plan adopted recently by the <b>Lloyd's of London</b> insurance market faces a new legal challenge from a group of "names" who met their underwriting commitments, and who say the plan favours names who did not.
<p>Industrial Bank of Japan, the country's largest long-term credit bank, plans a &#165;225.7 billion ($2.1 billion) <b>rights issue </b>to bolster its capital-adequacy ratio. Britain's largest bank, National Westminster, made a &#163;450m ($700m) <b>share buy-back</b> despite being on the lookout for a life assurer and despite declaring a half-year net loss of &#163;111m. That came about from a writedown of &#163;690m on the sale of its American retail banking business and on restructuring charges.Russia has sealed hundreds of tonnes of Soviet rouble notes deep underground in decommissioned strategic <b>missile silos</b>. It reckoned it was cheaper than burning them.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><h2>Channel-hopping</h2></p>
<p><p>An epic battle to win control of Germany's digital pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> market was won by <b>Kirch Group</b> as <b>Bertelsmann </b>conceded on several humiliating points, including agreeing to use a common decoder developed by Kirch.
<p>First-half profits at <b>Glaxo Wellcome</b> rose strongly, boosted by a range of new drugs that more than counteracted a worse-than-expected slide in its flagship Zantac anti-ulcer drug. Pre-tax profits rose to &#163;1.55 billion ($2.37 billion) from &#163;1.16 billion a year earlier.
<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Britain's <b>Stagecoach</b>, a bus and train group whose growth has been built at the gallop, snapped up Porterbrook Leasing, owner of a third of Britain's passenger trains, for &#163;475.6m ($737m). Stagecoach plans to help pay for the takeover with proceeds from a &#163;111m rights issue and a &#163;550m bridging loan from the Union Bank of Switzerland. This is the second rail deal for Stagecoach since the government began privatising British Rail.
<p><b>Microsoft</b>, the world's biggest software firm, and <b>American Express</b>, its biggest travel agency, are teaming up to offer on-line travel services to business customers.</p>
<p><h2>Currents</h2></p>
<p><p><b>USAir </b>launched legal action in an American court against a proposed alliance between <b>British Airways </b>and <b>American Airlines</b>, just as the pact was endorsed by a British parliamentary committee, which believes that it would enhance the chances of an "open skies" deal between the two countries. British Airways holds a 24.6% stake in troubled <font size=-1>USA</font>ir, which alleges that an alliance between the two giant airlines would be anti-competitive and would breach the terms of a 1993 agreement between itself and British Airways.
<p><b>McDonnell Douglas</b> appears to be discussing a merger or some other link with <b>Raytheon</b>, whose specialities are defence electronics and missiles. After failed talks with Boeing, McDonnell is eager to halt the erosion in its lead as America's largest military-aircraft maker.
<p>South Korea's <b>Kia Motors</b> announced plans for a $1 billion car factory in Kaliningrad, a Russian enclave on the Baltic Sea. The investment would be one of the largest in Russia by any foreign firm.
<p>Swissair reckons that it is about to become the first big carrier to convert its long-haul aircraft into <b>flying casinos</b> when it installs an $80m in-flight gambling system provided by Interactive Flight Technologies. Armed only with a credit card and a video screen, passengers will be able to win or lose money without leaving their seats.
<p><p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
<p align=center><a href="wtw1.html">POLITICS THIS WEEK</a></p><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
