<html><head><title>http://www.nuts</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>http://www.nuts</h1>

<font size=1>ST LOUIS</font>
<p>A GENERATION ago the followers of any American oddball movement would have been content to mimeograph their manifestos and hand them out at gun shows or read them aloud over local radio stations. Now the same dark conspiracies and gleaming new certainties reach millions, instantly, through cyberspace. All points on the political spectrum, from far right to far left, have sites on the Internet. The "sovereignty movement", the phrase covering among other things a variety of tax protesters and private militias, is particularly active. It has many sites on the Internet, and files available for downloading with links to other "patriotic" sites.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The American Patriot Network (<a href="http://users.aol.com/dritus/apn.htm">http://users.aol.com/dritus/apn.htm</a>) offers the novel idea that the zip postal code is a conspiracy to subject the innocent to federal taxation; it adds that anyone who refuses to use the zip code on his mail is exempt from paying federal taxes. The Sovereign Citizen Resource Centre (<a href="http://www.caprica.com/~scrc/">http://www.caprica.com/~scrc/</a>), which argues that there is no such thing as a citizen of the United States of America, offers citizenship in the "Washitaw" nation plus freedom from all taxes and regulations. Entry into this electronic republic costs $65 for a new birth certificate and $150 for a passport, not to mention fees for car and driving licences.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More serious, perhaps, are the "common-law courts" springing up around the country. The movement's web site (<a href="http://www.nidlink.com/~bobhard/commnlaw.html">http://www.nidlink.com/~bobhard/commnlaw.html</a>) offers advice and encouragement to would-be claimants and judges itching to impose multi-million-dollar computer-world judgments and liens against public officials and tax collectors. One site offers the set of documents used by the Freemen rebels in "Justus Township", the compound in Montana whose long siege by the <font size=-1>FBI</font> ended in June.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The make-believe lawyers of the common-law courts tend to select a smattering of favourable quotations from real-world court cases, and build upon them fanciful illusions about what people can demand from the government. They are capable of resting their arguments on state rulings dating from before the 1861-65 civil war, or even on the constitution of the defeated Confederacy. Most Americans had thought those issues were settled more than 130 years ago. One group has sternly declared the secession of Texas from the United States, proclaiming the new republic on its site in both the English and Spanish languages.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In case words alone are not enough, some web sites offer "survival training", including instructions on how to offer armed resistance to officers of the law. It is a tribute to the generosity of America, as well as to the power of technology, that the Internet is open to the opinions of all these people. Whether they will in the end benefit from it is another matter. Once their ideas have been thoroughly exposed to the cybersunshine, they may find themselves retreating under the rocks from which they came.



</td></tr></table>
