<html><head><title>A cheer for Olympo-Americans</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>A cheer for Olympo-Americans</h1>

<p>AMID the golden exploits of stars such as Carl Lewis in the long jump and the sprinter Michael Johnson, you might not have noticed Konstantine Starikovitch. Few people did. His is one of the less glamorous Olympic sports, weightlifting. In the Atlanta Olympics, he finished well out of the medals, in 12th place. To do so, he heaved a bar weighing 177.5kg above his head in the "snatch", rock music blared out in the arena (as happened for a few seconds after all successful lifts), and the spectators gave an almighty roar (as they did for all American competitors).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is the point about Mr Starikovitch. He is from Russia, but he became an American citizen last April. To the crowds, he was just another American, to be cheered on at the top of their voices. It was the same with other naturalised Americans, such as Monica Seles, of tennis fame, originally from Yugoslavia. It was the same with all American Olympians, regardless of origin or race. The triumphant women's gymnastic team included an Asian-American, an African-American, and white girls with names like Miller and Moceanu. The enthusiastic fans were not interested in hyphens, but in Americanness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In its monopoly television coverage of the Olympics, <font size=-1>NBC</font> took this jingoism to absurd extremes. Were people from other nations taking part in these Games? At times it was hard to tell, as the cameras concentrated on the Americans. What was happening in events where Americans were winning no medals? It was impossible to say, for <font size=-1>NBC</font>'s coverage largely ignored them, preferring to show American successes and to devote much air time to sentimental "up-close-and-personal" life stories of American sportsmen and women.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hence one interpretation of the Games, heard among some grumbling foreigners, much as it was the last time America staged the summer Olympics, in Los Angeles in 1984. It is that they bring out the worst in America: arrogance, isolationism, a tendency to turn everything into soap opera. But a moment's reflection suggests a more charitable view.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>NBC</font> was rewarded for its coverage with audiences of as many as 95m people. That is a stunning proportion of the population. It represents one of those rare occasions--the trial of O.J. Simpson is the most recent other example--when much of this continent-sized country is focusing on the same thing, sharing a common experience. In that alone, the Olympics are serving a benign function: they bring a disparate nation together.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is not often that Americans have a good excuse to belt out chants of "<font size=-1>USA</font>, <font size=-1>USA</font>, <font size=-1>USA</font>", as they have done in Atlanta these past two weeks. Along with the chants there are the patriotic clothes and the star-spangled banners, big ones for athletes to drape themselves in or smaller ones sold for fans to wave (or, in the case of Shell, given away with petrol to lure customers to the company's pumps). Soccer-obsessed Europeans and Latin Americans have ample opportunities, thanks to frequent international matches, to express patriotism-through-sport. But America is unusual in that it largely ignores foreign competition in its three most popular sports, American football, baseball and basketball. The pinnacle in these things is not some World Cup, but a purely American World Series or Super Bowl.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Olympics are the big exception. There is virtually no television audience for American athletes between these competitions, but for a few days once every four years the nation watches and cheers en masse. Basketball's "Dream Team" is a complete bore so far as sporting tension is concerned (it can run Olympic rings for boredom around most opposition), but Americans adore it because it represents perfection, a coming-together of the country's very best.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The jingoism would look particularly ridiculous if Americans were not beating the competition very often. But of course they are doing just that. They tower over the rest of the world in the Atlanta medals table.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The last time America was so dominant was in the Los Angeles Olympics, but that was thanks to the Soviet-led boycott. In Seoul in 1988, America came third behind the Soviet Union and East Germany. Four years ago in Barcelona it came behind the just disbanded Soviet Union, whose Olympians competed under the Orwellian name of the "Unified Team". Now, at last, the medals tally truly reflects post-cold-war geodynamics: America as the sole superpower, a few second-rank European powers behind it, China poised to emerge as a 21st-century force.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;America's friends, who think that America's geopolitical strength on the whole makes the world a safer place, should not mind about the jingoism in Atlanta. On the contrary, they should welcome it. For in a small but significant way, such a celebration of Americanness helps to keep the country strong. It is a powerful antidote to the forces of fragmentation that a lot of Americans spend a lot of time worrying about. The worriers fret about "multiculturalism" , about an America in danger of losing its common values and identity. They feel compelled to push legislation through Congress that would make English the official language. In a word, they see a danger of America succumbing to its own sort of Balkanisation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Events in the real Balkans show that it would be foolish to rely too much on displays of sporting loyalty as a reflection of political reality. Serbs, Croats and Muslims were once enthusiastic supporters of Yugoslavia's national soccer and basketball teams. That did not prevent Yugoslavia's murderous collapse.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But America, though it has had its own bloody civil war, is not threatened by such age-old schisms. From time to time it merely needs reminding of the things that hold it together, lest its divisions get out of perspective, and possibly out of hand. Part of the glue is a patriotism capable of transcending colour or creed. The strength of the patriotism that has been on display during the Olympic fortnight, embracing such new Americans as Konstantine Starikovitch, should give comfort to those who worry that America is in danger of coming unstuck.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="ir1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
