<html><head><title>Down the tube</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>London Underground</b></p>
<h1>Down the tube</h1>

<p>LONDON commuters have been fuming in traffic jams caused by a series of day-long strikes by London Underground drivers. They would be fuming all the more if they knew what Fleet Street's finest have failed to tell them: that the drivers' case is as defective as a broken-down train.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Associated Society of Locomotive Engineers and Firemen (<font size=-1>ASLEF</font>), the drivers' main union, blames London Underground. It claims that its management has welshed on a deal it made last year to shorten the drivers' working week from 38.5 to 37.5 hours. <font size=-1>ASLEF</font> has turned down binding arbitration on the grounds that you cannot split the difference between implementing and not implementing a pledge.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They would have a point if there were such a pledge, but there is not. True, last year's agreement said that "a 37.5 hour week shall be introduced during 1996". However, it also said that "this improvement shall be contingent upon appropriate measures being designed and agreed to enhance business performance." No such deal has been struck.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, the real criticism of London Underground is not that it has been too tough, but that it has been too accommodating. The drivers have in fact been offered the shorter hours without the productivity agreement, but only if they accept a pay increase of 2.4% rather than the 3.2% offered to other Underground workers, to help meet the cost. They refused. Talks to resolve the dispute were taking place at the official Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service this week, with a deal for even shorter hours a possibility.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet these are not oppressed workers. They get a basic &#163;24,647 per year for their 38.5-hour weeks compared with under &#163;18,000 earned by the average male manual worker in London. Their biggest grievance, other than having to do a job which combines tedium with stress, seems to be the performance bonuses paid last year to London Underground directors, which ranged up to &#163;24,079 for Denis Tunnicliffe, the managing director. As London Underground has been cutting its costs per train kilometre, he (arguably) earned it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>ASLEF</font> is not the only public-sector union now exercising its quasi-monopoly muscle. On July 30th the national executive committee of the Communication Workers Union turned down a deal made by its officials with the Post Office over the introduction of teamworking to make the service more efficient. Here, too, a series of one-day strikes have disrupted the business just as it is facing increased competition from private operators, foreign postal services, and from the fax and e-mail.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some ministers think the strikes buttress their arguments that both industries should be privatised. Unfortunately a third threatened strike suggests that privatisation is not a total solution.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Train conductors voted on July 30th to strike against privatised rail companies that refused to guarantee them their usual 30-minute "physical-needs" break between journeys, even when their first train arrives late. They had sought for more than 20 years to get the old British Rail to agree this, without success. However, some new train companies, for example Regional Railways North East, have now conceded the point. The unions are using their success with these companies to pressurise the rest--and are hoping that a strike vote will force other employers into line.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These disputes are manna from heaven for the Tories. Mr Major has Ian Lang, his favoured son and trade secretary, working on proposals to clobber such strikers, for inclusion in the Tory election manifesto. One-day walk-outs that impose pain on the public without hitting strikers' pockets may be a target. Unions might even be liable to be sued for damages by employers whose businesses they hit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sensing the danger, Tony Blair, Labour's leader, has called for binding arbitration on the tube strike. But union solidarity dies hard, even in New Labour. Some shadow cabinet members, including John Prescott, his deputy, and Clare Short, his erstwhile transport spokesman, have gone noticeably quiet.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
