<html><head><title>Beaten by Kazakhstan</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Olympics</b></p>
<h1>Beaten by Kazakhstan</h1>

<p>WITH the British Olympics team threatening to turn in its worst performance since Helsinki in 1952, when it won only one gold and 11 medals in all, Britain's politicians indulged in some equally feeble competition of their own: allocating blame for the debacle in Atlanta. On July 30th, John Major invited Dick Palmer, secretary of the British Olympic Association, to meet him after the Games to explain the poor performance. No sooner was the prime minister out of the blocks than Tony Blair, the Labour leader, sprinted past, ordering an urgent inquiry of his own and hinting that this was one more effect of 17 wasted Tory years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Olympics have returned British sport, uplifted briefly by England's strongish showing in the European soccer championship, to its usual doldrums. By August 1st Britain, which finished in the top 15 in every Games since 1952, languished in 31st place in the medals table, below such giants as Belarus, Ethiopia and Kazakhstan. Worse, France had overtaken Britain to take third place in the all-time total of gold medals. Desperate for heroes, the British media adopted Michelle Smith, an Irish swimmer who won three golds, as an honorary Brit. A 400m silver medal for Roger Black was headlined "good as gold".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite Labour's determination to allocate blame, bad luck has a lot to do with Britain's failure. British success has always relied on the heroic feats of a few--it last won more than five golds in 1956, the Games that followed the 1952 disaster--as well as chance, such as America's boycott of the 1980 Moscow Games and the Soviet block's boycott of the 1984 Los Angeles Games. This time, there were few absentees and Britain's stars came a cropper. Neither of its track gold medallists contested their final: Sally Gunnell was injured, Linford Christie disqualified. Several Britons started favourites, but performed poorly, some through injury, others inexplicably.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tony Blair says that he will make Olympic success a "national priority" (along, presumably, with all his other national priorities). In doing so, he will be following in the tradition of such revered leaders as Adolf Hitler and Nicolae Ceausescu.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
