<html><head><title>Tripping out on the Web</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<p><b>Amex and Microsoft</b></p>
<h1>Tripping out on the Web</h1>

<font size=1>NEW YORK</font>
<p>WILL business travellers be willing to plan their worldwide trips on the Internet? American Express and Microsoft hope so. On July 29th the world's biggest software maker unveiled an alliance with the owner of the world's largest travel agency to provide on-line travel services to business travellers via both the Internet and private corporate intranets. The two firms' goal, says Ed Gilligan, president of American Express Corporate Services, is to "reinvent the travel process"--and, presumably, to win a bigger slice of the $145 billion American firms spend on travel each year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;American Express and Microsoft reckon that the key competitive advantage of their system, which should be up and running next year, is that it offers more than on-line airline, hotel and car-rental reservations and information. The system's software will allow firms to impose restrictions (eg, no first-class travel) on employees, to monitor expenses and to ensure that travellers take advantage of negotiated discounts and low fares. All this, says Bill Gates, Microsoft's boss, should "make purchasing travel easier and more cost-effective." Happily, it will also cut American Express's processing costs and allow the firm to reach the desktops of most of America's business travellers. It will ensure that yet more Microsoft software is used on those desktops too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The snag is that, far from reinventing travel booking, American Express and Microsoft are latecomers to a crowded market. In March Travelocity, a Web-based service offering everything from on-line reservations to customised travel guides, was launched by Sabre, the computer-reservations sibling of American Airlines, and Worldview Systems, a joint venture between Ameritech and Random House. Sabre also has a Web-based service aimed at business travellers in the works. Other Web travel services, such as Internet Travel Network, <font size=-1>PC</font>Travel and TravelWeb, abound. And thousands of independent travel agents around the world offer travel and reservation facilities on the Web.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such services, reckon American Express and Microsoft, appeal mostly to leisure travellers who have no use for the extra facilities promised by their new product. And, in any case, both firms have plans for the 11m or so travellers who, according to a survey by <font size=-1>CIC</font> Research, are currently using the Web to search for holidays. The American Express Travel site, aimed at leisure travellers, hit the Web in March; later this year Microsoft launches Expedia, a rival Web-based travel service unrelated to the company's deal with American Express.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The business- and leisure-travel markets do, however, share a key characteristic. In each, would-be travellers tend to shop around for the best deal and best service, and look elsewhere if they are not getting either. With the number of Web travel services soaring, many companies may be reluctant to lock themselves into American Express's offering (or into Microsoft's networking software). And a majority may prefer to leave their itineraries in the hands of a live travel agent.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
