<html><head><title>Nintendo wakes up</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<p><b>Video games</b></p>
<h1>Nintendo wakes up</h1>

<font size=1>TOKYO</font>
<p><b>Aroused from complacency, Nintendo has proved that it can still dazzle youngsters with a whizz-bang games machine. But can it regain leadership of an industry that has changed dramatically?</b></p>

<p>AFTER a month in Japanese stores, Nintendo's new video-game player, the Nintendo 64, is still drawing crowds to gawk at its dazzling 3-<font size=-1>D</font> graphics. The crowds are good news for the Kyoto firm, which has slumped from its dizzying heights in the late 1980s, when it was making more money than all the Hollywood studios put together. But the gawking teenagers are not enough. In the past five years, competition in the video-game industry has grown tougher, and the all-important game-software makers have become rebellious. Nintendo will need more than a hot box to regain its perch.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although the whole of Japan's home-entertainment business was badly bruised by the protracted recession, Nintendo fared worse than most (see <a href="wb2.gif">chart</a>). Its sales slid disastrously two years ago, when the company failed to update its Super Famicom model (called Super <font size=-1>NES</font> overseas), which had been on the shelves since 1990 and could process only 16 bits of data at a time. Sega Enterprises, its Tokyo-based rival, snatched the initiative in late 1994 with a 32-bit game-player called Saturn that provided richer graphics and cleverer stunts. Then Sony entered the fray with an even more exciting 32-bit machine, the PlayStation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite initial prices of around &#165;40,000 ($370) for their new video-game machines, both Sega and Sony have had little difficulty in luring away Nintendo's customers. In the latest financial year, for the first time ever, Sega overtook Nintendo in total sales, ringing up &#165;384 billion during the year ending March 1996. Sega's revenue would have been even greater had it not got itself into a pickle in America, where marketing mistakes led to piles of unsold game machines. As for Sony, the PlayStation is reckoned to have contributed &#165;195 billion to the company's global revenue of &#165;4.6 trillion last year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new Nintendo 64 is the company's comeback bid. It uses a whopping 64-bit microprocessor specially designed by Silicon Graphics, a hot-shot computer workstation maker in California. Video-game addicts swear the wait (the Nintendo 64 should have hit the stores last December) has been worth it. Instead of the usual two-dimensional characters that slide back and forth or up and down, the Nintendo 64 provides fully rounded figures that can turn on their heels, rotating through 180-degrees on screen like animated characters in a cartoon film. Advanced "ray-tracing" tricks used in military simulators and engineering workstations add to the realism by providing proper highlighting, reflections and shadows. In prelaunch trials, the 64-bit version of Nintendo's classic game, Super Mario, left even hardened teenagers agog.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With preordering rampant and queues outside the stores, some 300,000 Nintendo 64 machines were snapped up by eager addicts on the first day. Over the past month, Nintendo has sold 800,000 of its new &#165;25,000 toys. Industry-watchers expect the company to sell 5m-6m by next March, by when they will have been launched in America and Europe as well.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile, most observers believe that Sega and Sony will be hard-pressed to ship 3m apiece of their top-of-the-line game machines this year, despite aggressive price cuts. Sony slashed the retail price of its PlayStation from &#165;24,800 to &#165;19,800 (from $299 to $199 in the United States) in mid-May, following Nintendo's new product announcement. Sega promptly followed suit. Within a year or so, Nintendo will also have to drop the price of its 64-bit machines to below &#165;20,000--the most the average family is ready to pay for yet another electronic gizmo. The battle for the trigger-fingers of 14-year-olds everywhere is set to become even more brutal.
</p><p><b>Now, what will it play?</b> </b>
<br>Some of the smallest video-game makers, such as <font size=-1>NEC</font> and Sanyo, may have to drop out. It will be tough even for Sony and Sega. Both companies are thought to be losing money on each of the 32-bit machines they sell, but making it up with royalties from sales of games that run on them--a razor-and-blades model common in the industry. Nintendo will have to adopt the same policy, but software will be more than just a source of profit for the Nintendo 64. It needs plenty of popular games to show off the machine's capabilities: it was launched with just three. And Nintendo will have to sell them at lower prices, too. The Nintendo 64's first games were priced at around &#165;9,800 compared with &#165;5,800 for top-selling Sony and Sega games.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nintendo can create some of these games itself, but like other game-machine makers, it counts on independent software companies for most of its titles. Winning the best of them for the Nintendo 64 will be harder than it was with Nintendo's first hit machines, for three reasons.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first is that writing clever software that exploits the full features of Nintendo's powerful new game-machine is horrendously complex. Some 150 programmers were needed just to produce the latest version of a popular role-playing game, Final Fantasy, for Sony's PlayStation. Nintendo's new 64-bit machine is going to require bigger programming teams. On top of that, the company will have to rebuild its chain of software suppliers. Tired of waiting for the Nintendo 64 to arrive, a number of independent software houses--Namco and Square, in particular--started churning out titles for Sony's PlayStation instead.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Second, game-makers have an even bigger rival for their affections: the <font size=-1>PC</font>. When Nintendo's first machines came out, the <font size=-1>PC</font> was mostly a business machine, without the sound and graphics of dedicated games boxes. But today's multimedia <font size=-1>PC</font>s are a fair match for the games machines and, with more than 30m of them in homes, a much larger potential market for software firms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Finally, Nintendo has to overcome its reputation for mistreating independent software firms with take-it-or-leave-it terms and steep royalties. Releasing a hot new machine was essential for Nintendo's survival--and certainly improves its chances with the software makers. But the battle to regain its dominance has only just begun.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
