<html><head><title>Cloning California</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Cloning California</h1>

<font size=1>TOKYO</font>
<p>WHY are there so few bright little software firms and other high-tech start-ups in Japan? Nintendo, Sega and the other video-game firms say the dearth of "code shops", capable of turning out exciting new video games, crimps their business plans. Many look longingly at California, where hundreds of new software and multimedia firms spring up each year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Officials at the Ministry of International Trade and Industry (<font size=-1>MITI</font>) in Tokyo think they have an answer. Henceforth, fledgling Japanese firms hoping to go public on the back of a wizard new product will be allowed to offer stock options to their employees. The aim is to let unlisted venture businesses in Japan offer their staff American-style rewards for all their long hours of little pay while the company is finding its feet.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On July 15th the first of seven fledgling firms given the go-ahead by <font size=-1>MITI</font> handed two of its 16 employees contracts that allow them to buy equity at a given price in five years' time. <font size=-1>LTEL</font>, a maker of infra-red data-communications equipment in Omiya, north-west of Tokyo, granted its two star employees the right to acquire 10-20 shares in the company, with a par value of &#165;50,000 ($468), for &#165;250,000 apiece. If, after going public in five years' time, the company's share price exceeds the option price, the employees will be free to buy the stock at a discount and sell it for a profit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While common in America and elsewhere, such ways of motivating top-notch employees have been rare in Japan. Sony grabbed the headlines last year when it cleverly circumvented regulations by offering top executives a special incentive plan linked to the company's share price. By issuing &#165;1 billion of warrant bonds and then stripping the warrants (options to buy shares in future at a given price) from the bonds and handing them to the staff, Sony has been able to link executive remuneration to the company's overall performance. Konami, one of Japan's leading video-game makers, swiftly followed suit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In response to such gimmickry, <font size=-1>MITI</font> has revised Japan's commercial code. The time allowed for stock options to be exercised has been changed from six months to ten years. Taxation is now deferred until the option is exercised; it is then reduced by taxing the profit as capital gain rather than as straight income. For now, only privately held companies qualify for the scheme; and no more than a third of their outstanding shares can be offered to the staff as options.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All told, <font size=-1>MITI</font> expects to grant some 40-50 small, high-tech firms the right to issue stock options to staff by the end of the year. It has printed 1m brochures explaining the scheme and advertised it widely on television and in the press. Even if less than 1% of those brochures spark the founders of little start-ups into action, Japan could be on the way to cloning California.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
