<html><head><title>Harder than a garden party</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/mo.gif"  alt="Moreover">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Harder than a garden party</h1>

<font size=1>ATLANTA</font>

<p>IF ONLY the rest of the Olympics could have been as carefree as the bit that took place, not in Atlanta, nor even in Georgia, but across the state line in Tennessee. The Ocoee river, in the Cherokee National Forest, was the venue for the whitewater canoeing. It was a delight.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the school-bus shuttle there, through lush, rolling country and up the lovely river valley, Ron from Chattanooga introduced himself as "your shuttle ambassador" and described how the area had been an ecological disaster. Sulphur burned during the processing of copper mined upstream from the 1840s had produced acid rain, killing river life and leaving 50 square miles of barren moonscape. But conservation efforts in recent years had brought the vegetation back, and now $27m had been spent to shape a slalom course out of the natural flow of the river (previous Olympic courses were entirely artificial). Canoeists thought it among the finest in the world.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In these largely private-sector Olympics, here was something strangely unfashionable: a small triumph of state enterprise, masterminded by that child of the New Deal, the Tennessee Valley Authority, and by the United States Forest Service. It was also charming. On their way to their seats, spectators strolled past banjo-players, stopped at exhibits by Cherokee Indians and Tennessee craftsmen, and were shown a bald eagle. The biggest struggle at Ocoee was, as it should be, that between the Olympic competitors paddling furiously through "Humongous", "Slam Dunk" and other colourfully named rapids.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Back in Georgia, Atlanta was struggling with the humongous scale of the Games, and with the aftermath of an atrocity. The deadly pipe bomb planted in the Centennial Olympic Park, the main mingling area for Olympic visitors, was especially cruel because it came just as Atlanta was beginning to look beyond the troubles of transport and technology that had plagued the first week of the Games. There had been stories of lost buses, stranded athletes, an endurance-test subway system--and of <font size=-1>IBM</font>'s state-of-the-art information service that at times seemed a step back from the carrier pigeon. The organising body's initials, <font size=-1>ACOG</font>, stand for Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games. But mocking and disappointed members of the foreign press quickly suggested an alternative: Atlanta Couldn't Organise a Garden party.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Olympic spirit is resilient, however. American television specialised in schmaltzy profiles of Olympians who had overcome adversity--depression, injury, poverty, war, for example--to achieve greatness. If the competitors could triumph over their troubles, why not the Games themselves? Before and (defiantly) after the bomb people flocked to Atlanta to enjoy themselves, and by and large they succeeded. They enjoyed just being there, in the crowded streets lined with vendors of food and memorabilia. The Olympic sports provided plenty to cherish, including the fastest-ever 100-metre sprint, by Donovan Bailey of Canada.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By far the most popular off-track sport in Atlanta was collecting and trading commemorative pins, which came in perhaps 2,000 varieties and constituted a mini-economy of their own. Pins were sold for cash, exchanged for goodwill and bartered for other pins or even for Olympic tickets and hotel rooms. Limited-edition "Day Eight" pins soared in value thanks to the bomb, though since the bomb went off at 1:25 in the morning there was some dispute over whether the "Day Nine" pin should not in fact be the hot number.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ticket sales for the Olympic events were brisk, through both official and unofficial channels. (A consolation for Britons disappointed at their country's paltry tally of medals: the British are world-class scalpers, to judge by the confident touts with lots of international experience operating in teams along Atlanta's main street.) So the organisers were happy, because higher-than-expected ticket sales could help them end up in the black. And the sponsors were happy, because higher-than-expected American television audiences gave them value for their advertising money.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And yet these, the biggest-ever Olympics, would not have been the best even without the security lapses and the organisational glitches. Atlanta is no match for the architectural splendour of Barcelona, which held the Games four years ago, or for the sensational setting of Sydney, which will play host four years hence. It is rich in history, but it is physically dull, and has been sadly under-enhanced by the building for the Games. A brand-new stadium will remain, but the almost-new stadium next to it will be torn down.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>IBM</font> computer system had no trouble producing for this correspondent its official descriptions of past Olympics. The future record of Atlanta does not deserve to be as grim as that for Munich in 1972 ("what began as the Games of hope and harmony ended as the Games of terror and tragedy."). It is also hard to imagine Atlanta being remembered with such warmth as Barcelona, which "represented everything the Games were intended to be...joyful, beautiful, dramatic and boycott-free." These Games were a struggle. But there is nowhere better than Atlanta, city of Martin Luther King, to turn a struggle into a dream.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
