<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><h2>Bearish</h2>
<p><p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>Tokyo shares</b> had their worst one-day fall this year, pulling the Nikkei average below 21,000 for the first time in four months. Investors continued to fret about a possible interest-rate rise in Japan and about a still-jumpy Wall Street, which also dragged down European and Asian bourses.
<p>The Bank of England announced changes in the way it will <b>regulate banks</b>, after recommendations made by Arthur Andersen, a consultancy firm. It will recruit more supervisors and technical experts, and is developing new ways of monitoring the risks that banks take. The &#163;35m ($54m) it spends each year on supervision could increase by up to 25%. The bank was criticised last year for its failure to prevent the collapse of Barings bank.
<p>Continuing its process of deregulating <b>Germany's financial system</b>, the government announced plans to encourage more institutional investors into the stockmarket. Insurance companies will be able to invest much more of their insured revenue in stocks, the period during which investors can sue firms over the contents of prospectuses will be slashed, and mutual funds will get more issuing rights.
<p>An unexpected rise in personal bankruptcies and late or non-payment of <b>credit-card bills </b>in America has prompted issuers to stop throwing money at people. In the first quarter 3.53% of bills were unpaid for two or more months, a 15-year high, with the picture worsening in the second quarter.</p>
<p><h2>Big deal</h2></p>
<p><p>With no white knight in sight, <b>Docks de France</b> succumbed to a sweetened FFr19.6 billion ($3.9 billion) offer from a rival supermarket group, <b>Auchan</b>, putting the new force in fifth place among distributors. Auchan's hostile takeover, a rarity in France, was a response to legislation curbing the number of hypermarkets and therefore retailers' potential for growth.
<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Profits and revenues soared at the world's biggest software maker. <b>Microsoft</b> revealed a 52% leap in fourth-quarter net income to $559m on sales up 39% to $2.26 billion, giving a record profit for the year of $2.2 billion, up from $1.45 billion a year earlier. But even Microsoft could not stop Wall Street, bearish on technology stocks and much else, from clipping its share price.
<p>In a $2.1 billion deal, plus assumed debt, Houston-based <b>Enron</b> added an electricity seller to its natural-gas and wholesale-electricity interests with the purchase of <b>Portland General</b>, positioning Enron to tap the giant California market. The new concern will be America's biggest gas and electric utility.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Maybe it's still peace: an <b>Egyptian-Israeli</b> <b>consortium</b>, Midor, signed a $1.2 billion contract to build an oil refinery at the Egyptian port of Alexandria. Israel's Merhav Group and the Egyptian General Petroleum Group formed the venture.
<p><b>Perrier</b> cancelled a poster campaign in Belgium after complaints from a women's lobby group. The advertisement for the bottled water featured a drawing of women with only the drinks company's bottle caps covering their nipples.
<p>The European Space Agency will not launch its next <b>Ariane 5</b> rocket until the middle of next year, heavily delaying a project aimed at retaining a lead in the commercial space-transport industry. The news came as an inquiry decided that faulty software caused the crash of the first Ariane 5 rocket last month.
<p>Shareholders approved a &#163;73.6m ($114.4m) rescue package for <b>Costain Group</b>, a British construction group which said a rejection of the plan would have meant receivership. But Costain's plans were later put in doubt after Lonrho, a British conglomerate, withdrew from the purchase of Costain's American coal operations.
<p><b>Rolls-Royce</b> is to shed two unprofitable power-generating units to concentrate on its core aerospace operations. Shaking off Parsons Power Generation Systems and International Combustion could cost &#163;248m ($385m), but investors were happy.
<p>Saks Holdings, parent of Saks Fifth Avenue, and Isetan, a Japanese department-store chain, are considering a restructuring of <b>Barney's</b> that would give Saks control of the upmarket clothing chain. Isetan, Barney's partner until a bust-up in January which led to Barney's filing for chapter 11 protection from creditors, would manage the property assets.</p>
<p><h2>A family business</h2></p>
<p><p>A new car project was launched by an Indonesian conglomerate, <b> Bimantara</b>, in co-operation with <b>Hyundai </b>of South Korea. The project will compete with the "national" car project of Timor Putra Nasional, which has secured exclusive tax privileges. Timor is owned by President Suharto's son, Hutomo ("Tommy") Mandala. Bimantara is also well connected. It is controlled by Tommy's elder brother, Bambang Trihatmodjo.
<p>The Clinton administration rejected a call from six American airlines to cool <b>"open skies" talks</b> with Britain until America's Justice Department has finished investigating the planned alliance between British Airways and American Airlines. The airlines reckon the British government will make only token concessions on slots for foreign carriers at Heathrow.
<p><p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
