<html><head><title>Cut and grow--hope and woe</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width=105 height=26  alt="Europe">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Cut and grow--hope and woe</h1>
<p><b>Europe's economies are trapped between a need to cut and a need to grow. Without easier money from their central banks, it will be hard to do both</b></p>

<p>IN A political Olympic Games, it would be the most gruelling event: chopping budget deficits at a time when economies are wobbly, in pursuit of a prize that most people are not sure they want. The prize is European economic and monetary union (<font size=-1>EMU</font>), and the hot-heads chasing it are the politicians running most European Union countries. Nobody is sure they will reach their goal of introducing a single European currency, the euro, in 1999, though the odds may be marginally in favour. But either way, will the exercise pep their economies up or cripple them?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the face of it, the answer depends largely on central banks, which control short-term interest rates and influence the value of currencies. They are being unhelpful. On July 25th Germany's Bundesank missed a chance to cut interest rates before breaking for its summer holiday. Two days earlier the Bank of Italy, one of the toughest of Europe's big central banks, sliced its benchmark discount rate by three-quarters of a point to 8.25%. Industrialists had wanted a bigger cut. Without monetary medicine, many people, politicians especially, argue that Europe will not recover from its economic malaise.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the malaise is not a monetary one. It is deeper-seated than that. Although the economies of continental Europe differ, most are still suffering from policies, some now abandoned, that had for years encouraged an expansion of the state at the expense of private industry. That preference taints nearly every economic endeavour. Generous welfare programmes, financed mainly through payroll taxes, raise the cost of labour and impede job-creation. High public borrowing keeps interest rates up and discourages private investment. And so on.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The vagaries of the business cycle sometimes mask the problem. That happened in 1990, when unification triggered a 2.5-year boom in Germany. It may be about to happen again. Although forecasts are unusually divergent, most predict that Germany and France, Europe's two biggest economies, are about to recover from a mini-recession that took hold at the end of last year. Italy, the equal third-biggest (alongside Britain), may be about to slide into one. But it too should bounce back next year, while Britain is looking quite perky.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet recovery may not bring full relief. A pick-up in growth next year will not banish Europe's familiar plagues: an average unemployment rate that is double America's and more than three times Japan's; idle factories and offices and a reluctance to build new ones. By letting factories dawdle and by under-employing its people, Europe could continue to expand at rates well below its potential for non-inflationary growth. Worse, potential output growth may be falling. German investment in machinery and equipment has dropped.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rather than succumb to the temptation to coddle their sickly economies, politicians are wielding a whip. The Maastricht treaty, which tells countries that want to join <font size=-1>EMU</font> in the first wave to cut their public-sector deficits to no more than 3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> next year, is the biggest reason for this brutality. The first-round candidates include Germany, France, the three Benelux countries, Austria, Ireland and Finland. Italy and Spain are hopeful, but hobbling; Britain and Denmark remain undecided.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The aspirants promise to impose unprecedented fiscal austerity. Germany's conservative government proposes to cut DM50 billion ($34 billion) from the projected public-sector deficit next year. Even after trade unions and opposition votes water it down, the savings package will not fall far short of 1% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>. France is bracing for its first cut in real government spending, while Italy promises to shrink its public-sector deficit from 7.2% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> last year to 4.4% in 1997. The <font size=-1>OECD</font> frets that the Europe-wide effort to rein in deficits could in the short run be a "significant negative influence" on growth.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is not the only dampener. Employers are squeezing wages, either to curb inflation, as Italy has done, or to boost employment, as in Germany, the Netherlands, Finland and Denmark. Company restructuring, which in Germany alone has thrown another 400,000 people out of work since last summer, is another drag on growth. So consumer spending is unlikely to give European economies a big lift.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is nerve-racking for politicians, especially France's president, Jacques Chirac, and Germany's chancellor, Helmut Kohl, who both face parliamentary elections in 1998. They would normally be thinking up electoral bribes, not demanding sacrifices. In a Bastille Day outburst, Mr Chirac demanded lower interest rates in place of the usual handouts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Central banks--the Bundesbank in particular--are apparently reluctant to grant Mr Chirac his wish immediately. At first glance this looks odd. Inflation looks under control. It is less than 2% in Germany and just above in France. Even in inflation-prone Italy it has apparently dipped below 4%. On a continent stuffed with jobless workers and factories at low-speed, there is little immediate threat that it will come roaring back. The Bundesbank admitted that the high level of monetary growth in Germany does not pose much threat of inflation. What makes its stubbornness on rates more surprising is that Hans Tietmeyer, the Bundesbank's president, so clearly wants the dollar up and--by implication--the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark down. He told a German newspaper this week he sees "no reason" why the dollar should not beat its recent highs against the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So why did the Bundesbank refuse to cut rates after raising expectations that it would? One reason may be the recovery most economists are expecting in the German economy. Another may be that central bankers are reluctant to cut rates based on mere promises by politicians. Mr Chirac has yet to carry out his plans to spend less. And the German budget savings package will not be wrapped up until autumn. It is, after all, the mix of fiscal and monetary policy that matters, not the mere level of interest rates.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This points to two risks facing hopes of a revival prompted by looser monetary policy. The first is that the policy mix could again go awry, either before or after <font size=-1>EMU</font>. Some economists argue that monetary policy will be too tight. But the risk is as great that, after monetary union, governments could return to their spendthrift ways--especially if the rules are bent to let in such over-spenders as Italy and Spain. Hence German efforts to tighten <font size=-1>EMU</font>'s fiscal rules.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The other risk is that the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark and currencies allied to it will go on getting stronger. The recent jitters on America's stockmarket coupled with the Bundesbank's refusal to cut rates helped spark a rise in the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark against the dollar from DM1.55 in May to its current level of DM1.48. Hard evidence of recovery in Europe could trigger another rise in the continent's currencies, blunting that recovery. Italy has already discovered that the foreign exchanges reward fiscal virtue by buying a country's currency--which is one reason why the Italian economy is slowing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some European leaders must be hoping that the euro will solve this conundrum. In theory, a European currency less prone to over-valuation than the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark could be a boon for the long-suffering <font size=-1>D</font>-mark zone, generating rather faster economic growth. But there are dangers ahead. One is that the euro might turn out to be too strong, especially if it lures foreign-exchange reserves to switch out of the dollar. Another, however, is that the markets may view the euro as fragile, leading Europe's future central bank to prove itself by pushing up interest rates. In either case, politicians who struggled to cross the Maastricht finish line might ask why they bothered.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838422000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
