<html><head><title>Cheap cuts</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Politics</b></p>
<h1>Cheap cuts</h1>

<p>IN POLITICS as in life, those who pretend to be what they are not eventually get rumbled. This is now the single biggest threat to the career of John Redwood, a right-wing Conservative who resigned from the cabinet to fight John Major in last summer's leadership election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Redwood is clever, a former fellow of All Souls who as head of Lady Thatcher's policy unit in 1983-85 forced through privatisation by weight of logic. He has shown prodigious stamina in his undeclared campaign to succeed Mr Major. Yet his populist pronouncements this month on public spending cuts--three sets, in the Commons, <i>The Times </i>and the <i>Evening Standard</i>, all disconcertingly different in detail--reveal, at best, muddled thinking.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Redwood, like most voters, wants the state to tax less and spend less. Again like voters, he also wants to "have a first-class education service, defence, law and order policies and a health service, and to ensure they get reasonable increases." He affects to square the circle by arguing that &#163;7 billion can be cut from planned spending in 1997-98 without damaging any of these things.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, under scrutiny, his cuts turn out to be illusory. First, he wants to take &#163;2.5 billion off the chancellor's original reserve of &#163;5 billion set aside in his 1995 budget for unexpected spending in 1997-98. Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, is likely do this when he resets the reserve in his November 1996 budget, as all chancellors provide less for the year ahead than for two years ahead. But this is not a saving, since the government is already committed to spending all of the &#163;5 billion, including at least &#163;2 billion for agriculture for its anti-<font size=-1>BSE</font> slaughter programme.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Redwood seeks to score a further &#163;2.5 billion by cuts achieved because inflation is 0.9% lower than the government expected, meaning that each pound of spending buys more. Mr Clarke is trying to do this too, but it is not easy. Many government contracts with the private sector have already been signed at a fixed price. They cannot be cancelled just because that price now looks more attractive, any more than the contractors could have cancelled them had inflation turned out faster than expected. Moreover, lower inflation affects both sides of the accounts, since the lower prices are, the lower is the revenue from <font size=-1>VAT</font>. No room for tax cuts here.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thirdly, he wants to save &#163;500m by cutting grants to the Housing Corporation, which provides public housing for low rent. But, as most tenants are not well off, higher rents would simply increase what the state pays out in housing benefit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Finally, Mr Redwood wants to cut "bureaucracy" and increase privatisation to yield another &#163;1.5 billion in savings. So do ministers. But they have to answer questions on which Mr Redwood is curiously silent. What is it that they are not selling which they should sell? Is it right to use a one-off receipt from asset sales to finance tax cuts that go on from year to year? What bureaucrats should they sack? What functions, if any, should go with them?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government's target for public spending, reaffirmed by the cabinet on July 18th, is tough stuff. It implies a virtual freeze in real terms from 1994-95 to 1997-98. It has forced the cabinet to freeze public-sector pay for a fourth successive year. To hit the target in an election year would be an achievement. To beat it would be a triumph, requiring far more controversial cuts than those Mr Redwood suggests.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Economists have taught us that there is no such thing as a free lunch. Serious politicians should teach a second lesson: that there is no such thing as a painless cut. The right has a case to argue for real cuts, achieved by cutting middle-class benefits such as child benefit and by privatising much of the welfare state. But the gain, lower taxes, cannot be achieved without pain. For Mr Redwood's country, and, in the long term for him personally, honesty would be the best policy.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838422000,iss">Search</a>
