<html><head><title>Non-jobs for the boys</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Non-jobs for the boys</h1>
<p>NO DISRESPECT to Phillip Oppenheim, the perky little minister appointed by John Major to the Treasury in his July 23rd mini-reshuffle, but he should not have got the job--for the simple reason that there isn't one. The three junior ministers at the Treasury, David Heathcoat-Amory, who resigned over the European single currency on July 22nd, Michael Jack and Angela Knight had at most two jobs-worth of work. Mr Heathcoat-Amory filled in his spare time penning the anti-Euro pamphlet which he quit to publish.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;You might have thought that Mr Major would by now have got the point that junior ministers are a mixed blessing. He has wasted time this summer trying to persuade Mr Heathcoat-Amory (unsuccessfully) and the foreign office minister, David Davis (successfully) not to quit, because of the political damage that ministerial resignations do the government. If they had not held office, their views on matters European need not have detained him. As it is, more juniors may quit over the months ahead, to establish their claims for preferment under a different leader in opposition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet Mr Major remains addicted to junior ministers. Praise be, he cut the industry department from seven to six, though what even six do in a government that prides itself on leaving industry alone is a mystery. But the Foreign Office, which lost one post in last year's reshuffle, has since grabbed it back. Even excluding the 14 whips, 51 Tory <font size=-1>MP</font>s outside the cabinet now hold junior jobs, practically exhausting the ration of ministerial salaries that Mr Major is permitted by law to pay. There are 5% more junior ministers today than there were a decade ago.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If ever there was a time for a cut, it was this year. Ahead of the election, government business is minimal. Junior ministers also have less to do because they have fewer civil servants to supervise. Mr Major cannot even pretend he keeps them for training as potential cabinet appointees. Although every cabinet minister today, save Lord Mackay, first served as a junior minister, most junior ministers will not make cabinet. According to Kevin Theakston of Leeds University, 60% of the lowlier junior ministers are aged 45 or over, too old to have any real hope of making cabinet even in the unlikely event that the Tories win again.



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838422000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
