<html><head><title>Whose fault?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Ministers and Parliament</b></p>
<h1>Whose fault?</h1>

<p>A NEW code governing the way that ministers treat Parliament will be proposed by the all-party parliamentary Select Committee on Public Service in a report due out on July 30th. The code would lay down for the first time precisely what Parliament expects of ministers in terms of frank answers to questions and disclosure of information. Crucially, its wording will be decided by <font size=-1>MP</font>s, reducing the scope for the government to wriggle out of its demands by holding back information.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The code would supplement the government's own "Questions of Procedure for Ministers". It is Parliament's answer to Sir Richard Scott's report into the sale of arms to Iraq, which complained that ministerial accountability had been undermined because assorted ministers answered questions in ways that misled Parliament. Sir Richard blaming particular civil servants for drafting the misleading answers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Under the doctrine of ministerial accountability, ministers are answerable to Parliament not only for their own actions but for those of their civil servants. Sir Richard, by blaming civil servants as well as ministers, threw doubt on the viability of this convention.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some radical critics of the doctrine who gave evidence to the committee believe that it should be amended, so that civil servants, in some circumstances, answer directly to Parliament for what they have done. However, the committee, which is chaired by Giles Radice, a Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>, regards its proposal as a sensible "half-way house" between the status quo and changes that would mean bigger reforms in the constitutional convention.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The committee canvassed the code with two ministers, Tony Newton and Roger Freeman, when they appeared before it on July 17th. They made sceptical noises but did not entirely reject it. Mr Radice has been here before: the government was at first equally sceptical of his proposal for a code of Civil Service conduct, only to adopt it in 1995.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The committee's deliberations centred on the modern interpretation of the doctrine of ministerial responsibility. Advanced by Sir Robin Butler, the cabinet secretary, it draws a distinction between accountability as a constitutional burden that rests on the shoulders of ministers and cannot be set aside, and responsibility, which can be delegated to officials. If something goes wrong, it is not always necessary for the minister to take the blame. It is however necessary for him to sort it out, at least to Parliament's satisfaction.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This new orthodoxy has its attractions for all parties. Ministers like it because it gives them opportunities to shift blame on to officials, who are debarred from arguing publicly with them. A recent example was Michael Howard's sacking of Derek Lewis, the head of the Prison Service. Parliament likes it, because it can preserve the illusion that it can control the executive, summoning its highest representatives to account before it. Many old-guard civil servants like it because it provides a protecting veil, behind which they can as before exercise private power without responsibility.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Freeman, the minister responsible for the civil service, was roused to rare passion in defending the doctrine in his statement on July 17th. He said that diminution of the doctrine would be "giving unelected officials the political influence that can only be earned in a parliamentary democracy through election. Elected ministers would be eliminated from the accountability loop. I believe that the inevitable outcome would be the politicisation of the civil service."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This would be plausible if elected ministers were truly accountable now; but in practice they are not. When a minister is under pressure in the Commons, what matters is not whether he is doing his job properly, but whether the whips can arm-twist his party colleagues to back him. William Waldegrave, the minister in the dock after the Scott report, survived because the Tories in the Commons voted that he should, for reasons that had nothing to do with the merits of the case.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many civil servants find the present rules hard to live with. What do you do if the minister for whom you work asks you to draft a parliamentary answer in terms you regard as misleading? What if he seeks to transfer blame to you, as the home secretary did in the Lewis case? Elizabeth Symons, general secretary of the First Division Association, the top civil servants' union, wants the doctrine to be changed so that officials can defend themselves.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is one clear precedent for making civil servants more directly accountable to Parliament. Before the Public Accounts Committee, permanent secretaries are themselves responsible for what they say about the propriety of their departments' expenditure. The Pergau dam scandal broke in 1991 when Sir Tim Lankester, permanent secretary of the Overseas Development Agency, had formally warned ministers that spending aid money to secure arms exports to Malaysia was indefensible.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That was a triumph for accountability, but a severe blow to the government, which had hoped to hush up the deal. That may explain why ministers want no further change in the doctrine.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The argument will not end with the publication of the committee's report. An incoming Labour government, committed to constitutional change, may be less conservative than the present administration. Meanwhile Sir Robin Butler, Whitehall's most powerful constitutional conservative, retires at the end of 1997.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838422000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
</p>
