<html><head><title>A wafer-thin case</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Semiconductor trade</b></p>
<h1>A wafer-thin case</h1>

<p>FEW things in business move as fast as the semiconductor industry. Every couple of years it produces some new, cost-slashing item of wizardry. Although its sales are stalling this year, they almost tripled in the past five years (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>). Yet even in such a zippy industry, trade politics evolves as slowly as ever. Ten years ago America browbeat Japan into accepting a semiconductor trade deal. A second agreement, signed in 1991, is due to expire on July 31st. That is now the deadline for a new deal into which the Americans are trying to push the reluctant Japanese.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The best outcome for trade, although an improbable one, would be for the whole agreement to be torn up. Ostensibly, its aim was to open the Japanese market; but its effect was to bully the Japanese government into reserving some of the country's chip market for foreigners. That has helped both American and Japanese firms: carve up the market, and there is less need to compete.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Under the 1986 deal the Japanese government promised to try to push foreign chip makers' share of the Japanese market up from 8% to around 20%, a pledge they made again in 1991. Since the fourth quarter of 1993, Japan has hit the target consistently; in the first quarter of this year foreign firms' slice topped 30%, of which American companies accounted for about two-thirds. At the same time, the agreement has fostered plenty of co-operation between American and Japanese chip makers: several joint ventures have been started since 1991.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite this, the Americans are in no mood to call it quits.They worry that with no deal at all, their share of the market may slip back. American officials say that foreigners' penetration of the market is recent, and borne on the past few years' surge in demand for semiconductors; it may prove fragile, now that demand has turned down and many producers are left with excess capacity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The American government insists that it no longer wants anything as crude as a numerical target. Nevertheless, it says that both governments should continue to "monitor" the Japanese market and to publish market-share figures. The Japanese suspect, probably rightly, that this will amount to pretty much the same thing as a target: a sharp drop in American sales would surely provoke howls of protest.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until a few weeks ago, the Japanese were insisting that governments should at long last leave the industry alone. Lately, though, they have softened a little. They want to kick the whole thing into two grand talking shops--one, the "Global Government Forum", for bureaucrats, and the other, the "World Semiconductor Council", for companies. Both would be open to the European Union and other chip-making countries. The Americans, although they reacted sniffily at first, now say this "could be workable"--provided that their worries about monitoring are sorted out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of this suggests that a traditional trade-policy fudge will probably be served up when officials from the two sides are due to meet in Vancouver, Canada, on July 28th. (By then, being ambitious fellows, they hope to have sorted out another dispute, over a 1994 pact on insurance.) The Americans will be able to claim that they can keep an eye on the Japanese; the Japanese, that they have once again stood up to the Americans. And consumers? Well, what did they ever have to do with it?


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838422000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="wb2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
