<html><head><title></title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

TECHNOLOGY BRIEF<br>
<h2>The final frontier</h2><p><b>Why tart up the old telephone networks when you can bypass them by satellite? This is the last of our briefs on access to the Internet. The box compares the rival technologies</b></p>

<p>BILL GATES and Craig McCaw have a dream. The founders, respectively, of Microsoft and McCaw Cellular (now part of <font size=-1>AT&T</font>) want to swathe the earth with satellites--840 of them. The name of their dream is Teledesic, and if it came true it would bring cyberspace to outer space--providing direct satellite links to personal computers and freeing them from the constraints that affect telephony, cable television and even wireless transmission.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Satellites have been part of the world's telephone and television networks for decades. Some carry calls over oceans. Others broadcast pictures directly to millions of viewers. But as they stand, neither sort is quite right for the Internet, which requires individual, two-way and preferably high-speed ("broadband") connections.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Combining all three requirements is difficult. Over the past decade, satellite companies have been preparing to extend cellular telephony to space. Four projects--Globalstar, <font size=-1>ICO</font>, Iridium and Odyssey--plan to launch satellite networks to provide global telephone services. Such networks are "individual" and "two-way", but hardly "broadband". To carry lots of calls, they give each little room: most carry data no faster than the 2,400 bits per second (bps) modems of a decade ago (see <a href="st1.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In contrast, broadcast satellites like those used for digital television have plenty of bandwidth, but at the cost of individual channels and two-way communications. They simply beam one massive data stream over an area as big as a continent. Hughes Network Systems uses a few tricks to make this one-way flood imitate a two-way personal Internet connection. With Direct<font size=-1>PC</font>, its Internet service, subscribers send data requests over their regular telephone lines. Hughes routes the responses to its control centre, which codes them so that a subscriber's <font size=-1>PC</font> can recognise them as its own, and then sends them up to a satellite for broadcasting.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Leasing only one satellite channel in America (similar services will soon be offered in Europe and Canada) Hughes has just 12m bps of bandwidth to serve the entire country--about as much as cable <font size=-1>TV</font> networks plan to distribute between 300 homes. Hughes limits each subscriber's connection to 400,000 bps, but even so it can handle only a few hundred users simultaneously (only a tiny fraction of its 2,000 subscribers use the service at any one time). Hughes can lease more satellite capacity if needed, but broadcasting data to an entire country for the sake of a single user will never be the most efficient way to do things.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the ultimate in Internet surfing, a different sort of satellite network is needed. Most communications satellites are parked 36,000km (22,500 miles) above the earth--the height at which their orbits take 24 hours and thus match the planet's rotation. From this lofty eyrie, hovering over the same spot, individual machines can communicate with large areas of land.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Gates's and Mr McCaw's flock will fly lower (at around 700km) and faster than this. With enough satellites, one will always be overhead when necessary. Each satellite will be like a cell in a cellphone network, except that the cells can move as well as the callers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The advantage of this is broadbandedness. Each satellite can devote all its capacity to the relatively few users beneath it. Teledesic's cells will be 53km across, small enough to keep the number of users in each to a manageable level. The network aims to provide 18 simultaneous 1.5m bps Internet links in each cell, and 20,000 worldwide. And because the satellites are so close to earth, they avoid the half-second delays that are the price of the lofty orbits required by Direct<font size=-1>PC</font> and its proposed competitors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even so, plenty of experts are sceptical. No one has ever built satellites with off-the-shelf parts as Teledesic plans to do. Nor have so many satellites been put into orbit so quickly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The plan is to have the network operating by 2002. This would mean launching all 840 satellites in two years--more than the rest of the world's launches combined. Add in an orbit full of dangerous space debris, and the complexities of passing signals from one satellite to another as the first goes out of range, and it is easy to see how Teledesic might fail.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But if the technology works, a market for Teledesic's "Internet in the sky" should be there. New Yorkers and Londoners may be able to wallow in the abundant data of their own fibre-optic cables in a few years' time, but it will be a while before many others can do the same. Counting on traditional telecommunications to be inadequate for the Internet in most parts of the world is one of the safest bets around.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838422000,iss">Search</a>
