<html><head><title>Victor ludorum</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h4>LEXINGTON</h4><br><h1>Victor ludorum</h1>


<p>HERE is a seasonal riddle. It happens once every four years, features a marathon race and is watched by the whole
world. What is it? (Or, as they say in Atlanta, referring to the peculiar lizard-like mascot of the Games, What Izzy?)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If your answer is the Olympic Games, you are right. If, on the other hand, your answer is the American presidential election, you are also right. This year the twain are, inevitably, intertwined. The Olympic Games may now be post-cold-war. But they are not, never have been and probably never will be even remotely post-political.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;True, the boycotts that kept the Americans from Moscow in 1980 and the Russians from Los Angeles in 1984 are a thing of the past. But the intrusion of politics did not begin or end with the superpower conflict. War prevented the summer Olympics from taking place in 1916, 1940 and 1944. In other years, politics has almost always forced its way into the Games, be it through brutal suppression of dissent (Mexico, 1968), black-power salutes (ditto), terrorist atrocity (Munich, 1972), or strange boycott (Montreal, 1976). The 1976 boycott by African countries was in protest against a tour of South Africa by a New Zealand rugby team, never mind that rugby is not an Olympic sport. For sheer absurdity, it is hard to beat the time when Brazil sent two teams representing different political persuasions; neither was allowed to compete.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That was in 1936, at the infamous "Nazi Games". Hitler was neither the first nor the last to use the Games for national propaganda. People who run countries have all too often fallen for the notion that sporting success somehow confers political legitimacy. Each new victory, proclaimed a Stalinist propagandist in 1951, "provides irrefutable proof of the superiority of socialist culture over the decaying culture of the capitalist states." On the other side, the commercial success of the 1984 Los Angeles Games irrefutably proved that there was life in capitalism yet.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With the collapse of communism, the number of countries taking part in the Games has grown, and the propensity for high political drama has shrunk. Yet the temptation to use the Games for political purposes remains irresistible. So it was for the Spaniards--or should one say Catalans?--who were the hosts of the first post-cold-war Olympics in Barcelona four years ago. And so it is this time.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Clinton-Gore campaign has long said that its model is Ronald Reagan's re-election campaign in 1984. The Clintonites well remember how President Reagan basked in the patriotic glow of the Los Angeles Games that year, donning the jacket of a gold-medal winner and talking of national heroism. They know the modern trick is to extract the maximum political benefit from the Games without appearing to politicise them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The question is not whether Mr Clinton will exploit the Olympics (he is already doing so, with all his customary enthusiasm), but whether he can restrain himself from going over the top. Mr Reagan had a sixth sense that told him not to upstage the athletes during the Games, says Peter Ueberroth, the impresario of the 1984 Olympics. The sense was not always shared by his staff. Before the Olympics, for example, White House aides wondered whether the president might deliver more than the statutory formula of words to open the Games, and had to be reminded that the last person who had had that idea was Hitler in 1936. Mr Reagan himself wisely refrained from attending any Olympic events beyond the opening ceremony, and left the possibility of putting the Games to more blatant political usage until after they were over.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton has been less patient. He dispatched his wife and daughter to Greece for the lighting of the Olympic torch in April. His vice-president has been busy opening the Olympic stadium and announcing dollops of federal help (worth at least $230m) for the Games. Last month, after the Olympic flame spent the night at the White House on its way to Atlanta, Mr Clinton staged a parting ceremony timed for the morning television news. He opens the Games on Friday, he will entertain the American Olympians after the competition (and just before the Republican convention), and he will be back in Atlanta on August 16th to open the Paralympics for the disabled.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Starting with his state-of-the-union address in January and with increasing intensity since, Mr Clinton has been weaving references to the Games into his speeches and linking his campaign themes to Olympic values. The Olympic spirit, he says, is the "spirit of personal responsibility and best effort, the spirit of community, the spirit of unity." At the Rose Garden signing ceremony for the Church Arson Prevention Act last week, it was no surprise to find the president constrasting the evil flames destroying southern churches with the virtuous Olympic flame, symbol of the best of the human spirit, "now burning throughout the South."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Over the top? "It's become almost obscene," complains John McCain, a Republican senator from Arizona, who objects in particular to the deployment of some 13,000 military personnel to tasks that include driving buses for athletes. Mr McCain sees the White House's Olympic antics as the latest example of Clintonian excess. But whether the flag-waving American public will see things that way is doubtful.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At his party for the Olympic torch last month Mr Clinton singled out for special mention one of the torch-bearers, Carla McGhee, who almost died in a car accident but fought back to basketball triumph at the University of Tennessee and into the American Olympic team. The president did not mention another fine young athlete who years ago fought back from the brink of death and is also going for gold this year. His name is Bob Dole. But he is limping along some way down the track; it is, for the moment, Bill Clinton who wins the resounding title of <i>victor ludorum</i>.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838421999,iss">Search</a>
