<html><head><title>Terrific Pacific</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width=67 height=26  alt="Asia">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Terrific Pacific</h1>

<p>AFTER a year or more of living too dangerously for their own liking, the foreign ministers of virtually all the countries of East Asia, and the United States, are converging on Jakarta for security talks early next week in the wake of this weekend's annual meeting of <font size=-1>ASEAN</font>, the Association of South-East Asian Nations. Seemingly little more than a giant cocktail party and only formally established two years ago, the <font size=-1>ASEAN</font> Regional Forum, as the wider gathering is called, nonetheless stands out as a diplomatic must in a region that otherwise lacks the habits of multilateral diplomacy. But already the forum is under fire for its failure to confront the main challenge to stability in East Asia: the rise of a more assertive China.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For those who had argued that the new focus on wealth-creation and trade would be enough to protect East Asia from the sorts of tensions that have disfigured it for much of this century, the events of the past 18 months have come as a rude shock. <font size=-1>ASEAN</font>'s seven governments (Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam) are still reeling from China's occupation last year of Philippine-claimed Mischief Reef, one of the Spratly chain in the South China Sea. Since then China has reaffimed its long-standing claim to virtually the entire sea, adding to <font size=-1>ASEAN</font>'s troubles. More recently, China's attempts to intimidate Taiwan before its presidential election in March, by firing missiles into nearby waters, brought the largest flotilla of American warships to the region since the Vietnam war ended more than 20 years ago.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tensions have since subsided somewhat. America and China recently agreed to work to improve their strained relations and there is talk of an exchange of presidential visits next year. Last week, Anthony Lake, President Clinton's national security adviser, won China's approval for a joint American-South Korean proposal to include prickly and possibly nuclear-armed North Korea in four-way talks aimed at reducing tensions on the divided Korean peninsula. Meanwhile, the general regional unease has bolstered support, at least in private, for a continued American presence in the region as a stabilising force. It has also brought about a needed strengthening of the American-Japanese alliance (though neighbouring governments remain wary of Japan's taking on any wider security role).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To the region's trade-weighted optimists, all this shows that East Asia's recent troubles were nothing more than a few inevitable bumps on the road to a prosperous Pacific century. But there are potentially deadlier hazards ahead.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Taiwan is one. Although both China and Taiwan have since sought to talk down their differences, their confrontation earlier this year sent a frisson of fear through the region. Though most countries recognise only one government of China, in Beijing, Taiwan pays a large role in the region's trade and investment flows. A future Chinese grab for an increasingly independent-looking Taiwan could do enormous economic and financial damage to several countries. What is more, China's bullying of Taiwan augurs ill for the stability of Hong Kong, after its handover from Britain to China in 1997.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though China is East Asia's biggest worry, it is not the only one. Continued economic growth is fuelling competition for the region's reefs and their nearby oil deposits and fish. Ironically, the <font size=-1>UN</font> Convention on the Law of the Sea, which was devised to help settle competing claims, has added to them. Since governments can now claim "exclusive economic zones" that stretch up to 200 nautical miles from their shores (well beyond their 12-mile territorial limit), the number of overlapping claims has multiplied. Many will eventually be sorted out amicably. However, the demand for new patrol boats, submarines and aircraft to police these zones--to keep out pirates, as well as acquisitive neighbours--is pushing up defence spending around an already jittery region.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In theory all this should give East Asia's assembled foreign ministers plenty to talk about when they meet next week. In practice, however, <font size=-1>ASEAN</font>'s regional forum has played little part in sorting out the recent tensions. As Michael Leifer argues in a new analysis for the London-based International Institute for Strategic Studies, <font size=-1>ASEAN</font>'s own preference for ducking difficult issues rather than confronting them presents the forum that it sponsors with "the same order of difficulty as the biblical Hebrew slaves in Egypt who were obliged to make bricks without straw."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet any new organisation in the region would have many of the same limitations. The forum includes China, because to leave out the region's fastest-growing economic and political power would be to emasculate it from the start. Yet China has blocked all mention (and membership) of Taiwan. The blight not only affects official discussions, but also those in "track two" , where academics and policy analysts toss about practical ideas on how to create regional confidence-building measures, environmental protection and the like.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is concern, too, that the forum is losing what little coherence it once had by taking in too broad a membership. This year India joins the forum, along with Myanmar. Yet India refuses to go along with the forum's support for the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and a ban on nuclear testing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>ASEAN</font>'s regional forum is, however, a beginning. What is needed now is the will to apply the habit of dialogue that <font size=-1>ASEAN</font> has sought to foster to the region's real security problems. Though some would argue that bricks without straw are better than no bricks at all--that talks for their own sake are better than no talks at all--East Asia's continued economic success needs a sturdier security foundation to rest on.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838421999,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="ir1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
