<html><head><title>Love or money</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width=224 height=26  alt="International">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Brazil</b></p>
<h1>Love or money</h1>

<font size=1>SAO PAULO</font>
<p>BRAZILIANS love a good soap opera. The <i>telenovelas </i>that fill their television screens follow a standard formula: glamorous women, sex, infidelity, violence, a touch of political intrigue and a dash of social realism. For the past month, the country has been gripped by just such a soap--but this is a real-life one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It began on the morning of Sunday June 23rd, when two bodies were discovered sprawled across a bed in an opulent beach house outside Maceio, the capital of the north-eastern state of Alagoas. One of the bodies was of the house's owner: Paulo Cesar Farias, a 50-year-old former used-car salesman who achieved notoriety as the man who operated a huge influence-peddling scheme that led to the resignation of Fernando Collor as Brazil's president in 1992. The other victim was Suzana Marcolini, Mr Farias's 28-year-old lover.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the local police, the case was a straightforward crime of passion. Mr Farias, a widower, had been introduced to the exuberant Miss Marcolini, who counted Mr Collor among her former lovers, while he was serving a lenient sentence for his part in the corruption scheme, in an improvised cell in Maceio's fire station. But he had begun to tire of the liaison, having met Claudia Dantas, a blonde divorc&eacute;e from a prominent local family whom he may have planned to marry. He invited Miss Marcolini to a late (and drunken) dinner at the beach house to tell her of his decision to end their relationship. She objected, and they argued. Miss Marcolini shot Mr Farias and then herself with a revolver she had bought nine days earlier.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is the hypothesis, and the evidence appears to support it; but few Brazilians are persuaded. This is because there are many powerful people who may be presumed to wish Mr Farias dead. As Mr Collor's campaign treasurer in 1989, Mr Farias was deluged with donations from Brazilian businessmen who feared the election of a left-wing president. After the election, he went on to extract money from many of the country's leading firms in return for promises of public contracts or other government favours. He assembled a fortune of at least $300m. Some was spent on Mr Collor and other officials. Much of the rest may be in the 50 or so bank accounts opened by Mr Farias in the world's tax havens.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ever the loyal retainer, Mr Farias had refused to reveal the details of this massive corruption scheme, although he was the only one involved to be punished. (Mr Collor is living, comfortably, in Miami.) But Mr Farias faced further charges. Some of those compromised by the scandal, it is argued, may have feared his silence would not last forever. For the many conspiracy theorists, his death amounted to "burning the files" . They point to shortcomings in the police investigation as suspicious. Why was Mr Farias's family allowed to burn the bloodstained sheets before they were submitted to forensic analysis? And why were Mr Farias's bodyguards, who discovered the bodies, not subjected to tests to discover whether they had recently fired a gun?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For many in Brazil's more sophisticated south, such questions merely reveal the feudal backwardness of Alagoas, a state which was a Collor family fief for decades. Its policemen are owed several months' wages and many of them (including those who worked for Mr Farias) double up as private security guards. The state Institute of Forensic Medicine is so hard up that the post-mortems on Mr Farias and Miss Marcolini were carried out with a kitchen knife, as the institute's director admitted in a tearful television interview.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The federal police and some distinguished forensic scientists, called in to help with the case, are due to report their findings later this month. Whereas in television soap operas all the loose ends are tied up in the final chapter, in this case Brazil will probably never know beyond all doubt whether Mr Farias was a victim of passion or of more sinister intrigue--or whether Miss Marcolini killed herself, or was also murdered. However, if there is one thing Brazilians like more than soap operas, it is sport--and already the country's attention is moving on to the Olympic Games.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838421999,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
