<html><head><title>Overcooked leak</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Government</b></p>
<h1>Overcooked leak</h1>

<p>AT <i>The Economist,</i> the leak this week of a Treasury paper canvassing a British version of Newt Gingrich's "Contract with America" triggered an odd sense of <i>d&eacute;j&agrave; vu</i>. Fourteen years ago, a paper by the government's Central Policy Review Staff (<font size=-1>CPRS</font>) was leaked to us. It warned ministers that, without dramatic cuts in spending on social security and education, public spending would rise as a percentage of gross domestic product. "Publish the lot and let the people judge," we said. Instead, the cabinet threw out the document, and Britain's welfare state staggered on.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The latest leaked document should be a lot less controversial than that earlier one. Its origins are not political at all, but managerial. Sir Terry Burns, the Treasury's permanent secretary, wanted to rebut claims that his department was short-termist and reactive. So he commissioned one of his brightest younger officials to look at possible scenarios facing the department in the years 2000-2005, and to advise on how it should tool up to meet them. Any public company which failed to plan ahead in this way would deserve to be roasted alive by its shareholders.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The document sketches out different possible futures, including one in which pensions, unemployment benefit and sickness pay are covered by private insurance. But since Labour will probably be in power in the year 2000, more important than the Newt Gingrich scenario may be one which attempts to get to grips with New Labour thinking. As the document points out, "Treasury officials have a high level of commitment to the efficiency of the market mechanism, to neo-classical welfare economics and to the utilitarian ethics on which they are based". So have current ministers, but even "New" Labour may not be so keen.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bravely--though ironically in view of the leak--the author explains that traditional Treasury secrecy is a dead letter. With greater parliamentary demands for information and the drive towards greater accountability "we would not be able to rewrite or edit papers or fillet files as now". It canvasses options for a greater openness which is now inevitable as well as overdue.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The document's firmer conclusions do not concern policy but manpower. The Treasury will probably need more lawyers to regulate private pension providers. It will certainly need more officials who understand the European Union. Hear, hear.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this represents a creditable attempt at forward planning. So why did Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, instantly take to the airwaves to denounce the document, which he had not read, as the work of "kids in the office"? The reason, alas, is the same as that that caused Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, to denounce it as a plan for "the demoliton of Britain's welfare state": politics. With a Commons debate on the economy held on July 17th, the day the leak appeared in the <i>Times</i>, any ammunition was welcome to an opposition eager to snuff out Mr Clarke's attempts to propagate the "feelgood factor".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1982, as recorded above, our appeal for the <font size=-1>CPRS</font> document to be published in full was ignored, and it was suppressed. However, there was a sequel. During the 1983 election campaign, Peter Shore, the shadow chancellor, was able to provide a full text of a paper by the Chancellor which went with the <font size=-1>CPRS</font> paper to the <i>Sunday Times</i>. "It gave us the most uncomfortable few days of the election campaign," one Tory aide of the time recalls. If they do not want to suffer <i>d&eacute;j&agrave; vu</i> again during the forthcoming campaign, the Tories would do well to take the advice we proffer to them today as we did then: publish the document now, in full, and relish a public debate of its contents. They are not scary--indeed, the evidence that Whitehall is for once planning ahead before the future hits it in the face might win the government some credit.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838421999,iss">Search</a>
