<html><head><title>Murdering the cathedral</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Roads</b></p>
<h1>Murdering the cathedral</h1>


<p>PRESSED by a fearsome alliance of the Treasury and environmentalists, the government has ditched most new road construction. The notable exception is city bypass roads. But although saving cities from thundering lorries sounds like sense, such roads have many opponents, and not all of them are hairy tree-dwellers camped around Newbury. John Gummer, the environment secretary, has for six months been locked in dispute with the Department of Transport over its determination to build a bypass around Salisbury. This battle, on which a decision is expected shortly, is the culmination of an argument that has been going on for a generation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Described by its opponents as "a concrete necklace which will disfigure one of the loveliest cities in England", the 11-mile bypass has been controversial since it was first mooted twenty years ago. It would carve through chalk hills, three sites of scientific interest and one of the most beautiful views in the whole of England, made famous by Constable: Salisbury Cathedral seen across the Avon water meadows.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Local opposition is fierce. An official from the environment department reckons that if ministers gave the go-ahead, the resulting row would make the protests that obstructed the building of the Newbury by-pass look like a picnic. On the other side, the local Tory <font size=-1>MP</font>, Robert Key, a former minister for roads, is infuriated by Mr Gummer's resistance to a scheme which he claims is widely backed by local opinion. "The lone figure of Mr Gummer is now throwing doubt on this project. If it is kicked into touch, it will have very serious consequences," he warns.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The project's fate appears to be finely balanced. The environment secretary's filibuster is making his cabinet colleagues uneasy. The transport secretary, Sir George Young, who is scarcely less green than Mr Gummer, is expected to announce that, after a lengthy public inquiry, he is "minded to approve" the bypass but is prepared to listen to further representations from interested bodies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One such group, Salisbury District Council, called on July 15th for the public inquiry to be re-opened to consider new evidence on traffic growth. The government's own environmental watchdog, English Nature, also wants the inquiry reopened. The most pressing case for a rethink is made in a new study by the government's Standing Advisory Committee on Trunk Road Assessment, which casts doubt on the claimed benefits of the bypass. Using this research, the Metropolitan Transport Research Unit, a consultancy, claims that additional traffic generated by the bypass would cancel any benefits to the city.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Gummer may be a lonely figure in government but his case is strong. There are other ways of restricting the city's traffic growth without ruining some of the most beautiful countryside in Britain. Pricing people out of the centre of the city, for instance, would do it; or, if a bypass were essential, build it in a tunnel. Those options, however, would require political courage--or money.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838421999,iss">Search</a>
