<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>No service</b> &nbsp;Postal and underground workers staged their third one-day strike this summer. The rail drivers' strike will bring more disruption than earlier strikes, because a second union is now taking part. A further eight days of underground strikes are threatened.</p>
<p><b>Labour pains</b> &nbsp;Tony Blair, the Labour leader, has sought to distance his party from growing industrial unrest by urging rail unions to abandon their London underground strike.</p>
<p><b>Beef beef</b> &nbsp;Legislation for slaughtering 120,000 cows, essential to getting the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s ban on British beef lifted, has been postponed until the autumn. Ministers cannot agree on how much compensation to give farmers.</p>
<p><b>It's working</b> &nbsp;Figures released on July 17th showed that unemployment was at the lowest level in five years. The fall was higher than expected.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>The triple</b> &nbsp; The government overcame rebellions to win three important votes in the Commons. Restrictions on asylum seekers, the introduction of nursery vouchers and the selling of 60,000 armed-forces homes will now become law.</p>
<p><b>Shop till you drop</b> &nbsp;Britain's biggest shopping and leisure centre will be built in Kent. The &#163;700m Bluewater centre will be the largest construction project in Britain.</p>
<p><b>Pay restraint</b> &nbsp;Tony Blair will refuse the 26% increase that <font size=-1>MP</font>s voted themselves, in order to encourage lower industrial pay settlements.</p>
<p><b>Wight flag</b> &nbsp;The Isle of Wight is to poll its residents to gauge support for the island's devolution from Britain. The council may not hold a referendum without the government's permission, so it is sticking to an opinion poll.</p>
<p><b>Gnomes, sweet gnomes</b> &nbsp;A bungalow in Pembrokeshire has gone on sale for &#163;90,000, with one condition: the buyer must be willing to care for and dress daily 191 garden gnomes left by the late owners.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
