<html><head><title>Taken to the air</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>TECHNOLOGY BRIEF</b></p>
<h1>Taken to the air</h1>
<p><b>A wired world sounds like a splendid thing. But the third in our series of articles on access to the Internet asks whether a wireless one might be better still</b></p>

<p>GETTING wired without having to use wires is an Internet zealot's dream of mobile Internet access. It even thrills some companies--but for a different reason. They see wireless as a way to challenge those telephone or cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> firms that have seemed set to capture the market for high-speed, but fixed, Internet connections.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a limited sense, it is already possible to use the Internet wirelessly. With a laptop computer, a cellular telephone, and a gadget to connect the two, you can tap into the Internet from anywhere within range of your mobile-telephone company's network. But this is expensive and slow. Data can travel no faster than 9,600 bits per second (bps), just a third the speed of transmission over an ordinary telephone line.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Three better methods are now gaining ground. They are direct satellite links (which will receive the separate article they deserve next week), packet radio networks and "wireless cable". Each is designed for different needs and markets (see <a href="st1.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Packet radio is for the cyberpunk on the move. A couple of firms already provide this service, which consists, much like a cellular-telephone system, of a network of cheap, short-range, two-way radios. A few of the radios are connected to a wire network, which is itself connected to the Internet. The user buys a subscription, and a special modem for his laptop computer. He can then keep in touch through the nearest radio.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This can work out to be several times cheaper than a cellular-telephone connection, because packet radio squeezes data on to the airwaves more efficiently. But it is still more expensive to use--for about the same speed--than regular telephone lines. Its advantage is its mobility; some customers may prefer a slim and agile Internet connection to a fat, fixed one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Wireless cable, which is fat and fixed, may have broader appeal. Its oxymoronic name is due to its origin: a way to offer cable television without the cables, by beaming programmes through the airwaves from a transmitter to homes within a certain area. Also known as the multichannel multipoint distribution system, wireless cable <font size=-1>TV</font> already has about 900,000 American subscribers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Wireless cable can carry Internet traffic as well as <font size=-1>TV</font> broadcasts--all that is needed besides an antenna is a special modem to translate the signals going to and from the ether. Like wired cable, it has plenty of capacity: the amount of data delivered by a television signal is huge by Internet standards. But wireless, already fast, can be more easily and cheaply converted to carry the digital signals that will make it faster still.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At present, each wireless-cable channel carries 30m bps of data. By going digital (as America's regulators have now said they can), these wireless networks will be able to multiply that figure five or six times.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Wireless cable is also cheap to set up. A transmitting station, or "head-end", from which <font size=-1>TV</font> programmes or Internet data can be broadcast to any house in the line of sight within 40 or 50km (25-30 miles), only costs around $1m (although it will be four times that for digital broadcasts). The costs at the "foot-end"--an antenna, modem and installation--are only incurred when a paying customer signs up. The costs of wiring up a customer are therefore matched by immediate revenues--a dramatic contrast with the wired-cable business, where providers are still paying off the debts they took on to lay their underground lines.
</p><p><b>Not so fast</b></b>
<br>Investors think this sounds pretty tasty. When one of the larger wireless-cable operators, <font size=-1>CAI</font> Wireless, announced at the end of May that it was testing a wireless Internet service, its shares more than doubled. But the technology does have limitations. Unlike television, where everybody gets the same signal, on the Internet each user is typically looking at something different--and needs a separate bit of the airwaves. Further, big central transmitters beaming signals in all directions are good at sending lots of data, but less good at receiving it. Since the wireless-cable system is not broken into small cells, as are the packet-radio or cellular-telephone networks, it is less able to distribute scarce radio spectrum efficiently over the thousands of homes that may want to talk back at once.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some trials of wireless Internet access have worked around this by having users send out data through their telephone lines, while the response comes back through the airwaves. This works for most purposes, since what goes out is little more than requests for more to come in. But it is hardly wireless: it ties up a telephone line and delays connections. So companies are now trying two-way access: these systems can juggle the wireless capacity between incoming and outgoing data, but accommodate fewer users.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though wireless operators claim impressive speeds for their modems--10m bps, soon to rise to 27m bps--these will only apply when a tiny handful of people are using a channel. In practice, operators will probably have to limit most users to 128,000 bps, with up to 1m bps for those customers willing to pay more.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Capacity can, however, be increased in several ways. One, already used in cellular-telephone systems, is called "sectorising" . Instead of sending the same signals out in all directions, the antenna splits the transmission area into wedges. Each wedge is treated as a separate area, and the frequencies reused in each one. A recent trial in Lakeland, Florida, by two operators, American Telecasting and People's Choice <font size=-1>TV</font>, used 48 wedges. Even more vigorous sectorising should become possible in the future. With digital transmission, the wireless operators estimate they will be able to serve up to 50,000 users per channel, all at a speed of 128,000 bps.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Wireless cable should also benefit from the advent of more channels. Initially, only 33 frequencies were set aside for wireless cable in any given area. America's Federal Communications Commission is now expected to license some new higher-frequency bands, which will have lots of capacity but a shorter range for transmissions, about 5km. These networks would be much more cellular, with booster transmitters to carry the signal to and from the main one. With their high capacities, these might serve densely populated areas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nonetheless, wireless cable will not beat other rival technologies on speed. Its technical advantages are less evident to consumers than to the companies trying to get in on some Internet action. In fact, the telephone operators hope to use this to forestall competition from rival cable companies. They see it as a cheap way to reach homes with video and high-speed data while they upgrade or build faster wire networks. Last month Bell Atlantic and Nynex, two American regional telephone companies, announced a $100m investment in <font size=-1>CAI</font> Wireless to provide television and Internet access; <font size=-1>CAI</font> Wireless is meanwhile buying several smaller wireless companies. But the attitude to this kind of wireless among industrialists is still fluid. Some think that it will complement wire networks; others, only that it will prepare the way for them.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838421999,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
