<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Sects and violence</h2>
<p>A stand-off between police and Orange Order marchers set off <b>Protestant riots</b> throughout Northern Ireland. On July 11th the police changed their minds and violently cleared Catholic protesters from the marchers' route.
<p>Boris Yeltsin, newly re-elected president of Russia, said he would reappoint <b>Viktor Chernomyrdin</b> as prime minister and appeared to rule out a coalition with the defeated Communist Party. Mr Yeltsin gave Alexander Lebed broad powers to fight crime in Moscow. Shortly afterwards, a bomb exploded in the city's centre, injuring at least five people.</p>
<p>Despite Boris Yeltsin's campaign pledge to end it, Russia stepped up the <b>war in Chechnya</b> by attacking two villages with artillery and air-force strikes. A news agency said at least 20 civilians had been killed in an attack on a village thought to be the headquarters of the Chechen leader, Zelimkhan Yandarbiev. A Russian general was killed by a land mine.</p>
<p>The "Serb Republic", nominally part of Bosnia &amp; Herzcegovina, has named Radovan Karadzic leader of its new senate in defiance of the Dayton peace accord, which bars those indicted for war crimes from holding public office. <font size=-1>UN</font> investigators found the remains of more than 40 people, believed to be Bosnian Muslims executed by Serb soldiers, in a <b>mass grave</b> near Srebrenica.</p>
<p>Germany's government approved a 1997 <b>budget</b> that cuts spending by 2.5% to <font size=-1>DM</font>440.2 billion ($288.4 billion). It claims that will be enough to bring public-sector deficits to below the 3% ceiling for countries joining the single European currency. The labour, transport, economics and defence ministries took the biggest cuts.</p>
<p>France is having a summer of <b>scandal</b>. Investigators detained Loik Le Floch-Prigent, chief of the state-owned railways, in connection with investments made by Elf Aquitaine, a big oil company he once headed. The defence ministry admitted tapping the telephones of two aides to a former minister, Fran&ccedil;ois L&eacute;otard.</p>
<p>A French court has sentenced <b>Claude Gubler</b>, the doctor of the late President Fran&ccedil;ois Mitterrand, to a four-month suspended prison term for breaking professional secrecy. In a book now banned, Dr Gubler wrote that Mitterrand was ill with cancer during much of his presidency.</p>
<h2>Soft on peace</h2>
<p>On a visit to Washington, <b>Binyamin Netanyahu</b>, Israel's new prime minister, told President Bill Clinton that he was committed to negotiation with Arab neighbours but would not talk to Syria unless it renounced support for terrorism. Mr Netanyahu invited the hardline Ariel Sharon to join his cabinet as minister of infrastructure.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>At the annual summit of the Organisation of African Unity, African leaders backed a plan to send regional <b>peacekeepers to Burundi</b>.</p>
<p>Unofficial results showed that President Idriss Deby of <b>Chad</b>, who seized power in 1990, won the country's first multi-party presidential election. In neighbouring <b>Niger</b>, General Ibrahim Bare Mainassara, who also grabbed power in a coup, was declared winner of the presidential election. Opposition groups claimed that the vote was rigged and took to the streets.</p>
<h2>Common ground</h2>
<p>Anthony Lake, America's national security adviser, held out the prospect of <b>friendlier relations </b>between the United States and China after a period of tension over trade and human rights. On a trip to Beijing, he suggested that the American and Chinese presidents should eventually visit each other's countries.</p>
<p><b>Flooding</b> in southern China has killed 500 people and destroyed 30,000 houses but has spared most crops. The death toll is expected to rise.</p>
<p>China has <b>executed</b> at least 1,000 people since a campaign against crime, called Strike Hard, started in May.A South Korean news agency reported an <b>outbreak of cholera</b> in the north and west of North Korea. Food shortages were said to have lowered people's resistance to the disease.</p>
<p>India's new government ran into trouble when Parliament was adjourned in uproar after the opposition demanded the <b>scrapping of fuel-price rises</b>. Some members of the 13-party ruling coalition joined the protest, creating doubts about its future.</p>
<p>The International Court of Justice said the use of <b>nuclear weapons </b>would not by itself break international law. Their use would be lawful, however, only by a country threatened with extinction.</p>
<h2>Hopefuls</h2>
<p><b>Richard Lamm</b>, an ex-governor of Colorado, announced that he would run for president as a candidate for Ross Perot's Reform Party. His platform, he said, would be "fiscal sanity" . Mr Perot has said he would run himself if the party nominated him.</p>
<p>The Senate voted to raise the <b>minimum wage</b> for the first time since 1991. The bill, like another passed by the House, would raise the lowest wage by 90 cents an hour to $5.15. The president is expected to sign the final version.</p>
<p>Abdala Bucaram, a populist champion of the poor, won the run-off in <b>Ecuador's </b>presidential election, polling 54% of the vote.</p>
<p>A Cuban <b>hijacked</b> a plane to the United States' naval base on the island. America condemned the hijacking but did not say whether it would agree to hand him back.</p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
