<html><head><title>Hard to be young</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Students in debt</b></p>
<h1>Hard to be young</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font>
<p>AMERICA's newest game-show does not have the usual sports cars, pinball machines and fabulous vacations to Hawaii. On the show called "Debt", whoever best answers a series of insipid questions on pop culture is unburdened of many thousands of dollars-worth of credit card bills or home loans. It is instructive that the show, presided over by an unctuous 60-something, Wink Martindale, was conceived by a 29-year-old producer. Increasingly, debt haunts America's young.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unemployed or still at school, often unaccustomed to budget discipline, young people now have unprecedented opportunities to outspend their means. Many bite at the credit-card offers that flood campus mailboxes--and get stuck with fat interest rates. One study, by Claritas, a market-research firm, found a 20% jump in the average credit-card balance in southern California from 1993 to 1995. For those in their 20s, the jump was a startling 70%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These figures, however formidable, are dwarfed by the sums on student loans. Those who borrow to pay for college (and most do) end up owing an average of more than $7,500 for a public education; for private colleges, the figure is nearly $11,000. Graduate degrees bring additional debt. In 1985, only 3% of medical students graduated owing more than $75,000. In 1995, a third had debt in that range.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tuition fees are one large cause. The $100,000-plus cost of a Harvard or Yale undergraduate degree affects only a tiny minority. More telling are the precipitous cost increases at state universities, which account for four out of every five college diplomas. Governors have taken to raiding education budgets in order to finance the ballooning costs of Medicaid and prisons. So the students pay more: from 1981 to 1994, the cost of going to public universities rose by 55% in real terms (see <a href="am1.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At federal level, Pell grants (the chief need-based aid programme for higher education) have gone down in real terms since 1979. Last year the federal government paid out only $1.4 billion--an inflation-adjusted eighth of the 1975 figure--in <font size=-1>GI</font>-Bill money, which has provided college funds for ex-servicemen since the end of the second world war. In 1992, Congress expanded federally guaranteed loans, allowing more people to borrow larger amounts--which got more poor youngsters into college, but also into debt. The pinch is tightest on the poorest, for whom a debt of several thousand dollars can be frightening. Even students who can handle their debt are discouraged from taking useful low-paying work, such as jobs in health clinics, because their fixed-loan payments are too high.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Republicans' budget proposal for 1995 would have eliminated the subsidy students can get while in college. President Bill Clinton vetoed that, and proposed instead some small tax credits and tax deductions for higher education. He has also defended an idea started by the Bush administration, to disburse federally guaranteed loans direct from the Treasury rather than through banks. This has the advantage of saving money--banks are notoriously lax about collecting loans when they are reimbursed by the feds anyway--and also allowing the government, rather than for-profit institutions, to set the terms of the loan. The government also allows more flexible repayment options. For example, graduates can pay a percentage of their income, rather than a fixed amount, allowing them to take low-paying jobs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Every American agrees that more education leads to higher productivity and a richer country; yet the country stays stingy about paying for it. Health care for the elderly, on the other hand, though it does little to benefit society as a whole, plucks at the heart: so it now eats up an increasing percentage of the federal budget. The politician will explain this easily enough. The elderly constitute a powerful voting block. The young, less likely to vote, get stuck with the bill.



