<html><head><title>Netanyahu brings the politics of low expectations</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width=224 height=26  alt="International">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Netanyahu brings the politics of low expectations</h1>

WASHINGTON, DC
<p>ISRAEL'S new prime minister returned this week to the town where, as a young diplomat appointed by the Likud party he has since come to lead, he had achieved his first public triumphs. Back in the 1980s, Binyamin Netanyahu--articulate, American-educated and good-looking--went on American talk-shows to project a hopeful side to rightist Israeli policymaking. This week, confronting a Washington desperate not to see the peace process die, Mr Netanyahu's rhetorical skills seemed to desert him. At a press conference on July 10th, he fumbled for phrases to reassure his hosts. Still, he may not have minded. He was evidently not in the mood to tell Americans that the peace process was, after all, humming along nicely under his control.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bill Clinton was less than ecstatic. He listened coldly to Mr Netanyahu's thoughts on Jewish settlements in the West Bank and remarked: "The tide of history cannot be turned back." Mr Clinton has given enthusiastic support to the Oslo accords reached in 1993 and doggedly implemented by the Labour government that Mr Netanyahu defeated in May.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But these are early days, as Mr Clinton implied when he spoke of Israel's "period of adjustment". Certainly, no serious erosion in America's relations with Israel is likely before the presidential election in November. On the contrary, both men pronounced them "rock solid". Mr Netanyahu may be resentful of Mr Clinton's open support for Mr Peres in the Israeli election, and he might prefer to see Mr Dole in the White House. But he will not be saying so.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Netanyahu came to Washington resolved to attack. He did not want to have to defend his grudging recognition of the Oslo agreements as ill-conceived and dangerous but nevertheless binding on his government. Instead, he argued in the Oval Office and on Capitol Hill that honouring commitments was a matter for both sides, and the Palestinians had not been honouring theirs. The Palestinian Authority had set up branch offices in Jerusalem in explicit contravention of the accords. The Palestinian security police had even been patrolling Jerusalem and arresting people there--another violation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Netanyahu attacked Syria too. No longer would Israel "turn the other cheek" in the face of Hizbullah's attacks on its troops in south Lebanon, attacks condoned if not instigated by Syria. Damascus itself, he said, was home to several Palestinian terrorist groups. He wanted the peace talks between Israel and Syria to resume--but if they did, terrorism would be top of the agenda. Even Egypt was not spared. Mr Netanyahu told the president that the Egyptians were launching hostile initiatives against Israel.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The message was: peace yes, but on Israel's terms. Israel would, Mr Netanyahu explained, continue the peace process "in our own way", with "our own interpretation" of the principle of land for peace, as well as of <font size=-1>UN</font> Security Council Resolution 242, the basis of all Middle East peace diplomacy. He was not setting preconditions, he insisted, any more than he would accept them: the Arabs needed to be educated as to Israel's legitimacy in the region.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The tone of such statements harks back to the doldrum years of the 1980s and even earlier to the era before the first Likud prime minister, Menachem Begin, surprised the world and struck a land-for-peace deal with Egypt. The doughty Golda Meir always demanded "direct negotiations without preconditions" and went on to issue a slew of terms whose effect was to prevent talks from ever starting.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Peace could be achieved the Likud's way, argued Mr Netanyahu. At the Madrid peace conference in 1991, Israel (under the Likud) and Syria had come with diametrically opposed positions, but this had not prevented the talks from starting. If Mr Clinton was convinced, he did not say so. He pointedly made no reference to Madrid, extolling instead the changes wrought in the region over the past four years. He repeatedly praised Yasser Arafat's efforts to curb terrorism in the Palestinians' self-ruled areas. Ignoring Mr Netanyahu's strictures, the president said he was "impressed" by the Palestinian Authority's growing ability to run its own affairs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The main conclusion to be drawn from the Israeli prime minister's performance in America is that peace will be pursued with considerably less urgency. The next item on the Oslo agenda is Israel's redeployment from the West Bank town of Hebron (which Mr Netanyahu said was to be "redeployment in Hebron, not out of Hebron"). The issue was immensely complicated. He was studying all the aspects. Similarly, on the fraught question of meeting Mr Arafat, he merely repeated that he did not preclude it--"if I deem it in the interests of peace."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some Netanyahu-watchers, believing him to be more of a pragmatist than a dogmatist, had expected him to be less strident in America. Instead, he seemed at times to be almost spoiling for a fight. On the settlements issue, for instance, which poisoned relations between the previous Likud-led government and the Bush administration, Mr Netanyahu presented figures showing that the number of settlers had risen by half (from 96,000 to 145,000) over the four years of Labour rule. "I assume", he said, "that no one here is expecting us to do less."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Americans, say Mr Netanyahu's aides, understand that things have changed in Israel. "There's a new game in town, and we're not going back to the old one. They accept that." Clearly they do. But, just as clearly, they do not like it. Nor do the Palestinians. The reaction from Mr Arafat's men back home has been ominously sharp.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="eu1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
