<html><head><title>Rules of the game</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Prostitution</b></p>
<h1>Rules of the game</h1>

<p>THE laws on prostitution do not work. That is what police, prostitutes, health workers and people who live in areas rife with prostitution told a parliamentary committee on prostitution. The only people involved who did not give evidence were the clients. Perhaps that is why the committee's solution, published in its report on July 8th, was to amend the law to be tougher on them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Residents' groups in areas such as Streatham in London and Forest Road in Nottingham say that prostitution on their streets is a nightmare. Local men are bothered by women trying to climb into their cars; local women and girls are harassed by men trying to buy sex. The nights are noisy, with people shouting, engines running and car doors banging. The streets are littered with condoms and soiled tissues. Prostitutes ply their trade in people's basements and garden sheds. The police, say locals, do nothing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The police admit that prostitution is low down their list of priorities, but say that it is impossible to implement the law effectively. Since the Police and Criminal Evidence Act of 1984, they have to release prostitutes as soon as they have arrested and charged them. As a result, they often end up arresting the same woman several times in a night. Fines go up to &#163;1,000, but many magistrates are unwilling to impose high fines because they believe they force the women to work harder to pay them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both police and residents' groups liked the idea of targeting the clients. Currently, kerb-crawling is dealt with in the same way as traffic offences: the police cannot arrest offenders, although they can prosecute and fine them up to &#163;1,000. Police reckoned that arrest might be a more effective deterrent than a routine fine in the post; and residents' groups also favoured shaming kerb-crawlers by publishing their names in local papers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a curious suggestion for a country with a proper respect for privacy. But this is the sort of dark alley down which attempts to make an unworkable law work inevitably lead.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most sensible suggestion on the prostitution laws came from the prostitutes who gave evidence to the committee: scrap them. Then prostitutes would be happy because they could work indoors (which many avoid because of the risk of police raids); residents would be happy because the trade would move off the streets; and the police would be happy to be relieved of the impossible task of trying to suppress the world's oldest profession. The committee, however, rejected this option out of hand.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
