<html><head><title>Bleeding tartan taxpayers</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Scottish devolution</b></p>
<h1>Bleeding tartan taxpayers</h1>

<font size=1>EDINBURGH</font>
<p>THE Labour Party thought it had spoilt the Tories' devolution plans. Last month it promised to hold a referendum asking Scottish voters not only whether they want a parliament in Edinburgh, but also whether they want it to have tax-raising powers. The Tories appear unimpressed by this tactic. On July 8th Michael Forsyth, the Scottish secretary, pronounced that Labour's proposed "tartan tax" showed the party's "lust to bleed Scottish wealth creators white."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Forsyth's lurid diatribe misses the point. The key question about Labour's proposals is not whether they will allow an Edinburgh parliament to bleed anyone dry, but whether they will allow it to do much of anything at all.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour says a power to tax is essential both to make a Scottish parliament accountable to its voters and to stop it whingeing about Westminster's meanness. In fact, Labour's taxing proposal is so modest that it will achieve neither.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour wants a Scottish parliament to be able to raise or lower the basic rate of income tax by up to 3p. If the parliament put up current tax rates by the maximum amount, those paying the highest tartan tax would pay an extra &#163;648 a year, which would give the Scottish parliament about &#163;450m. This would amount to a mere 3% of the parliament's revenues. Most of the money it would be responsible for spending would come from the grant currently made to the Scottish Office by Westminster (&#163;14.5bn in the current fiscal year). So much for accountability.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, the parliament's capacity to tax earned income even to this limited extent (investment income is excluded) would still depend on decisions taken at Westminster. Martyn Jones, a lawyer with Maclay Murray &amp; Spens, a corporate law firm, points out that Labour's proposal is (oddly) for a regressive tax, applicable only to the basic rate of income tax, levied presently on income between &#163;7,665 and &#163;29,265. Any decisions by the chancellor of the exchequer to narrow this band throughout Britain would also cut the Scottish parliament's revenue. So much for the idea that a Scottish parliament would eliminate Scottish grumbles about decisions taken at Westminster.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;George Robertson, Labour's Scottish spokesman, is enthusiastic about the political bartering over tax rates between Edinburgh and Westminster which might result. "There will be openness in the system instead of the closed-doors bartering which goes on all the time inside government," he says.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And yet, however desirable such a system might be from the point of view of open government, it might also mean that the Edinburgh parliament could not lower income tax in Scotland. The reason is that spending per head tends to be higher in Scotland than in England. This discrepancy has survived the introduction, back in 1978, of a formula intended to close the gap. Spending per head on the services to be devolved was 22% higher in Scotland than in England in 1976-77, and in 1993-94 it was still 21% higher.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour says that it would not change the Scottish spending formula. But the pressure to reduce the discrepancy would increase if powers were devolved to the Scottish parliament, and English <font size=-1>MP</font>s lost their say over how the money was spent. It would redouble if the Scottish parliament ever tried to reduce taxes. English <font size=-1>MP</font>s would hardly agree to the continuation of such large transfers north of the border if the Scots were using some of the money to give themselves a tax cut.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So the parliament's powers to reduce taxes would be a fiction, and its power to raise them severely restricted. Sir Edward Heath, a former Tory prime minister, was surely right when he said on July 9th that his party's predictions that devolution would produce civil war were "fantastic nonsense" . But then, on close inspection, Labour's claims that an Edinburgh parliament would be financially independent look just as wild.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
