<html><head><title>Taxed in cyberspace </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>Taxed in cyberspace </h1>

<p>THE success of America's $60 billion home-shopping business is often credited to whim and convenience, but the truth is more about tax. Thanks to a legal loophole, Americans rarely pay sales tax when they buy things through the post or over free "800" telephone numbers from companies based in other states. That saves them nearly $4 billion a year. On the Internet, hundreds of companies plunging into the promised boom market of electronic commerce are assuming the same is true for them--virtually all of them are treating Internet sales just like telephone sales. This could prove an expensive mistake.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Taking their lead from Connecticut and the Multistate Tax Commission, several states are proposing a rather tortured interpretation of the Internet that would make all commerce over it, in effect, local everywhere for tax purposes. Most of the 45 states that charge local sales taxes argue that a business has a sales "nexus" (the equivalent of a physical presence) in a particular state if its telecommunications equipment--usually its call centre or corporate headquarters--is in that state.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By that definition, one might think that the Internet is no different from ordinary telephony. Just as callers reach a company's telesales centre over the public-telephone system, cybershoppers reach a company's Web site over the public Internet, which is made up of hundreds of interlinked network providers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the states claim one key difference: they argue that each of the hundreds of independent firms that provide Internet access to their subscribers across the United States is, in effect, working on behalf (as an "agent") of all those companies that have a Web site or otherwise do business over the Internet. And therefore, they claim, every company selling goods over the Internet has a telecommunications nexus in every state, and must pay local sales tax on goods that it sells in each state.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Internet commerce will be worth more than $500m this year, and is expected to reach more than $6 billion by 2000, so the stakes are high--sales tax ranges from 4% to 7% among American states. Kent Johnson, head of the sales-tax practice at <font size=-1>KPMG</font>, an accounting firm which has been studying the problem, reckons that uncertainty about tax could cause companies to think twice about selling over the Internet: nobody wants to face a multi-million-dollar back-tax bill. In a <font size=-1>KPMG</font> survey of nearly 300 large companies, one-third thought that state and local taxes on Internet sales would hurt their company's electronic-commerce efforts, and some even planned to move their operations offshore to avoid them. If a sign were needed that the Internet has become a real market, the arrival of tax avoidance is surely it.


</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="wb2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
