<html><head><title>Not quite the right moral</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<p><b>European entrepreneurs</b></p>
<h1>Not quite the right moral</h1>

<font size=1>PARIS</font><p><b>Does the success of Business Objects symbolise the future of European high-tech companies?</b></p>


<p>IN THE rise of Business Objects, a small French software company, some see cause for great hope. With skill and a bit of luck, other high-tech European companies can also best their American rivals. Business Objects is thus much more than a rarity: it has become a symbol. Its history has even encouraged the French bourse to launch a new market for small fast-growing firms. The business press has heaped prizes on the company's founders.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is odd. For if Business Objects encapsulates any lesson, it is that European start-ups are most likely to succeed by escaping their European roots as fast as possible.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are few Porsches and Ferraris in the car park opposite the firm's head office in Puteaux, a drab suburb to the west of Paris, but that probably reflects the French antipathy to flaunting wealth. Since it was founded in 1990 by two Frenchmen in their late 20s, the company's sales have been doubling each year, reaching $60m in 1995, with net profits of $8m (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is no accident that the accounts of this French firm are denominated in dollars: its shares are quoted on Nasdaq, a New York stockmarket which lists many American high-tech firms. There they climbed from $17.50 to $29.50 on the day when they were issued in September 1994. This year they have done better than the Nasdaq composite index, hitting a high of more than $50 before falling back to $27, possibly on worries about the latest version of its software.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although Business Objects is growing, it has a total market capitalisation of $650m, making it still a tiddler in the programming world. It specialises in software for client/server computing, networks of independent computers hitched to a central machine which contains shared databases and programs. The firm has made its fortune with a program that allows managers to question databases in more or less everyday language. Pulling information out of a database used to mean learning a special programming language or getting the help of a computer professional. According to a survey by <font size=-1>META</font> Group, an American market-research firm, Business Objects now accounts for a third of the worldwide sales of database-query programs, a market that is expected to grow to $800m by 1997, ten times its value in 1993.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In one respect, those worried by Europe's conspicuous weakness in computing are right to take comfort from Business Objects. The firm owes its success to solid commercial skill rather than to an unrepeatable stroke of programming genius. Bernard Liautaud and Denis Payre, the two founders, both worked for Oracle, an American database firm, as technical and commercial staff.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the reassurance stops there. The new company turned its back on the conventional French route to prosperity. Although Business Objects was founded in France by Frenchmen, it seems mightily American to an outsider.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even the name hints at the firm's inspiration. Mr Liautaud admits that French customers thought the company was the European subsidiary of an American parent. "Objets Commerciaux" would have been more politically correct, but might have scared them off. And in the United States, where the company has grown fast, it has not suffered from the stigma, in high technology, of being European.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new firm's capital structure is one of its most unFrench characteristics. Many entrepreneurs in France fear that selling shares to outsiders means losing control. The typical result is a series of holding companies buttressed by double-voting rights for a few privileged shares. By contrast, the founders of Business Objects invited investment from American and French venture capitalists. After successive rounds of finance, and flotation on Nasdaq, the pair retain only around 14% of the equity. As Mr Liautaud says, power comes from success: it is better to have a small part of a large company than a large part of a small one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The typical European entrepreneur, according to Jean-Louis Barsoux, an academic based at <font size=-1>INSEAD</font>, a business school outside Paris, who has studied Business Objects, is authoritarian and unwilling to give up power. By contrast, Mr Liautaud and Mr Payre set out to hire skilled managers by offering them stock options, consciously imitating what they saw as the approach of entrepreneurs in Silicon Valley.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The result was that the company had enough capital to see it through the early years, and the confidence to spend a large part (initially as much as 50%) of its revenues on <font size=-1>R&D</font>. The money and depth of managerial talent meant that the firm could set up foreign offices almost from the start. This was essential to make an impression in a fast-moving business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To flourish, the firm needs its niche to grow, but not so fast that really big competitors are drawn in. The fortunes of European high technology depend upon the creation of more Business Objects.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The very fact that an example is there to copy will help. So, too, will the development of European capital markets. Shocked that a French success should float in America, the French bourse has set up the Nouveau March&eacute;, which is just one of a handful of new European markets designed for small, fast-growing companies. So far only seven firms have been launched on the market, though the exchange hopes for few dozen listings in the coming years. One of the recent listings was a chain of hairdressing salons. High-tech Europe still has a lot of catching up to do.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="st1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
