<html><head><title>Yeltsin's next round</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<h1><center>Yeltsin's next round</center></h1>

IT IS quite an achievement. Though Boris Yeltsin is erratic in temperament and unsound in body, and though he has presided over a period of change in which most Russians have grown poorer, they have re-elected him. Few, if any, reformers in other ex-communist countries have been given a similar second chance. That undoubtedly owes much to the alternative on offer in Russia: the primitive Communism of Gennady Zyuganov, the defeated candidate. But it is also a tribute to Mr Yeltsin. His success means that hopes for reform are still alive.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Alas, the sighs of admiration, and of relief, are already giving way to gasps of anxiety. Democracy and prosperity in Russia are far from secure. So is Mr Yeltsin's presidency. Having suffered two heart attacks in the past year, and something serious this week, he cannot be certain of serving his full four years in office. His very will to govern may even be in doubt: during his first term he occasionally seemed to abdicate for months at a time, allowing unsavoury cronies to take advantage of the ensuing vacuum. Should he leave the presidency prematurely, Mr Zyuganov's Communists might well have another crack at the Kremlin.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What if the president does die in office? The constitution says the prime minister then takes over until another presidential election is held; the swiftly reappointed incumbent, Viktor Chernomyrdin, probably therefore has a head start, if he wishes to succeed. At present, no one--and certainly no one reassuring--can be considered Mr Yeltsin's heir-apparent. Competition for the job would be intense and divisive.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Alexander Lebed, the former general whose backing for Mr Yeltsin in this week's run-off clinched the president's re-election, thinks he is already all but anointed. He is probably wrong, though he has at least a chance of emerging on top. If that happened, however, confidence would take another knock. Even in the past fortnight Mr Lebed has made a series of ugly, economically illiterate and anti-democratic remarks that confirm suspicions that he is the wrong man for the succession. If in his new post as security overseer he can reduce crime, well and good. But Mr Yeltsin will have to watch his back. The Kremlin is awash with intrigue.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In any event, a daunting pile of tasks awaits Mr Yeltsin. The rebellious territory of Chechnya must be pacified, preferably by letting it secede, if that is what most Chechens want to do. Within months, he will need to squeeze public spending brutally, despite his rash campaign promises--a good $10 billion-worth of them, by some calculations. The anger of those Russians who, for instance, have not been paid for half a year, could start to mount. But to keep the economy stable and to meet the <font size=-1>IMF</font>'s conditions for a continuing flow of loans, Mr Yeltsin must tighten belts ever more painfully.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He must also embark on a gruelling course of longer-term reforms. A drastic overhaul of land-ownership and farming is urgent. A new tax code, simpler, friendlier to businessmen and investors, especially from abroad, is also needed: partly through fear of a Communist victory, tax evasion has reached chronic proportions in the past six months. Privatisation has stalled since the parliamentary election last December. The government's ownership of vast swathes of energy and other natural resources is holding back growth. Monopolies in industries like railways and various utilities need breaking up. Despite big recent advances, Russia still lacks a truly independent judiciary and an enforceable legal system. It needs a smaller, and properly paid, professional army. And war must be waged on organised crime.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately the Duma, the lower house of parliament, which is dominated by Communists and nationalists, will oppose nearly all these changes. It has already done its best to block or hobble many of them. In the rare instances when it has approved a reform or a new institution, it has usually done so in order to take control itself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The hope is that a more reform-friendly Duma will emerge after the next election, due in three years' time. At present, Mr Yeltsin can issue decrees, laying down broad policies which may sometimes be wangled into effect, despite the Duma's hostility. He can try to chip away at the edges of the Communist and nationalist blocks. Given the momentum of his big win on Wednesday, however, he may in due course be tempted to force a showdown, perhaps by challenging the Duma to accept a reformist prime minister to replace the dull and dependable Mr Chernomyrdin. Fresh Duma elections would be risky. But Mr Yeltsin is nothing if not a risk-taker.
</p><p><b>The hope amid the worry</b>
<br>The election showed that Mr Zyuganov's mixture of xenophobic nationalism and nostalgia for communism still has an alarmingly potent appeal in Russia. It is not much less worrying that Mr Yeltsin had to co-opt a crude law-and-order figure in the shape of Mr Lebed to ensure re-election. But time, especially if Mr Yeltsin manages to survive four more reasonably active years, is against the Communists. The most hopeful aspect of Mr Yeltsin's win is that the forces of reform, faced with the possibility of Communism's return, did manage to put their differences aside and rally to democracy's cause. If they can now help Mr Yeltsin to put Russia on the road to a just and civil society as well as a vigorous capitalist one, it may yet be said that the presidential election of 1996 was almost as significant as the collapse of Soviet power in 1991.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836607600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="eu1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
