<html><head><title>Russia's daunting future</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width=105 height=26  alt="Europe">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Russia's daunting future</h1>

<font size=1>MOSCOW</font><p><b>It was a stunning electoral achievement by Boris Yeltsin, but his health and a hostile Duma remain formidable obstacles to building a new Russia</b></p>


<p>TOO SICK or too tired to vote at his intended polling station, but well enough to win a landslide victory, Boris Yeltsin triumphed by 54% to 40% over his Communist challenger, Gennady Zyuganov, in the second round of Russia's presidential election on July 3rd. (About 5% of votes were cast "against both candidates".) Russian shares and government securities firmed on the news. Western leaders sighed with relief. "We can send the Communists to hell," said an elated Kremlin adviser.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a television speech on July 4th, Mr Yeltsin struck a conciliatory note, saying that Russia should not be divided "into winners and losers". The incumbent prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, said he would be presiding over Mr Yeltsin's new government, indicating a continuation of Russia's broadly reformist policies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most people had expected Mr Yeltsin to win, but not by so wide a margin. In a first round of voting on June 16th, he had led Mr Zyuganov by 35% to 32%, with nine more candidates trailing. But regions that had favoured Mr Zyuganov in the first round swung Mr Yeltsin's way in the second. Mr Yeltsin seemed to gain many new votes from supporters of Alexander Lebed, a gruff law-and-order general who finished a strong third on June 16th with 15%. Two days later Mr Lebed entered the Kremlin as national security adviser, behaving as Mr Yeltsin's de facto deputy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Yeltsin also gained votes from supporters of Grigory Yavlinsky, a moderate reformist who came fourth on June 16th with 7.4% after an agonisingly clumsy campaign. He gave Mr Yeltsin a roundabout endorsement after round one, so may be rewarded with a job in government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The historic victory in Russia's first free presidential election as a fully sovereign state capped a remarkable comeback for Mr Yeltsin, whose poll ratings had languished at a mere 8% in January. To restore his popularity when campaigning, he promised handouts and subsidies to dozens of regions and interest-groups, running up a bill that threatens to top $10 billion. He was helped by feeble campaigning from Mr Zyuganov, by a slavishly pro-Yeltsin bias in the Russian media, and at the end by the Kremlin's insistence that the second-round ballot should be held on a special mid-week public holiday. The president's more urban electorate, which might have defected en masse to its country dachas had the vote been held as usual on a Sunday, turned up in dutiful droves at the polling stations. In Moscow Mr Yeltsin led Mr Zyuganov by 78% to 18%; in St Petersburg by 74% to 21%, according to preliminary returns. Those two winning margins added up to 5m votes, or roughly half Mr Yeltsin's winning margin across Russia as a whole. Despite fears of election fatigue, some 67% of voters turned out across the country, only three percentage points below the first-round turnout (see <a href="eu1.gif">table</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A shadow was cast over Mr Yeltsin's victory, however, by the mysterious illness that caused him to duck a series of public engagements in the six days before the final vote. His few brief television appearances in that time were recorded by private Kremlin cameras. Officials insisted that Mr Yeltsin was suffering from "a cold" or "laryngitis", and that he was working normally again in the Kremlin on July 4th. But pessimistic outsiders worried that Mr Yeltsin's slurred speech and awkward posture when seen on television hinted at a mild stroke or heavy medication. Exhaustion, depression or a recurrence of long-standing heart trouble seemed equally plausible explanations. An unfit 65, Mr Yeltsin suffered two serious heart attacks last year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If voters seemed not to worry about Mr Yeltsin's health, that was because most of them knew little or nothing about it. The story was ignored or played down by Russian television and most newspapers, which continued their campaign coverage in a vein so partisan as to demand a good dose of soul-searching on the part of the country's journalists.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Victory safely banked, Mr Yeltsin's next big step will probably be to invite the Duma, the lower house of Russia's parliament, to endorse Mr Chernomyrdin as prime minister. That would leave the Communists, who dominate the Duma, to decide if they wanted to pick a fight (see <a href="eu2.html">page</a>). When it came to choosing other ministers, officials said, Mr Yeltsin would not want a coalition government as such, but would be looking for new allies. Attempts might be made to weaken the Communist block by dividing it rather than by attacking it head on--perhaps by inviting Aman Tuleyev, an ally of Mr Zyuganov, into government, and by scheming to unseat Gennady Seleznev, a rival of Mr Zyuganov, as speaker of the Duma.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Yeltsin cannot afford to be too conciliatory, however, if he hopes to follow through on some of the second-term policies at which he has hinted. A strong presidential agenda might include reforms of taxation, of farming and of the army, a rooting-out of organised crime and the making of a durable peace in Chechnya. It would mean riding roughshod over the Duma in pursuit of legislation, and knocking rebellious officials into line. It would also mean a return to stricter fiscal discipline and with that, almost inevitably, a fresh surge of public hostility as cash limits on public spending began to bite, dodgy banks were left to topple, and the sale of state assets resumed. For those reasons, it may be Mr Yeltsin's reserves of energy, as much as his political instincts, that determine what--and how much--he gets done.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One worry, if Mr Yeltsin remains weak, is that he will be more vulnerable to the capture of his power by others. First in the queue would be the ambitious but wholly inexperienced Mr Lebed, who within a fortnight of entering the Kremlin was urging Mr Yeltsin to appoint him vice-president. And somewhere in the shadows, doubtless, would be Alexander Korzhakov, Mr Yeltsin's long-time bodyguard and confidant. Mr Korzhakov was sacked as chief of the presidential guard on June 20th amid allegations that was he was preparing to wreck the election. But he has stayed friends with Mr Yeltsin and has kept a place in the presidential entourage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The biggest worry of all would be that Mr Yeltsin's health might deteriorate to the point at which he could no longer continue to rule. If that happened in the near future, Russia's strained nerves could not easily cope with another presidential election--any more than Russia's newly minted democracy could cope without one.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836607600,iss">Search</a>
