<html><head><title>The cities come back to life</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Planning</b></p>
<h1>The cities come back to life</h1>
<p><b>Britain's cities are growing for the first time since the first world war. There are plenty of ideas about how to improve them, and the government has announced new measures to promote their health</b></p>

<p>IT IS hard to make anybody sit up and listen when what you have to announce is "the government's revised planning policy-guidance note on town centres and retail development." So it is not surprising that John Gummer, the environment secretary, did not get the attention he deserved when outlining his new policy at the end of last month. When future social historians record the turn-around in the fortunes of the British city at the end of the 20th century, Mr Gummer should get some credit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britons dream of country gardens. Their aspirations, unlike those of the continental bourgeoisie, lie outside the city. As long as the middle class has existed, it has been trying to leave the city; so when 19th-century urbanisation stopped, the cities' populations started dropping.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because the well-off moved to the suburbs, the cities had no powerful lobby to stop the planners doing their worst. Over the past 50 years, this is precisely what they did. Aside from London, whose spots of villagey organic charm have mostly been preserved, Britain's cities have been brutally treated. In Manchester, Liverpool, Birmingham, planners ripped out the old city centres and dense streets, and redesigned them with two ideas in mind: the car and the zone.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Cars were given primacy, so radial dual-carriageways blasted away long-established neighbourhoods. And homes, factories, offices and shops were to be kept apart, so small shopping streets next to residential streets were destroyed in favour of lumping most retailers together in shopping malls, and offices and workshops in business parks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It did not work. And the worse the cities got, the keener the middle classes were to move. So the cities' cores were left to those who could not afford to go anywhere else.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Recently, however, the drain of people from the cities seems to have stopped. According to Bob Armitage of the Office for National Statistics (<font size=-1>ONS</font>), "there are clear signs that the population of inner London is beginning to increase again." The <font size=-1>ONS</font> forecasts that six inner London boroughs will be among the 11 fastest-growing local-authority areas in the country in the period 1993-2001, with Newham, the fastest-growing, gaining 9.5% more inhabitants and Kensington &amp; Chelsea, the slowest, increasing by 7.1%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"We're expecting the same to happen in the other metropolitan areas," says Mr Armitage. The main reason for the flow of people back to the inner cities, he reckons, is their redevelopment. The government has brought this about largely by pouring money into slums like Hulme in Manchester or old industrial wastelands like Docklands in London, where smart new estates welcome families and refurbished warehouses offer Manhattan-style lofts to young professionals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Social trends may have something to do with it, too: the increase in single parents, for whom sociable city life is more attractive than isolation in the countryside; job insecurity, which makes people feel they need to be close to a big labour market; perhaps even the mass coming-out of gays, who openly colonise areas such as Canal Street in Manchester.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the same time, there seems to be a rebirth of civic consciousness. A Manchester Civic Society was established earlier this year to lobby for the city's welfare. In London, an organisation called Vision for London, sponsored by local government and business, has been orchestrating discussion on how to improve the city. The Architectural Foundation and the <i>Evening Standard</i> newspaper are together running a summer-long series of lectures on "London in the 21st Century" with such luminaries as Tony Blair, Labour's leader, and Lord Gowrie, the Arts Council chairman, as speakers. Audiences have exceeded 1,000. Liam O'Connor, architectural adviser to Mr Gummer, says "I have never known a time when there have been so many amenity groups taking an interest in the height of buildings and public spaces."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Behind much of the burgeoning activity is a set of ideas called "new urbanism", which originated in America and was brought to Britain by people like Rob and Leon Krier, American architects whose Seaside development in Florida has influenced many. According to Alan Baxter, an engineer in the forefront of the movement, who is currently working on the redevelopment of the site of the hideous Department of the Environment offices in Westminster, "there's a wave of new thinking going through planning 15 years after something similar went through architecture."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;New urbanism sees cities as organisms whose many parts work together to keep the whole alive; thus, it rejects the zoning that underpins existing planning regimes. Cities come alive, it believes, in places like Notting Hill Gate, in London, where people can work, live and play. It believes in dense terraces, not isolated blocks on wide open spaces; it approves of interlinked streets, not cul-de-sacs. It demands that buildings be seen in context, not as separate structures that happen to be next to each other. It upholds the unity of the European-style city that survives in Britain in places such as Bath; it decries the American, car-dominated sprawl that influenced British planners in the 1960s. The model is Siena; its antithesis, Los Angeles.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;New urbanism insists that beauty, which has been low on planners' agendas for much of the 20th century, matters as much as function. It wants the disciplines of planning, architecture and engineering, which have grown apart, to start working together, so that road engineers think about what effects they have on pedestrians, not just on traffic flows, and architects think about what will go on in the street as well as inside their buildings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These ideas were first promoted in Britain by the Urban Design Group, which was set up in the early 1980s, bringing together around 1,000 architects, planners and engineers determined to put right the wrong that had been done to cities. This movement is at last beginning to have an impact. Local-government officials, who have seen the disaster brought upon the cities by the old ideology, are coming on board. And, most important, Mr Gummer, who has been in a position to change the planning system, has been enthusiastic.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;New urbanism is filtering into the development process partly through special projects like Hulme in Manchester. There, the deeply disgruntled locals were consulted about what they wanted, and much of what they said (dense housing, shops, lots of street-level activity, no wide open spaces, enclosed gardens) accorded with the new ideas. The planning guide for Hulme was then written by a former student from Manchester University's architecture and planning department who espoused "new urbanism"; and it is reckoned to have been so successful that it has been adopted for the whole city.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The redevelopment of the Department of the Environment site, similarly, will push the new approach. It is high time that penance was done for that piece of official vandalism, which killed off city life in a slice of Westminster. Once the buildings themselves have been vaporised, it will be returned to mixed use in the hope of bringing the streets back to life.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Gummer's changes to the planning regime, the most recent of which he announced last month, are also intended to push cities in this direction. Councils will be told to consider the city as a whole when making planning decisions, instead of proceeding case by case. They will be expected to favour mixed-use developments, rather than shopping centres, or housing estates, or business parks. Planners will be required to look at buildings in their context, so that they should be in harmony with their surroundings. And aesthetics will take a more prominent place than under the old, functional regime.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Planners, too, are changing. Many realise the damage that has been done to cities, and see that things now need to be done differently. According to Michael Hebbert, professor of town planning at Manchester University, "planning schools have been training people to do social science and administration. Now there's a stronger design element coming in to planning." All over the country, urban-design courses are springing up at universities as local authorities try to recruit a different kind of person to their planning departments.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As these ideas start having an impact, so Britain's cities should become more welcoming, and more people should want to live in them again. However, there are matters still to be resolved. One concerns out-of-town shopping centres, which drain activity away from the centres of towns. Although Mr Gummer has restrained that sort of development, it is still happening. A huge development called Dumplington is scheduled to go ahead outside Manchester, for instance; it will reduce the chances of bringing the city centre, bombed by the <font size=-1>IRA</font> last month, back to life.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Secondly, planning regulations are still not geared to the small-scale economic activity that mixed-use development implies. They are used to dealing with big proposals, not the patchwork of small-scale start-ups that is needed. If councils cannot get their officials working for, rather than against, little businesses, then Mr Gummer's ambitions will be frustrated.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The third problem is the car. "The crux of these ideas," says Mr Hebbert, "is the private car. European cities are cohesive, American ones individualistic. Public transport links bits of a city for pedestrians, while roads slice it up. You can't revive the cities and bow to the dominance of the car." Even given the new plans for the centre of London, Britain is well behind Europe in pedestrianising parts of its cities. Eventually, though, it will have to catch up.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836607600,iss">Search</a>
