<html><head><title>Victory for Nelson</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Victory for Nelson</h1>
<p>THE government is at last thinking of pedestrianising two of the most public of London's public places, Trafalgar and Parliament Squares. At a recent meeting John Gummer, who is the minister for London as well as environment secretary, Sir George Young, the transport minister, Steven Norris, one of his junior ministers, Jocelyn Stevens, chairman of English Heritage and officials from Westminster Council, agreed that a feasibility study should be commissioned. That will probably start in November, and take around a year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The idea--since it is an obvious one--has been mooted many times before. However, according to Paul Drury of English Heritage, all previous studies have assumed that a scheme would have to be able to deal with the existing traffic flow. None of them, therefore, has worked. The big change is that politicians and local officials now seem ready to see drivers suffer a little.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The two squares will probably not be pedestrianised altogether. Cars will still be allowed through on one or two sides to minimise the effect on the traffic flow. But enough will be closed off so that they cease to be massive roundabouts and return to their former state: piazza-style places for people to relax, parade and meet. The scheme will also reclaim for the public Horseguards' Parade, one of the most beautiful pieces of urban space in Europe, which is currently used as a car park by the Ministry of Defence and the Foreign Office.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;London has lagged a long way behind most European capitals in removing traffic from the most beautiful bits of its centre. "Democracy is different here," explains Malcolm Murray-Clark, Westminster's assistant transport director. "We don't have mayors to push through schemes like this." 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless, Westminster Council is trying, at last, to stand up for feet. Last year, it pedestrianised the area in front of Buckingham Palace, where an average of 20 accidents a week were taking place as motorists collided with tourists. There was a furore from drivers, and a barrage of hostile questions in the House of Commons. But fewer tourists now get run over, and the muttering has died down. After that victory, the council is moving on to greater things.


</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836607600,iss">Search</a>
