<html><head><title>Poor politicians</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Parliamentary pay</b></p>
<h1>Poor politicians</h1>


NOTHING is more certain to provoke hostile tabloid headlines than politicians voting themselves a juicy pay rise. Britain's politicians are already widely portrayed as a sleazy bunch of self-servers who milk their public office for all they can get. Yet, it seems, the Senior Salaries Review Board, which advises the government on the remuneration of judges, military top brass, senior civil servants and <font size=-1>MP</font>s, has recommended a 26% pay rise for ordinary backbenchers, a 49% rise for cabinet ministers, and a thumping 70% increase for the prime minister. If this is agreed by <font size=-1>MP</font>s (not a certainty), it would take effect in July 1997.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The proposed pay rise is not quite as generous as it seems. The review board wants to slash the generous mileage allowances <font size=-1>MP</font>s get for car travel to and from their constituencies. But, in any case, there is a strong case for paying British politicians more. Since 1979, ordinary <font size=-1>MP</font>s have seen their pay rise by 34% in real terms. However, the real average earnings of the whole workforce have risen by 45%. The money the prime minister receives on top of his basic parliamentary salary is actually worth 1% less in real terms than it was in 1979. As the chart shows, John Major and his predecessor Margaret (now Lady) Thatcher have shown admirable restraint.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Restoring pay ratios to their 1979 levels would mean raising backbenchers' pay to &#163;36,812 a year (compared with the &#163;34,085 they get now) and the prime minster's to &#163;85,695 (from &#163;58,557). The rises now proposed are bigger, giving backbenchers &#163;43,000 and the prime minister &#163;143,000. This is probably justified, assuming it is desirable to attract high quality people into Parliament and to give them as little reason as possible to do well-paid work on the side. Idealists may argue that public service should not be the product of market forces. Realists point out that pay for top jobs has risen much faster than average earnings, and that <font size=-1>MP</font>s have missed out entirely. To restore the 1979 ratio of the prime minister's pay to that of the highest-paid director of British Gas, Mr Major would need to earn &#163;373,500 (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). And who could deny he deserves it?


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836607600,iss">Search</a>
