<html><head><title>New destination?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>London Underground</b></p>
<h1>New destination?</h1>

<p>TO THE average passenger on London's underground railway, privatisation probably conjures up images of huge salaries for fat-cat bosses, instant profits to share-buying punters and (less justifiably) low quality and high prices. Many passengers would not regard privatisation as the obvious way to bring an end to the strikes--now as regular a part of the summer season as tennis at Wimbledon--that on June 27th and July 3rd severely disrupted services (with more disruption promised). Yet selling the Tube is the answer.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although privatisation has had many different goals, from boosting government finances to widening share-ownership, it was first proposed by the Tories as a way to curb the power of public-sector trade unions. Public ownership gave unions more clout in pay negotiations because they knew that nationalised industries, with the government's resources behind them, would not go bust even if they lost a fortune as a result of strikes. Privatisation, by allowing bankruptcy and reducing the chance of a state bailout, would concentrate workers' and managers' minds, argued the Tories.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;History has proved them right. Days lost to the economy from industrial action have fallen to barely 1% of the total in 1979, and, along with reforms to labour law, privatisation played a crucial part. Since being sold, notoriously strike-prone industries such as steel, coal and car making have barely experienced industrial action. Some of the businesses still subject to disputes are state-owned, including the Tube and the Post Office (also currently strike-affected and crying out to be sold). True, privatisation is no cure-all. But when strikes are threatened, as they are now at British Airways, disputes have mostly been settled fast, with the threat usually unexercised.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Stephen Glaister, an economist at the London School of Economics and a former board member of London Transport, London Underground's parent company, reckons that the best way to sell the Tube would be to auction franchises to run individual lines (Bakerloo, Jubilee, etc). Although the entire system could be sold as a single firm, incentives for greater efficiency would be greatest if each line were sold separately, enabling their performances to be compared. Managers currently have little incentive to provide a better service, says Mr Glaister. Running costs have crept higher on the Tube, whereas on London's buses, which are competitively tendered to private firms, real unit costs have been cut by half over the past ten years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A sale would not be a money-spinner for the government. London Underground earns a profit but, as with the sale of British Rail, investors would want guaranteed finance for the extra investment (perhaps &#163;5 billion) that will be needed in the next few years. Sadly, without the incentive for the government of juicy sale proceeds, and given the public's deep dislike of privatisation, it seems unlikely that the Tube will be sold anytime soon. Expect strikes to remain part of the London summer.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836607600,iss">Search</a>
