<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><b>Poor law</b> &nbsp;The government unveiled plans to end free legal aid by making all applicants, even benefit claimants, pay a minimum contribution at the start of the case. They would also risk paying their opponents' legal costs if they lose.</p>
<p><b>Still standing</b> &nbsp;Sir George Gardiner, a Eurosceptic Tory <font size=-1>MP</font>, was reselected to fight the Reigate parliamentary seat at the next general election. He had threatened to wipe out the government's majority if not reselected by resigning and causing a by-election.</p>
<p><b>Feelgood</b> &nbsp;Figures were published showing that real personal incomes are rising at the strongest rate since 1989, and that manufacturing output is rising for the first time in six months.</p>
<p><b>Trade boost</b> &nbsp;Other official figures put Britain's balance of payments deficit last year at &#163;2.9 billion--half the amount in earlier estimates.</p>
<p><b>Bomb attack</b> &nbsp;A suspected <font size=-1>IRA</font> mortar attack on a British army base in Germany caused no casualties.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Helping hand</b> &nbsp;Government plans to deny welfare benefits to asylum-seekers suffered a narrow defeat in the House of Lords as bishops voted with the opposition to give immigrants more time to claim refugee status.</p>
<p><b>Scorcher</b> &nbsp;Southern England will have the climate of the Champagne region in 25 years and the Bordeaux region in 50 years as the climate in Europe moves 150 miles north, according to a Department of the Environment report.</p>
<p><b>Bowing out</b> &nbsp;Alex Carlile, the Liberal Democrats' leader in Wales, will stand down as an <font size=-1>MP</font> at the general election to spend more time with his sick daughter.</p>
<p><b>There's gratitude</b> &nbsp;A man suffering from cancer has been granted legal aid to sue doctors because his survival flouted their predictions.</p>
<p><b>Food for thought</b> &nbsp;The opening night of an art exhibition in Middlesbrough was spoiled by a visitor who ate the noses of five sculptures in a sequence of faces cast in jelly.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
