<html><head><title>SuperPsionic</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Mobile computing</b></p>
<h1>SuperPsionic</h1>

<p>GLORIOUS things of Psion are spoken by the businessmen who use its Series 3 electronic organisers. They effuse about the British company's miniature computers in much the same way that their predecessors raved about the product's paper precursor, the Filofax. Last year Psion sold 350,000 of the machines, which pack diary, address book and other computer tools for the slim-fingered into a plastic shell a little larger than a spectacles case. That is about a third of total world sales of such "palmtop" computers--more than either Sharp Electronics or Hewlett-Packard account for.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Psion's net profits rose 77% last year to &#163;7.5m ($11.8m) on sales of &#163;90.5m, 48% up on 1994. Its market capitalisation has trebled in the past year to &#163;304m. Dataquest, a consultancy, expects the market for palmtop computers to grow to 6m a year by 2000. So what is this rare paragon of British high technology doing sniffing around Amstrad? The latter, a shop-worn consumer-electronics firm, has been sputtering downwards since a burst of glory in the mid-1980s when it sold Britain's first cheap <font size=-1>IBM</font>-compatible <font size=-1>PC</font>s. Yet Psion's chairman, David Potter, seems close to paying around &#163;230m for the company.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Amstrad, which made a net loss of &#163;4.6m on sales of &#163;162m in the last six months of 1995, has three main divisions. Amstrad Consumer Electronics (<font size=-1>ACE</font>), the rump of the 1980s company, is a grab-bag of television, cheap hi-fi and video businesses that loses money. Viglen is a profitable direct-sales <font size=-1>PC</font>-manufacturer. And Dancall is a mobile-phone business. From Psion's point of view, <font size=-1>ACE</font> is useless and Viglen is pretty irrelevant. But Dancall has exactly what Mr Potter is after.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dancall was one of the first companies to use the Global System for Mobiles (<font size=-1>GSM</font>), a European communications standard, in its digital mobile phones, of which it now sells 70,000 a month. Psion is convinced that it needs digital-communication technology if it is to keep abreast of the way palmtop computing is developing, towards machines (which have started to appear) that are as much communications devices as organisers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Series 3 is now five years old: despite its popularity, it no longer has a clear design or technological advantage over rivals with richer parents. The new generation of palmtops will have to do more than work well alone; they will have to bind their owners into the Internet, and share information with computers at work and at home. Many companies, including Psion, think that the ambitious businessman will want his two favourite tools, palmtop and mobile telephone, in one package.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Is this true? On balance, the marriage of the palmtop and the telephone does indeed look inevitable, but it may have a rocky start. A combined phone-palmtop will be much bigger and heavier than the palmtop, much of whose value stems from its portability. One doubter, Kimball Brown, an analyst at Dataquest, cites BellSouth's unsuccessful Simon, a phone-organiser that flopped last year, as an example of the folly of doubling up.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, the main reason why Simon failed was because it did not work well, rather than because the concept was a dud. Nokia's version of a palmtop-telephone, released in March, has received warm reviews--despite a price of $1,100.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if Psion is right to aim for a palmtop-phone combination, does it really need to buy a whole phone company (let alone a big, famously complicated consumer-products group)? Psion argues that any combined palmtop-communicator will need to integrate computing and telephone technologies so thoroughly that its developers need access to both. Designers, it says, will have to focus on minia-turisation and power management from the start in order to produce a device that, like the Series 3, is small but does not run out of zip within minutes of leaving home.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This explanation is not entirely convincing. Hewlett-Packard has collaborated with Nokia, a Finnish phone maker, to produce its OmniGo palmtop-cum-telephone. Would not a temporary partnership with another <font size=-1>GSM</font> company--for instance Ericsson, a Swedish mobile-telephone maker--work just as well for Psion?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, Psion has got where it is by marching steadily and doing a relatively simple thing extremely well. It has let others--notably Apple with its ill-fated Newton--show off, and then fail. Perhaps it was inevitable that, one day, Psion would have to make a bold takeover of one sort or another. All the same, Amstrad seems to be an unnecessarily tough test, even for the redoubtable Mr Potter.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836607600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="wb2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
