<html><head><title>From couch potato to cybersurfer</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>From couch potato to cybersurfer</h1>
<p><b>A flaw of the Internet is that most home users lack a high-speed means of using it. A series of articles on competing solutions to this problem starts this week by looking at the efforts of the cable-TV companies</b></p>


<p>THERE is something about a computer modem, with its winking lights and noisy squeal of battle with the telephone line's 19th-century analogue technology, that deadens the souls of Internet surfers. With their screens frozen as pages from the World Wide Web trickle slowly down a telephone line, they dream of the day when home computers will be connected straight into the Internet through a fat digital pipe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In America, cable-television companies, telephone companies and satellite and wireless firms are competing to provide that pipe. Three technologies contending to become the Internet's "on-ramp" of choice are "x<font size=-1>DSL</font>" digital phone lines, digital satellites, and wireless. This article looks at a fourth contender: the "cable modems" on offer from the <font size=-1>TV</font> companies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because all these solutions look technically sound so far, the battle is only partly technological. Much also depends on economics. In this respect, the cable-television companies start with two big advantages. In America, nearly two-thirds of homes are already subscribers (see <a href="st1.gif">chart</a>). And unlike telephone companies, which reach into homes via twisted copper wires, the <font size=-1>TV</font> companies deliver their signals on a coaxial cable capable of carrying 40 or so <font size=-1>TV</font> channels.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Like telephones, however, almost all cable networks are analogue. To unleash their digital potential requires a modem to convert the incoming analogue signal into digital data, and vice versa. And if it is to take advantage of the available capacity, this modem must carry data up to 1,000 times faster than the 33,000 bits per second (bps) of the best telephone modems.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More than a dozen companies have started producing cable modems (as these new devices are called) at a typical cost of between $300 and $500. Cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> companies are, naturally, wild about them. The leading cable suppliers--<font size=-1>TCI</font>, Comcast, Time-Warner and Cox--have already ordered 650,000 between them, and plan to start deploying them later this year. They see the prospect of big, badly needed revenues. Having taken on billions of dollars of debt to build their networks, they need new ways to milk their investment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble is that selling fast Internet access is not as simple as buying cable modems by the boatload. Cable networks were designed to broadcast signals to the home, not to carry data back the other way. Before they can handle two-way traffic, they must be upgraded.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is tricky. The networks are laid out, roughly, in the shape of a tree--with branches going to each home. For television, this works splendidly. Every customer receives the same signal, which is sent out along the trunk and then along the branches. But Internet users will be viewing different things at different times. And although coaxial cable can carry enough Internet data for one house, or even a few hundred, it cannot serve the needs of a whole city. To prevent the trunks of the tree becoming hopelessly crowded, coaxial cable must be replaced with something more capacious.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That something is optical fibre. As it happens, most cable companies have already been upgrading their main trunks to fibre, both because it is more reliable and because it lets them offer more channels. In the affluent areas where firms plan to offer Internet services first, virtually all of the networks are already a hybrid of fibre and coaxial cable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To complete the upgrade, firms need to add switching and routing equipment to direct the correct information to each house, to "tighten" the network with filters to cut noise, and to extend the main branches in order to cut the number of customers each must support.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If offering Internet access over cable were no more difficult than this, most companies would be doing it already. But the few that have tried have run into technical troubles with noise. Again, the problem is the tree-and-branch structure.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Each branch to an individual home introduces a bit of noise, despite the coaxial cable and filter. Because the branches are separate, none of the cable modems in each home can hear the noise from the others. But the trunk hears the noise from them all. So, while "downstream" data (from the Internet to the home) can travel at top speed, "upstream" data must fight the noise of the entire system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This thwarted the first generation of cable modems. Designed to operate at 10m bps, they could barely manage a few hundred. The latest versions, however, can identify a noisy frequency on the line and avoid it, or simply re-send data that have been disrupted. Sending data upstream is still a problem, but most networks should soon be able to handle 2m bps of it. Since home users usually generate little more than a bit of e-mail and a few data requests, that should probably be plenty.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the tree-and-branch structure has another disadvantage: the trunk's capacity gets spread between its branches. Most cable networks have neighbourhood hubs that serve an average of about 300 customers. Such a hub may be able to deliver data at 10m-20m bps, but that must be shared by all its users.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Simulations by CableLabs, the industry's research consortium, suggest that customers would start to feel the drop in capacity when they had to share it with about 100 others. The cable companies' answer to this is that by the time they sign up that many subscribers in any neighbourhood, they will be earning enough to add another cable to the node, thus doubling the capacity available.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The remaining objections to the cable companies' Internet ambitions are not technical. They are that these firms are notorious for unreliable television service, know little about managing interactive networks, and have none of the telephone companies' experience in billing customers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fortunately for prospective customers, however, someone else will be doing most of these jobs. A firm called @Home, co-owned by three of America's biggest cable operators, is setting up a national "backbone" network to connect many of the largest regional cable networks to the Internet, and will handle most of the network-management and billing problems.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Altogether, the infrastructure needed to bring a cable company into the Internet business will cost it about $500-700 a customer. Of the $40-50 a month they hope to charge for the service (including the lease of the cable modem and some Internet content), they might keep $10 at best. On its own, this might not look like much of a lure. But the same network upgrades will allow the cable firms to offer telephony, plus 150 or more channels of digital television.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With America's local telephone market newly opened to competition, long-distance telephone companies are keen to join up with the cable firms to challenge local telephone companies. No wonder the locals rubbish cable's Internet chances. Their own chances will be the subject of next week's brief.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836607600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
