<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Private means</h2>
<p><b></B>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>Privatisation revenues around the world dipped in 1995, but the urge to privatise is strengthening again. Top floaters in 1995 were Australia ($9.4 billion), Italy ($7.2 billion) and France ($5.7 billion). Germany this year will raise $16.9 billion, $10 billion of that by selling part of Deutsche Telekom, its telecoms monopoly. Outside the <font size=-1>OECD</font>, Eastern Europe raised $4.5 billion in 1995. Revenues in Latin America, which fell to $2 billion in 1995, are growing again.</p>
<p>One of America's food giants, <b>Nabisco</b>, is cutting 4,200 jobs from its 54,000-strong workforce around the world and taking a $428m pre-tax charge in the second quarter that will knock out most of its profits for the year. But Nabisco reckons the restructuring will save it $50m this year, $160m next and $200m annually after that.</p>
<p>Sweden's <b>Astra</b>, a pharmaceutics firm, fired Lars Bildman, the head of its American subsidiary, after investigating allegations that he had behaved "inappropriately" at company parties and had used company funds for holidays and home renovations. Mr Bildman denies the allegations.</p>
<p>The original $20 billion merger of equals between two of America's Baby Bell telephone companies has been restructured so that <b>Bell Atlantic </b>is now, in effect, buying <b>Nynex</b>. The change is being made to avoid the need for regulatory approval in each of 13 states, and in the District of Columbia, where approval looked slow in coming.</p>
<p><b>America Online</b>'s new president and chief operating officer quit after only four months. William Razzouk said he was reluctant to shift his family from Tennessee to Virginia. Steve Case, chairman and chief executive, takes over for the time being. Meanwhile, he faces an embarrassing investigation into the firm's billing practices. The firm's share price weakened.</p>
<p>Britain's <b>Alan Sugar</b>, a technology entrepreneur, could soon be devoting even more time to his football club, Tottenham Hotspur, if a &#163;234m ($361m) deal being considered by Psion to buy his Amstrad company comes about. Psion reckons Amstrad's digital-telephone unit (minus its tired computer business) would be useful for introducing communications technology into its hand-held computers. Amstrad's shares rose on the news, but Psion's fell.</p>
<p>Managers everywhere trembled as id Software, whose hit computer game,<b> Doom</b>, became 1994's favourite corporate time-waster, released the long-awaited sequel, <b>Quake</b>. The Internet sizzled as Doomaholics raced to download a free version.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>An upheaval in France's <b>hypermarkets</b> seemed likely after Auchan launched a FFr16.3 billion ($3.2 billion) takeover bid for a reluctant Docks de France, owners of Mammouth. After the signing of a recent law designed to limit the spread of hypermarkets, further consolidation seems the only way to grow. The combined firm would have sales of some FFr111 billion, still making it only the fifth biggest distribution group in France.</p>
<h2>Acquisitive</h2>
<p>Britain's biggest life-assurance company, <b>Prudential</b>, is planning a global &#163;1.5 billion ($2.3 billion) flotation of its Mercantile &amp; General reinsurance unit. Shedding capital-eating <font size=-1>M&G</font> and concentrating on its core activities of life assurance and retail banking should help to restore Prudential's flagging share price--and give it cash to buy a building society or another life assurer.</p>
<p><b>Morgan Stanley</b> is paying $745m for Van Kampen American Capital and assuming $430m of debt as the American investment bank further expands its asset-management activities. The acquisition will take its total assets under management to $157 billion, consolidating its number two position among Wall Street brokers, behind only Merrill Lynch.</p>
<p>Continuing repercussions from the <b>Sumitomo scandal</b>, in which a dealer ran up $1.8 billion in copper losses over ten years, dragged copper prices to 2.5-year lows on worries that Sumitomo was starting to shed some of its vast stocks of the metal. Sumitomo held its annual general meeting behind closed doors.</p>
<p><b>Banque Nationale de Paris </b>rejected a FFr4.25 billion ($822m) offer from <font size=-1>SBC</font> Warburg to buy its 84% stake in Companie d'Investissements de Paris, a holding company. Warburg was trying to make a point: its offer of FFr205 a share was in response to what it reckoned was the bank's low offer of FFr180 a share for Warburg's 3% holding in <font size=-1>CIP</font>.</p>
<h2>Striving</h2>
<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>The Italian lira is testing the 1,000 level against the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark, its best showing in nearly two years. Gains have been strong since the election in April of a new prime minister, Romano Prodi, who wants the lira back in the European exchange-rate mechanism, and a central bank keen to have a strong lira in the fight against inflation.</p>
<p><p>Germany's economics ministry expressed doubts about an <b>upturn in the economy</b> this year when real <font size=-1>GDP</font> contracted by 0.5% in the first quarter after two quarters without any growth. Even so, some indicators were more positive, and inflation in the western half of the country slowed to 1.2% in June on a year-on-year basis.</p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
