<html><head><title>Buy British?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>The defence industry</b></p>
<h1>Buy British?</h1>

<p>IT IS a big moment for Britain's defence companies. The Ministry of Defence is about to award a clutch of contracts, worth some &#163;4 billion. The ministry's decisions on cruise missiles, anti-tank weapons, maritime patrol aircraft and amphibious assault vessels will cast some light on its policy towards the defence industry--a policy which has, for the past year, seemed murky.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That policy was fairly clear from the mid-1980s to the early 1990s: the overriding aim was value for money, the principal means was competitive tendering, and confrontation between defence companies and the ministry was normal. Then Roger Freeman, procurement minister in 1994 and 1995, shifted the stance so that the long-term future of the British defence industry and the need to promote pan-European restructuring counted for more. The Department of Trade and Industry became more involved in decisions, and the National Defence Industrial Council--a gathering of business chiefs and officials, chaired by the secretary of state for defence--was revived.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since James Arbuthnot became procurement minister a year ago, policy has appeared to lurch in all directions. The government bought American Apache attack helicopters, rather than the Franco-German Tiger. But then it decided to join the French and the Germans in developing a new multi-role armoured vehicle, and in creating an agency to manage such multinational projects. Crude nationalism came to the fore in January, when the government bought battlefield ambulances from Rover, although its procurement executive found that Austrian Steyr vehicles were more reliable and better value.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The broad thrust of Mr Arbuthnot's policy is probably similar to that of Mr Freeman, although he expresses it with masterful equivocation. Mr Arbuthnot has continued to involve the Department of Trade and Industry and has given the industrial council some real work to do, such as proposing rules for the new European armaments agency. "Where some see blur in procurement policy, we see pragmatism, which is fine," says a manager at British Aerospace, praising the government's new willingness to discuss issues with defence companies, and its lack of dogmatism.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His company feels chirpy: understandably so, given that it has a good chance of winning two big contracts. Seven firms are competing to supply the <font size=-1>RAF</font> with a cruise missile that its bombers will be able to launch several hundred miles from a target. The Hughes Air Hawk and the McDonnell Douglas Grand Slam are strong American contenders for this &#163;650m contract, while Taurus, from Germany's Daimler-Benz, is a low-cost option. But the favourite is Stormshadow from British Aerospace and France's Matra--if only because, if chosen, the French government would unblock a merger between the missile businesses of these two firms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The two front-runners in the &#163;700m competition for anti-tank missiles, <font size=-1>GEC</font> and Hunting Engineering, are both British. And <font size=-1>GEC</font> is certain to win a &#163;600m contract for two amphibious vessels, through its newly acquired <font size=-1>VSEL</font> subsidiary. <font size=-1>GEC</font> would also supply the electronics for Lockheed Martin's Orion <font size=-1>2000</font>, a propeller-driven contender for the maritime patrol aircraft. However, British Aerospace, which is offering to refurbish old Nimrod jets with Boeing electronics, is expected to win that &#163;2 billion contract.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is likely that British firms will fare well in these competitions, and American firms poorly. That would not merely confirm the ministry's "pragmatic" policy and the proximity of a general election. It would also send a firm message to the Americans: if you want the British market to remain as open as it has been, lower your own protectionist barriers. American firms have had $6 billion of British armaments orders in the past 18 months, but the Pentagon has bought nothing of substance from Britain.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However these competitions go, British firms will continue to call for the government to do more to encourage European companies to restructure. Dick Evans, British Aerospace's chief executive, has asked the government to help reshape the industry through its procurement decisions, and to hold fewer competitive tenders.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Arbuthnot maintains that "restructuring in Europe has to be driven by companies. It is up to them to seek the rationalisation that makes the best commercial sense." He frets that the absence of large cross-border mergers--and so of rationalisation--means that European industry is becoming uncompetitive. As he inelegantly puts it, "The companies have got to pull their finger out," adding, "but we can't say that this or that merger should go ahead."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some industrialists find that view disingenuous, given that the ministry buys 80% of what British defence firms make. While the industry and the government blame each other for the lack of pan-European restructuring, American defence firms are becoming more competitive by merging and cutting spare capacity--a task made easier by the fact that they have only one government to deal with.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836002800,iss">Search</a>
