<html><head><title>Initiative test</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Public spending</b></p>
<h1>Initiative test</h1>

<p>LAUNCHED as a way to lure private money into public projects in 1992, the "Private Finance Initiative" (<font size=-1>PFI</font>) is proving a struggle for the government. Cheerful forecasts of the value of projects "about to be signed" have turned out to be hugely optimistic. Ask private-sector firms about the <font size=-1>PFI</font>, and if they have tried bidding under it they will usually complain. On June 26th the government mounted a fierce defence of the initiative against criticisms by an all-party committee of backbench <font size=-1>MP</font>s who worry that it might make the public sector's accounts more opaque than ever. A minister insisted that "the <font size=-1>PFI</font> is here to stay". As Labour is even keener than the Tories to get the private sector to pay for its ambitious plans, that is probably true. Whether it is desirable is another matter.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Certainly, the <font size=-1>PFI</font> does now seem to be gathering pace. The value of projects currently agreed exceeds &#163;5 billion. Contracts to design, build and operate prisons, roads and public buildings have been signed recently. The government believes it has finally laid to rest concerns about who will pick up the tab for hospitals built under the <font size=-1>PFI</font> if an <font size=-1>NHS</font> trust goes bankrupt. The answer is: the government will. Hospital deals are "imminent".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The initiative is also being seen, for the first time, as a serious money-making opportunity by big investors. This is reflected in the recent appointment of Alastair Ross Goobey to chair the Private Finance Panel, a Treasury-sponsored body established to promote <font size=-1>PFI</font> projects. Considered a safe pair of hands, Mr Ross Goobey runs Hermes, which manages the enormous pension-fund assets of <font size=-1>BT</font> and the Post Office. In January, Hermes established the &#163;50m Innisfree <font size=-1>PFI</font> Fund, with <font size=-1>AMP</font>, an Australian insurer. Since then, similar funds have been launched by <font size=-1>CIBC</font>, a Canadian bank, and, on June 24th, by Charterhouse, a London investment bank.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;According to David Metter, chief executive of the Innisfree fund, one of the biggest problems with the <font size=-1>PFI</font> so far is that the main bidders for projects have been construction firms, which are used to being paid for projects as they go along and thus do not need, or have, much capital. As a result, they have been reluctant to take on equity-type risk from the government, and contracts have tended to resemble hire-purchase deals with contractors competing primarily on construction costs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new funds will provide the missing equity, which should ideally account for around 10% of the private finance invested in public projects, says Mr Metter. This would enable the private-sector to take on large amounts of the "volume risk" now mostly borne by the government--for instance, on how many cars will use a privately financed road. But if this is to happen, says Mr Metter, the government must become willing to structure the payments on <font size=-1>PFI</font> contracts to suit equity rather than debt, particularly by allowing "equity-style" (ie, big) profits when things go well.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The more <font size=-1>PFI</font> projects are undertaken, the greater the need for them to be effectively measured in the public sector's accounts. One of the biggest attractions of the <font size=-1>PFI</font> to politicians is that it allows projects to be bought now and paid for later. Traditionally they would have been paid for now and so added to current government spending and to the public-sector borrowing requirement (<font size=-1>PSBR</font>)--the measure that the financial markets regard as the best guide to whether the government is spending prudently. The Treasury argues that the <font size=-1>PFI</font> allows only projects that save money compared with using traditional public finance, and that involve a significant transfer of risk from the government to the public sector. <font size=-1>PSBR</font>-evading deals, in which the government in effect leases an asset from the private sector but continues to bear all the risk, are not allowed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble is, as the House of Commons Treasury Committee pointed out in April, the public sector's accounts shed little light on whether the Treasury is sticking by its claims. On June 25th the Treasury responded by promising to include measures of additional spending commitments resulting from the <font size=-1>PFI</font> in its future three-year forecasts (though the main impact of many projects will be felt much further into the future).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the long term, it is possible that these worries will be eased by the planned adoption of "resource accounting" . This will create a public-sector balance sheet and thus (potentially) reduce the significance of the <font size=-1>PSBR</font> as financial markets will instead focus on overall changes in the government's assets and liabilities. As yet, however, it is far from certain that resource accounting will adequately reflect <font size=-1>PFI</font> commitments and so prevent politicians using the initiative to deceive voters about the true state of government finances. Suspicion of the <font size=-1>PFI</font> as a potential politicians' fiddle is still justified.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836002800,iss">Search</a>
