<html><head><title>The rabbit and the pick-up truck</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Software</b></p>
<h1>The rabbit and the pick-up truck</h1>
<p><b>Once, it looked as though the Internet was Netscape's territory. Astonishingly, Microsoft has now caught up with its upstart competitor</b></p>

<p>LAST December, Bill Gates, Microsoft's boss, called analysts and journalists to his headquarters in Redmond, Washington, to confess the errors of his ways. The world's biggest software company had almost missed the most important event in the computer industry since the birth of the <font size=-1>PC</font>: the rise of the Internet. While Microsoft had snoozed, an upstart called Netscape Communications had created a massive new market in Internet-navigating "browser" software (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Microsoft, Mr Gates insisted, could learn these new wired ways just as quickly as any young software pretender. This looked unlikely. After all, 15 years before, the computing industry's giants had said exactly the same thing about the <font size=-1>PC</font>--and then proceeded to fail miserably. Just as companies such as <font size=-1>IBM</font> had once been fixated by mainframe computers, so Microsoft seemed to be fixated on the <font size=-1>PC</font>. In a business as remorselessly Darwinian as this, it seemed only fitting that Microsoft should give way to a new breed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Netscape was set up in 1994 by Marc Andreessen, a 24-year-old with Gatesian qualities, and Jim Clark, a veteran of the computer industry. In a mere two years, it has distributed 38m copies of its browser, Navigator, making it the most successful software launch in computing history. Until recently, analysts reckoned Netscape had perhaps a year's lead over its competition--a long time in a market where cycles are said to be measured in "dog years", seven for one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now, only six months later, Microsoft may have proved its point. On June 21st Microsoft released an arcane snippet of software that adds the ability to run a must-have Internet computer language called Java to Microsoft's own browser, Internet Explorer. With every company in the industry spewing out new Internet software once a week, this would not normally count for much. But the Java release is significant.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With Java, Microsoft's Internet Explorer now matches Netscape's Navigator virtually feature for feature. Navigator can do a few things (mostly those used only by the most demanding users) Explorer cannot; but the reverse is true, too. The important thing is that, from the average consumer's point of view, there is no longer any significant difference between the two. Just six months after Mr Gates's call to arms, Microsoft has caught up with Netscape's flagship product.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is more to the war between these two than the browser battle. Netscape still retains a lead over Microsoft in some other sorts of Internet software, particularly "servers" that run the big computers that store information for the Internet's World Wide Web. But the browser sits at the heart of Netscape's empire.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Netscape made its name by giving away Navigator, with the hope that its popularity would help it to sell lots of server software, which can make the most of the browser's features. The give-away strategy worked better than anyone dared hope (within months it had around 85% of the market), but sales of server software lagged. So Netscape changed tack: it now charges $50 for its browser, and browser sales make up 60% of its revenues.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now, that $50 is the principal difference between the browsers because Microsoft's Explorer is free; Microsoft is shipping it with most new <font size=-1>PC</font>s. Moreover, the two main commercial on-line services--America Online (see <a href="wb2.html">page</a>) and CompuServe--are preparing to distribute Explorer as their main browser. In recent months Microsoft's market share has crept from almost nothing to more than 7%, according to Dataquest, a consultancy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, Microsoft does not need to take much of the browser market from Netscape to do it harm. Netscape maintains its grip on the market by endlessly introducing innovations, which then become industry standards. Last year, for example, Netscape introduced a much-needed way to create tables of information on the Web. Because most users had Netscape browsers, owners of Web sites could be confident that, if they added tables, most readers would be able to read them. John Robb of Forrester Research, a Cambridge, Massachusetts consultancy, reckons that Web-site owners would be less co-operative if Microsoft were to gain more than about 20% of the market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That prospect will become more likely as Microsoft incorporates browser functions into the next generation of its operating systems in the coming year or so. Mr Gates's ultimate aim is to eliminate the stand-alone browser market altogether--just as he has in effect destroyed the market for other once-independent programs, from utilities to simple fax software, that are now part of his operating system.

<p><b>Splat?
</b><br>
All this counts as a sizeable achievement for Mr Gates (who gushes about his Internet project as "the most fun six-month period I've had ever since the start of Microsoft"). Last year, many in the industry greeted his Internet promises with a sceptical "put up or shut up" . Microsoft has now emphatically put up. The next move is therefore Netscape's.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The smaller firm is not defenceless. Given a choice between similar products, many Netscape users will stay with what they know. Netscape's products tend to run on a greater variety of computers and operating systems, from the Macintosh to <font size=-1>UNIX</font> machines, than do Microsoft's, which tend to favour its own Windows 95 (although that comes with more than 70% of new computers). And there are still a few techie features, including a way for other companies to make their software work with Netscape's browser, that Microsoft has not yet matched.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Netscape will bolster these defences by releasing new software and standards later this year that will make Internet video, audio and other multimedia faster and more universal. And the next versions of its browser will come loaded with everything from an Internet telephone to collaboration software. But there are now some signs that users are rebelling against the rush of change--much of it only half thought through--in Internet software. About half of Netscape users are still using the first version of its browser, having declined to take either of the two subsequent versions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Jim Barksdale, Netscape's homespun chief executive, likens his company's position to a rabbit, about to be run down by a speeding pick-up truck. Just when it is about it be squashed, it leaps over the nearest hedge instead. Netscape is indeed more nimble than Microsoft; but the truck has drawn much closer.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836002800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="wb2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
