<html><head><title>The key to immunity?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>The key to immunity?</h1>

<p>TO DO its damage, <font size=-1>HIV</font> must first get into the lymphocytes it damages. An important detail of how it does so has been clarified by a series of discoveries published over the past fortnight. These results also hint at the way in which the bodies of the lucky few who seem unable to catch <font size=-1>AIDS</font> are able to keep the virus out--in other words how the immune system might, itself, be able to remain immune from the attentions of <font size=-1>HIV</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It has been known for ten years that one molecular lock which <font size=-1>HIV</font> must open to get into <font size=-1>T</font>-cells is a protein called <font size=-1>CD4</font>. Having this protein distinguishes so-called "helper" <font size=-1>T</font>-cells, which act as cheer-leaders for other parts of the immune system, from "killer" <font size=-1>T</font>-cells, which destroy cells that are infected with viruses or bacteria (the equivalent protein in killer cells is called <font size=-1>CD8</font>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>CD4</font> is a form of molecular Velcro. It allows helper cells to attach themselves to other cells of the immune system in order to pass on their messages of encouragement. Unfortunately, it also allows <font size=-1>HIV</font> particles to enter helper cells themselves. It has also been known for some time, though, that <font size=-1>CD4</font> is not enough for <font size=-1>HIV</font> to gain access to a cell. At least one other lock must be turned.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One of these extra locks now appears to have been found. Three groups of researchers have published papers describing it over the past fortnight--Tatjana Drajic's team at Rockefeller University in New York, HongKui Deng's at New York University, and Philip Murphy's group at the National Institutes of Health, in Bethesda, Maryland. The new molecular lock rejoices in the name of <font size=-1>CC-CKR-5</font>. What is exciting is not merely its discovery, but its link with a group of messenger molecules known as chemokines. These are secreted by cells of the immune system in order to attract each other prior to the exchange of other chemical information.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last year a group at the University of Maryland, led by Robert Gallo, found that three of the chemokines now shown to be involved with <font size=-1>CC-CKR-5</font> could suppress the activity of <font size=-1>HIV</font> in cell cultures. And in April of this year, William Paxton, also at Rockefeller University, found elevated levels of these chemokines in a group of homosexual men who are still <font size=-1>HIV</font> negative despite a history of risky sexual activity. The suggestion--for it is as yet no more than that--is that by binding to the <font size=-1>CC-CKR-5</font> receptor, these chemokines make it unavailable to the virus. With this second lock jammed, it cannot find its way into the <font size=-1>T</font>-cell and the lucky possessor of the extra chemokines will remain <font size=-1>HIV</font>-free.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836002800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
