<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Yeltsin's battle</h2>
<p>President Yeltsin pipped his main rival, the Communists' Gennady Zyuganov, by 35% to 32% of the votes cast in the first round of <b>Russia's presidential election</b>. But confusion broke out after Alexander Lebed, an ex-general who came third with 15%, threw in his lot with Mr Yeltsin. Rumblings from Kremlin hardliners led to the sacking, among others, of Alexander Korzhakov, Mr Yeltsin's chief bodyguard, and talk of an attempted coup.<p>
An <b>IRA bomb </b>devastated the centre of Manchester, injuring more than 200 people and causing damage estimated at up to &#163;250m ($390m). The bomb dashed hopes that the <font size=-1>IRA</font> would call a second ceasefire to get Sinn Fein, its political wing, into multi-party talks about Northern Ireland's future.<p>
The European Commission issued a proposal for phasing out the European Union's ban on the export of <b>British beef</b>. Britain indicated it would accept it, and agreed to cull a further 25,000-67,000 cattle. Thus the scene seemed set for a deal at the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s weekend summit in Florence. Tory backbenchers, however, may object.<p>
In <b>Germany's biggest post-1945 demonstration</b>, 350,000 trade unionists turned out in Bonn to protest against austerity measures. The government allowed a small pay rise for public-sector workers after demanding a freeze and will delay a planned rise in the retirement age for women.<p>
Turkey's Islamist Welfare Party voted to reject a parliamentary corruption investigation of <b>Tansu Ciller</b>, leader of the True Path Party. The vote helps the two parties to form a government.<p>
Greece abandoned plans to cut defence spending. The defence minister said military spending would rise faster than economic growth over the next five years to counter <b>Turkish claims</b> to islands in the Aegean.<p>
<b>Latvia</b>'s strongly pro-western reformist president, Guntis Ulmanis, was re-elected by parliament to a second term.

<h2>Awash</h2>
<p>After 14 months of hearings, the final report of the Senate <b>Whitewater </b>committee claimed that Bill Clinton, while governor of Arkansas, had given "inappropriate assistance" to an Arkansas bond dealer. It also concluded that Hillary Clinton had probably played a role in limiting the investigation into the suicide of Vince Foster, a White House aide, in order to prevent potentially embarrassing documents coming to light.<p>
The gap between Mr Clinton and his Republican rival, <b>Bob Dole</b>, narrowed to six points according to a <i>Time</i>/<font size=-1>CNN</font> poll. Mr Clinton, however, retained a commanding lead in California.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
The White House said it would put a civil servant in charge of <b>security clearances</b> to avoid a recurrence of the alleged misuse of <font size=-1>FBI</font> files.<p>
Theodore Kaczynski was charged in California with four of the <b>Unabomber</b> mail-bomb attacks, two of which resulted in deaths. Pete Wilson, the governor of California, urged the federal government to seek the death penalty for him.<p>
Right-wing bandits in northern <b>Nicaragua</b> kidnapped a large party of election officials.

<h2>Trading terms</h2>
<p><b>India</b>'s new finance minister, P. Chidambaram, upset left-wing supporters of the new coalition government by announcing plans to cut public spending and streamline state-controlled firms. Separately, India said it will not sign the <b>Comprehensive Test-Ban Treaty</b>, currently under negotiation in Geneva, in its present form.<p>
A leader of Myanmar's ruling junta, Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt, called on teachers and students to "annihilate" the <b>political opposition </b>for urging foreign investors and tourists to stay away. His target was assumed to be Aung San Suu Kyi.<p>
A leaked report from America's Defence Department said that ten to 15 <b>Americans taken prisoner </b>in the war with North Korea (1950-53) may still be held. But the department said there was no "conclusive proof" that the men were alive.<p>
The Malaysian High Court ruled that a $5.5 billion dam being built in <b>Sarawak </b>was illegal because local people had not been consulted. The government refused to order work on the dam to be stopped, claiming that the ruling was a technicality that "can be rectified".

<h2>Israel's hard line</h2>
<p>Binyamin Netanyahu's new <b>Israeli government</b> was sworn in, with difficulty. Trying to please his allies, he had to backtrack to avoid a revolt from his own party, the Likud. He called for negotiations with the Arabs, with no preconditions--then set Israeli preconditions that make peace harder: no Palestinian state, continued Israeli sovereignty over Golan, and no talks on Jerusalem.<p>
Boutros Boutros-Ghali said he would seek a second term as secretary-general of the <b>United Nations</b>. The Clinton administration made it clear that it would oppose him.<p>
Amnesty International's 1996 report condemned western exporters for the growing trade in <b>instruments of torture</b>.<p>
Talks between <b>Burundi</b>'s political parties began after it was reported that some 70 Hutus had been killed by soldiers. The army claimed it had killed 50 terrorists.<p>
A ship with 400 Liberians on board reappeared at<b> Monrovia</b> after drifting off the West African coast for three weeks.<p>
<p>
<p>

</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
