<html><head><title>A message from the IRA</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>

</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<h1>A message from the IRA</h1>


<font size=1>BELFAST</font><p><b>The huge bomb which destroyed the heart of Manchester has also exposed deep divisions among Irish republicans</b></p>

THE people of Manchester have little need to ponder the meaning of the <font size=-1>IRA</font> bomb which exploded on June 15th. A vibrant city centre is in ruins, traders despair, dozens of people still suffer from pain and shock. Among more than 200 other victims, one 42-year-old woman has had seven hours of surgery in the first of a series of operations which will be required to salvage her shredded face.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But in the rest of Britain and especially in Ireland, north and south, the bomb has been greeted not just by despair, but by angry questions. What is the <font size=-1>IRA</font> up to? Have all those who have supported the so-called peace process simply been duped? Do Irish republicans want peace, or war? Americans who have backed the peace process were equally puzzled and appalled. Angry denunciations of the bomb came not just from Bill Clinton, but also from Irish-American leaders such as Senator Edward Kennedy, who had pressed Mr Clinton to get involved in the Northern Ireland issue.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The bomb seemed designed to wreck the very multi-party talks which Sinn Fein, the political wing of the <font size=-1>IRA</font>, had been demanding for so long. Indeed, the <font size=-1>IRA</font> itself had claimed that it tore up its first ceasefire, and exploded a bomb in London's Docklands because the British had refused to set a date for such talks. After years of constant negotiations between the British and Irish governments, and the personal intervention of Mr Clinton, those talks at last got under way--five days before the Manchester bomb.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The talks began acrimoniously, and Sinn Fein had been excluded. But the acrimony was predictable. And Sinn Fein was excluded only because the <font size=-1>IRA</font> had refused to declare a second ceasefire. The British and Irish governments had made huge efforts to come up with a framework for talks which would make them acceptable to nationalists, and especially to Sinn Fein. The decommissioning of terrorist weapons had been delegated to a subcommittee, so that unionists could not use the issue to torpedo talks even before they began. George Mitchell, a former American senator and close associate of Mr Clinton, whom nationalists trust, had been appointed as the talks' chairman.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There had been no bombs since April. Hopes had been rising that, eventually, a ceasefire declaration would let Sinn Fein into the talks. There was much talk of a <i>de facto</i> ceasefire. Gerry Adams and Martin McGuinness, Sinn Fein's two most prominent leaders, continued to declare that peace, and a negotiated political settlement, were their goals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And then the <font size=-1>IRA</font> exploded its bomb in Manchester, the biggest it has ever planted in England. Carnage was averted only by a hurried evacuation of thousands of Saturday morning shoppers. Miraculously, no one was killed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whatever the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s rationale for the bomb, signs of deep division within republican ranks are obvious. On June 7th an <font size=-1>IRA</font> gang shot dead Jerry McCabe, an Irish police detective, during a botched robbery in Adare in the Irish Republic. The killing shocked Ireland. Some 20,000 people, including the president and prime minister, attended Mr McCabe's funeral. For a week the <font size=-1>IRA</font> adamantly denied that any of its men had been involved. Mr Adams publicly poured scorn on those who suggested otherwise. Then, a mere half-hour before the Manchester bomb went off, the <font size=-1>IRA</font> issued a statement saying that its men had killed Mr McCabe, but that the action was "not sanctioned". For a movement which has always prided itself on its discipline, and which desperately fears splits, this was ominous.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More significantly, Sinn Fein had campaigned vigorously in May's special elections on an explicit platform of peace. "Vote for peace, vote Sinn Fein" had been its slogan. During the campaign, Mr Adams said that Sinn Fein would be willing to agree to the Mitchell principles, a commitment to exclusively peaceful methods, if other parties did so too. Of course, Mr Adams may have simply been lying, but what was the point of doing that if he knew that another bomb was only two weeks away? Sinn Fein officials frankly admit that the party's increased vote was the result of its calls for peace, and that the first <font size=-1>IRA</font> ceasefire was the most popular thing that republican leaders have ever done.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Republican supporters, even activists and former <font size=-1>IRA</font> prisoners, are as bewildered and gloomy as anyone else. Many express frustration at the slow pace of the peace process; most distrust British intentions. But few deny that the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s bombs have damaged the standing of Mr Adams and Mr McGuinness, or that the two men have lost control of the <font size=-1>IRA</font>. "I think the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s in charge of the agenda now and I don't know what that means for the Sinn Fein leadership," says one ex-prisoner.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, in the days after the Manchester bombing, Mr Adams looked like a high-wire walker struggling ever more frantically to keep his footing. He said that he wished that the bomb had not "happened" but, as with his earlier verbal convolutions over the killing of Mr McCabe, he refused to condemn it, or the <font size=-1>IRA</font>, outright. Pressed by journalists to explain the relationship between Sinn Fein and the <font size=-1>IRA</font>, he was reduced to repeating, like a mantra, the sentence: "I have told you, we are not the <font size=-1>IRA</font> and the <font size=-1>IRA</font> is not Sinn Fein."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, no one is any longer interested in such polite fictions. The leaderships of the <font size=-1>IRA</font> and Sinn Fein have been entwined for years, and still are. The Irish government put questions to Mr Adams. Had he gone to the <font size=-1>IRA</font> and asked for a ceasefire, and if not, why not? Did his party continue to support the "armed struggle" of the <font size=-1>IRA</font>? In attempting to answer both questions, Mr Adams virtually admitted that there was a deep division among republicans. "I want to see an end to armed struggle. We [Sinn Fein] are not involved in it and we do not advocate it."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the House of Commons John Major also stopped short of slamming the door irrevocably in Sinn Fein's face, instead inviting it to repudiate the bombers once and for all: "The time has come for Sinn Fein to make up its mind. Either it is going to be a democratic organisation, taking part in democratic politics, or it is going to stay side by side as the reverse coin of the <font size=-1>IRA</font>."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, what both governments were demanding was a formal and convincing split between Sinn Fein and the <font size=-1>IRA</font>, with the kind of absolute condemnations of the <font size=-1>IRA</font> which everyone could believe. Splits of that kind are familiar in the history of Irish republicanism. Mr Adams and Mr McGuinness seized the leadership of the movement after the last split among republicans in the 1970s. Another split now makes sense. Sinn Fein's leaders have spent years building support for the <font size=-1>IRA</font> ceasefire, and trying to lead republicans into multi-party talks. They have declared that the <font size=-1>IRA</font> cannot drive the British out of Northern Ireland, and that only a negotiated political settlement can resolve the conflict. They claim authorship of the "peace process". They have successfully courted support in America, Ireland and Britain for it. But, it is now obvious, they cannot deliver all the hardliners in the <font size=-1>IRA</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A split may make sense, and yet few republicans seem to think it will happen. "They will walk away from Sinn Fein before they repudiate the <font size=-1>IRA</font>," is one typical comment. If what <font size=-1>IRA</font> hardliners are trying to do is to keep Sinn Fein out of talks indefinitely, and so halt what they see as a slide towards political accommodation, they seem about to get their way.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?835398000,iss">Search</a>
