<html><head><title>A house divided</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Divorce</b></p>
<h1>A house divided</h1>

<p>IN AN attempt to please everyone, the last-minute amendments to the divorce reform bill resulted in legislation that managed to satisfy almost no one. But considering the wide range of opinion on this most intimate of issues, from staunch traditionalist to the marriage-is-oppression set, this muddled law may be a fair reflection of British values.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Family Law Bill, as it is euphemistically known, does two somewhat contradictory things. First, it asserts the value of marriage as a social institution. Second, it makes dissolving a marriage less ugly by removing the basis of fault.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Neither of these principles was changed in the months-long and often unseemly squabbling over the bill. The amendments that did pass are ornamental. One established that the waiting period between filing for divorce and dissolution would be no more than 18 months (instead of a year) for couples with children or in contested cases. Another nudged the government to take action on the division of pensions--which it was doing anyway. A third requires the government to pay for marriage counselling for couples who want it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Its effect will be to make a couple divorcing in 1998, when the bill comes into force, wait longer and jump through more hoops than they would now. On the other hand, they will not be asked to lie or cheat, and their children's interests are better protected: no divorce will be granted until the couple have settled their children's future and agreed on the division of assets. The government will pay for mediation rather than legal advice if qualifying couples decide on that course, again in the hope that divorce can be a kinder, gentler agony.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the moment, the median delay between filing for divorce and dissolution is less than seven months; for eight out of ten couples, the process takes less than a year. The new law requires every couple to wait at least a year, and those with children up to 18 months. This interval is to be used to give reconciliation a go, to simmer down, and to arrange financial and family affairs in a civil manner. Lord Mackay would like salvageable marriages to be rescued during this period, an idealistic but not wholly unrealistic hope. A study of divorced British couples found that both partners wished they had stayed married in 10% of cases. American researchers have consistently found that a third of divorced people think they have made a mistake.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The chief objection to the bill was that the removal of fault makes ending a marriage too easy. But the stigma of fault seems to be weak. Currently three-quarters of the 158,000 divorces in England and Wales each year are based on allegations of adultery or unreasonable behaviour. Couples often make up nasty tales about a spouse to speed up the process, rather than having to wait during a two-year separation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Critics also pointed to the American experience. The extension of no-fault in the 1970s has not made divorce less contentious. As David Blankenhorn of the Institute of American Values in New York notes, one increasingly common tactic is to allege horrible, unprovable things: "Whoever first says child abuse gets custody."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But America's no-fault divorce was also a no-responsibility divorce: one partner could walk and the other would have to give chase in order to settle family affairs. The Family Law Bill avoids that mistake by requiring couples to put their affairs in order before they divorce. In an ideal world, a better bill would have emerged from a less sanctimonious Commons debate--but in an ideal world, all marriages would be happy ones. This bill could have turned out a great deal worse.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?835398000,iss">Search</a>
