<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><center><p><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p><p><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p><p><font size=-1>These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.</font></p></td></tr></table></center><hr size=6 align=center width=65%><center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><p><b>Disarmed</b> &nbsp;Jonathan Aitken, a former cabinet minister, was cleared by an all-party Commons committee of wrongdoing in the arms-to-Iraq affair. Mr Aitken was a director of a firm accused of breaching the arms embargo.</p><p><b>Smoking gun</b> &nbsp;Tony Blair, Labour's leader, set out his party's health strategy. He said he would get rid of the internal market in the health service and ban tobacco advertising.</p><p><b>Child care</b> &nbsp;The government announced proposals to make it illegal for paedophiles to apply for jobs which would involve contact with children, and to create a national register of sex offenders.</p><p><b>Bill's cash</b> &nbsp;John Major criticised Lady Thatcher, his predecessor, for giving money to the European Foundation, a Eurosceptic body run by Bill Cash, a Tory backbencher.</p><p><b>Bad language</b> &nbsp;Tougher English tests for 14-year-olds were announced after a study found that there is little teaching of grammar in schools.</p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><p><b>Hot air</b> &nbsp;British Gas rejected a call from Ofgas, its regulator, for it to lower household gas bills by about &#163;30 a year by cutting the running costs of its network of pipelines. If the two sides cannot resolve the dispute, it will go to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.</p><p><b>About time</b> &nbsp;Plans to stage the giant Millennium Exhibition at Greenwich finally won enough business sponsorship for the government to allow the project to go ahead.</p><p><b>Big bang</b> &nbsp;The <i>Planet on Sunday</i>, a new newspaper devoted to environmental issues, set a record when its publisher closed it down after one issue because he did not like it.</p><p><b>Leg over</b> &nbsp;Scientists examining relics of St Chad, a 7th-century Archbishop of York, found that the casket contained three sets of leg bones. One historian suggested that the extra leg may have belonged to St Chad's brother, Cedd, who was also canonised.</p></td></tr></table></center><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?835398000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="wb1.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
