<html><head><title>Mini Mouse</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Hollywood</b></p>
<h1>Mini Mouse</h1>

<p>HOLLYWOOD is having a wonderful summer. "Summer Cum Laude" is how <i>Variety</i>, a waggish trade paper, described it. Two films, Paramount's "Mission: Impossible" and Warner Brothers' "Twister", have together taken $330m in barely a month. The first five months of the year look likely to bring in almost $2.2 billion at the American box office, 18% more than the same period last year, which was itself a record.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why, then, has Walt Disney, widely seen as a Hollywood pace-setter, chosen this moment to announce that it will halve its output of films? Joe Roth, the studio's chairman, plans to produce about 20 films a year from now on, compared with the 35 it is releasing this year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The answer is, in part, that Disney is reversing the policy it has followed under Michael Eisner since 1984 of ramping up its output of live-action films. The aim of the policy was partly to build up a library--the growth of themed television channels and of video shops has produced a lucrative demand for old films--and partly to cover the overheads of Disney's huge distribution engine, which would otherwise handle only one or two animated pictures a year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Disney has specialised in making cheapish "family" films, using fading stars or, better still, children and animals. The policy brought Disney a few hits, such as "Pretty Woman" (which starred the then-pass&eacute; Richard Gere), "Honey, I Shrunk the Kids" and "Three Men and a Baby". But, according to <font size=-1>CS</font> First Boston, an investment bank, Disney's live-action films averaged a dingy $35m in American box-office receipts between 1984 and 1994. Many recent offerings, made with irredeemable stars and creakingly low budgets, have vanished: not into valuable library stocks, but into oblivion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By contrast, eight of America's all-time top-selling home videos are Disney animated films. "The Hunchback of Notre Dame", this summer's Disney cartoon offering, cost perhaps $75m to make. The market will judge it a failure, says David Londoner of Schroder Wertheim, an investment bank in New York, if it takes only $500m over the next three years, including the inevitable spin-offs of music sales and other memorabilia. Not surprisingly, whereas the animation business makes annual profits--of well over $1 billion--live-action films do not. Jeffrey Logsdon, an entertainment analyst at Seidler in Los Angeles, thinks it probably broke even in the year to the end of September 1995. Mr Londoner thinks it lost money.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now it seems that Disney has decided to make fewer, but more expensive, live-action films. Mr Roth is keen to give each film broader appeal, and especially to drum up interest abroad, where Hollywood now makes more than half its box-office takings. The template may be "The Rock" , a loud, violent, mass-market film that has cost a reported $60m to make ($15m for its star, Sean Connery, alone) and took more than $37m in its first week.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some other studios--Paramount and probably Warner--are retrenching too. But others are still increasing their output. A classic conflict between the interests of one (to make more films) and the interests of all (to make fewer)? Not so, says David Davis of Houlihan Lokey Howard &amp; Zukin, an investment bank in Los Angeles. He calculates that a studio needs to release about a dozen films a year to have an acceptable spread of risk. Once the number of releases rises above that, it becomes harder to nurture and market each film. Those drawbacks outweigh the savings in overheads.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So downsizing makes sense for all the big studios. A vast number of mainstream films have been released in the past 18 months. The complex business of timing a launch has thus become ever more difficult. Conventional wisdom says that a film must be an American box-office hit if it is to succeed in foreign markets or at the video store; but that Americans go to the cinema <i>en masse</i> only in early summer and at Christmas. As Harold Vogel, an analyst with Cowen in New York, points out, vast confections that may have cost $100m or more to create have one brief weekend--or at best 72 hours--in which to be judged successes or failures.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite the good summer in America, and expanding foreign markets, the economics of the film business is harsh. The cost of making and distributing a big film has risen inexorably, with the sharpest rise coming in the past couple of years (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>). The need to be noticed in the crowd forces studios to spend massively on advertising, or on established stars, or both.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The effect, the analysts agree, is alarming. Margins, even bolstered by video revenues and television sales, are frail. Mr Vogel says that the domestic box-office revenues of the top 20 films are no bigger in real terms than they were in the early 1980s. Mr Londoner thinks film-company profits may fall by almost a third this year, admittedly from a peak reached last year. Worse may lie ahead if the economy turns down or if the plethora of digital-television stations coaxes people to stay at home and watch films cheaply on the small screen, not expensively on the big one.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?835398000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="wb2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
