<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p>
<p>


<h2>Up in the air</h2>
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>British Airways struck a deal with <b>American Airlines</b> to form the world's most formidable air alliance. A code-sharing deal will give both companies access to huge new markets, with cost savings even greater than those gained from <font size=-1>BA</font>'s link with troubled <font size=-1>US</font>Air. The deal depends on America granting it antitrust immunity. This, in turn, depends on Britain agreeing to an "open skies" policy that would allow American carriers freer access to London's main airport, Heathrow, and "beyond rights" , the freedom to pick up passengers and take them to third countries.<p>
News Corp, the media group headed by Rupert Murdoch, is to spend $300m-400m over the next two years setting up a 100-channel <b>satellite-TV business</b> in Japan to be called <font size=-1>J</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>.<p>
The new Portuguese government's ambitious privatisation plans were rewarded when demand for shares in the second stage of <b>Portugal Telecom</b>'s privatisation far outweighed supply. The government sold 22% of its holding, raising 150 billion escudos ($947m) and leaving it with a 51% stake.<p>
The British government's prospectus for the privatisation of <b>British Energy</b>, which runs eight modern nuclear reactors, was rather more cautious. Somewhere between &#163;2 billion ($3.1 billion) and &#163;2.4 billion will be raised. This is at the low end of market expectations.<p>
<b>Gazprom</b>, Russia's gas monopoly, bought 30% of <font size=-1>NTV</font>, the country's main commercial television station. It will share control of <font size=-1>NTV</font> with Most, a private banking and property group.<p>
Daewoo, a South Korean conglomerate, said that it was ready to buy <b>Thomson </b>Multimedia, which is for sale as part of a privatisation by the French government. The defence arm of Thomson could be bought by France's Lagard&egrave;re Groupe, which is bidding against Alcatel Alsthom, a French firm willing to take control of Thomson in its entirety.<p>
Britain's Boots is to become sole owner of loss-making <b>Do It All</b>. WH Smith pulled out of the joint venture, handing over its 50% stake to Boots for a nominal &#163;1 and agreeing to inject &#163;50m ($77m) into the do-it-yourself chain over four years. WH Smith also announced a shake-up of its flagging retail chain, which includes Waterstone's, a bookseller, and Virgin Our Price, a music business. The group is to write off &#163;285m ($435m) and shed 400 jobs.<p>
<b>Levi-Strauss</b>, a clothing firm, is to pay bonuses of a year's extra pay to all its 37,000 employees in 2002--provided cash-flow targets are met, as the firm expects.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
The head of China's central bank said it plans to make <b>the yuan</b> convertible in time for the annual <font size=-1>IMF</font> meeting in Hong Kong next year, which China, after the July 1997 handover, will host.<p>
America took its trade complaint about Japan's paper and film market to the <b>World Trade Organisation</b>, and dropped its threat of bilateral sanctions.

<h2>Banque ruptured</h2>
<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br> Only a year after its second bail-out, <b>Cr&eacute;dit Lyonnais</b> is apparently going back to the French government in search of more cash. The state-owned bank, which produced a token profit in 1995 but shows every sign of sinking into loss again this year, says the burden of its restructuring costs is too much. The government, which has twice bailed out the stricken bank, to the tune of FFr21.4 billion ($4.1 billion) in all, claims there will be no more state aid.<p>
As <b>Orange County</b>, California, emerged from bankruptcy 18 months after running up losses of $1.6 billion in bad investments, it marked the occasion with five lawsuits worth $1.5 billion against some of its advisers. They include Standard &amp; Poor's credit-rating agency and a broker, Morgan Stanley. The county is already suing another broker, Merrill Lynch, and its former accountants, <font size=-1>KPMG</font> Peat Marwick, for $5 billion.<p>
<b>National Westminster</b>, one of Britain's big clearing banks, is paying Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan $590m for Greenwich Capital Holdings, a leading American broker and bond trader, to fill a gap in NatWest Markets, the bank's burgeoning investment-banking operation.<p>
Singapore's Commercial Affairs Department said that it would not bring charges against two of <b>Barings</b>' main employees in Asia at the time of the bank's collapse.<p>
<b>Takashimaya</b>, a smart Japanese retailer, fired its president after the firm was caught paying off gangsters who threatened to disrupt shareholder meetings.<p>
An appeal court upheld the 1992 conviction of <b>Carlo De Benedetti</b>, head of Olivetti, for his involvement in the 1982 collapse of Banco Ambrosiano, of which he was briefly deputy chairman in 1981, but reduced his prison term by nearly two years to 4.5 years. He plans to appeal to Italy's supreme court, a process that could take several more years.<p>
The <b>London Stock Exchange</b> appointed a new chief executive, five months after sacking Michael Lawrence. Gavin Casey, a senior executive at Merrill Lynch, will oversee the final stages of the modernisation of the exchange's trading and share-settlement systems.<p>
<p></p>
</td></tr></table></center>
