<html><head><title>Is Russia different?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif"  alt="Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Is Russia different?</h1>
<p><b>Yes, Russia is different. No, this does not mean that democracy and free markets are bound to fail there</b></p>


<p>"RUSSIA is a special world...a special type of civilisation." It is "hostile in its soul to the West" because of the West's "extreme individualism, militant soullessness, religious indifference [and] adherence to mass culture."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These remarks obviously tell you a lot about the writer: Gennady Zyuganov, the leader of Russia's Communist Party. Do they also tell you anything useful about Russia? Is it "a special type of civilisation"? And does that mean--as some say--that it can never be a democracy or a free market? (See <a href="sf1.gif">table</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the face of it, the standing of Boris Yeltsin in the opinion polls before the election provides an optimistic answer. He is the candidate of liberal reform and his popularity suggests Russians are willing to follow him as he moves his country closer to the West. Optimists could even make out a case for their view of Russia if he were to lose: voters, after all, might well reject a president who has presided over a rise in crime, a collapse in living standards and massive human-rights abuses in Chechnya. Similar rejections have occurred in every formerly-communist East-European country. If it happened in Russia, it would not necessarily mean Russians had turned against the whole idea of liberal reform.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such arguments cut no ice with pessimists. To them, Mr Yeltsin's popularity stems from his manipulation of the levers of power, from his willingness to adopt his opponents' nationalist agenda and even from the traditional Russian respect for the man in the Kremlin. Some would go further: the stubborn popularity of the Communists, they say, reflects something deep-seated about the Russian character. As Thomas Masaryk, the first president of Czechoslovakia (and a Russian scholar) put it: "The Russians are very revolutionary. They are not very democratic." Eventually, this will lead them to reject the political and economic arrangements of the West--and this might happen even if Mr Yeltsin were to win. So which view of Russia is right?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One piece of evidence that Mr Zyuganov is justified in what he says is that so many--perhaps most--Russians agree with him. And if they think Russia is different, then that is part of what makes it so."We do not belong to any of the great families of mankind, neither to the East nor to the West" wrote Petr Chaadaev, one of the earliest "Westernisers" (those who thought Russia should modernise by learning from the West). Nikolai Mikhailovsky, who translated John Stuart Mill and Karl Marx into Russian, also thought that "Russia can lay down a new historical path from that taken by Europe."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And these were Westernisers. How much more nationalist have been the "Slavophiles", who, like Mr Zyuganov, thought Russia could learn useful lessons only from its own history. The founder of Slavophilism, Alexei Khomyakov, called Russia "God's instrument". Dostoevsky thought that "Our great Russia will speak its new word, a word never heard before by the world." In 1992 the head of parliament, Ruslan Khasbulatov, wrote that "While [Peter the Great] imposed elements of European culture in Russia...the spiritual and cultural fabric of the people remained untouched. As a result, we have Russia, which is neither Europe nor Asia but a very special, very peculiar part of the world."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The peculiarity lies not only in Russian opinion but also in (as Communists like to say) "the objective facts of history". "There was no Renaissance among us" lamented an early-20th-century philosopher, Nikolai Berdyaev. "We never had feudalism, the more's the pity" said Alexander Pushkin, Russia's national poet. And Russia was never part of the Roman empire.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the fact that Russians believe themselves to be different and have some historical justification for their belief does not get you very far. Every country thinks it is distinctive. An eminent political scientist, for example, has just published a book called "American Exceptionalism"*<font size=1>1</font>. And every country's history backs up its belief.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The question is what do you conclude from this. Do you say, with Mr Zyuganov, that the "western" rules of economics and liberal democracy will be rejected in Russia? Or do you say, with Henry Ford, that "history is bunk" and, as Dmitri Likhachev, a respected intellectual, puts it, "there is no such thing as the Russian soul; we can create whatever future we want."?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Those who think Russia is so different that it cannot change make three claims. First, they say, Russia is naturally collectivist, so the market economy will not work there. Second, they say it is inherently autocratic, so democracy will fail. And third, that it is inherently anti-western, which means that not only will it reject "western" ideas about markets and democracy but it will either run an anti-western foreign policy or perhaps sink into the isolation of its cultural peculiarities. Take these in turn.
</p><p><b>All for one?</b>
<br>It is true that collectivism has been extremely strong in Russian history. After the abolition of serfdom in 1867, serfs did not own their land; they held it in common. It is also true that communism entrenched the collectivist tradition. Uniquely, Russia was transformed from peasant farming to an industrial economy under communist rule. And, compared with other countries, an extra Russian generation lived under communism: no Russian remembers the Tsarist stage of capitalism.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What is more doubtful is whether the collectivist-communist tradition means Russians are bad at private enterprise. As a general rule, claims that markets will fail anywhere because they are "western" ought to treated with extreme scepticism. Not only do they work fine in Japan--a country far less western than Russia--but evidence from all countries suggests that cultural factors are little use as guides to economic behaviour. The reason is that they are so varied and complicated that they contain features which both help and hinder growth. So it was in East Asia where Confucianism was once taken to inhibit business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And so it is in Russia. Collectivism hindered private enterprise. But under the Tsars, life in the towns was always more individualistic than in the countryside. Factories were privately owned and in 1880-1917 Russia enjoyed a boom comparable to that of 1870s America or China today. Even under the Communists, much then happened to erode the collectivist spirit. In 1939, as Stalin's crash-course industrialisation began, two-thirds of the population lived on the land, a share comparable to Morocco's. Now, three-quarters of Russians live in cities (a higher proportion than in Italy) and 98% of the population can read and write (a rate higher than in Britain). Town life and education do not necessarily destroy collectivism but they do undermine it for, in Russia, the collective tradition was rooted in the illiterate countryside.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Russians are not hostile to private enterprise. A study carried out before the reforms found that Russian attitudes to economic incentives and "fair prices" were roughly the same as those of Americans*<font size=1>2</font>. Since then, markets have taken root and anecdotal evidence suggests Russians are just as keen at profit-seeking as anyone else. True, there is a popular association of business with crime--as in all post-communist countries. But, as elsewhere, Russians want more equitable income distribution rather than the complete reversal of market reforms. Obviously, growth and macroeconomic stability are far from guaranteed in Russia. But it does seem that cultural factors--especially collectivism--are unlikely to explain Russia's economic failures.
</p><p><b>Or one over all?</b>
<br>When the debate turns to politics, claims about Russian distinctiveness subtly change. Instead of stressing the collectivist tradition that everyone be consulted--something which should, on the face of it, help democracy--those who argue that Russia is different emphasise the country's autocratic tradition. This appears to support their view that Russia cannot have democracy--at least not yet.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Clearly, until 1991, Russia had neither an elected government nor a democratic opposition (the opponents to Tsarism were mostly revolutionaries). But this in itself is not proof that Russia is stuck with autocracy. This century, Germany, Spain, Austria and Italy have all abandoned authoritarian forms of government, some as extreme as Russia's. And, whatever one thinks of the result, the Russian government has unquestionably changed. President and parliament are elected (the presidential election will be the eighth nation-wide poll in seven years). There is freedom of assembly and a free-ish press. Russia has been transformed from the most centralised state in Europe to a decentralised federation, with roughly half of public spending going through local governments.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of course, if Russian politics can change once, it can change back. And it might do that because the Russians do not seem committed to democracy: 23% of electors voted for Vladimir Zhirinovsky in 1993; now, only half of Russians think they need a democratic system and a mere 19% think they actually have one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But even supposing such attitudes persist--and they may be products of fatigue and confusion at the outset of democracy--there remains doubt as to whether they matter as much as one might assume. For surprising as it may seem, democracies can stumble along with a remarkable cargo of confusion and apathy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A study of two American towns (Ann Arbor, Michigan, and Tallahassee, Florida) tested the assumption that for a democracy to work well, you need full commitment to democratic principles and agreement on what these mean in practice. It found the assumption wanting. Almost everyone agreed with the propositions that "Democracy is the best form of government" and that "Public officials should be chosen by majority vote." But most people also thought that "If a communist were legally elected mayor of this city, the people should not allow him to take office." And "In a city referendum deciding on tax-supported undertakings, only taxpayers should be allowed to vote." Supporting democracy, it turns out, is one thing; understanding what democratic behaviour is, is another. Yet no one thinks democracy does not exist in Ann Arbor or Tallahassee--or in America generally. The conclusion is that democracies do not seem to require consistent support from all the people, all the time.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So, though Russians are even less supportive of democracy than Americans, this may not matter as much as it might appear. Only a relatively modest amount of popular support is really necessary--and Russia has that: millions demonstrated for free elections in the late 1980s; scores of political parties have sprung up (43 asked to be registered for December's parliamentary election); and the turn-out at elections has remained reasonably high (50%-70%) considering there have been so many of them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Clearly, Russian democracy is not stable. Clearly, it will not end up looking the same as the democratic systems of other countries: it may not be organised around two big parties; it may well be corrupt; it is likely to be highly personalised. But it will be a democracy, of sorts, for the evidence from other countries suggests that democracy is so simple the Russians can do it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The third claim--that Russians are innately anti-western--has two aspects to it:<p>
<font size=-1><li></font>Geography. "We are consumed with geography" writes Vyacheslav Ivanov, a literary critic, "and we have no real history." Vast size is not unique to Russia. America, Canada and Australia are continent-sized countries thinly populated by people of European descent. But Russia is larger than any of them and its sheer extent matters. It means that Russia is likely to maintain the huge army (over 1m men) that has grown up to defend Russia's empty spaces. It also provides the country with a range of non-western foreign-policy concerns. Sharing borders with China and North Korea, and sharing the same part of the world as Iran, Russia will always have more "eastern" foreign-policy worries than any European country. An expansionist China would be a concern for Germany or France; for Russia it would be a real military threat. Geography, then, gives Russia a unique set of interests--and these interests could indeed produce conflicts with either West or East.
<p><font size=-1><li></font>
The Russian soul. This article has argued that Russians are less inimical to democracy and free markets than they sometimes appear. Nevertheless, a last possibility has to be considered: that they are unstable in their views, prepared to swing behind one populist or another and likely to be unreliable both in domestic policy and international conduct. This is especially worrying at a time when democracy is in its infancy and many foreign-policy interests are relatively unfamiliar (since Russia has not existed within its current borders before).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In stressing the difference between Russia and the West, the Slavophiles argued that the West was synonymous with rationality, scientific enquiry and self interest. These, they claimed, were inimical to the Russian character. As Dostoevsky put it: "It is indeed possible, and sometimes positively imperative (in my view) to act directly contrary to one's own best interest. One's own free and unfettered volition, one's own caprice... that is one's best and greatest good."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is, by western standards, an extraordinary belief. How is one to judge its importance? Certainly, the non-western, irrational strain has been strong in Russia. But, as with Slavophilism, it was stronger among a literary-cum-philosophical elite than among the population at large. And whether Russia's general cultural beliefs and norms make Russia anti-western remains highly debatable: its religious traditions are Judaeo-Christian; its artistic ones European (consider Russia's contribution to those European forms, the novel, the opera, the ballet and drama). Certainly, too, many Russians feel ambivalent about the West and object to what they see as outsiders "meddling" in their own affairs. But these feelings are stronger among the old than the young and so--for good or ill--are on the wane.
</p><p><b>Nationalists ashamed</b>
<br>Above all, Russian nationalism seems, like Slavophilism, to be more an elite concern than a grass-roots one. Many politicians claim to be highly nationalistic. Virtually all promise to make Russia a great power. Yet when asked to list the problems facing their country, ordinary Russians put other concerns top: crime, inflation, Chechnya. Surprisingly, the evidence of opinion polls does not show nationalism surging back. According to polls conducted in 1991-95*<font size=1>3</font>, less than one-third of young people see military service as a "duty and honour"; just 10% regarded "fidelity to national traditions" as "the main influence on matters of faith and morals". The pollsters concluded that "People shun identification with this country and this nation."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such nihilistic attitudes may be a temporary reaction to the immense problems of reform. Sooner or later, Russians will start rebuilding their sense of nationhood. But, if these polls are right, they are likely to do so not on the rejected features of the old Russia--collectivism, autocracy and irrationality--but on the qualities they now say they respect most: civil rights; freedom of conscience; freedom of expression. These are attributes not of a messianic, peculiar state, but of what Russian reformers have long claimed to be their ideal: a normal country--whatever that means.


<br><hr>
*1 By Seymour Martin Lipset. W.W. Norton. 352 pages $27.50 and 19.95<br><hr>
*2 "Popular Attitudes toward Free markets: the Soviet Union and the United States Compared." By Robert Schiller, Maxim Boycko and Vladimir Korobov. <i>American Economic Review.</i> June 1991.


<br><hr>
*3 "In Search of National Identity". By Sergei Filatov and Lyudmila Vorontsova. In "Remaking Russia" Edited by Heyward Isham. <i>Institute for EastWest Studies.<br><hr><br>


