<html><head><title>Yeltsin out in front</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width=105 height=26  alt="Europe">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Yeltsin out in front</h1>

<font size=1>MOSCOW</font><p><b>But nothing is certain in, or after, Russia's presidential election
</B><p>IF THERE are Russians to whom Boris Yeltsin has not promised a handout or subsidy in the course of his re-election campaign, they should stake their claims fast: the first round of voting takes place on Sunday. Moreover, the Central Bank has already lost its patience.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last week Mr Yeltsin ordered the bank to find an unbudgeted $1 billion to help cover a government deficit widened materially by his own efforts. This week a miffed bank official responded by disclosing that reserves had fallen from $16 billion to $12.5 billion since April--the cost of propping up the rouble as it sagged under the weight of money being printed to cover Mr Yeltsin's campaign promises. The price of government securities has slumped.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The next fortnight could thus be a turbulent one for Russia's financial markets if all that money threatens to have been spent in vain, and Mr Yeltsin emerges from the first round with less than a commanding lead--or no lead at all--over his main rival, Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist candidate. It could also be a turbulent fortnight for Russia generally if an explosion in a Moscow metro train on June 11th, which left four dead and 12 injured, presaged an eruption of violence in what had been a generally peaceful campaign.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But for all the Central Bank's grimaces, the price of re-electing Mr Yeltsin "remains a great deal cheaper than the alternative", insists a member of the president's campaign staff--reasonably enough. For Mr Zyuganov has proposed a programme that would drag Russia back towards a planned economy and ruin its financial markets. Fear of its effects has been one of Mr Yeltsin's main campaign weapons.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another of his advantages has been his freedom to exploit shamelessly the powers of incumbency. His bogus but popular union treaty with Belarus in April and his peace negotiations with Chechen rebels have been masterpieces of political illusion. State-run television has given him adulatory coverage. Regional bigwigs have rallied to his cause.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The combination seems to have been effective. The latest poll conducted between June 5th and 10th by the All-Russia Centre for Public Opinion found 36% of voters backing Mr Yeltsin, putting him 12 points ahead of Mr Zyuganov. In January a poll by the same firm had shown Mr Zyuganov besting Mr Yeltsin by 20% to 8%. All nine other candidates lag far behind the two leaders.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dizzied by his ascent, Mr Yeltsin was predicting rashly this week that he would win a knock-out victory on Sunday--taking more than half the vote, and so obviating a run-off. His advisers, less cocksure, are planning for a run-off against Mr Zyuganov in a manner revealing of the Kremlin style. This week Sergei Filatov, head of Mr Yeltsin's re-election staff, said the second round might take place on Wednesday, July 3rd, and not, as hitherto expected, on Sunday, July 7th. (The law says a second round may be held up to 15 days after the result of the first round is declared.) To have the vote on a Wednesday, specially declared a holiday, should raise the turnout: if the run-off were held on a weekend, many Yeltsinites might head for their dachas rather than the polls.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though most Russians may have come to expect a Yeltsin victory, few can have a clear view of what would follow in policy terms. Some may think the populist, free-spending Yeltsin of 1996 is here to stay. A forward-looking few want to see the return of the resolute, reforming Yeltsin of 1991-92. Others fear that the panicky, Chechnya-bashing Yeltsin of 1994-95 still lurks in the shadows. Probably, the president himself does not know how he would conduct himself. He might not even see his term out: at 65 he has already outlived the average Russian male of his generation by eight years. After two heart attacks in the past year, one priority for the re-elected president would have to be time off for by-pass surgery.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Mr Yeltsin did opt for an energetic, all-systems-go second term, he would find plenty to occupy him. Among Russia's more urgent needs are a new tax code, a war on organised crime, a wholesale restructuring of government, a reappraisal of foreign-policy, a lasting peace deal in Chechnya, a reform of collectivised farming and a modernisation of the army. All this would demand a return of the brave Yeltsin of five years ago, willing to appoint strong ministers and give them their heads.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Alternatively, Mr Yeltsin might prove a spent force whose re-election campaign had been an end in itself. At best he might continue with the lax, avuncular populism that had proved a voter-pleaser this year. At worst infirmity might leave him an absentee leader, his powers captured by the clique around him. Neither need spell disaster in the short-term: a re-election of Mr Yeltsin would alone be enough to encourage investment and get Russia's economy moving. But a spendthrift or directionless government would mean Russia's hopes of real recovery would sink beneath the weight of unreformed institutions and dud industries.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Should Mr Yeltsin win, he might signal his intentions by choosing a new prime minister (see <a href="eu1.gif">table</a>). Russia's constitution obliges a "newly elected president" to seek the consent of the lower house of parliament, the Duma, for his nominee; if the Duma rejects three nominees, the president can dissolve it. Were Mr Yeltsin planning a quiet second term, he would probably seek a compromise candidate acceptable to the Communist-dominated Duma. But if he planned a gung-ho second term, he might court confrontation, hoping that a dissolution and a fresh general election would give him a more liberal Duma with which to work. Some argue for the existence of a third possibility: that Mr Yeltsin might dispute that he was a "newly elected president" , hang on to his current prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, and so snub the Duma squarely.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such calculations presume that Russia's democracy has grown strong enough to take power-politics between president and Duma in its stride. Probably it has, even though this election is the first for the presidency of a fully sovereign Russia. But Tuesday's terrorist bomb represented someone's version of dissent; and Mr Zyuganov has done democracy no favours by threatening that millions of Communist voters might take to the streets if they felt victory had been denied them by ballot-box fraud. The final doubt hangs over the willingness of Mr Yeltsin and his clique to relinquish power peacefully within the 30 days prescribed by law if the vote goes against them. With luck, it will not be tested.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
