<html><head><title>The unskilled nation</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Education</b></p>
<h1>The unskilled nation</h1>

<p>SIR HUMPHREY APPLEBY, the slippery civil servant in the <font size=-1>BBC</font>'s political comedy series "Yes, Minister", would have called it "courageous"--ie, foolhardy. After 17 years in office, and a matter of months before an election, the government has published a detailed study admitting that education and skill levels in Britain are below those in Germany, France, America and Singapore. Unsurprisingly, Labour said it was a damning indictment of the government's record. Gillian Shephard, the education and employment secretary, hopes that voters will give the government credit for its honesty and will recall that, until recently, Labour opposed many of the government's school reforms. She has also announced a package of further reforms in response to the study's findings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The study, published on June 13th as part of the annual white paper on competitiveness, compared the qualifications held by the British population with those in the four other countries, chosen as key "economic competitors". This "skills audit" found that only 45% of British adults have qualifications that are at least the equivalent of <font size=-1>GCSE</font> grade "<font size=-1>C</font>" in maths, English and one other subject (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>), worse than all the other countries. The figure for Germany is 70%. Multinational firms were asked to compare their workers in each country. Confirming the findings of other recent studies, they reported that the British came bottom of the class at sums.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, America and Singapore did little better than Britain overall, even though their record of economic growth has been more impressive than Germany's in recent times. Germany's strong showing in part reflects its obsession with paper qualifications: some apprentices in Britain and elsewhere do not get a certificate when they complete their training, whereas their German counterparts almost always do.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When the multinational employers were asked about the actual skill levels of workers, as opposed to their paper qualifications, Germany's lead was not so strong, although British workers still lagged behind in a range of industries, from food to electronics. Comparisons of young people entering the labour market, as opposed to the population as a whole, suggest that Britain is improving its record on education and training, though not as rapidly as France. And Britain is second only to America in the proportion of the population with university-level qualifications.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even so, the findings of the skills audit add to the pressure that Mrs Shephard is under from some of her colleagues to regain the initiative after recent speeches by Tony Blair, Labour's leader, outlining bold plans for improving education and training. The day before the skills audit was published, Mrs Shephard announced a range of further reforms, including a drastic shake-up of teacher training. The universities and colleges which provide the initial training for teachers will, for the first time, have to follow a curriculum laid down by the government. Trainee teachers will spend less time on such things as psychology and "gender studies" and more time on practical teaching techniques--especially on how to teach children to read.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Those who run teacher-training courses are bound to squeal that the government is encroaching on their traditional academic freedom. But there may be less resistance than the government was expecting: the <font size=-1>NASUWT</font>, the second-largest teaching union, actually welcomed the proposals. Mrs Shephard's other plans, which include giving schools targets for improving their exam results, giving them greater powers to deal with disruptive pupils, and encouraging more schools to specialise in technology, are also unlikely to be too controversial. Labour has similar policies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government certainly deserves credit for being open about Britain's relatively poor educational performance, and its determination to do something about it. But, even if voters are impressed by this refreshing show of honesty, it seems unlikely to be enough on its own to restore the government's political fortunes. So it is a good job that Labour is promising to pursue much the same reforms with equal vigour.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,iss">Search</a>
