<html><head><title>A question of degree</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Oxbridge</b></p>

<h1>A question of degree</h1>

<p>"WHY can't a woman be more like a man?" mused Henry Higgins in "My Fair Lady". At Oxford and Cambridge, many women rather wish they were. In 1995, about 17% of Oxford's male undergraduates came away with a first-class degree. Only 10% of the university's women managed this distinction. At Cambridge (where Oxonians might suspect that the marking is rather laxer) 23% of men took firsts, compared with 12% of women. So nettled has Oxford become at the gender gap that it recently decided to finance an official inquiry to study the issue.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At several of Britain's other elite universities men do slightly better than women. At Imperial College, London, for example, 21.5% of men got firsts last year, compared with 17.4% of women, and at the London School of Economics, the numbers were 8.6% and 6.5% respectively. But women at Exeter and London's University College were just as likely as men to win firsts; at Durham, Edinburgh and Essex they were not far behind and at London's Kings College women were actually more likely to win firsts than men.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Against this background, Oxbridge looks peculiar. And the gap is growing: in 1970 11.3% of Cambridge men took first-class honours as opposed to 9.4% of women. Oxford recorded similar figures.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What has changed, then, is not that the women have got worse, but that the men have got better faster. There are many plausible theories to explain the gap, but all fail to explain why it has grown over the years. Except one: that the growing inequality of the results is a side-effect of policies intended to make the universities more inclusive. In the past few decades, both Oxford and Cambridge have attempted to increase the enrolment of women and take a larger proportion of all their pupils from state rather than public (ie, private) schools.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Gerald McCrum, a retired Oxford engineering professor who is researching the gender gap, thinks that part of men's improved performance since 1970 may be the lopping off of the "weak tail" from the independent schools. For example, Christ Church was once known as the cream of Oxford--"rich, thick and full of clots". Candidates for a "gentleman's third" are now much rarer, as men who once would have got in by virtue of their breeding or the income of their fathers have been weeded out in favour of smart fellows from state schools--the likeliest group, male or female, to win a first. A second squeeze on candidates for a "gentleman's third" is that the percentage of men has dropped at Oxbridge from about 75% in 1970 to 60% today; the smaller pool may yield a larger proportion of first-class intellects.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At Cambridge, men from state and independent schools do about the same, suggesting that the admissions process there now works fairly efficiently in choosing them. At Oxford, state-school educated men do a bit better.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, the selection process does not seem to work as well for women, with those from independent schools doing significantly better than those from state schools, though still worse than the men. "The independent girls really are far better than the state girls at Oxford," Mr McCrum concludes. "Since the introduction of comprehensives, women from state schools have gone off the boil academically." The implication is that a higher proportion of private-school women might yield more firsts--a touchy class issue that neither university is eager to broach.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Researchers in both universities are looking at other theories as well:
<font size=-1><li></font><b>Patterns of intelligence:</b> There are two related hypotheses. One is that men mature later intellectually. This would explain why men do conspicuously better than women at Oxford and Cambridge, but not so on the <font size=-1>GCSE</font>s or <font size=-1>A</font>-levels. (Girls do better at <font size=-1>GCSE</font>s and about the same at <font size=-1>A</font>-levels). But if this were the case, one would expect it to be universally true, not just at Oxbridge.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The other is that while men may mature later, they are also more likely to reach the greatest intellectual heights. Men dominate the top and bottom of the intelligence scale, while women cluster in the middle. There is much evidence to this effect: the ranks of Nobel prize winners, and village idiots, are mostly male. This is persuasive, but it does not explain why women with the same <font size=-1>A</font>-levels are less likely to excel than men--or why the gap is increasing.
<font size=-1><li></font><b>Course selection:</b> Men do a better job of choosing a course of study in which they are likely to excel. At Cambridge in 1995, of the 15 honours exams men were most likely to take they scored below the male average (23.5% firsts) in four; of the 15 exams women were most likely to take they scored below the female average (12.6% firsts) in eight.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Men are also more likely to take their degree in the sciences, which traditionally award more firsts (and thirds). At Cambridge in 1995, for example, in electrical and information sciences 28 men (30% of the total number of men taking the exam) and no women won firsts. In the natural sciences, 314 men (27%) and 139 women (19.6%) took firsts, and in computers, 61 men (26.9%) and two of 19 women who completed the course came out tops.
<font size=-1><li></font><b>The examination system: </b>Both universities retain a traditional marking system in which students take exams at the end of the second and third years (Cambridge) or in the third year only (Oxford). One theory is that the nature of this system may favour the male turn of mind, by rewarding intellectual daring over careful synthesis. "Men tend to have more of a journalistic style, taking a polemic stab at a theory. That goes down well with examiners," says Ruth Deetch, principal of Oxford's St Ann's College, who has been looking at the problem.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because the gender gap is so much larger at Oxbridge than elsewhere, it has become a particularly sore point. Gillian Sutherland, vice principal of Newnham College at Cambridge, wants the universities to do a detailed study of assessment, teaching methods and women's results. After a good five years, she thinks they may have a better idea of what to do. Or maybe not. Students have a way of confounding expectations. In 1993, Cambridge women were one-seventh as likely to win a first as men on Part I of the History Tripos. A year later, they evened the score. And a year after that, they slipped back again. Nobody knows why.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,iss">Search</a>
