<html><head><title>Bribing for Britain</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Inward investment</b></p>
<h1>Bribing for Britain</h1>

<font size=1>EDINBURGH</font>
<p>MINISTERS like nothing better than to announce that a big foreign firm is to invest millions in building a new factory, especially if it is going to create jobs. Such news is trumpeted as further evidence of Britain's competitiveness compared with mainland Europe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Inward investment comes at a price, however, and the Treasury is baulking at the subsidies being doled out to foreign investors. If Britain's flexible labour market and friendly corporate-tax regime increasingly makes it the preferred location for American and East Asian firms looking to invest in Europe (as ministers claim), the subsidies ought to get smaller. However, there is no sign of that happening; and the Treasury is concerned that the regional development agencies are breaching its limits on how much subsidy they are allowed to offer.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Treasury reckons that the problem is caused by regional development agencies, especially those for Scotland and Wales, bending the subsidy rules to outbid each other. Officials also suspect that foreign companies play the agencies off against each other to extract bigger dollops of money.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;William Waldegrave, the treasury chief secretary, thinks that this auction is getting out of hand and should be stopped. He has written to Michael Forsyth, the Scottish secretary, and William Hague, the Welsh secretary, suggesting that the effort to attract inward investment should be centrally controlled through the Invest in Britain Bureau under the scrutiny of the Department of Trade and Industry (<font size=-1>DTI</font>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Neither Mr Forsyth nor Mr Hague are taken by this idea. They know that any Treasury move to clip the wings of their agencies, Locate in Scotland and the Welsh Development Agency (<font size=-1>WDA</font>), would lose them votes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the argument cannot be brushed aside, because at the moment an unusually large number of foreign firms are considering sites in Britain for big job-creating investments. One, <font size=-1>LG</font> of Korea (formerly Lucky Goldstar), plans to spend around &#163;1.4 billion on an electronics factory employing up to 4,000 people.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The firm is not expected to announce its choice of site until August but rumour has it that, after vigorous lobbying by Mr Hague and a <font size=-1>WDA</font> offer of &#163;150m of aid, the company now favours Newport in Wales. Such a package would mean a price to taxpayers of &#163;37,500 for each job created, well above the &#163;20,000 per job limit which agencies are supposed to observe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>WDA</font> says these reports are wide of the mark, but rival agencies which have been trying to lure <font size=-1>LG</font> reckon that the <font size=-1>WDA</font> has offered at least &#163;26,000 per job. That would still be above the ceiling, although the <font size=-1>WDA</font> could argue it represents about the same cost per job as the &#163;80m package given in 1994 to another Korean electronics firm, Samsung, to build a factory employing 3,000 in north-east England.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Samsung settled on the north-east only after Michael Heseltine, then president of the Board of Trade, agreed to up the <font size=-1>DTI</font>'s contribution to the deal to &#163;58m. This allowed the Northern Development Company to outbid a rival deal which it feared Samsung was about to accept from Locate in Scotland for a site in Lanarkshire.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Inter-agency rivalry like this is commonplace. While Scottish Office minister George Kynoch was in Taiwan last year to rubber-stamp a deal which brought Chunghwa Picture Tubes and 3,300 jobs to Lanarkshire, for instance, his Welsh counterparts were still faxing offers to the company. To the Treasury, this looks like a collection of bellboys tripping over each other to grab a guest's luggage, and then tipping the customer for the pleasure of carting it to his room.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Barry Hartop, chief executive of the <font size=-1>WDA</font>, says this view is mistaken. Subsidy grants are tightly controlled by treasury and European rules and, he argues, are a good deal for the taxpayer--the average cost per job works out at &#163;15,000, equal to the annual cost of keeping an unemployed person on welfare benefits.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He and his counterparts at Locate in Scotland are more worried about the increasing subsidies being offered by other European governments to foreign companies. One Scottish official says that the Irish government is prepared to offer up to three times more than he could. These differences matter--a survey of potential inward investors by Coopers and Lybrand, an accountancy firm, found that subsidies were the third most important factor in decisions about where to build new factories.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Arguments like these may help Mr Forsyth and Mr Hague to block Mr Waldegrave's proposal. But he has another, political, point up his sleeve--that inward investment is going not where unemployment is worst, but to those parts of Britain with the best-equipped development agencies. Of the &#163;276m offered in regional selective assistance by the government in 1995, half went to Scotland and Wales. As the Tories have only ten seats in Scotland, and six in Wales, Mr Waldegrave may calculate that the government has more to gain if more of the money, and of the jobs, were to go to the English regions.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834188400,iss">Search</a>
