<html><head><title>Names writ in water</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<p><b>The Internet</b></p>
<h1>Names writ in water</h1>

<p>WANT to buy shares in the United Nations High Commission for Refugees? Just click on "www.unhcr.org" on the World Wide Web, and you will be offered stock options in the Refugee Republic Corporation, incorporated (it says) in Nevada to demonstrate that "refugees are essentially unrealised capital", but in no way related to the worthy international organisation known everywhere as <font size=-1>UNHCR</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Refugees are just the latest cybervictims of the confusion caused by the rules for allocating "domain names" on the Internet, those on-line signatures that are the Internet's equivalent of telephone numbers. The principle is mainly first come, first served. The imaginative and nimble have registered lots of famous corporate names before their sleepy owners realised what was happening.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For most of the past year the squabbles over domain names have been a sideshow--irritating mainly for large American companies. But the spread of Internet use outside the United States is converting a national mess into a global one. Part of the problem is that, although each country has its own trademark law, companies based outside the United States increasingly want to register their names without the <i>d&eacute;class&eacute;</i> addition of a national tag.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Users outside the United States generally tag their names with country codes--commercial users in Australia, for instance, are ".com.au". Thus tagged, their trademarks are protected by national law. But because the United States dreamt up the Internet, most of its users grandly carry no country code: if they are businesses, their names end simply with ".com". At least 7% of all those that register under the aristocratic banner of ".com" are non-Americans, and the proportion is rising.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble is, when they register, non-Americans frequently find what many American firms have already discovered: a nimble amateur has beaten them to it. For instance, Rolex Watches of Switzerland has only recently discovered that Janice Ard of Colorado owns "rolex.com".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To discourage speculators, Network Solutions Incorporated (<font size=-1>NSI</font>), which registers domain names in the United States, decided last year to impose a $50 fee (to the huge irritation of Internet boffins, who complain that it is earning more than $12m a year for allocating an international resource). It also allows the owner of a registered trademark to complain if its name has been grabbed by somebody else. Amateur name-grabbers, threatened with a court case, can usually be bribed to relinquish a valuable name.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But some important names--such as <font size=-1>UNHCR</font>--are not registered as trademarks. Moreover, the complexities of trademark law are overwhelming the unworldly academics who keep the Internet afloat.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The cross-border implications of such arguments are now starting to appear. Roadrunner Computer Systems, a small Internet-service company in New Mexico, registered "roadrunner.com". But Warner Brothers, which has a cartoon character called the Road Runner, also laid claim to the name for a while.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most interesting aspect of the case was that Roadrunner had registered its trademark in Tunisia--in 48 hours, for a mere $1,100. Under <font size=-1>NSI</font> policy, that gives it a right to the domain name. In fact, Roadrunner registered only after it ran into Warner Brothers' wrath. But many similar cases will end up in American courts as companies around the world with identical names vie for space in the narrow confines of the ".com" domain. The arguments will grow political: to the dismay of Taipei, the official Chinese news agency has craftily registered "Taiwan.com".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, just as non-American companies have belatedly discovered that their trade names had been registered as domain names in the United States, so American companies are just beginning to realise the need to register their domain names in other countries, if they want to avoid confusion. While Yahoo!, one of the Internet's most widely used guides, owns yahoo.com, an unrelated British company called Yahoo Research Development has already bagged yahoo.co.uk. Given that Yahoo! has no trading presence in Britain, there is not much that the company can do.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What is the answer? Some Internet engineers argue that the creation of more international domains, on the lines of .com, would allow several companies with the same name to register it. Suppose a new ".bus" domain were created, one company could be, say, yahoo.com and another yahoo.bus.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But what if Yahoo! felt the need to register itself under both domains? An alternative proposal, put forward by (among others) Robert Shaw, an official at the International Telecommunication Union, would be to bring the United States into line with the rest of the world by insisting that ".us" is attached to all American domain names. The trademark rows would continue, but at least each country would deal with its own.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But that would not end the difficulties of Yahoo! or Rolex either. If they wanted exclusive global use of their name, they would still need to register around the world. All that would be clearer is the country the company was based in. Only a global trademark registration system would offer a real answer-- and that is nowhere in sight.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834188400,iss">Search</a>
