<html><head><title>The passion of the newly converted</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>The passion of the newly converted</h1>
<p><b>John Petrillo once sent AT&T down the wrong on-line path. Perhaps that is why he can now see the right one so clearly</b></p>

AT THE PC Forum, an annual gathering of the biggest names in the computer and communications industries, sartorial details are telling. Last year, Bert Roberts, the boss of <font size=-1>MCI</font>, one of America's biggest telephone companies, made the <i>faux pas</i> of wearing a suit and tie. This year he came to the podium a reformed man, with a collarless shirt under his blazer. Ray Smith, head of Bell Atlantic, another big telephone company, pointedly left his jacket on his chair. Both were trumped by John Petrillo, who heads the new-media side of the biggest telephone company of all, <font size=-1>AT&T</font>: "I didn't even pack a jacket to worry about," he smirked.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This geek <i>savoir faire</i> has been learnt the hard way. Mr Petrillo, like most telecoms bosses, originally dismissed the Internet as a boffin's distraction from the information superhighway that the telephone companies planned to build--and control. At <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, Mr Petrillo set up a range of proprietary networks, such as Network Notes (which allowed companies to communicate with each other via their internal Lotus Notes networks) and PersonaLink (a network for people with handheld "personal digital assistants"). <font size=-1>AT&T</font> also paid $50m for a fledgling proprietary network called Interchange. When Mr Petrillo did think of the Internet it was, he now admits, only as "a different kind of e-mail system".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In retrospect, <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s main gains from dabbling in proprietary data networks were the people it hired to run them. They came from computer companies--including Microsoft, Sun Microsystems, <font size=-1>IBM</font> and Lotus--and they pestered Mr Petrillo until he eventually came to agree with them that the future lay with the Internet, not with <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s proprietary services. Late last year, he started to move those services on to the Internet: customers using Lotus Notes in different offices can still use an <font size=-1>AT&T</font> computer as an intermediary, but they can now reach it through the Internet rather than <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s own lines. More radically, in February <font size=-1>AT&T</font> introduced WorldNet, its own Internet access service for individual consumers, offering it free to all users in the United States for a year. After just three months, WorldNet already has more than 150,000 users, making it America's third-largest stand-alone Internet provider (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To bet on the Internet was undoubtedly wise, but hardly visionary. Plenty of other companies, from Microsoft to General Electric, had already abandoned proprietary data networks for the open Internet; since <font size=-1>AT&T</font> launched its Internet service, other telephone companies have done the same. But Mr Petrillo has now begun to wonder whether open networks might be the future direction for the traditional telephone business, too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The case for this view has been fortified by the bill which Congress passed earlier this year to open America's telephone markets to competition. The effect will be to force the local monopoly telephone companies to separate, or "unbundle", services from infrastructure. Instead, they must now lease their lines at fair prices to all comers, and ensure that other firms can connect with their network switches and software. (Most European telephone companies will face similar obligations from the start of 1998.)
</p><p><b>Parallel revolution</b>
<br>Most people see telecoms liberalisation and the growth of the Internet as two separate developments. Mr Petrillo sees them as two sides of the same coin. Because liberalisation requires interconnection, it will eliminate most of the advantages of proprietary networks and software.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The effect will be to drive telecommunications towards an Internet model. Just as anybody can offer any service across the Internet, so in time any company will be able to offer any service--whether it be customer identification, voice-mail or the software for a network computer--across a telephone network, whether or not it owns part of it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last autumn, this reasoning contributed to <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s decision to split itself up, spinning off its services, equipment and computer businesses into separate companies. Mr Petrillo claims no credit for this--indeed, financial arguments played as large a role as strategic ones--but his star has risen since the "trivestiture". He is now the company's vice president for strategy, and oversees its on-line activities and <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s part of the old Bell Labs. Responding to more than 100 e-mail messages a day at work and surfing the Web with his two sons from a fast connection at home, a newly wired Mr Petrillo is now <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s chief internal evangelist for open networking.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Where might this vision lead? Today, <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, like most telephone companies, carries calls mostly over its own network. But the Internet can carry calls, too. They do not sound great yet, but in principle the Internet's technology should be able to transmit voice as clearly as the telephone network and far more cheaply, in part because it uses capacity much more efficiently, allowing many transmissions to share one line rather than devoting it to a single call. Most telephone firms either see Internet telephony as a terrifying threat or dismiss it as a technical curiosity, decades away from widespread use. Not Mr Petrillo. He recently hired David Nagel, Apple Computer's research chief, to run <font size=-1>AT&T</font> Labs, and told him to focus on developing Internet telephones.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One day, <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s customers may have a choice: to put their traffic across the Internet inexpensively, or across the old <font size=-1>AT&T</font> network at a premium rate to reflect guaranteed top quality. Whether that traffic consists of telephone calls or e-mail, <font size=-1>AT&T</font> will still benefit. Mr Petrillo is, in effect, betting that <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s telephone skills will make it an equally skilled Internet company. He reckons that, while the Internet may reduce revenues per call, volume will rise even more. Anyway, he admits, "It's not a question of if, but when, and there are real advantages in being first." If <font size=-1>AT&T</font> does not grab the chance, someone else certainly will.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834188400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="fn1.html">Next article</a>
