<html><head><title>Who goes there?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Speaker recognition</b></p>
<h1>Who goes there?</h1>

<p>THE policeman motions you out of the car. "Have you had any alcohol?" he asks. "No," you respond. Sceptical, he sniffs the air. "I'm sorry, I'll have to test you. Please speak into this microphone."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This vision of a possible future is held by Kathleen Cummings at the Georgia Institute of Technology, in Atlanta. She is trying to elicit patterns from drunken speech that a computer could recognise. In related work, Renetta Tull and Janet Rutledge at Northwestern University, in Evanston, Illinois, are looking at what having a cold does to your voiceprint. These efforts are also parts of a greater goal: to put together the implements a computer needs to tell one person's voice from another's.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Speech recognition is already commonplace. Dictation software for personal computers learns how just one particular dictator says each word. Telephone systems, increasingly used to lighten the load on operators, can understand (almost) any caller, but only a few words. To expand the vocabularies of such systems involves working out what all human voices, in their riot of diversity, have in common. Speaker recognition, by contrast, means picking out the voiceprint--the things that make each voice unique. But it also entails recognising the voice of a person, even with a bunged-up nose or whisky-sodden consonants.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A voice is born in the vocal cords. It is then modified and articulated in the vocal tract--the throat, mouth and lips--before it finally emerges. A computer, to recognise a voice, must convert the sound into mathematical formulae. There are several ways to do this, each highlighting different aspects of the voice. First is the raw sound: the waveform. This can be turned into a spectrum, which shows how much sound of every frequency (pitch) the voice contains. Further numerical fiddling converts the spectrum into a "cepstrum", which magnifies the low-frequency parts of the spectrum. The researchers' strategy is to relate bits of these voice patterns to the body parts that made them. By finding which bits of a voiceprint come from the nasal cavity, for instance, they hope to be able to detect a blocked nose.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Drunkenness most obviously affects articulation: speech becomes slurred. But explaining "slurred" to a computer is not simple. It requires a mathematical description of what slurring does to, for instance, consonants. That means teaching the computer what a consonant is, again using equations. So, instead, Dr Cummings examined the first stage of speech, looking at the waveform from the glottis--the slit between the vocal cords.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To unpack this waveform, Dr Cummings passed a speech recording backwards through a series of filters that mimic the vocal tract, returning it as closely as possible to the pristine glottal sound. She then analysed it and found that, unsurprisingly, a drunk person not only walks more shakily, but has unsteadier vocal cords too. This makes a more reliable computer test of intoxicated speech: you can enunciate deliberately when drunk, but just try to control your glottis.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ms Tull and Dr Rutledge, meanwhile, began by looking at how a cold affects the cepstrum. They put snuffly and normal voice recordings through another filter--one that simulates how the human hearing system processes sound. Cepstrums from healthy and unhealthy voices turned out to possess differences that a computer could easily measure.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One of their next aims is to look at the spectrum. Sounds resonate differently in each part of the vocal tract, each adding characteristic patterns known as "formants" to the spectrum. The nasal cavity, for instance, produces certain low-frequency sounds. If your nose is blocked and these sounds are absent, your voice's spectrum will have smaller (or no) nasal formants. A cold could also alter the glottal waveform: mucus lying on the vocal cords makes them vibrate more slowly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dr Cummings accepts that her work may not deal breathalysers the death-blow. But she and her fellow researchers hope, ultimately, to track down parts of the voiceprint that do not get affected by drink or the sniffles, or by other things like stress. These would probably correspond to unalterable features of a speaker, like mouth size. His voice patterns for such features could be singular enough for a computer to pick out. Alternatively, if there were a distinctive pattern in all people with colds, the computer might be taught to spot it and to filter it out before trying to recognise the voice--or at least to know that the speaker could not be reliably identified. It is just possible that, one day, you will ring up the automatic telephone banking service to be told, "Sorry, you have not been recognised. Please blow your nose and try again." 
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834188400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
