<html><head><title>A new kind of alliance?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif"  alt="Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>A new kind of alliance?</h1>
<p><b>In Berlin on June 3rd-4th, NATO foreign ministers will endorse a shake-up of the alliance's military structure. This is but a prelude to bigger changes</b></p>

<p>THE North Atlantic Treaty Organisation has had a good year. The success of its implementation force (Ifor) in Bosnia has made it feel useful. The French have rejoined some of the <font size=-1>NATO</font> bodies they quit 30 years ago. The ignominy of having a secretary-general struggling to shake off allegations of corruption has been forgotten since Spain's Javier Solana replaced Belgium's Willy Claes in December. So has the row over whether <font size=-1>NATO</font> should enforce the arms embargo on former Yugoslavia, which poisoned transatlantic relations two years ago. And now the organisation's 16 nations have agreed, just in time for the Berlin meeting, to create "combined joint task-forces" (<font size=-1>CJTF</font>s), a new means of projecting power beyond the alliance's territory. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>NATO</font>'s robust health is particularly striking for an organisation that had seemed, at the end of the cold war, to be in danger of becoming redundant. The threat that had held <font size=-1>NATO</font> together, of a Soviet invasion, had all but disappeared. The United States was slashing its troop numbers in Europe, from 300,000 in the late 1980s to 100,000 today. And the Europeans were toying with the idea of a "European defence identity"--perhaps based on the Western European Union (<font size=-1>WEU</font>), a defence pact of ten <font size=-1>EU</font> countries--that might have undermined the transatlantic alliance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet five years on from the collapse of the Soviet Union, few mainstream politicians in Europe or North America are now questioning <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s utility. It used to be said that the purpose of <font size=-1>NATO</font> was to keep the Russians out, the Americans in and the Germans down. In some ways, at least, it still has to perform those three tasks. The West cannot be certain that Russia will never again pose a military threat; <font size=-1>NATO</font> helps to keep the United States engaged in Europe; and many Germans (and their neighbours) still want reassurance that Germany's foreign and defence policy will remain firmly embedded in multinational institutions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But <font size=-1>NATO</font> has also acquired two newer functions. One is to put out fires. In Bosnia <font size=-1>NATO</font> has shown, by unleashing a massive aerial bombardment and then deploying peacekeepers, that it is the only international organisation which can stop a war. This is why, in Berlin, <font size=-1>NATO</font> ministers will approve <font size=-1>CJTF</font>s. Traditionally, the alliance's military organisation has been based on article five of the North Atlantic Treaty, which commits signatories to defend each other from attack. They agree in time of war to put their forces under an "integrated military structure", a hierarchy of multinational headquarters that report, in Europe, to "Saceur" (the Supreme Allied Commander Europe, always an American).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since this structure was designed to block Soviet armies on the plains of Germany, it is little use for <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s new role. Hence the need for <font size=-1>CJTF</font>s, ad hoc headquarters to run peacekeeping operations or other out-of-area interventions. Each headquarters will be based on elements of the integrated structure, modified to reflect the nationalities of the troops involved. They will answer either to <font size=-1>NATO</font> or, if American troops do not take part, to the <font size=-1>WEU</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These task-forces are a significant innovation for <font size=-1>NATO</font>. They will become its normal means of running a mission that does not involve territorial defence. And they will help to foster a European identity within the alliance, by enabling the <font size=-1>WEU</font> to embark on real, if modest, military enterprises. A <font size=-1>WEU</font>-led task-force would need to borrow military equipment from <font size=-1>NATO</font>. The Americans have decently said that, in normal circumstances, they will not prevent <font size=-1>NATO</font> from lending its "assets"--many of which are really American--to its little brother.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Having approved these task-forces, <font size=-1>NATO</font> foreign ministers will launch a study on how to overhaul the entire military structure. The French say that, if they like the result, they will rejoin it. But that is not the only reason for changing the structure. Most of the allies agree that the existing one, designed for the cold war, is top heavy, too expensive and insufficiently mobile.
</p><p><b>Partnership material</b>
<br>The second new task for <font size=-1>NATO</font> is to help make the East European states stable and secure, granting membership to some and strengthening ties with others. At the Berlin meeting, in addition to ministers from the 16 <font size=-1>NATO</font> countries, there will be 27 ministers, mostly East European, from <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s "Partnership for Peace" (see <a href="sf1.gif">table</a>). Faced with the strong desire of East European states for security guarantees, the alliance said in 1994 that it would, in principle, admit new members, and that in the meantime European countries that were not in <font size=-1>NATO</font> could become Partners for Peace. This scheme offers a kind of associate membership to those keen to join but too impatient to wait; and a consolation prize to countries that will never be full members.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The partnership has, surprisingly, turned out to be better than a mere talking-shop. Several partners have taken part in <font size=-1>NATO</font> exercises. Some have opened representations at <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s Brussels headquarters; a few have even submitted details of their forces to a <font size=-1>NATO</font> planning review. Some have agreed to an "individual partnership programme" that is tailor-made to their needs and expectations. The Poles, Hungarians and Czechs are treating the partnership as a school for membership and subscribing to everything on offer; central Asian partners are rather less active.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Russia, too, has become a partner and, after much foot-dragging, agreed to an individual partnership programme. <font size=-1>NATO</font> has tried to woo the Russians by offering, beyond the partnership, an as yet undefined "special relationship". But neither the Russians nor western governments appear to have thought much about the specifics of what this might entail.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The alliance's attempts to renew itself to meet these new tasks have been aided by its experience in Bosnia. There had been no agreement on the theory of <font size=-1>CJTF</font>s, for instance, by the time that Ifor deployed in December 1995; yet it was, in effect, just such a task-force. The Bosnian headquarters was based on the integrated structure's Rapid Reaction Corps, with French officers added to reflect France's involvement. Nor had the Russians worked out their special relationship with <font size=-1>NATO</font> before Ifor; but they still sent a brigade to Bosnia and a general to work beside Saceur. The Czech and Polish contributions to Ifor also put the Partnership for Peace into practice.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the success (at least for the time being) of Ifor should not make <font size=-1>NATO</font> complacent. The alliance cannot remain a valuable organisation unless it embraces further, far-reaching reforms.
</p><p><b>Five tasks for a new NATO</b>
<br>Its first challenge is to find some way of making the French fully paid-up members. Only two European countries, France and Britain, can easily project as many as 10,000 troops out-of-area (Germany's constitution prevents it from being the third); so long as one of them remains semi-detached, the alliance is visibly weakened. France's condition for rejoining the military structure, that a European identity within <font size=-1>NATO</font> be made more pronounced, should not be too hard to satisfy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The French have proposed that some staff in <font size=-1>NATO</font> headquarters should have an extra responsibility as Europeans: in the event of a <font size=-1>WEU</font>-led mission, these officers would detach themselves and reassemble as a European command. The French argue that, although the Europeans would have to spend time together on exercises in order to be effective, this scheme would neither rival nor copy <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s existing organisation. Some Americans have their doubts. The British, however, are supportive, and have even suggested that the deputy Saceur, traditionally a European, should, when the Europeans embark on a <font size=-1>WEU</font> mission, be that organisation's supreme commander.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>NATO</font>'s second challenge is to carry the reform of its military structure beyond <font size=-1>CJTF</font>s, and not only in ways that highlight its European character. Like many a downsizing multinational company, <font size=-1>NATO</font> would benefit from fewer levels of command, slimmed-down headquarters and greater flexibility. In order to defend future members in Eastern Europe, <font size=-1>NATO</font> will need more mobile forces and an improved ability to sustain them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some have suggested scrapping the integrated structure altogether. Charles Kupchan, of the Council on Foreign Relations in Washington, <font size=-1>DC</font>, wants <font size=-1>NATO</font> to be more of a political and less of a military club, so that the Russians will not be upset by its expansion. But the fact that future missions are more likely to involve task-forces than territorial defence does not make the integrated structure useless. A task-force which was a loose coalition of national forces that had never trained together would be ineffective. One reason for Ifor's success is that it has been built around the integrated structure--and run by officers who know how to work as a team.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another lesson from Ifor is that the European members of <font size=-1>NATO</font> depend on the Americans for such essentials as transport planes, communications systems, attack helicopters and satellites that look and listen. Since few European countries are prepared to spend much more on defence, it is crucial for them to find ways of strengthening America's commitment to the alliance. This is <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s third challenge. These days few of America's main security worries are centred on Europe. They concern such nightmares as Iran making nuclear weapons, Iraq building new missiles to fire at Israel, or attacks on Taiwan or South Korea. European leaders seldom have the breadth of vision that would make them willing to help tackle such distant menaces.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Robert Blackwill, who once advised President Bush, has proposed a pact between <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s European members and America. The Europeans would share the burden of dealing with global threats that might affect their security, particularly in the Middle East, and would enhance their ability to project power in such places. In return the Americans would support European efforts to stabilise their continent, for instance by supplying peacekeepers on request. Mr Blackwill wants new institutions to manage this pact, yet few governments would want another formal commitment. Some kind of understanding along these lines, however, might give the alliance a stronger common purpose.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The alliance's fourth, and perhaps biggest challenge, is to plan and implement its own enlargement. <font size=-1>NATO</font> currently intends to hold a special summit early next year, to pick the first batch of new members--almost certainly Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary. Negotiations for their entry may take up much of 1997. Assuming that <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s existing members ratify the necessary treaty changes, this first group should formally join in about 2000.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But it remains far from certain that <font size=-1>NATO</font> will open its doors, if only because opponents of enlargement have come up with some strong arguments. For a start, the Russians see <font size=-1>NATO</font> as a hostile coalition bent on surrounding them. If <font size=-1>NATO</font> expanded, the Russians might carry out their threat to renege on arms-control agreements, while Russia's nationalists would be strengthened at the expense of its liberals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In any case, say opponents of enlargement, it could not make East European states secure for the simple reason that Russia is virtually no threat to the countries most likely to join <font size=-1>NATO</font>. The countries which may have genuine cause to fear Russia--the Baltic, Caucasian and Central Asian republics, and Ukraine--have almost no chance of joining. If the Poles want to belong to a western club, let them join the European Union instead.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A larger alliance would also, these opponents maintain, be a less efficient one, since all <font size=-1>NATO</font> decisions have to be unanimous. They cite the example of the sclerotic Organisation for Co-operation and Security in Europe, which has 52 member countries. Enlargement would also cost money, even if, as is likely, <font size=-1>NATO</font> chose to defend new members by rapid deployment, rather than forward stationing of troops. The alliance would have to pay for base modernisation, training, new equipment and communications systems. Rand, a Californian think-tank, reckons that the cost to <font size=-1>NATO</font> of admitting Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic and Slovakia could be $42 billion, spread over ten years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Extending the article five security guarantee eastwards might also, some say, dilute it. Suppose that Ukraine attacked the Slovaks just after they had joined <font size=-1>NATO</font>: would Americans really be ready to die for Bratislava? Would the alliance be prepared to use nuclear weapons to defend Romania from the Russians? It is because those questions are hard to answer that the American Senate, for all its avowed enthusiasm for <font size=-1>NATO</font> enlargement, may balk at ratifying it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And where should enlargement end? There is a tacit understanding among <font size=-1>NATO</font> governments that it should not encroach on to the territory of the former Soviet Union. That still means that 12 East European countries, four neutral <font size=-1>EU</font> members, Cyprus and Malta could all be candidates. But if Europe is split into two gigantic security blocks, <font size=-1>NATO</font> and the former Soviet Union, would not the dividing line be ludicrously arbitrary? Why should the Romanians--and ultimately, in theory, even the Serbs--have a security guarantee, but not the Estonians?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A partial answer, says the pro-enlargement school, is to make the difference between active involvement in Partnership for Peace and full <font size=-1>NATO</font> membership minimal. A partner that trained with <font size=-1>NATO</font>, participated in its task-forces and joined the planning process would have the essentials of membership, bar article five. Ultimately, they say, the benefits of enlargement are so great that it is just too bad if some countries are, somewhat arbitrarily, left out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One clear benefit would be to reinforce the security of East Europeans. Even if Poland is pretty safe from Russian aggression, taking the Poles into <font size=-1>NATO</font> would help to bind them, culturally, into a democratic, transatlantic club. The enlargers also claim that <font size=-1>NATO</font> can improve the behaviour of potentially awkward neighbours: Greece and Turkey might have exchanged shells rather than sharp words if their belonging to the same military club had not made the prospect ridiculous. If <font size=-1>NATO</font> stuck at 16 members, or let in only the Poles, Czechs and Hungarians, some disappointed states might even drift towards Russia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Robert Zoellick, another senior figure in the Bush adminstration, believes that enlargement would help to counteract the ugly nationalisms of Eastern Europe. "<font size=-1>NATO</font>, like the <font size=-1>EU</font>, represents an integrationist model of relations among states," he says. Such organisations seek to promote stability through "adherence to the common norms of an international civil society", rather than through realpolitik and the balance of power. Mr Zoellick hopes that Russia will learn to see <font size=-1>NATO</font> enlargement not from the perspective of a "19th century" power that laments its inability to dominate weak neighbours, but as a welcome opportunity to have strong, westernising economies next door.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Russians are not there yet. And they continue to predict dire consequences if <font size=-1>NATO</font> enlargement goes ahead. That gives <font size=-1>NATO</font> one more reason to do it: if it were seen to bow to Russian bluster, its credibility would suffer. The Russians might even be encouraged to table new demands.
</p><p><b>Hugging the bear</b>
<br>This is the fifth big challenge for <font size=-1>NATO</font>: to work out a new relationship with Russia, beyond the Partnership for Peace. There has been loose talk of treaties and charters. For all their hostility to <font size=-1>NATO</font> expansion, the Russians remain eager to be included in discussions on European security. That has led some to suggest that the alliance should offer the Russians as much consultation as possible, while still stopping short of any formal role in decision-making.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Christoph Bertram, a German writer, has proposed a new <font size=-1>NATO</font>-Russia forum, with a joint committee of ambassadors and a common council of defence and foreign ministers. The two sides could swap information on defence planning and peacekeeping in a military committee. They could deal with nuclear proliferation and the dismantling of nuclear weapons in a nuclear planning group. And they could discuss defence exports and industrial co-operation in an arms-control group.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such a forum would doubtless generate plenty of hot air. But it might have a value in drawing the Russian elite into a regular dialogue with <font size=-1>NATO</font>, so that each side better understood the other. Mr Bertram believes that the forum could make it easier to resolve diplomatic wrangles, such as the revision of the Conventional Forces in Europe treaty. The Russians may not, for the time being, be interested. Yet they have it in their power to determine the nature of a future <font size=-1>NATO</font>. The better they behave and the more they co-operate and share information, the less anti-Russian <font size=-1>NATO</font> will be.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if the alliance manages to surmount all these challenges, it will have changed enormously. It will be less coherent and disciplined than it was in the past. Philip Gordon, of the International Institute for Strategic Studies in London, predicts that "the <font size=-1>NATO</font> of the future will be less about protecting its members from an all-out assault, and more about consulting like-minded nations that sometimes have similar interests and values to protect around the world." Yet even if Mr Gordon is right, Bosnia has shown that <font size=-1>NATO</font> is far from redundant. It is a useful constraint on nasty and unpredictable international behaviour, whether of its own members, or of other powers. As such, it makes everyone feel safer--which is not, in today's world, a negligible achievement.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?833583600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
