<html><head><title>Trouble in the air</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Spectrum allocation</b></p>
<h1>Trouble in the air</h1>

<p>AIR is money, as the Americans have discovered. Over the past couple of years, their federal government has made around $20 billion from auctioning bits of the radio spectrum to the highest bidder. Now the British government is planning a white paper on how to sell off the airwaves.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a relief to the Radiocommunications Agency (<font size=-1>RA</font>), the body in charge of dispensing frequency slots, which for a decade has been trying to introduce a rational way of allocating the airwaves. Two developments have helped push the government in that direction. Digital technology allows the spectrum to be used far more efficiently than does analogue technology; at the same time, demand for frequencies from new wireless uses is booming.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the moment, spectrum is mainly handed out on the basis of first come, first served. This leads to inequity and inefficiency. People who want to run private mobile radio systems (truck radios, say, or taxi-pagers or courier radios) have to jostle for small slivers of the ether. Cellular telephones are suffering from congestion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Great swathes of spectrum, meanwhile, are occupied by users who are paying virtually nothing for it. Some dog-in-the-mangers are enormous: <font size=-1>BT</font>, Britain's telecoms giant, and <font size=-1>NTL</font>, which transmits television programmes across the country, both use microwave links between transmitters. If they had to pay a market price for the large amount of spectrum this needs, they might well use cable links instead.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;An American-style auction would be the best solution, but such radicalism has run into big obstacles in the industry ministry. Ministers fret that big, rich companies might outbid smaller ones simply in order to keep out competitors. They also fear that existing users, such as taxi companies and lorry drivers, will grumble noisily at having to pay more. An even bigger obstacle is the resistance of other countries in the European Union to spectrum auctions, which make it easier for new entrants to offer telephone and broadcasting services. The likely outcome is a British fudge: part-auction, part-sale at a price set to reflect the spectrum's value.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In theory, the government would like to treat public and private spectrum-users equally. But the Ministry of Defence sits on about 30% of the most congested bands: it is not keen to make room for commerce. The three emergency services pose special problems: they are on different frequencies, which means that they cannot talk to one another. Other users have to be kept well clear of them to avoid interference. They have been offered a new part of the spectrum to launch a digital service, but do not want to give up their scattered analogue bands.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A further complication is television: at present, the four (soon to be five) terrestrial channels are gluttonous users of spectrum. One of the main reasons the government wants to launch digital terrestrial television is to free up space for more lucrative uses. But the government has resisted setting a date to shut down analogue transmission. A research paper for the <font size=-1>RA</font>, intended to be published with the spectrum white paper, suggests an alternative scheme: subsidise the price of digital sets to speed up the transition and allow the spectrum to be rapidly re-allocated. Now that sounds dangerously radical.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?833583600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
