<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Going mad</h2>
<p>Britain said it would <b>sabotage the work of the European Union</b> until the <font size=-1>EU</font> eases its ban on the export of British beef. It started by refusing to sign an <font size=-1>EU</font> bankruptcy convention. Leaders of other European countries denounced the decision as blackmail. Their fury did not stop the European Commission from again recommending that farm ministers lift the ban on exports of beef tallow, gelatin and semen.<p>
About 240,000 public-sector workers in Germany staged more <b>warning strikes</b> to protest against the government's plan to cut the budget deficit by freezing their wages, but the two sides were negotiating. Germany's economy contracted for the second consecutive quarter, putting it in recession by some definitions.<p>
Romano Prodi took office as prime minister in Italy's <b>first left-leaning government</b> in half a century. He pledged to discourage secessionist sentiment in the north by decentralising the state and to prepare Italy for the introduction of Europe's single currency in 1999.<p>
Radovan Karadzic, the <b>Bosnian Serb leader</b> wanted for war crimes, ceded some of his duties to deputies, but he appears to have lost little power. The Bosnian Serb parliament has broken the promise it made to western diplomats to push him aside. The vice-president, who assumed responsibility for foreign relations, and the new prime minister are considered as hardline as Mr Karadzic.<p>
Russia and Britain expelled four of each other's diplomats and declared an end to their <b>spying row</b>. It began when Russia accused Britain of buying secrets from a Russian civil servant.<p>
<p>
(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>
The European Union's <b>foreign population</b> was 3.3% of its 369m total in 1993. Turks were the largest group of non-<font size=-1>EU</font> nationals, making up 14.7% of the total. They are followed by citizens of ex-Yugoslavia, at 7.9%, and by Moroccans, who made up 6.2%. Some 400,000 Americans lived in the <font size=-1>EU</font>, half of them in Britain and Germany.

<h2>Business as usual</h2>
<p>As expected, President Clinton said he would renew China's <b>most-favoured-nation</b> status in its trade with the United States (Congress permitting). China complained that the need to renew <font size=-1>MFN</font> each year disrupted trade and political relations.<p>
China ratified the <font size=-1>UN</font> <b>Law of the Sea </b>convention and promptly announced new claims to contested parts of the South China Sea around the Paracel Islands, alarming some of its neighbours. Further claims, including those to the Spratly Islands, will be announced "at another time".<p>
Myanmar's military rulers detained around 200 <b>democracy activists</b> who were planning to attend a meeting this weekend at the home of the country's opposition leader, Aung San Suu Kyi.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
The president of <b>Bangladesh</b>, Abdur Rahman Biswas, sacked several senior officers, including the head of the army. All were placed under house arrest. The presidential palace is being protected against a threatened rebellion by troops loyal to the ousted officers. A general election is due to be held in the country on June 12th.

<h2>Welfare as weapon</h2>
<p>President Clinton endorsed a radical Wisconsin plan to abolish the main federal welfare programme, Aid to Families with Dependent Children. His main purpose was to pre-empt a big speech on welfare by the rejuvenated and <b>repackaged Bob Dole</b>, who had travelled to the mid-west to deliver it. Mr Dole was duly pre-empted.<p>
The Supreme Court struck down as irrational a Colorado law that barred cities from enacting statutes to <b>protect homosexuals</b>.<p>
Voters bark, but Latin America's <b>privatisation </b>caravan moves on. Brazil sold 55% of Rio de Janeiro's power company for $2.2 billion. Peru signed a deal with Mobil and Shell to exploit its huge Camisea gas field.<p>
<b>Mexico</b>'s Zapatist peasant rebels threatened to renew violence. <font size=-1>PAN</font>, the right-wing party, agreed to rejoin talks on democratic reform.<p>
In <b>Ecuador</b>'s presidential election, right-of-centre Jaime Nebot won a first-round lead, but by less than expected. In the <b>Dominican Republic</b>, leftist Jose Francisco Pe&ntilde;a Gomez led with 46% of the votes. But the right still hopes to unite and defeat him in the second round.

<h2>Iraqi oil is back</h2>
<p><b>Iraq and the United Nations</b> reached a deal at last. It allows Iraq to sell $2 billion-worth of oil over an initial six-month period. Two-thirds of the money will go on food and medicine for Iraqi civilians, including Kurds, one-third on Gulf war reparations and <font size=-1>UN</font> expenses. The <font size=-1>UN</font> will supervise the sale of oil and the purchase and distribution of food.<p>
Shimon Peres, Israel's prime minister, facing a tight election on May 29th, accused <b>Iran of plotting terrorism</b> to spoil his chances. Warren Christopher, America's secretary of state, agreed, and called on European countries to join the American trade boycott. Iran said it was the Americans who were fomenting tension.<p>
A <b>Tanzanian ferry</b> capsized on Lake Victoria, drowning several hundred people.<p>
Troops mutinied in the <b>Central African Republic</b>. French soldiers based there--and more specially flown in--protected foreigners and actively opposed the mutineers.<p>
<b>Zambia</b>'s parliament passed a bill raising technical hurdles to bar Kenneth Kaunda, voted out of the presidency in 1991, from standing again this year.<p>
<p>
<p>

</p>
