<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p>


<h2>Spat over Cuba</h2>
<p>At the Paris summit of the 27 rich countries in the <font size=-1>OECD</font>, Sir Leon Brittan, the European Union's trade commissioner, said America's <b>unilateral actions</b> on trade had set back global economic liberation. He called the new Helms-Burton act, which allows legal action against foreign companies investing in Cuba, "extra-territorial and expropriatory". And <b>Russia</b>, unexpectedly, asked to join the <font size=-1>OECD</font>.<p>
<b>Russia's Central Bank </b>said it was taking over the running of Unikombank, a Moscow commercial bank with assets of $1.8 billion and some 250,000 depositors. A Unikombank official admitted to a "management crisis" but gave no details. Much of Russia's banking industry is considered fragile.<p>
<b>Japan's trade surplus</b> contracted sharply, and unexpectedly, in April to its lowest monthly level in 13 years. It narrowed by 66% to &#165;321 billion ($3 billion). Meanwhile, Japan's big <b>trading companies</b> strengthened their profits.<p>
Jeff Vinik resigned as the manager of <b>Fidelity Investments'</b> Magellan Fund, the largest mutual fund in the world. He had been criticised recently because of the fund's poor performance. Fidelity said he was not forced to go. He plans to start his own investment company.<p>
Renato Della Valle, an Italian entrepreneur, sold his 23.4% stake in<b> Telepiu</b>, an Italian pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> station, to <b>Kirch</b> for 250 billion lire ($160m). The secretive German media firm is an ally of Fininvest, an Italian company under investigation for having given Mr Della Valle the money to buy the stake in Telepiu.

<h2>Bionic</h2>
<p><p>
(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Shares in <b>British Biotech</b>, a firm that has yet to produce a single product, soared. Its market capitalisation of around &#163;150m ($265m) at its flotation in 1992 reached close to &#163;2 billion after trials of marimastat, a cancer treatment, proved promising.<p>
<b>Goldman Sachs</b>, one of Wall Street's most profitable investment banks and its last big private partnership, said it will become a limited-liability partnership from November 30th.<p>
<b>Bankers Trust</b>, an American investment bank that had made its derivatives business too fancy for some tastes, took further steps to bolster its customer relationships. It lured Paul Volcker, a former Fed chairman, on to its board, and purchased Wolfensohn &amp; Co, a merger firm founded by the present president of the World Bank.<p>
Less than two weeks into his new job as <b>Swiss Bank Corporation</b>'s chief executive, Marcel Ospel announced the final stages of a restructuring. Switzerland's third-largest bank will be split into four, the big change being the formation of two new divisions, one for private banking, the other for its huge fund-management business.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
As the Securities and Exchange Commission opened its case against <b>Joseph Jett</b>, a former bond trader at Kidder, Peabody accused of covering up vast trading losses, his former supervisor, Melvin Mullin, offered to pay $25,000 to settle <font size=-1>SEC</font> charges that he failed to supervise Mr Jett adequately. Mr Mullin agreed to be suspended for three months from the securities business.

<h2>Scratching a living</h2>
<p>America's Supreme Court reversed the notorious $2m award made against <b>BMW</b> for selling a doctor a car with retouched paintwork. An Alabaman court had awarded him $4,000 in compensation--and $4m in punitive damages (later halved by the state supreme court).<p>
A turnaround at its Brooks Brothers subsidiary helped pre-tax profits at <b>Marks and Spencer</b>, Britain's leading retailer, rise to &#163;965.8m ($1.5 billion) in the year to end-March, from &#163;924m a year earlier. <font size=-1>M&S</font> says Brooks is America's fastest-growing men's retailer. Its operating profits leapt by 81% to &#163;10.7m after a &#163;2.5m first-half loss.<p>
<b>McDonald's</b> and <b>Walt Disney</b> announced a global alliance, sharing exclusive marketing rights for everything from films to food, to run for ten years from January 1997.

<h2>Transported</h2>
<p><b>British Airways</b> soared past Singapore Airlines to become the world's most profitable airline, with record pre-tax profits of &#163;585m ($916m) in the year to end-March, nearly 30% up on the previous year.<p>
A possible strategic alliance between <font size=-1>BA</font> and American Airlines will happen only if the British government at last relents and agrees to an <b>open skies </b>agreement with the American government (that is, better access to Heathrow). Such a deal has just been forged with the German government, allowing Lufthansa and United to form a link; other European deals are nearing completion.<p>
<b>Japan's car makers</b> are expanding in China. Toyota won permission for a joint venture with Tianjin Auto to make 150,000 engines a year. They will be used in Charade cars which Tianjin already makes under licence from Daihatsu, a Toyota affiliate. Toyota hopes to open a new car plant in China. Suzuki is considering a direct stake in Changan Auto, with which it already has a joint venture.<p>
(See <a href="wtw3.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>ValuJet</b> halved its 320 flights to allow governmental safety checks after one of the low-cost carrier's aircraft crashed in the Everglades killing all 110 people on board.<p>
<p></p>
</td></tr></table></center>
