<html><head><title>Cheap, dumb and connected</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>


<h1><left>Cheap, dumb and connected</left></h1>

<p><left><b>Even so, "network computers" are not yet ready to change the world</b></left></p>


IF YOU know one thing about the history of the computer industry you know that in the 1980s the personal computer toppled the mainframe, making life miserable for <font size=-1>IBM</font> and turning Microsoft into one of the world's richest companies. On May 20th a collection of computer and software companies, led by Oracle, announced what they claim to be an equally revolutionary change. They have developed a common standard for simple machines that could do the job of a <font size=-1>PC</font> for a fraction of the price. These "network computers" will get their brainpower not from their own chips and software--which are cheap compared with those in a <font size=-1>PC</font>--but from the Internet and other networks to which they will be wired.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The companies involved say that there is a vast market for these slimmed-down computers. It includes hundreds of millions of households that cannot now afford a <font size=-1>PC</font> and the many offices where <font size=-1>PC</font>s are proving even more expensive than the mainframes they replaced. That may be true--some day. But for today, the numbers do not quite add up.

</p><p><b>The digital Achilles heel</b>
<br>In principle, the idea of network computers is sound enough. What a stand-alone <font size=-1>PC</font> can do, a networked one can often do better, simply because by linking up with many other computers it has more of everything--information, processing power and people--at its disposal. The rise of the Internet has taken that idea from offices to the world at large (see our survey of the <a href="http://www.economist.com/surveys/software/">software industry</a>). Now anyone dialling in from home has as much information and computing power within reach as the biggest companies. Cheap network computers, perhaps as part of a video-game or a small box beside a television, could spread such benefits from today's relatively few <font size=-1>PC</font> owners to the masses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Just as long, that is, as the masses do not mind interminable delays. The problem with network computers is that they are no better than the networks they are connected to. In the home this usually means the telephone line, which is fine for voice but excruciatingly slow for data. To really shine, network computers need fast, digital connections, of the sort found in many offices but in hardly any homes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Here's the rub: the people who would benefit most from cheap Internet terminals are the very people who would need the most expensive new networks to make them work well. It would cost billions to connect only those homes that already have cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> lines to high-speed data networks. Upgrading the telephone networks to do the same might cost even more. Better communications networks will come one way or another, but until the economic case for them becomes stronger, the day most homes have a fast digital connection is a decade or more away.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many offices, on the other hand, already possess fast data networks. There, the case for network computers is focused more on the desktop itself. Advocates of network computing point to the high cost of <font size=-1>PC</font>s: by some estimates as much as $10,000 a year for each user, mostly for support and training. Surely, they argue, by giving each user a cheap, low-maintenance machine, with all the software stored and maintained centrally, much of that could be saved. Perhaps. But most of the saving from such a solution would come from switching to new "intranet" software, not network-computer hardware; the lump of metal and plastic on the desktop accounts for less than 20% of total computing costs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What the Oracle camp overlooks is that the <font size=-1>PC</font>s on most office desks are practically network computers already. Most are wired to some network, and with the right software they can work just like Oracle's whizzy black box. In a few years it will be clearer whether specialised network computers really do offer any other advantages. It would be unwise, until then, to take Oracle's revolutionary manifesto too seriously.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832978800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
