<html><head><title>What election?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Northern Ireland</b></p>
<h1>What election?</h1>

<font size=1>BELFAST</font><p>
YOU would not know that Northern Ireland's election was due on May 30th. Hardly anybody is talking about it. Instead, debate is about what the elections are really about: the all-party talks due to be held on June 10th, and the chances that they will produce anything of substance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The British government insists that Sinn Fein must satisfy three conditions if it is to take part in the talks. It must stand in the election. It must accept the "Mitchell principles" set out by the International Body on Decommissioning, chaired by George Mitchell, an American senator--essentially, forswearing violence. And it must persuade the <font size=-1>IRA</font> to declare a ceasefire.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sinn Fein fully intends to stand in the election. It is expected to get around 10% of the vote. And this week, Sinn Fein's leader, Gerry Adams, said that his party accepted the "Mitchell principles".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, another ceasefire seems no closer. In a speech at a republican ceremony in Belfast on May 12th, Brian Keenan, a republican hardliner, threatened that "those who don't want peace will get war." Mr Keenan, released from an English jail three years ago, sees decommissioning--getting the <font size=-1>IRA</font> to give up their weapons--as Britain's only aim in talks. He also called Irish ministers "bastards" for putting insufficient pressure on Britain.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Adams says that a ceasefire is in the gift of the <font size=-1>IRA</font>, not Sinn Fein. His growing insistence that he speaks only for Sinn Fein feeds speculation that an open split is imminent among the republicans he has led for almost 20 years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unionists, meanwhile, fear that the government will not push hard enough to disarm the <font size=-1>IRA</font>. David Trimble, the Ulster Unionist leader, threatens to withhold the support of his party's nine votes in the Commons if the government shows signs of backsliding. John Major has been trying to reassure his Unionist-sympathising backbenchers that decommissioning will indeed be "addressed" at the start of talks. Unionists prefer the word "resolved".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Irish government wants the arms question raised during negotiations, rather than as the first (and therefore probably the last) stage of talks. This was what the Mitchell commission recommended. It recognised that for both the <font size=-1>IRA</font> and Loyalist paramilitaries disarmament before negotiations meant surrender and humiliation. It argued for "modest steps on decommissioning" at the same time as progress towards political compromise. Talks between the Irish and British governments held on May 22nd once again failed to resolve the issue.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832978800,iss">Search</a>
