<html><head><title>Selective cull</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Politics</b></p>
<h1>Selective cull</h1>


<p>"SHORT of being caught in the act of sodomy, it's virtually impossible for a Tory <font size=-1>MP</font> to be deselected", one ex-cabinet minister said last week. Yet Sir George Gardiner, the <font size=-1>MP</font> for Reigate and no sodomite, may be about to achieve deselection nevertheless. His local party votes on June 28th on whether to unseat him for disloyalty to John Major, following a 15-14 majority against him last week in the local party executive. He is apparently strong in party branches with few members and weak in those with more, which means that his chances are no better than 50:50.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, deselection of Tories is much more common than the conventional wisdom has it. In all, this century, 37 Tories have been dumped by their constituencies. Two, David Ashby and Robert Banks, have already been deselected in this parliament; homophobia played a part in the first case, and constituency neglect in the second. A third, Sir Nicholas Scott, whose problem was that he drank and drove, narrowly avoided the sack.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What makes Sir George's case stand out is what he is threatening to do about it. He says that if he is dropped, he will immediately resign, precipitating a by-election. No previous Tory has done any such thing, though Dick (now Lord) Taverne, did it as a Labour <font size=-1>MP</font> when dropped by his Lincoln party in 1973. (He fought the seat as an independent and won.) It would be an expensive gesture by Sir George, as <font size=-1>MP</font>s who quit voluntarily in mid-parliament forgo the &#163;34,000 in redundancy pay they would get if they held on until the general election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With the government's overall Commons majority down to one, Sir George presumably hopes that his threat will persuade his opponents to back off. However, it is not as potent as it looks. Even if he quits, the by-election will not have to be held until December--and if the Tories cannot win a seat as safe as Reigate at a by-election come December, Mr Major is anyway doomed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many of his colleagues in parliament are strangely uncharitable towards Sir George. They point out that he describes himself as a "grassroots Conservative"--ie, a supporter of the narrow Thatcherite views presumed to be held by Tory activists. To their ill-concealed glee, it turns out that those very activists don't think much of his carping at John Major.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Party deselection was long feared by Tory and Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>s alike because it allowed party extremists to subvert the voters' choice by defeating moderate <font size=-1>MP</font>s. But in the Labour Party over the last ten years, more left-wingers have been deselected than have moderates. Sir George's case suggests that the same may now apply to <font size=-1>MP</font>s on the wilder fringes of the Tory right.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832978800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
</p>
