<html><head><title>http://manhattan</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/mo.gif"  alt="Moreover">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Netting New York</b></p>
<h1>http://manhattan</h1>

<p>NEW YORK, if you believe New Yorkers, is always on the brink of disaster. Yet the place invariably confounds its doomsayers. Because New York is so expensive to do business in, it has to dump yesterday's industries and embrace tomorrow's more quickly than anywhere else. Among America's big cities, it was first in and first out of shipping, manufacturing and corporate head offices. Now it is shifting fast into electronic publishing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;An area of wired lofts and offices on Manhattan known as Silicon Alley has spread from around the old Flatiron Building on 23rd Street. A survey in April by the New York New Media Association (<font size=-1>NYNMA</font>) and Coopers &amp; Lybrand, a consultancy, found that about 18,000 people in New York city were working full-time for more than 1,100 new media firms, compared with fewer than 17,000 in <font size=-1>TV</font> and radio and 13,000 in newspapers. Most of this growth has come in the past two years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why New York? Part of the answer is the city's strength in traditional media, or "trad med" as the new digerati (digital literati) call it. It needed nerds tinkering brilliantly in California to create new communication technologies. But it took writers, editors and phrase-makers, all New York specialities, to provide content. While the technologists financed by venture capitalists from California's Menlo Park tinkered happily in Mountain View, Cupertino, Milpitas and other Californian towns, the creative folk headed for New York, America's traditional media hub.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More concretely, when trad-med powerhouses such as Time Warner and Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation began to pour money into new media they did so from their established New York bases, rather than starting afresh on the west coast. But giants like these which have traded their typewriters for mice, and like Dow Jones, which has launched an online edition of the <i>Wall Street Journal</i>, are vastly outnumbered by small start-up companies. And it is these small companies--half of the new media firms in the New York area have a turnover of less than $500,000 a year--that are mainly responsible for the new media boom in New York.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Total New York, which produces a faddish Internet-based listings magazine and a soap opera, and SonicNet, the Web publisher of a music magazine, are the sort of firms that crave loft spaces and industrial design. The result: the heart of Silicon Alley is an area south of the Flatiron Building and encompassing Chelsea, SoHo and Tribeca.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The high concentration of new media companies is now New York's greatest advantage in electronic publishing: it is simply easier to do business with a neighbour than a stranger. This provides the city with an edge over its rivals, notably the technology enclaves of the west coast. In San Francisco such contenders as <i>Wired</i> magazine, the rattle-bearer of new media, cluster in an ill-defined sprawl.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Silicon Alley is much less amorphous. <font size=-1>NYNMA</font> and the Worldwide Web Artists Consortium and the companies themselves have created a new business community. Cybersuds, the <font size=-1>NYNMA</font>'s monthly networking social, where cyberspace artists and directors mix with each other and beer (hence the suds) has served as a catalyst. When Cybersuds began in mid-1994, it attracted a couple of dozen developers, most of whom already knew each other. Today its monthly meetings draw 1,000 artists, designers and programmers to a frenzy of networking and business-card swapping. Some of the new firms are more hip than profitable and, unfortunately, hip won't pay the bills.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;New York's record is not unblemished. Two of the bigger names in the business, News Corporation, whose online service, Delphi, is based in the Flatiron district, and Prodigy have had to lay off workers. Many companies complain that Nynex, the local telephone utility, does a poor job in providing the infrastructure needed for Internet connections. As a result, new media companies have swarmed around points in the city where rival telephone companies provide access to data pipes. A few others have headed for the New York Information Technology Centre at 55 Broad Street.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Next to Wall Street and far south of the heart of Silicon Alley, this building brags that it is the first to be hardwired for the information revolution. It provides every mod con for high-tech tenants: built-in computer networking and high-speed Internet access. It also benefits from big tax breaks provided by the city and state governments. Its landlords, Rudin Management, insist that tenants have a suitable multimedia pedigree. The approach seems to work: some of them have even struck deals in the lift.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832978800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
