<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Dole gets serious</h2>
<p>Bob Dole, the Republican presidential candidate, announced that he was not only giving up his post of majority leader but was <b>retiring from the Senate</b> altogether to concentrate on his campaign against President Bill Clinton.<p>
A <font size=-1>DC</font>-<font size=-1>9</font> <b>aircraft crashed </b>in the Florida Everglades, killing all 110 people on board. Federal officials insisted that low-cost airlines such as ValuJet are safe.<p>
<b>Brazil</b> announced a new human-rights programme. Five days before, the Senate scuppered a bill that would have brought abuses by the armed police to civil, not army, courts.<p>
The <b>Dominican Republic </b>held first-round presidential elections. Its 89-year-old, blind president, Joaquin Balaguer, was barred by law--after 6.5 terms--from standing, and his favoured candidate was expected to come a poor third.

<h2>Conferring</h2>
<p>After talks with some of <b>Algeria</b>'s political leaders, President Zeroual revealed his proposals for reforming the constitution, and rescuing the country from its four-year civil war. These would enforce the separation of religion and politics--presumably outlawing religious parties such as the <font size=-1>FIS</font>--and encourage political pluralism.<p>
Hosni Mubarak of Egypt, King Hussein of Jordan and Yasser Arafat of embryonic Palestine met in Cairo to denounce<b> Israel</b>'s "concepts of expansion, superiority and domination". Israel, meanwhile, tightened control on Palestinian movement: no workers to be allowed in from Gaza until further notice, none into Jerusalem until May 19th.<p>
Amid great pomp, Iran and Turkmenistan inaugurated a 300km (190-mile) railway link between Mashhad and Tedzhen. This plugs a gap in the <b>Silk Road </b>railway route through Central Asia, putting Iran, or so it hopes, at the hub of east-west trade links.<p>
A truce stopped <b>Liberia's civil war</b>--for two days, after which fierce gunfire broke out afresh. Some 2,000 refugees were allowed to land in Ghana, after nine days packed on a cargo vessel. Sierra Leone took 700 from another ship.<p>
<b>South Africa</b> picked itself calmly up from the National Party's May 9th decision to leave the coalition government. The rand strengthened against the dollar; stocks and bonds were uneasy, no more. Municipal voting in troubled KwaZulu-Natal was rescheduled for June 26th.<p>
Ten years after he seized control of <b>Uganda</b> in a coup, Yoweri Museveni was elected, democratically, to a five-year presidential term.

<h2>A new leader, just</h2>

<p>The Hindu-nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party formed <b>India's new government</b>, with Atal Behari Vajpayee as its prime minister. The party and its allies have 194 seats in the new 545-seat hung parliament, but may not muster enough support in a vote of confidence due by May 31st to stay in power. Previous governments in India, which has a large Muslim minority, have been secular in policy.<p><td valign=top width=30%>
Six western and three Indonesian <b>hostages </b>held by a separatist group in the Indonesian province of Irian Jaya were freed by the Indonesian army. Two other Indonesian hostages were found dead.<p>
Hong Kong speeded up the repatriation of <b>boat people </b>to Vietnam after 120 escaped from a detention camp. The British colony aims to deport its remaining 17,500 boat people before the territory is handed over to China next year.<p>
A tornado ripped through northern <b>Bangladesh</b>, killing more than 550 people.

<h2>Tightened belts</h2>
<p>Real <b>growth in the European Union</b> will be a scant 1.5% this year but will rise to 2.4% in 1997, the European Commission predicted. It said that Germany and France would cut their public-sector deficits to 3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> or less in 1997, allowing them to qualify for Europe's economic and monetary union (<font size=-1>EMU</font>) two years later.<p>
Other <font size=-1>EMU</font> hopefuls readied plans for <b>deficit reductions</b> this year and next. France wants to cut taxes and freeze spending. Italy's outgoing prime minister, Lamberto Dini, wants 12 trillion lire ($7.7 billion) in spending cuts. And Belgium's parliament gave its prime minister, Jean-Luc Dehaene, special powers to push through social-security reforms and BFr25 billion ($791m) of budget savings in 1996.<p>
Postmen and other public-sector workers in Germany staged <b>warning strikes</b> against plans to cut public spending by DM70 billion ($46 billion) next year largely by denying them a pay rise. Germany's 16 states rejected the federal government's proposals for tax reform.<p>
International pressure grew for the extradition of <b>Radovan Karadzic</b>, the hardline Bosnian Serb leader, after he dismissed Rajko Kasagic, the (moderate) Bosnian Serb prime minister.<p>
Bulgaria's government decided to shut down 67 <b>loss-making state companies </b>as part of a programme to cut its debt and restore confidence in its creditworthiness.<p>
Turkey's parliament voted to investigate <b>corruption charges</b> against a former prime minister, Tansu Ciller. Many of the votes came from the Motherland Party, which governs in coalition with Mrs Ciller's True Path Party. Their coalition was further weakened when the constitutional court said a parliamentary vote of confidence in the government was invalid.<p>
<p>

</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
