<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<h2>Leaner and meaner</h2>
<p>A <b>trade war</b> edged closer as the United States and China threatened each other with punitive tariffs in a dispute over intellectual-property rights.<p>
(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>Two big defence contractors, Lagard&egrave;re Groupe's Matra and British Aerospace, are to merge their <b>missile businesses </b>to create Europe's biggest missile maker. The new company, Matra <font size=-1>BA</font>e Dynamics, could join Daimler-Benz Aerospace and Britain's <font size=-1>GEC</font> in bidding for Thomson-<font size=-1>CSF</font>, the defence-electronics subsidiary of Thomson, soon to be privatised by the French government.<p>
European ministers approved plans designed to enhance <b>Airbus Industrie</b>'s ability to compete with its arch-rival across the Atlantic, <b>Boeing</b>. The Airbus consortium, which shares work between its four partners from France, Germany, Britain and Spain, will cut costs by becoming a single company.<p>
The French government is selling a further chunk of <b>Renault</b>, ending 50 years of state control. The 6% sell-off will raise about FFr2 billion ($380m) and reduce the state's holding in the car maker to 46%, but a full privatisation still seems some way off.<p>
First <b>General Motors</b> filed suit against <b>Volkswagen</b> in an American court, citing fraud. Now, two months on, Volkswagen is demanding DM10 billion ($6.5 billion) from the Detroit giant for defamation. The long-running dispute between the two car makers goes back to 1993, when Jose Ignacio Lopez and several others left <font size=-1>GM</font> to join <font size=-1>VW</font>, allegedly taking industrial secrets with them.

<h2>Crossed lines</h2>
<p>The new head of <b>Apple Computer</b>, Gil Amelio, announced a plan to avoid "a long, slow decline into irrelevancy". The loss-making computer firm will halve the number of models on offer to about 40, cut costs by 15%, license the Macintosh operating system to more computer makers and concentrate more on the Internet.<p>
Arrest warrants were issued for seven senior managers at <b>Fininvest</b>, an Italian media group controlled by Silvio Berlusconi, a former prime minister, for allegedly falsifying accounts in 1989-95.<p>
The government of Abu Dhabi, principal shareholder in the failed <b>Bank of Credit and Commerce International</b>, paid a $1.55 billion settlement to <font size=-1>BCCI</font>'s liquidator.<p>
Two American oil giants, <b>Philips </b>and <b>Conoco</b>, are talking of dumping their gasoline-refining and marketing operations into a joint venture with over $5 billion-worth of assets, a cost-saving measure already adopted by British Petroleum and Mobil. <b>Mobil</b>, meanwhile, at last reached agreement to buy <b>Ampolex</b>, an Australian energy group, after the American oil giant raised its bid to A$1.78 billion ($1.43 billion).<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
A new startRussia said it would set new trading bands for the <b>rouble</b> with effect from July 1st. The official floor-rate, currently 5,150 roubles to the dollar, is to be lowered to 5,600 roubles, and then progressively to 6,100 roubles by the end of 1996.<p>
One of Britain's big electricity generators, <b>PowerGen</b>, reported pre-tax profits of &#163;687m ($1.08 billion) for 1995 against &#163;545m a year earlier, and said it would buy back 10% of its shares. The sale of PowerGen's 21% stake in Midlands Electricity to America's Avon Energy for &#163;353m will pay for the buyback: Avon is now proceeding with the takeover of Midlands that was barred to PowerGen by the British government.<p>
(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Up to a fifth of shareholders in <b>Montedison</b> want the sprawling Italian food, chemicals and energy giant broken up, and accuse the board of poor corporate governance. But Montedison is 32% owned by Ferfin, in turn owned by Mediobanco, a shadowy merchant bank which would prefer to expand Montedison, not break it up. At least Montedison's share price received a boost.<p>
The drama at <b>Sony Corp</b> may finally have produced a happy ending. Thanks to rising sales of semiconductors and mini-disc players, the Japanese electronic giant reported a group net profit of &#165;54.3 billion ($564m) for 1995, with better to come, reversing 1994's loss of &#165;293.36 billion. That year, its Hollywood-based entertainment group ran up losses of &#165;50 billion and resulted in a &#165;265 billion write-off for the group.

<h2>The big one</h2>
<p><b>Lloyd's of London</b> offered an improved &#163;3.1 billion ($4.7 billion) package to the insurance market's investors (names), cutting by nearly half the average amount names must find to cover their past losses--though some will find themselves worse off. All in all, the package is worth an extra &#163;1.2 billion. And in California, home to a large cluster of names, the threat of litigation has been shelved by a "standstill agreement" , allowing Lloyd's to negotiate further.<p>
The long-running derivatives dispute between <b>Bankers Trust </b>and <b>Procter &amp; Gamble </b>was settled before it went to court when <font size=-1>P&G</font> agreed to pay only $35m of the $195m it owed the bank under two unprofitable swap agreements. The consumer-goods firm had sued the bank for fraud, claiming it had been misled over the risks.<p></p>
</td></tr></table></center>
