<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/18-05-96/sf1.html 199.173.162.110 19970215035857 text/html 20117
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 03:54:51 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:03:59 GMT
Content-length: 19929
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Two are two, and all alone</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif"  alt="Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Two are two, and all alone</h1>
<p><b>Neither Bob Dole nor Bill Clinton, it seems, warms the hearts of America's voters. The moment for a third force to stride on the scene? Don't count on it.</b></p>


<p>BACK in the beginning, America hoped it could do without parties. It nonetheless acquired them almost as soon as it was born. One group of men wanted the constitution adopted, the other did not. Result: a Federalist party and an Anti-Federalist party. The Founding Fathers hated this blight on the harmony of their new republic; they thought that party spirit must have entered man's soul, like sin, with Adam's first bite of the apple in the Garden of Eden. Yet parties were indispensable to organise political activity, to select candidates for office, to mobilise voters, and--in a constitutional system that had carefully separated the executive from the legislature--to get legislation passed at all. They were dreadful, but nothing worked without them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The ambivalence persists to this day. Americans are deeply dissatisfied with their two huge parties, the Democrats (born circa 1832) and the Republicans (born 1854). Yet they cannot agree on the reason for their dissatisfaction. Some say the parties are too strong: they hold a duopoly of power, keep interesting contenders out, tie up all political money and pander outrageously to special interests. Others say they are too weak: they stand for nothing at all, try to be all things to all men (and fail), and have fewer and fewer serious members; they are ripe for euthanasia at the hands of either a new third party or a hero of truly independent mind.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, both accusations are true. America's two old parties are dauntingly strong: not so much at the national level, where they are all vapid speeches and patriotic platforms, but powerful indeed at the local level of wards, city halls and congressional districts. Barely a politician can be found at this level who is not a Republican or a Democrat. Bill Weld of Massachusetts, Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin, George Bush Junior of Texas, all the rising governors making a name for themselves, would never dream of going independent; that is the sort of thing dreamy senators do in their retirement. Parties are enabling machines through which men rise to power. Without them, most still get nowhere.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Besides, America's system of single-member congressional districts, elected on a winner-take-all basis, means that there is no point in a multiplicity of parties at local level. Two is quite enough: one For, one Against. If there were any movement for proportional representation in America, the picture would look different. But there is none; the word "Italy", evoking memories of multi-party corruption, is enough to scotch the thought. If special interests want to gain influence and power, they set out to link themselves to one or other of the two big parties. They give it money, butter up its candidates, and hope for the desired result. The local habit persists when men start to think about running the country.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With so much inherent strength, reports of the death of America's two main parties are greatly exaggerated. Both have several times been prematurely killed off.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Democrats were thought unlikely to survive the rise of the Populists in the 1890s; the Republicans seemed likely to collapse with Wall Street after 1929. The fact that the Democrats now seem a rump party of the disadvantaged, and the Republicans sometimes look like an impossibly volcanic combination of gun-owners, militant Christians, businessmen and anti-taxers, should not be taken as indication of imminent demise for either. The Republicans can probably live for many years with the running sore of Pat Buchanan's populism, just as the Democrats lived for years with the nagging segregationists of the South.
</p><p><b>Less ideological...</b></b>
<br>They can do so because the two main parties are like giant umbrellas, covering almost anything. Each now stands for approximately the reverse of the principles it once held. In their beginnings, the Democrats were the party of states' rights and of western pioneers; now they are renowned as the party of big government and urban minorities. The Republicans were radically against slavery and in favour of high tariffs; now they are mostly free-traders, and leave civil rights to the Democrats.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>Autres temps, autres moeurs</i>: neither party is remotely embarrassed about these changes. Fluidity in ideology, or even outright lack of it, is not the weakness in America that it would be in Europe. Most Americans dislike ideology in their politics. If they want to make a statement, they join a pressure group, from the Anti-Saloon League to the Sierra Club; and such groups sometimes have more influence on politics than the established parties. Pundits who proclaim that the rise of single-issue politics since the 1980s will spell the death-knell of parties are curiously blind to history. Single-issue groups have always been there, biting at the hide of the major parties. Few grow into parties themselves, because it is hardly worth the effort.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tiny parties espousing vigorous principles certainly exist in America. Those worth mentioning include the Greens, the Libertarians, the Socialists and the Communists. From year to year, they put up candidates for presidential elections, and regularly get around 0.1% of the vote. Meanwhile, the two giants now seem in broad and bland agreement: free enterprise, free (or free-ish) trade, mild internationalism, leaner government, balanced budgets, preservation of all the benefits of vital groups of voters. Comity goes even further: both Democrats and Republicans often represent the same broad interests, draw money from the same groups, and are, of course, dead set against any attempt to reform the electoral system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Curiously, this is not how many Americans see it. A prime source of dissatisfaction with the parties nowadays is not that they are too alike, but that they are too far apart. They are too "partisan", "too ideological in a silly way", as Bill Kristol, a Republican wise man, puts it. To such Americans, last winter's budget impasse, when the government was partly shut down over the issue of which programmes should be cut and how fast, was the last straw. After the long gridlock of the late 1980s, when a Republican president vetoed the bills of a Democratic Congress, Americans got a Democratic president truculently asserting his manhood against the Republicans.
</p><p><b>...means more flexible</b></b>
<br>In America's experience, things are more likely to get done when approached in a bipartisan--or non-partisan--spirit. Progress comes from co-operation among liberal Republicans (" boll weevils") and conservative Democrats ("gypsy moths"), plus a small number of genuinely bipartisan souls. President Clinton's effort to reform health care failed, in large part, because he failed to forge compromises between the parties. It is notable that after the budget showdown of 1995-96, which displayed partisanship at its worst, the moths and weevils once again crawled out of the woodwork and tried to put centrist alliances together.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Increasingly, Americans seem to be heading for this non-ideological land. For years, the number identifying themselves as either Democratic or Republican has been falling. The young ones, those aged between 18 and 29, seem particularly disenchanted. Even among voters bold enough to register with a party, 30% of Democrats and 26% of Republicans claim to be unhappy with their own organisations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is also true that the electoral performance of third forces has been improving. Since 1968, three leaders of such movements--George Wallace, a segregationist ex-governor of Alabama, John Anderson, a scholarly ex-Republican from Illinois, and Ross Perot, a pint-sized Texan billionaire--have won more than 6% of the vote in a presidential election. In 1992 Mr Perot, despite a three-month withdrawal from the race and a full rack of alarming phobias, won 19%, the best showing since the 27% won by Teddy Roosevelt and the Bull Moose Party in 1912. Since January, Mr Perot has been priming himself to run again this year; in mid-May, the odds are that he will do so.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both Mr Anderson and Mr Perot (though decidedly not Mr Wallace) made their pitch to the shifting centre. Yet the centre was, and is, no solid and coherent entity. It is an amalgam of the downsized and the disillusioned--pitchfork Buchananites, libertarian Perotistas and a huge number of people who feel vaguely dissatisfied with life. Some of these would call themselves "independents", but the number answering to that label has barely increased over the past ten years. "Floating voters" would be a better tag. The signs are, in fact, that any party promising change in more than a token fashion (or fielding a startlingly attractive candidate) could capture these folk. That includes the Democrats and the Republicans just as much as any new-fangled force: witness the Republican triumph in the congressional elections of 1994.
</p><p><b>The power of size</b></b>
<br>The big parties keep their grip, and third parties stay feeble, for two chief reasons. The more obvious is that the big parties put up obstacles. Republicans and Democrats control the state legislatures, and state legislatures set the conditions for listing parties or candidates on the local ballot.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Once a party has performed respectably (meaning getting more than 20% of the vote in Kentucky, but 5% in Illinois and a mere 1% in Michigan) in one election, it is usually assured of a place on the ballot at the next one. This is how the Prohibitionists and the Socialist Workers' Party manage to limp from election to election. But a new-minted third party (or a candidate launching a run independent of any party) must go through a gruelling process of gathering signatures in every state in order to appear on the ballot. In Maine, an aspiring candidate must gather 4,000 signatures; in Kentucky, 5,000; in huge California, 147,238.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even when these are painstakingly collected, in shopping malls and outside libraries, state officers from the dominant parties may well find some way to invalidate dozens of them. In 1980, Mr Anderson's effort to get on the ballot as an independent in all 50 states (with equal-access lawsuits along the way) drained away all the money he needed for television commercials. In 1992, the same task cost Mr Perot $14m of the $62m he spent on the election; and now, because he is running at the head of the new Reform Party, he is having to go through the process all over again.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Money, of course, is the next problem. Third parties tend not to emerge in America because they cannot afford it. Unless the third force in question is headed by, or consists of, a billionaire such as Mr Perot, it needs rich private sponsors; and even these are limited by law to contributions of $1,000 or less. The way round that--since there is no limit to what individuals may spend on their own candidacies--is to put the rich sponsor on the ticket. David Koch, a New York millionaire, was put on the Libertarian ticket as vice-presidential candidate in 1980. Not uncoincidentally, that was the year the Libertarians made their best showing. Mr Perot, too, would be subject to campaign-spending limits unless he became the Reform Party's nominee: which is the best reason for supposing that he will either be its nominee or abandon the party and run as an independent.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The question of organisation is a vexed one. Should a man run an insurgent candidacy by himself? Should he form a new party? Should he allow himself to be drafted by an existing small party of roughly similar outlook? Or should he wait for some more general call, perhaps as late as the party convention?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are always in American politics distinguished figures kicking their heels, apparently waiting for this moment. It can be a long tease, on both sides. The present crop includes Bill Bradley, an ex-senator from New Jersey; Lowell Weicker, an Independent ex-governor of Connecticut; Pat Buchanan, who keeps hinting that he may bolt the Republican Party for a more red-blooded group; and everyone's favourite, ex-General Colin Powell, who has lost none of his free-standing charisma by admitting that he is a Republican.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such men may benefit from being part of a party structure: it brings money, organisation, volunteers and the hope of a longer life on local ballots. For their part, third parties are almost bound to fail without a charismatic figure to lead them. The American Independent Party, though it survives, limps without George Wallace and the segregationist fervour that fired it. There would be no Reform Party at all, not even a shadow, without Mr Perot. Men like this grab media attention and get a party treated seriously: an essential complement to--and sometimes a substitute for--hard cash.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But charismatic figures may also insist on going their own way. This can strangle a nascent party in its cradle; or, if the party exists already, it may cause dangerous dislocation to the message. Ralph Nader, a consumer activist chosen in March as the candidate of the Green Party in California, brings instant name recognition (lugubrious face, organic food, hatred of big car companies); but he will not endorse the whole party platform. Mr Buchanan has been touted as the nominee of the <font size=-1>US</font> Taxpayers' Party; but his conservative baggage may prove an embarrassment. In general, minor parties prefer to choose candidates no-one outside their own circle has heard of. This ensures ideological purity, and continuing oblivion.
</p><p><b>The one that nearly made it</b></b>
<br>Third parties would like to blame the Republican-Democratic duopoly for all their woes. But that would not be right. Much of the fragility of third forces comes from the way they are formed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Far more are created from the top down than from the bottom up, out of popular demand. Typically, a party splinters at the top; a man or a faction breaks off over one particular issue, such as tariffs or segregation, and tries to drum up a following. This raises all the problems of personality and free agency already discussed. It is much rarer for new parties to grow out of the grass-roots, however many disaffected people there may be around the place. When this does happen, it is far more likely to produce lasting results. Both the Democrats and the Republicans came into being in more or less this way. So did the third party that came closest to supplanting one of them, the Populist Party of the 1890s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Populists, struggling farmers and small businessmen from the South and the West, wanted the country to abandon the gold standard and go to silver, or to paper money. The two major parties, comfortably ensconced in power and cosy with big business, offered them no hope. Under their charismatic leader, William Jennings Bryan of Nebraska, the Populists became a crusading force that looked as if it might win the 1896 presidential election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There was, however, a fatal snag. Bryan was actually a signed-up Democrat; and the Democrats promptly pre-empted the Populists by choosing him as their nominee. Quite soon (and after the Democrats under Bryan had lost the election), the Populists withered away. The Democrats in this case showed a nimbleness that neither they nor the Republicans have ever lost. Big parties do not win elections only by making a dash for the centre; they also marshall their forces to absorb adroitly upstart movements on their flanks. For the Populists, the result was predictable: a radical third force was swallowed up by an ageing body that had money, organisation, contacts--and a better chance of winning.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite these dismal precedents, excited speculation about a third force is still alive in 1996. If America is indeed in the midst of a new information revolution as disruptive as the old industrial one, many people may well feel that the two old parties no longer represent their interests or recognise their worries. A third party that claimed to do so might start to gather strength, though it is more likely to happen in 2000 than in the present campaign.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Besides, in a narrow race, any plausible third candidate can cause disruption. This year, Mr Nader is likely to siphon off votes from Mr Clinton in California, a state the president must win if he is to hold on to office. And Mr Perot, if he runs, can cause discomfort to either side. In 1992, he was generally credited with stealing votes that would otherwise have gone to George Bush. His present supporters, apparently poorer and less well-educated than those of 1992, may steal votes from Bill Clinton.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet few expect Mr Perot to do as well this year as in 1992. He no longer strikes the same chord. A downsizer himself, he is no spokesman for the economically anxious; a social liberal, he is not in tune with voters' worries about the loss of "values" . Worse, he has already suffered the classic fate of third forces: many of his best ideas, such as budget cuts and smaller government, have become the bread and butter of both the big parties.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This happened to the Populists, too; their ideas, among them a graduated income tax and currency reform, were adopted by the big parties years after the Populists had expired. And it happened to the Progressive Party, whose support for equal rights and labour reform both before and after the second world war did much to push the Democrats to the left.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even the most potent third force must often content itself with just that: pricking the conscience of a big party, and pushing it along the way of reform. For most purposes, a pressure group could do as much. But America's two huge old parties, like Mount Everest, invite direct assault just because they are there. The assaults will go on. What third parties fail to realise is that, if the present duopoly were overturned with no change in the electoral system, it would merely result in a new duopoly with different names; and that, if they were to replace either the Democrats or the Republicans, they too would probably become just as bland and complacent as today's big boys.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="am1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
