<html><head><title>Can this caterpillar fly?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Can this caterpillar fly?</h1>

<font size=-1>WASHINGTON, DC</font>
<p>THE metamorphosis was something to behold. With uncharacteristic eloquence, Bob Dole announced on May 15th that he would within a month give up not only his job as majority leader but leave the Senate altogether, his home since 1968. He will become Citizen Bob, devoting his energies to the presidential campaign, leaving Washington behind to "seek the bright light and open spaces of this beautiful country", and promising to overcome the odds "the hard way", as he has before. Friends promptly praised the move as an act of courage, which it is. But it is a courage born of panic.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Having clinched his party's nomination, a presidential candidate is wont to suffer from the onset of "voters' remorse" (as William Schneider, a political analyst, calls it). Do we really want this fellow, the voters groan? Normally, they punish the presumptive nominee in the late primaries. This time, with the primary schedule compressed, the phenomenon struck in a broader way. Remorse about Mr Dole, reflected in the opinion-poll chasm between him and Bill Clinton, swept the nation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With good reason. Stumbling through his speeches, talking of leadership without showing much of it, Mr Dole looked almost an embarrassment of a candidate. His weaknesses were exposed by his Republican rivals in the primaries, but he prevailed because their weaknesses were even worse. Since then, he has been woefully slow in putting together a strategy for November's election. He allowed himself to slip back into his beloved job of majority leader at the expense of concentrating on the world beyond Washington.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dole's own flaws are not his only troubles. Between now and his official nomination at the party convention in August he is strapped for cash, because of campaign spending limits. His opponent, on the other hand, can hop around the country on Air Force One, basking in presidential publicity. The newly disciplined Mr Clinton relentlessly links Mr Dole to the unpopular Newt Gingrich and the "extreme" Republican Congress.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The president is reinforced by an economy that briefly threatened to stop growing but is instead expanding nicely. <font size=-1>GDP</font> grew at an annual rate of 2.8% in the first quarter of 1996, inflation is low and unemployment is down to 5.4%. Four years ago, according to <font size=-1>CBS</font>/<i>New York Times</i> surveys, only 24% of Americans considered the economy to be in good shape; now 56% do.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this is translating into a formidable advantage for Mr Clinton in the polls. Since the Gallup Organisation started systematic polling 60 years ago, no incumbent president with an approval rating of at least 50% six months before an election has gone on to lose. Mr Clinton's approval rating stands at 55%. He also has a 20-point lead in the match-up against Mr Dole, according to Gallup. Again, nobody has led by so much in May and managed to lose in November (Michael Dukakis holds the dubious record of frittering away a 16-point May lead over George Bush). In other words, for Mr Dole to overcome Mr Clinton's strong popularity and large lead would be unprecedented.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But not unimaginable. A dozen post-1945 elections are too few to serve as a basis for dependable predictions, especially at a time of unusual electoral volatility. The opinion-poll evidence is tricky to interpret, as some polls show the gap between the candidates to be even bigger (31 points, in a Harris poll) and others show it to be smaller (12 points, in a <i>Time</i>/<font size=-1>CNN</font> poll). Republicans take comfort from the electoral-college map, which brings out the difficulty Mr Clinton faces in winning enough states in a broadly conservative country. The gathering in Washington this week of Republican governors, who run 31 of the 50 states, underlined the point.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dole relied heavily on the support of these governors to carry the primaries, and they could be a big help in November, too. George W. Bush, the governor of Texas and a close observer of his father's two presidential campaigns, professes to be satisfied with the state of Mr Dole's effort. The strategy is "more fully-fledged than you would know", he says, and is "in the process of being articulated on paper".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bits of the strategy are emerging. At every opportunity and on every issue, Mr Dole will seek to contrast his own presumed conservatism with Mr Clinton's alleged liberalism. The Dole campaign's internal surveys apparently show that, when people are "reminded" of such contrasts, Mr Dole's numbers look far more perky.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dole's own life story, the rise from Dustbowl and war injury to national power and glory, will be increasingly brought into play. He is famously reticent in talking about his extraordinary physical ordeal.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Once again, last week, he skipped an opportunity to do so, omitting the mention contained in the prepared text of his address at Gallaudet University, a college for the deaf. But his speechwriters persist: in his announcement on Wednesday Mr Dole spoke of the time when "I arose from my hospital bed and was permitted by the grace of God to walk again in the world." And his handlers arrange interviews in which he describes the daily struggles of dressing with his crippled right arm and his preference for food that does not need cutting, such as sandwiches and ice cream.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Candidate Dole is, at last, adjusting his style to the task ahead. <i>USA Today </i>astutely observed that, in a speech last week, Mr Dole used the personal pronoun <i>"</i>I<i>"</i> 59 times and only once indulged in his much-mocked habit of referring to himself as <i>"</i>Bob Dole<i>"</i>. He has reportedly accepted the idea of working with a speech coach and of making greater use of teleprompters. Former speechwriters for Ronald Reagan are helping to sharpen his message. His performance on Wednesday was notable for its loftier tone and smoother delivery.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To be sure, many tactical questions have yet to be settled (whom to pick as running mate, whether to devote serious money to competing in Calfornia, how to handle the nettlesome issue of abortion). But, however painfully, the Dole campaign is taking shape. With the threat of a pitchfork breakaway by Pat Buchanan becoming ever more remote, and now that remorseful Republicans have had the chance to let off steam, it may even be that Mr Dole can count on a more unified party.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The president is, of course, a superb campaigner. By stealing Republican policies and keeping to the middle ground on almost every issue, he makes it hard for the "liberal" label to stick. No sooner does Mr Dole propose a bill banning homosexual marriage, for example, than Mr Clinton makes it clear that he too opposes the idea (though he might not sign a bill banning it).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, Mr Dole's spring fortunes have sunk so low that almost any movement is bound to be up. This simple fact leads to talk of the momentum swinging his way. There is still plenty of time for Mr Clinton, the frequent fumbler of 1993-94, to make mistakes, or to face some Whitewater or foreign-policy crisis. Plenty of time, too, for "voters' remorse" to bite into the president's apparently handsome lead, as more and more Americans ask: Do I really want to give this man a second term?

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
