</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>It didn't work</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Drugs policy</b></p>
<h1>It didn't work</h1>

<p>ADMITTING an uncomfortable truth is often bad, or at least risky, politics--as the response to the Tories' adventurous new poster campaign suggests. But such admissions are a necessary condition of good policy. The government has therefore done the right thing by facing up to the hard facts of drugs. The second leg of its "Tackling drugs together" strategy to curb the illegal use of drugs was launched on May 14th. It recognises that drug-taking is a mass recreation among the young, and that the scare tactics of the past are not the best way to deal with it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A few days earlier, the Home Office had published the results of research carried out as part of the British Crime Survey (<font size=-1>BCS</font>). Including questions about drugs in this survey is a fairly new idea. The findings are remarkable. Drug-taking among teenagers is so common that half of 16-19-year-old boys say they have taken drugs. That is a higher proportion than say they have played football in the previous three months. The figure for girls is slightly lower. A quarter of boys of that age, and a fifth of the age group altogether, have taken drugs within the past month, which implies that they are regular users (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such comprehensive surveying of drug use is recent, so it is difficult to discern a trend. However, in 1982 the <font size=-1>BCS</font> asked about the use of cannabis, and found that only a sixth of men and a tenth of women in their 20s had tried it. The equivalent figures now are two-fifths and a quarter.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of course, there is a danger that some youngsters are telling lies. The <font size=-1>BCS</font> has tried to guard against braggards by including in the questionnaire "Semeron", a non-existent drug. Only one person out of 9,646 respondents claimed to have taken it. The danger of under-reporting remains.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such widespread use is the cause, as well as the consequence, of the failure of the government's "Heroin Screws You Up" campaign of the 1980s. Too many young people know that moderate drug-taking does no perceptible harm.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government admits that the campaign was a failure and has taken a different tack. The booklet for parents published this week is remarkably honest and sensible. It includes good advice, such as setting an example by not drinking too much; it undermines the old chestnut that smoking marijuana inevitably leads on to harder drugs; it advises against bullying or lecturing. Instead it explicitly rejects the old approach. "Don't try to scare your children with shock horror stories. It doesn't work--and to somebody who uses drugs and has experienced their effects, it will be unbelievable," says the booklet.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
