<html><head><title>In a tangle</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Devolution</b></p>
<h1>In a tangle</h1>

<font size=1>EDINBURGH</font>

<p>TAXATION will undoubtedly be a difficult issue for Labour at the next election, but devolution may yet prove even trickier. Labour's plans to devolve power to a parliament in Edinburgh, an assembly in Cardiff and regional bodies in England have been long in the making, but the Tories are now making short work of unpicking them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;John Major told the Scottish Tories at their conference in Aberdeen on May 11th that Labour's plans for devolution would celebrate the millennium by breaking up Britain. This is a tiresomely familiar line of attack. Every big constitutional change ever proposed has been heralded as the end of British civilisation. Somehow, British civilisation has survived. (The Tories themselves often praise the "flexibility" of Britain's unwritten constitution--meaning, presumably, the ease with which it can be changed.) Lately, however, there has been more to the government's position than scare-mongering. Ministers have begun probing Labour's plans, much to Tony Blair's discomfiture.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As a result, Labour's leader has been treading cautiously with plans for regional government in England. Last year Jack Straw, the party's home affairs spokesman, published a consultation paper which set out a step-by-step approach. First, indirectly elected assemblies would be set up, manned by councillors from the region's local authorities. Directly elected regional government would follow only after a regional referendum.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This plan will be discussed on May 18th and 19th in Manchester by Labour's national policy forum, where ordinary members thrash out problems privately before policies are publicly adopted at the party's annual conference. In fact, most of the problems so far unearthed by Mr Straw are internal Labour difficulties.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Local authorities in north-east England think that they are ready to set up an elected regional government immediately, and that there is no need for a referendum. Across the Pennines, Graham Stringer, the leader of Labour-controlled Manchester City Council, thinks that a north-west regional government (covering Greater Manchester, Merseyside, Lancashire and Cheshire) would not work. Liverpool and Manchester, he reckons, would continually fight with each other, and both cities would be at odds with the rural counties of Cheshire and Lancashire. If power is to be devolved from Whitehall, it would be better handed over to a Manchester city-state, he says (led by him, presumably).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because of such widely varying opinions, Mr Straw is sticking to his cautious strategy. This may not please council leaders in north-east England, but Mr Straw is more worried about giving the Tories an opportunity to frighten voters by claiming that devolution will be imposed on them whether they like it or not.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, this still causes trouble for Labour in Scotland. The Scottish Tories have spent their time in government spurning all calls for a Scottish constitutional referendum. Yet in Aberdeen they unashamedly used Labour's proposals for English regional referendums to demand that Labour, if it wins the election, should hold a referendum on Scottish devolution.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This demand may come from an impeachable source, but it seems nonetheless quite sound. Significant changes in the system of government, as opposed to the business of government, ought to be tested against the popular will, rather than being decided upon by <font size=-1>MP</font>s alone. Labour should promise a Scottish referendum--and a Welsh one too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Blair worries, however, that a referendum would be seen by impatient voters in Scotland and Wales as a delaying tactic, and that it would split the party (especially in Wales, where substantial divisions over devolution remain). His speech to the Welsh Labour conference on May 10th was interpreted (widely but wrongly) as reflecting a wish to introduce proportional representation for elections to a Welsh Assembly. That caused a rumpus among Welsh Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>s, most of whom see nothing wrong with first-past-the-post elections.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One way to deal with these problems might be to promise a ratifying referendum after devolution had taken place, perhaps on the same day as a general election. This would also reduce the risk that a referendum might reject devolution if Labour became unpopular in mid-term for other reasons altogether. The Tories would rightly object to this as presenting voters with a <i>fait accompli</i>. Nevertheless, some voters' worries might be assuaged.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whatever it decides to do, Labour needs to be quick-witted on this matter. The emergence of the Scottish Tories as champions of the people, outlandish as it may seem, is not doomed to fail. According to one recent poll, the Tories' assault on Labour's plans to let a Scottish parliament vary income tax by up to 3p in the pound--the government calls it the "tartan tax"--may be causing some Labour voters to have second thoughts about devolution.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For this reason, Mr Blair has no intention of giving regional government anywhere else in Britain the power to tax. Yet some power to raise revenue is necessary if regional government is not to run into the same problems that local government now complains of: no financial freedom to allocate money to policies chosen by a region's voters at election time. The dilemma seems insoluble, but may not be. One possibility would be to take the "tartan tax" off the agenda and announce instead a review of Britain's system of local taxation. After the ill-fated poll tax and much other political tinkering, the system is creaking at the joints and needs an overhaul.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Devolution could and should be a good idea for Britain. But Labour needs to answer the many legitimate questions being asked by the Tories. Otherwise, the party could find the policy turning into an electoral liability next year, and an albatross around its neck if it wins power.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
