<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>




<p><b>Soothing words</b> &nbsp;
In a gesture to Sinn Fein, John Major said in an article in the <i>Irish Times</i> that the decommissioning of terrorist weapons should be addressed in all-party talks on Northern Ireland's future "without blocking the negotiation".</p>
<p><b>Gun law</b> &nbsp;
Labour called for a complete ban on handguns following the massacre at Dunblane. This would remove up to 200,000 firearms from circulation. The government said it would wait for the findings of Lord Cullen's inquiry into the massacre before announcing any new measures.</p>
<p><b>Safe schools</b> &nbsp;
The government promised to pay for improved security measures in schools, including the installation of closed-circuit television cameras, responding to the recommendations of an inquiry into the fatal stabbing of a London headmaster last year.</p>
<p><b>Big money</b> &nbsp;
Labour dropped its plans to curb the size of jackpots on the National Lottery. Jack Cunningham, the shadow national-heritage secretary, said he now accepted that the huge prizes encouraged people to buy tickets.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Overdue</b> &nbsp;
A second report by the National Audit Office into a much-delayed project to build a new home for the British Library said bureaucracy was to blame for a catalogue of building errors and management failures.</p>
<p><b>Dirty water</b> &nbsp;
A European Commission report said 50 of Britain's beaches failed to meet official standards of water cleanliness, out of 464 places tested. Portugal had an even higher proportion of dirty beaches and the cleanest ones were found in Sweden.</p>
<p><b>Angry not mad</b> &nbsp;
The family of an Oxfordshire woman who died of Creutzfeld-Jakob disease, the human form of "mad-cow disease", said they would sue the government for failing in its duty of care to inform the public about the dangers of eating beef.
</p>
<p><b>Grin reaper</b> &nbsp;
A crematorium in Aberystwyth plans to advertise its "friendly service" on television.
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
