<html><head><title>The road from imitation to innovation</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width=360 height=26  alt="Finance And Economics">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>The road from imitation to innovation</h1>
<p><b>Developing economies have long been imitators of western technology. Should rich economies worry as they turn into innovators?</b></p>

<p>BEING a copycat can sometimes get you into trouble, as China discovered this week when America threatened to impose sanctions on it for allegedly violating some American firms' intellectual-property rights. However, although producing cut-price copies of, say, software programs is illegal, imitating western know-how in other respects is a legitimate way for emerging markets to catch up rich ones. East Asia's breathtaking growth over the past couple of decades partly reflects this process.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At present, innovation is heavily concentrated in rich economies: they account for 96% of total world <font size=-1>R&D</font> spending. This reflects the fact that developed nations can afford to spend more on innovation, which, in turn, boosts future income and thus finances more research. Moreover, they also have better educated workforces. Poorer countries with a plentiful supply of less-skilled labour will tend to focus on basic manufacturing, copying western techniques. So, runs the theory, they will tend to specialise in low-tech industries; high-tech ones will remain the preserve of the rich world.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But things are changing: some Asian economies are fast becoming innovators. South Korea and Taiwan already spend as much on <font size=-1>R&D</font> as a proportion of their <font size=-1>GDP</font>s as many European economies (see <a href="fn1.gif">chart</a>)--and their spending has grown more rapidly in recent years than that of any rich economy. The results are beginning to show: Taiwan now registers more patents in America each year (per head of its population) than Britain does.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This worries some people in rich countries. They fear that jobs and living standards at home will be threatened as Asian dragons shift to more sophisticated products and production methods. But a recent paper* by a team of economists at the London Business School concludes that such fears are misplaced.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The study points out that the creation of knowledge--whether in developed or developing countries--spreads its benefits across borders. As a result, increased innovation in Asia should raise living standards in rich countries, too, by expanding both the range of goods that consumers can buy and the inputs that firms can use. Similarly, as innovation helps to lift Asian incomes, the market for rich-world exports will expand. All this will boost global growth. Poorer countries, such as China, will follow the catch-up path for some time, but as their incomes and technology approach western levels, the scope for imitation will shrink. To sustain growth they will also have to generate new products and processes.
</p><p><b>The smother of invention</b></b>
<br>Indeed, the <font size=-1>LBS</font> team argues that what the rich world should be worried about is not too much innovation in developing countries, but too little. The root of the problem is that <font size=-1>R&D</font> spending yields a public as well as a private return. Firms will invest in <font size=-1>R&D</font> if their expected future profits exceed their initial costs. Such research also yields general knowledge that is not product-specific, but which may be of use to other firms and countries. The snag is that this "externality" is not captured in firms' financial sums. As a result, the level of innovation in an economy may be less than it should be.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since the <font size=-1>R&D</font> externality is partly international, there is a case, on the face of it, for governments to join together and subsidise each other's innovation. To examine this question, the <font size=-1>LBS</font> team used a mathematical model in which two main factors determine the levels of imitation and innovation in low-income economies, and hence the pattern of trade between rich and poor countries. The first is the speed at which poor nations absorb ideas and techniques from rich countries. The more slowly a country assimilates knowledge because of, say, poor education, the harder it will be for it to be an imitator. And the second is the relative cost of imitating as opposed to innovating (as a rule, the lower wages are relative to those in rich economies, the greater will be the incentive simply to copy).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>LBS</font>'s economists tested the effects of various types of <font size=-1>R&D</font> subsidies on the model. If a subsidy is given to firms in developed countries, this will boost innovation and growth there, but as incomes rise (and hence the wage gap between rich and poor countries widens), this will also make imitation more attractive than innovation in poor countries. As a result, global innovation may be left unchanged, or it may fall. Likewise, if an <font size=-1>R&D</font> subsidy in a poor country is used to finance imitation, this will prove counterproductive: not only will it make innovation in poor countries less attractive, it will also discourage innovators in rich countries by eroding the returns from the <font size=-1>R&D</font> they pursue.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The authors conclude that the best subsidy for <font size=-1>R&D</font> from a global perspective is, in fact, one granted for innovation in a developing country. Thanks to its positive spillover effects, more innovation in these nations will also boost growth in developed economies, too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This leads the <font size=-1>LBS</font> economists to conclude that, since financial support for innovation in poor economies benefits rich countries as well, it may be in the west's interests to help pay for it. And, who knows, if developing countries are encouraged to become explorers, they may be less inclined to be pirates.

<br><hr><br>


* "Innovation, Imitation and Growth in a Changing
World Economy", by M. Chui, P. Levine, J. Pearlman and
A. Sentance. LBS Economic Outlook, May 1996.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
