<html><head><title>The top shelf</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Internet censorship</b></p>
<h1>The top shelf</h1>

<p>ON THE Internet the talk used to be all about the moral issues behind censorship. Nowadays, the debate has turned to the technical means of doing it. It is not that censorship is any less controversial on-line, just that it now seems inevitable. In France, the authorities recently arrested two Internet managers for not stopping child pornography from flowing through their systems. In countries such as China and Singapore, there is little debate on censorship at all: these governments will try to censor the Internet--the question is how.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most of the blocking methods so far have fallen into three categories: software that consults a list of known sites and blocks them according to criteria chosen by the <font size=-1>PC</font> owner; software that looks for suspect words to decide when to block sites; and the fencing off of portions of the Internet by firms that provide Internet access.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;None of the three can stop a curious ten-year old for long. The Internet is too big and changing too quickly for any list-maker to keep up. Screening out www.playboy.com is easy; tracking down an obscure Swedish site with even more skin on display is harder. These days many users start their Web-surfing at one of the many search services that index most of the Internet. The top five queries at one of these, Infoseek, are the names of such busty starlets as Pamela Anderson, each of which may turn up hundreds of Web sites devoted to their charms. Every day the list changes: a censor would be hard pressed to keep abreast.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Word-screening software is weaker still, largely because computers have a notoriously hard time extracting meaning from the written word. Simply looking for keywords is bound to fail: America Online faced a near riot when its word-screening software accidentally shut down a forum for discussing breast cancer (because it mentioned breasts), and a software package from another company blocked the official White House Web site because it mentioned the presidential "couple".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Weakest of all are the attempts to block whole sections of the Internet. Last year, CompuServe, an on-line service, banned more than 200 "newsgroups"--open discussion areas on many disparate topics--in response to a threat from Bavarian prosecutors. This was fairly simple. Unlike most Internet content, newsgroups are broadcast to each service provider's computers, where they can easily be screened. However, CompuServe's ban had only a limited effect: knowledgable users soon found other sources for the same material.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The largest part of the Internet, the Web, is even harder to block sensibly. The Web operates on a very different model: content stays in one place and viewers come to see it. Internet providers--normally spurred on by governments--can just cut off a site. But when German prosecutors tried to shut down a neo-Nazi Web site in America, copies of the material appeared Hydra-like elsewhere, as free-speech defenders copied it on to their own Web sites.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is another system that might work better: self-rating. At a meeting in Paris earlier this month, a consortium of Internet and computer firms released the specifications for such a scheme. The Platform for Internet Content Selection (<font size=-1>PICS</font>) allows Internet content providers, from <i>The Economist</i> to <i>Bianca's Smut Shack</i>, to label their offerings, much like a film rating. Software, running either on a user's own <font size=-1>PC</font> or on the computers of the Internet provider (where it is harder to bypass), would screen according to criteria set by a parent, an employer, or even a government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The ratings could cover anything, from sex to political leanings. Although many sites might be responsible in their self-assessments, judgements of this sort are inherently subjective. A swimming-costume catalogue that would pass muster with America's Boy Scouts might blow fuses in Oman. Likewise, one man's dry economic theory page is another's cesspool of counter-revolutionary thought.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So the <font size=-1>PICS</font> standard allows third parties to rate sites, too. Thus the Simon Wiesenthal centre might want to run a "ratings server" that ranked sites on the basis of anti-Semitic content. Parents who wanted to keep their kids away from Holocaust revisionism could configure their software to check that server before access was granted to any site. Government censorship with this system would probably be as leaky as earlier attempts: Chinese Internet users could find ways around a server on which their government might try to screen dissident sites. But the system would make it easier for parents to protect their children.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although it might seem curious that Internet advocates would want to create a tool that some governments are sure to use to suppress information, the alternative, as they see it, is worse: the prosecution of those who put content on the Internet or let it pass through their machines. The advantage of the <font size=-1>PICS</font> system is that it does not limit what people write on the Internet, only what they read. Free speech is protected, at the cost of a sort of self-censorship.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With the Internet growing at the rate of hundreds of sites a day, no list-maker can hope to keep up. The <font size=-1>PICS</font> scheme, if it takes off, is likely to be effective enough to block the most obvious sites, without being an impermeable barrier. If that keeps the more censorious nations at bay, most Internet users will still count it a success.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
