<html><head><title>The war of the wires</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>The war of the wires</h1>
<p><b>Two years ago America's local telephone companies dismissed the Internet as a fad. Now they worry it will ruin their business</b></p>

<p>WINTER 1997: on a snowy afternoon in New York city, an elderly grandmother feels sick and reaches for the telephone to call an ambulance, but there is no dialtone. She had always paid her telephone bills on time, just to ensure that help was at hand. Now the telephone system has let her down--all because a few dozen Internet junkies on her street are hogging all the available telephone circuits.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is the nightmare that America's local telephone companies, or "Baby Bells", are quietly describing to any regulator who will listen. It has already happened in a small way, they claim, during the recent snow storms on the east coast. While callers spend half an hour a day, on average, chatting on local calls, heavy Internet users may spend three times as long on the same lines with their modems (and the Internet users often have a second line). Some set their computers to dial in several times an hour to check their e-mail. Others remain connected all day.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The telephone network is designed on the assumption that the average call is about three minutes long, and that the average telephone is used for nine minutes or fewer during peak hours. But typical modem use starts at 15 minutes and quickly moves skyward. Staying endlessly on the line costs many Internet users nothing, thanks to a combination of free local calls in most of North America and the fact that most Internet services charge a flat fee, with no time charges.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Baby Bells reckon that these modem hogs should somehow pay for the extra equipment telephone companies must buy to keep up with their ravenous consumption. At least four Baby Bells--Nynex, <font size=-1>US</font> West, Pacific Bell and Bell Atlantic--are now lobbying the Federal Communications Commission (<font size=-1>FCC</font>) to apply per-minute access fees, much like those already applied to long-distance calls, for calls to Internet services.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The battle between the Baby Bells and the Internet is the first skirmish in what promises to be a wider war between the Internet and telephone companies of all sorts. This war will be international: in Britain, the telephone company serving Hull, the only town with free local calls, recently banned a large Internet service because its users would not get off the lines. And it will not just be confined to data transmission: already telephone companies on both sides of the Atlantic are begging for laws to restrict voice telephony on the Internet (see <a href="wb2.html">page</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From the point of view of the Baby Bells, the Internet is a parasite. Unlike the long-distance companies, which lease some of their capacity to carry Internet traffic, the local telephone companies have little say over how their networks are used. The Baby Bells (and ultimately their customers) bear a large part of the Internet's costs, while receiving little or none of its revenues.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is partly the Baby Bells' own fault for being slow to offer Internet services of their own. But in North America, it is also a function of a regulatory system that never considered the possibility that people would want to use their telephones all day. The economics of the Internet over long-distance routes are still a baffling maze of trickle-up payments and barters, but the picture over the last mile to a user's home is all too clear: it is a free ride.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In February, <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, America's biggest long-distance company, began to offer free Internet access for a year--a deal tempting enough to attract several hundred thousand users in its first month. As the Bells plaintively point out, they are paying for <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s largesse: the long-distance giant has set up a network of dial-in points located within a local call for most users, thereby exploiting the loophole that allows them to use local networks for Internet service without paying the access charges <font size=-1>AT&T</font> normally must pay the Bells for long-distance calls. <font size=-1>MCI</font>, the second-largest long-distance carrier, is now offering its own Internet service.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Without a way to charge Internet service-providers directly, the Baby Bells currently recover their money from the access fees they charge all long-distance users. Such fees typically amount to around 45% of the charge for long-distance calls. Within two or three years, around 20% of those access fees will be attributable to Internet users, reckons Bernd Pfeiffer, a Nynex executive. Why not bill the offenders directly, he argues, with a charge of as little as a penny a minute? Even for a heavy user the tax would be less than $50 a month.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Internet advocates see it differently. "It's their old strategy--they're seeking a regulatory handout instead of competing," says Dhruv Khanna, a communications lawyer with Intel, a semiconductor firm. The fast growth of the Internet in North America has been partly due to flat-fee rates, which encourage users to experiment at leisure. Subscribers in countries with per-minute charges, as is the case in most of Europe, use their telephones about a third as much as Americans; activists say that forcing the Internet into a system that charges by the minute would probably have the same chilling effect.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All the accusations and claims of high principle tend to obscure the fact that the dispute is over a relatively small number of people. Knock out all the Americans who use the Internet only for sending e-mail, and who use the Internet at offices which have direct connections (ie, bypassing the Baby Bells' lines), and you are left with about 9m home-based heavy users. However, around 7.5m of these use intermediaries such as America Online or CompuServe whose time-based charges discourage long sessions. The Baby Bells' case thus comes down to just 1.5m modem users.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, this understates the problem on two counts. First, the Internet is doubling in size every year. This year will see the first wave of mass-market Internet devices, from <font size=-1>TV</font> set-top boxes to game machines and cheap "network computers", that will make the matter worse. Meanwhile, the proliferation of multimedia sites on the Internet is only increasing the time users spend on-line.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Second, the clash between modem and voice calls is the first collision between century-old phone technology and the era of digital communications introduced by the personal computer. The voice calls carried by the Bells (and most other telecoms firms around the world) are connected by an electronic version of the old telephone operator known as "circuit switching": a call gets a line to itself for its duration, after which the circuit is switched to another call. The Internet uses a much more efficient technique called "packet switching" , which allows many transmissions to share the same line, with computers at both ends sorting them out.
</p><p><b>The digital divide</b>
<br>The modems that so annoy the Bells symbolise this rift: they exist to turn pure digital signals into the sort of analogue noise that a circuit-switched network can understand. The same line with a new switching technology called Asymmetric Digital Subscriber Line (<font size=-1>ADSL</font>) can carry up to 400 times as much data. Even a cheaper technology known as Integrated Services Digital Network (<font size=-1>ISDN</font>) that has been around for years can multiply transmission speed five-fold. Last year, for the first time, data exceeded voice traffic on the world's telecoms networks. Surely the day has come for data to move from voice networks to purely digital ones?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Baby Bells can already offer <font size=-1>ISDN</font> over most of their regions. Yet they have fewer than 400,000 <font size=-1>ISDN</font> users between them. <font size=-1>ISDN</font> is complicated to install, has never been widely promoted by the Bells, and can cost more than $40 per month (with a set-up fee that can amount to more than $200). Internet users are now trying to convince the Bells that they are foolish to let <font size=-1>ISDN</font> languish. If they were to offer their own <font size=-1>ISDN</font> Internet access, they could get more than $50 a month in subscription fees from the same users they claim are costing them nearly that much by hogging the voice network with their modems.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With some $30 billion invested in the old circuit-switching infrastructure, the Bells seem to be thinking more about recovering the investments they have already made than promoting alternatives. But the sooner they see the Internet as an opportunity rather than a threat, the sooner they can stop scaring grandmothers with tales of modem users run amok.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831769200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
