</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Restoring Germany's shine</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>

<h1><center>Restoring Germany's shine</center></h1>

"SOCIALLY obscene"; "the destruction of the welfare state". With such fine phrases, German trade unionists heaped abuse on the spending cuts and labour-market reforms that their government proposed on April 26th. However misguided, these opponents of change were at least right in recognising the significance of the package: if implemented, it could prove a turning point for Germany. The proposals, which aim to chop total public spending by 2% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> next year, would be the country's biggest spending cuts for decades. The significance of the reforms, moreover, lies not just in their scope but in the manner of their introduction: the government now seems willing to push ahead despite howls of protest from the unions. Many people will view this challenge to Germany's tradition of decision-making by consensus as dangerous; but it is unavoidable if the economy is to restore its old, now distinctly tarnished, shine.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The German model--a much envied system based on consensus between politicians, managers and unions--is in deep trouble. For many years, it worked well: until the late 1970s, Germany could boast of an economic miracle and could trace its success to the country's system of economic management. Because the framework within which markets operated was determined by consensus, there was comparatively little room for government tinkering. Policy was stable and companies were free to get on with the business of improving their products, seeking new customers and increasing wealth.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That was then. Now, the miracle has become a myth. Since 1979, productivity in German business has risen by only half the average increase in European economies; in the past two decades, Germany has created proportionately fewer jobs than most other big economies. And the country has become an uncompetitive place in which to do business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Part of the trouble can be traced to the shock of unification in 1990 and to the enormous bills which that has entailed. But much more is rooted in the German model itself (see <a href="sf1.html">pages</a>). To ensure that no one misses out on prosperity, an over-generous welfare system grew up in the late 1960s and the 1970s. Social benefits and holiday pay add a hefty 80% on top of basic wage costs. To underpin the contract between managers and workers, the country's labour and product markets have become riddled with rules and rigidities that hinder new firms and new jobs. Germany's income-tax system is complex and unfair, with high marginal tax rates alongside a multitude of tax loopholes: these allow the rich to escape tax, while average workers pay the highest tax rates among the big seven economies. The country's corporate tax rate is the highest of any large economy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hence, at a time when some Europeans are looking to Germany as a model for pan-European social policies, and even American cabinet-members are finding inspiration in Germany's "stakeholder economy", the German government itself is recognising that the model needs to change. It is proposing things which, by its standards, are radical, and deserves credit for that. To cut spending it wants a public-sector wage freeze, and reductions in sick pay and other benefits. To help create jobs it has proposed that small firms should be exempt from employment protection laws. The government's goal is to reduce public spending to 46% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> by 2000, from around 50% at present. That would still leave it above today's 42% share in Britain but below the 50%-plus in France and Italy. In part the measures were driven by the government's short-term need to slim its budget deficit to meet the Maastricht criteria to join Europe's single currency. But more important is the long-term need for structural reform.
</p><p><b>Wirtschaftsblunder</b>
<br>The biggest danger now is not that the government will, as its critics fear, destroy Germany's distinctive system of economic management through excessive zeal. The threat of that is remote. It is that the government will fail to push its reforms through--and the possibility of that is real.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For one thing, the ruling coalition has only a narrow majority in the lower house of parliament, while the opposition Social Democrats are in a majority in the upper house. They may force the government to dilute its proposals. For another, some of the impetus for reform comes from the state of the economic cycle, which could change again soon. At the moment, Germany is spluttering. Unemployment has risen above 4m; in the year to February industrial production plunged by 6%; the six German economic institutes have just reduced their forecast of <font size=-1>GDP</font> growth this year to a mere 0.75%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Economic gloom makes people more willing to accept the need for change. The danger is that recovery next year will appear to lessen the urgency of reform and make Germans complacent again. But recovery alone will not reduce unemployment markedly; most of that is structural. Nor will it affect those features of the German system that are now damaging the country's performance. Much remains to be done.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The system of centralised wage bargaining, under which trade unions and bosses set pay across whole industries regardless of individual firms' profitability, used to work well because it helped to avoid inflationary leapfrogging. But in the face of rapid technological change and competition in some sectors from low-wage economies, relative wages need to adjust, and the system inhibits that. High minimum wages prevent the low-skilled jobless from pricing themselves back into work. Hence, though the consensus has benefited existing workers and employers, it hurts the increasing numbers of jobless. The wage-bargaining system needs further reform.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In addition to encouraging a more flexible labour market and consolidating welfare reform, the government also needs to liberalise services, which must expand if new jobs are to be created. Of the big economies, Germany has the smallest service sector, thanks to archaic, job-inhibiting rules. Most notorious are Germany's ridiculous shop opening hours (eg, shops currently have to close at 2pm most Saturdays). The government is planning only modest reforms to these.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Against that litany of woes, Chancellor Kohl's package, for all its proposed daring, must be considered merely a start, a welcome signal that the welfare state is no longer regarded as untouchable. Because there is more to do, the critics of reform will argue that change risks destroying Germany's distinctive social-market economy. In truth, even if the proposals were implemented in full, they would fall far short of that. Reform of the system is needed; full-scale destruction is not. Chancellor Kohl is merely throwing his weight behind the operation of market forces. In coming years, such forces are more likely to represent the interests of Germany as a whole than is the mouldy old model, with its closed roundtable discussions between politicians, bosses and trade unions.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831164400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
