<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>




<p><b>Winners</b> &nbsp;
Two child-murderers found guilty of killing two-year-old James Bulger in 1993 won an appeal against 15-year minimum sentences imposed upon them by Michael Howard, the home secretary.</p>
<p><b>Loser</b> &nbsp;
John Major said that if he called a referendum now on whether Britain should join a single European currency, most people would say no.</p>
<p><b>United</b> &nbsp;
The Irish government and Mo Mowlam, Labour's Northern Ireland spokesman, said that the decommissioning of terrorist weapons should be dealt with separately from the main all-party talks on Ulster's future.</p>
<p><b>Result</b> &nbsp;
Glenn Hoddle, manager of Chelsea football club, quit to become coach of the England team when Terry Venables steps down in the summer.</p>
<p><b>Price ticket</b> &nbsp;
A value of nearly &#163;2 billion was put on Railtrack, owner of most of Britain's rail network, ahead of its stockmarket flotation on May 20th. A leaked official survey said Railtrack needed to spend &#163;11 billion on repairs.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Hot air</b> &nbsp;
The Gas Consumers' Council said complaints about British Gas continued to rise sharply despite its promise to improve services. Offer, the electricity regulator, said complaints about electricity firms fell by 20% in 1995.</p>
<p><b>Lotto worry</b> &nbsp;
It emerged that Peter Davis, the lottery regulator, told a closed meeting of a parliamentary committee in December that he had "considerable concern" about the business practices of <font size=-1>G</font>Tech, an American firm involved in running the National Lottery.</p>
<p><b>Flying off</b> &nbsp;
The government said the Royal Air Force would withdraw from Germany by 2002. It has been there since the end of the second world war.</p>
<p><b>Boob</b> &nbsp;
Berlei, a bra maker, was forced to withdraw claims that its products made the bosoms heave in a recent television adaptation of Jane Austen's "Pride and Prejudice". The <font size=-1>BBC</font> insisted that the actresses wore historically authentic costumes.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
