<html><head><title>The xenophobic tendency</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="brsf.gif"  alt="Britain Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>The xenophobic tendency</h1>
<p><b>Britons tend to think of immigration as a drain on the state. The evidence suggests that the opposite is true</b></p>


<p>"THANK God we are Saxons!" trumpeted <i>The Economist </i>in 1843. "Flanked by the savage Celt on the one side and the flighty Gaul on the other--the one a slave to his passions, the other a victim to the theories of the hour." The moist-eyed writer was deeply grateful to belong to such a sensible race.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He would have looked askance at his successors, 150 years on. A random selection from the editorial staff of this newspaper produces an English-Ukrainian, an English-Croatian, an English-Russian, two Scottish-Welsh-German mixes distilled in colonial Africa, a pure-blooded German and, the prize exhibit, a Welsh-Armenian. All are British citizens.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Comparing themselves with America, Britons tend to think they are a rooted, homogeneous lot. Yet the last millennium is a story of ethnic mixing, as the surnames in the telephone directory of any large town show.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Leave aside post-war immigration from the Caribbean and the Indian subcontinent: Saxon blood was spiced with variety long before then. The Danes ran much of eastern England from the 9th to the 11th century; then the Normans took over. Italian merchants swarmed into London in medieval times. The Dutch came to East Anglia, and informed the architectural style that still dominates the area. Huguenots fled France in the late 17th century. At that time, Bermondsey, one of the Cockneyest bits of London, was known as "Petty Burgundy".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Over the years, Sephardic Jews came from Spain and the Netherlands; at the end of the last century, Ashkenazi Jews fled pogroms in Russia and Eastern Europe. In 1880, there were reckoned to be 60,000 Jews in Britain; over the next couple of decades, another 200,000 arrived. Then came the 20th century, and communism, and fascism, and the movement of millions of refugees across Europe. (Among them were the East European parents of Michael Howard, the flag-waving home secretary, who would never had got in had their son's policies been in operation.) Then came post-war economic growth, and workers from the Commonwealth. Then came the laws to stop it all.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Marks and Spencer, Unilever, <font size=-1>GEC</font>, Tesco, Courtaulds: immigrants have made their mark in all sectors, and dominated some. Cloth and clothing, for instance, is a much-traded business, so tends to be international; and sewing, the sort of badly paid work available to immigrants, is a skill as useful in one country as in another.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So the Dutch ran the wool trade in East Anglia in medieval times; the Huguenots set up the silk business in the 17th century; and 19th-century Jewish immigrants set themselves up as tailors and shoemakers. In the mid-20th century, as imports pushed prices down, industrialists imported Pakistani and Bangladeshi labour in order to squeeze costs. As each wave of immigrants moved on and up, its place was taken by a new one; and the old Huguenot church in Fournier Street in the East End of London became a synagogue, and is now a mosque.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Finance is similarly linked with trade, and therefore with foreigners. And because finance is important to Britain, so are the immigrant banking families.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until they were expelled in 1290, Jewish immigrants from Spain ran British finance. Italians then got into the business: the Lombards left a street in the City named after them. As finance expanded, they came from everywhere: Barings from the Netherlands, Cazenoves from France, Hambros from Denmark, Rothschilds, Warburgs and Kleinworts from Germany. The pattern has changed only in the past decade or so, when foreigners streamed into the City via corporate takeovers rather than starting their own firms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But beyond listing the names of brilliant and successful immigrants, is it possible to measure their contribution to the economy? Immigration should raise <font size=-1>GDP</font> and lower wages by increasing the supply of available workers. But its effect will depend crucially on the immigrants' characteristics.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many countries--Australia, Canada and Germany, for instance--carry out studies over time of cohorts of immigrants, looking at what they do, and how successful they are in comparison with the rest of the population. The British government does not; so the information about immigrants in Britain is patchy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;According to a Home Office study of 263 people who had been granted, or had applied for, asylum, such people tend to be disproportionately professional and skilled. Some 30% had been professionals in their home country, 10% had been managers or employers, and only 5% had been unskilled. According to an analysis of the 1990 Labour Force Survey, some 25% of foreign residents--which would include people intending to leave as well as people trying to settle--are in professional or managerial jobs, or are employing other people, compared with 22% of British citizens.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Recent immigrants tend more often to be self-employed than British-born people (16% compared with 12%). Their children tend to stay in education longer than do the children of British-born parents. Refugees tend to be particularly well-educated. The Home Office study found that nearly half had some sort of higher or further education; over a third had a degree, compared with 12% of British adults.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One country's immigration, in other words, is another country's brain drain. Many of the 52,040 foreign-born doctors, dentists and nurses (23% of health-service employees) working in Britain in 1994 represented a loss of human capital to other countries, some of whose governments paid for their training.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But, for a systematic analysis of the economic effects of immigration, one has to look abroad. Stymied by the lack of data about Britain, the London-based Institute of Public Policy Research commissioned work on those migrating to Germany. The studies looked at the period 1988-92, when 4.2m immigrants entered Germany, mostly from Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union. The bulk of the immigrants were aged between 20 and 45. They were more mobile than locals, being willing to move around the country in search of employment. Within the first six months, 82% of immigrants from the former Soviet Union had found jobs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The immigrants did not appear to take jobs from the locals, which is what opponents of immigration most fear. This may have been because the economy was anyway very buoyant, or because the immigration itself generated a boom--nevertheless, the number of unemployed per vacancy, including both immigrants and natives, fell from 12 in 1988 to 5.6 in 1992. As the economy slowed down in 1992, so did the number of immigrants.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Researchers from the Rheinisch-Westf&auml;lisches Institut in Essen found that the new immigrants contributed around DM32 billion ($21 billion) in taxes and national insurance payments. Set against that are around DM18 billion received in unemployment benefit, family allowances and aid to help them integrate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, immigrants also had an indirect impact. More people meant a greater burden on public services and infrastructure. And because they were disproportionately young, with young children, they put a special burden on schools: the average number of pupils per teacher increased by two over the period, to 19. On the other hand, being young, immigrants used the health services less frequently than the average German.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Looking at their macroeconomic impact, the study estimates that they raised the annual <font size=-1>GDP</font> growth rate by around one and a half percentage points a year, to 3.5% per year. Since their presence meant downward pressure on wages, employers are reckoned to have got a larger slice of this extra wealth than employees.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Taking into account the additional tax revenues generated by the extra economic growth, the researchers reckon that, overall, the immigrants contributed something in the region of DM14 billion a year to government finances. That positive result, they maintain, comes about largely because the immigrants represented a large inflow of human capital for which Germany had not had to pay.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although both theory and practice argue that immigration is good for economies, people do not seem to see it like that. Instead, a gut belief that "they'll take our jobs," or "they'll sponge off the state," prevails. Liberals often find it hard to combat this fear, which is inextricably intertwined with racism. Moreover, it is a belief that has endured through huge social changes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A report to the commission set up by King James I on immigration echoes precisely the combined modern fears of the effect of technology and immigration on the job market. It complained of foreigners using machines "for working of tape, lace, ribbin and such, wherein one man doth more amonge them than 7 Englische men can doe; so as this cheape sale of theire commodities beggareth all our Englishe artificers of that trade and enricheth them."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Economic hard times sharpen these fears. One of the first recorded bouts of anti-foreigner rioting happened in a slump in 1456-57, against the Genoese, Venetians and Lombards in London who, according to a petition by the rioters, brought in "great numbers and multitude of aliens and strangers of divers nations" instead of employing native English.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Industrialisation and growth in the 19th century brought the opposite attitude. Pre-existing controls were abandoned, and people allowed to move freely in and out of the country. As Ann Dummett and Andrew Nichol say in "Strangers, Citizens, Aliens and Others" (Weidenfeld and Nicolson), an excellent study of British immigration policy over the years, "Victorian <i>laisser-faire </i>entry policies expressed <i>laisser-faire </i>economic theory as well as political liberalism."<p>
<b>The squeeze starts</b><br>
When the gate shut, it shut hard. At the end of the 19th century, economic conditions tightened and so did immigration policies. The Aliens Act of 1905 allowed immigrants to be expelled from the country if they were poor, vagrant, or convicted of any felony. In the four years after the act's implementation, 1,378 people were deported.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There were few protests. In a parliamentary debate on a follow-up act in 1914, Colonel Josiah Wedgwood, a lonely voice, said "We have not seen such a unanimous spirit of persecution since the time of the Popish Plot in 1678...Why cannot we follow the policies of our ancestors of assimilating this foreign element and teaching it that England is something worth living for?"
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the 1930s, economic worries combined with anti-Semitism and fear at the scale of the potential exodus from Germany. After Hitler annexed Austria, Britain introduced a visa system to restrict immigration further. Colonel Wedgwood opposed the idea, again with little support. The <i>Daily Mail</i>, which can boast consistency, if nothing else, in its attitude, argued that "to be ruled by the misguided sentimentalism of those who think with Colonel Wedgwood would be disastrous...once it was known that Britain offered sanctuary to all who cared to come, the floodgates would be opened."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Economic growth after the second world war led to the rules being loosened once more. Employers like the National Health Service and London Transport went fishing for workers in Commonwealth countries.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Immigrants have tended to be allowed in when the economy does well; the economy does well when immigrants have been allowed in. Very likely the causality goes both ways, though it is difficult to argue this case to voters convinced that immigrants are going to do nothing but take their jobs and claim their benefits. Such fears, and the restrictions that go with them, are understandable if irrational. But the odd thing about immigration policy in recent years is that, even during the periods of rude economic health, the government has tightened, rather than loosened, controls.<p>
<b>Women and children last</b><br>
Over the past 25 years, a stack of laws has transformed Britain from a country that welcomed people to one that it is virtually impossible to get into. The Immigration Act of 1971 stopped primary immigration; the British Nationality Act of 1981 abolished common citizenship, creating three different varieties, the least of which, British Overseas Citizenship, conferred no right to go or to live anywhere. Then a clutch of laws over the past five years, ending with this year's Asylum and Immigration bill, makes squeezing into Britain exceptionally tough (see <a href="brsf1.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The end of primary immigration left three principal ways of entering Britain: as the member of a family of a British national, as a refugee and on a work or business permit. All of those routes have closed further over the past few years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Changing the rules to keep out the families of the workers who had previously been welcomed does not always show Britain at its best. For instance, many of the young women who had come from the West Indies in the 1960s had left their children behind. Once they were established in Britain, they tried to bring them in. So the government changed the rules to say that, if the mother had "sole responsibility" for the child (if it had been left in an orphanage, in other words) then she could import it. If she had not (if it had been living with its grandparents, for instance) she could not. So those women had to choose between their children and their livelihood.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until recently, spouses could enter Britain relatively easily. That is no longer true. Immigration officers have at their disposal the "primary purpose" rule, by which the applicant is required to prove that coming to Britain was not the primary purpose of the marriage. Unless officials are satisfied of this, they must reject an application, even if they believe that there is a genuine relationship between the couple. Critics complain that this discretion is used to discriminate racially. American spouses are almost never ejected, while African and Asian ones (including the Thai and Filipino wives that desperate Englishmen buy through the post) are often thrown out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile, getting asylum in Britain has become harder and harder. Since 1988, airlines have been fined &#163;2,000 per person plus costs for each person they let on board without a proper visa. So if your government is trying to kill or imprison you, don't board a plane for London unless all your papers are in order (which, of course, might be difficult to arrange without being killed or imprisoned).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Be sure, too, not to change planes on your way to Britain: you may fall foul of the 1993 Asylum and Immigration Appeals Act, which invalidates your claim to asylum if you put your foot down on the soil of a third country <i>en route. </i>There are well-meaning Tories who think this has gone too far: they were responsible for defeating part of the new Immigration and Asylum bill, which will introduce further restrictions, in the House of Lords on April 23rd.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The work-permit regime has also been tightened. "Things snapped shut in the early 1990s," according to Elspeth Guild, an immigration specialist with the law firm Baileys, Shaw and Gillett.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until quite recently, Britain welcomed some types of people who are now being shut out. Doctors, for instance, coming in for post-graduate training used to be permitted to settle. Now they have to leave after four years even though Britain has a shortage of doctors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps the best illustration of the British attitude to foreign talent lies in its treatment of entertainers and sportsmen. Footballers, actors and musicians are the sort of people that make a country fun to live in and proud of itself. Nevertheless, Britain's immigration service is acutely aware that there are many British footballers, actors and musicians who may not be quite so good as the foreigners and would be out of a job if there were too much high-class foreign competition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Accordingly, entertainers who want to work in Britain are subject to procedures and rules even tighter than those applied to other professions (except chefs: Britain is determinedly protective of its gastronomic reputation). If the entertainer squeezes past the objections of the relevant union--the protectionist Musicians' Union, for instance, or the actors' union, Equity--he must abide by a complex set of rules. Thanks to a big fuss in the press, Ilie Dumitrescu, a Rumanian football player, just escaped deportation: his offence was to attempt to transfer from Spurs to West Ham without having played in 75% of first-team matches for Spurs, which had originally imported him.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Jon Bon Jovi, a pop star, got caught out when a Department of Employment official heard on the radio that he was planning to co-host a radio programme. The vigilant official knew that the terms of his work permit allowed him only to perform, not to act as a disc jockey. A department spokesman confirmed this: "Someone with a work permit to be an entertainer cannot suddenly become a broadcaster." So Mr Bon Jovi went on the programme but kept his hands off the knobs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Worse than such absurdities is the Home Office's refusal to countenance the idea of talented people who want to come to live in Britain. The fact that somebody is brilliant does not gain them admission. Excellence, apparently, is not something that Britain values. It prefers to protect mediocrity than to face the challenge that talented foreigners might pose.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831164400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="wb1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
