<html><head><title>Correlation is now causation</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Optical computing</b></p>
<h1>Correlation is now causation</h1>

<p>THE idea of using light, rather than electrons, to do the number crunching in a computer has been around for a long time. But the advantages (speed, and a lack of electrical interference between the signals in the machine) have been outweighed by the disadvantages (light is cussed stuff that will not easily bow to the disciplines needed to make it do sums). After three decades of research, however, a form of optical computing should make it to the market-place this year. <font size=-1>OCA</font> Applied Optics, of Garden Grove, California, has developed the first light-based processor that can be plugged into a personal computer. The processor is called an optical correlator.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Correlators are specialised devices designed to find "targets"--from car parts to cancer cells--inside "scenes" presented to them. They work by converting images of both the targets and the scenes into mathematical expressions known as Fourier transforms. A Fourier transform is a coded version of an image that shows the thickness, spacing and direction of every line in that image in a consistent way. The consistency and simplicity of Fourier transformation allows a computer to compare images easily and, usually, accurately.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, reaching this consistent, simple point can involve a long mathematical grind. In electronically based correlators the Fourier transformation is done by numerical analysis. First, the images to be compared are digitised. Each is defined as a series of pixels (picture elements), with a specific position and brightness, that can be represented by a set of numbers. Next, the computer has to perform a huge number of separate calculations, relating every pixel in an image to every other pixel. This can be time-consuming, especially if the image is big.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The advantage of an optical correlator is that the processing is done by the basic physics of the system, rather than a lot of electronic shuffling. A lens can be made to produce a Fourier transform of an image directly. This is done by shining what is known as "collimated" light (ie, a beam of parallel rays, in this case a laser beam) through an image of the scene made up of liquid crystals. When the collimated beam is then focused by a lens, the result is a pattern the composition and brightnesses of whose elements corresponds to the mathematical terms of the Fourier transform.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is an interesting step backwards. An optical correlator is, in effect, an analogue computer, rather than a digital one (though the results of its computations are then digitised for transmission to its host <font size=-1>PC</font>). By missing out the step-by-step processing that digital computing requires (and also by working at the speed of light), it arrives at its result very rapidly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For Jean-Baptiste Richon, managing director of Optical Flow Systems in Edinburgh, switching from digital processing could mean a thousand-fold increase in machine productivity. Mr Richon's work involves tracking the position of liquid and gas particles to determine the direction and speed of their flow. The system has to be able to recognise, or correlate, individual particles from one frame of video to another. This is a process that can take a traditional correlator up to two minutes, even on a specially souped-up <font size=-1>PC</font> with a Pentium chip.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Up to now, the alternative would have been to buy a huge, custom-built optical correlator, which would have cost around $100,000. But <font size=-1>OCA</font>'s correlator (which works at 1,000 correlations per second), takes advantage of new electro-optic components, such as tiny lasers, fast liquid-crystal displays and high-resolution detectors. It costs around $10,000 and is squeezed into a package only slightly bigger than an audio cassette. Using it, Mr Richon calculates that he could process a frame's worth of information in about one-sixteenth of a second. This would allow him to monitor fluid flows more or less in real time.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But optical processing is not for everyone. Roy Davies, professor of machine vision at Royal Holloway College, London, doubts that the new correlator will have more than a niche market. He reckons it is unnecessarily powerful. Industrial inspection, for instance, normally uses targets with either 3x3 or 7x7 pixels. All that is necessary to tell if a part is faulty is a single abnormal pixel--the details do not matter.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because these pixel grids are so small, the processing can easily be performed electronically, while the rest of the computer tries to make sense of the results. Dr Davies says that the process of making sense uses up far more computing power than the correlations themselves. <font size=-1>OCA</font>'s device may work fast, he says, but it is probably not cost-effective unless the unit price drops below $1,000.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are, however, many applications that require a good deal of detail. Stuart Schoenmann, one of the directors of <font size=-1>OCA</font>, claims that potential customers want to scrutinise a range of things from circuit boards and flat-panel displays to mammograms and <font size=-1>DNA</font>. Security applications--recognising unique body-features such as faces--look especially promising. At the moment Hamamatsu Corporation, in Japan, uses an optical correlator of its own manufacture to identify fingerprints. The company's designers are now interested in replacing their system with <font size=-1>OCA</font>'s. They reckon that combining the new correlator with Hamamatsu's holographic memories could create a formidable computing combination. There may yet be a chink of light in the armour of electronics.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831164400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
