<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Italy goes left</h2>
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>For the first time since the second world war, the left, with a backbone of reformed communists, is set to form a government in Italy, after winning the general election. <b>Romano Prodi</b>, an economics professor who heads the centre-left Olive Tree coalition, is near-certain to be prime minister; his views on fiscal rectitude helped the lira to strengthen. A right-wing alliance headed by Silvio Berlusconi, a media tycoon, and Gianfranco Fini, leader of the post-fascists, will form the main opposition.
<p>The rebel leader of Chechnya, <b>Jokar Dudaev</b>, who had been fighting for independence from Russia, was killed, probably in a Russian rocket attack. The war continued with unabated intensity, despite a ceasefire and peace proposal announced by Boris Yeltsin last month.</p>
<p>Turkey's Welfare Party, a pro-Islamic group which won December's general election but failed to form a government, won a parliamentary vote to launch an investigation into the personal finances of <b>Tansu Ciller</b>, who was prime minister until last month. The new prime minister, Mesut Yilmaz, who heads a coalition with Mrs Ciller's party, did not tell his party to vote against the proposal.</p>
<p>Talks between Chancellor Helmut Kohl, unions and employers to try to reach an agreement on reforming <b>Germany's welfare system </b>broke down. The government, intent on cutting public spending, wanted cuts in sick pay and job protection, proposals the unions firmly rejected.</p>
<h2>No let-up</h2>
<p><b>Lebanon</b> continued for a second week to be pounded by Israel from air, land and sea. Hizbullah continued to fire rockets into northern Israel. Warren Christopher shuttled between Jerusalem and Damascus, with a side-trip to Beirut, in his search for the ceasefire formula to bring Operation Grapes of Wrath to an end.</p>
<p>The<b> Palestine National Council</b> (the <font size=-1>PLO</font>'s parliament) convened in Gaza to revoke the clauses in its charter that deny Israel's right to exist.</p>
<p>Saudi Arabia's interior minister warned Britain that "a friend does not harm a friend" , feeding British fears that it would lose<b> Saudi trade</b> because of the decision not to deport Muhammad Massari, a Saudi dissident.</p>
<p>An American delegation arrived in Monrovia, the capital of <b>Liberia</b>, to try to secure a peace agreement during the current truce. The Americans promised $30m to help pay for a West African peacekeeping force.</p>
<p>Commonwealth countries threatened limited measures against <b>Nigeria </b>if its ruler, General Sani Abacha, refused to meet a delegation to discuss human rights. General Abacha sacked Ibrahim Dasuki as sultan of Sokoto, a position of spiritual leadership, and replaced several senior military officers.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Politicking</h2>
<p>The White House and Congressional Republicans cobbled together a <b>budget deal</b> for 1996. Negotiators agreed to add almost $5 billion for education, police and job training--President Clinton's chief priorities--and to find the money from other programmes.</p>
<p>A Harris poll showed Mr Clinton leading Mr Dole in the <b>presidential race </b>by 20 percentage points.</p>
<p>The Senate passed a bill allowing <b>health-care coverage </b>to be transferred from one job to another. This seemed as close as Congress was willing to get towards comprehensive health-care reform.</p>
<p><b>Bernhard Goetz</b>, who shot and paralysed a black youth on the New York subway in 1984 when he feared he was about to be robbed, was ordered to pay the victim $43m in damages.</p>
<p>A sale of items owned by <b>Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis</b> reached more than $11m in its first two days in New York. Meanwhile it was announced that the tools used by <b>Jeffrey Dahmer</b>, a serial killer, to dismember his victims would be auctioned to raise money for the victims' families.</p>
<p><b>Paraguay</b>'s President Juan Carlos Wasmosy sacked the country's army commander, General Lino Oviedo, who refused to go. Neighbouring countries and the United States suspended military aid. Mr Oviedo then went--to be defence minister.</p>
<p>Having floated its currency, <b>Venezuela</b> reached agreement--in principle--with the <font size=-1>IMF</font> for a $1.4 billion stand-by. The World Bank and <font size=-1>IDB</font> will help, making a total package of over $3 billion.</p>
<p>The <b>Brazilian</b> government said it would speed up land reform after the April 17th killing of some 20 landless demonstrators by police in the Amazon state of Para.</p>
<h2>Cult fear</h2>
<p>The trial began in Japan of <b>Shoko Asahara</b>, a cult leader accused of a gas attack on the Tokyo metro which killed 11 people and damaged the country's reputation as a safe society. Mr Asahara refused to plead either guilty or not guilty. The security arrangements included 18 helicopters hovering over the court.</p>
<p><b>Pol Pot</b>, the former leader of Cambodia, is ill, according to King Norodom Sihanouk. His death would be a good thing, the king said, and would probably mean the end of the Khmer Rouge guerrilla movement.</p>
<p>In a move to resettle 36,000 Vietnamese <b>boat people </b>still in camps in South-East Asia, the United States said it would take those who had ties with America. But they would have to return to Vietnam to apply.</p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
