<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Wedding Bells</h2>
<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>In the second coupling of Baby Bells since America deregulated its telecoms market earlier this year, <b>Bell Atlantic</b> and <b>Nynex</b> announced a "merger of equals". With a combined market value of $50 billion, the enlarged Bell Atlantic will cover the Atlantic seaboard from Maine to Virginia, taking in New York and Washington, <font size=-1>DC</font>. It will be America's largest telecoms operator after <font size=-1>AT&T</font>.</p>
<p>In a $4 billion share swap, <b>Cisco Systems</b>, a leading maker of Internet data-networking equipment, agreed to acquire <b>Strata</b><b>Com</b>, a marriage that will allow Cisco to provide networking switches for data, voice and video communications across public and private computer networks.</p>
<p><b>Eurotunnel</b>, the debt-laden operator of the Channel tunnel, declared a loss of &#163;925m ($1.5 billion) for its first full year. But revenues amounted to &#163;299m, with a promise of a 50% increase this year. Having suspended interest payments on more than &#163;8 billion-worth of debt last September, Eurotunnel said it hoped to reach a new agreement with its creditor banks by the summer.</p>
<p>America's <b>Digital Equipment</b> continued a remarkable recovery from near-bankruptcy. Results in the computer maker's third quarter showed a 68% jump in net profits to $124m, its sixth straight quarter of profits after running up $5 billion in losses in 1991-94.</p>
<p>Struggling after its recent takeover of another entertainment colossus, Capital Cities/<font size=-1>ABC</font>, <b>Walt Disney </b>declared a net loss of $25m in the second quarter after a $316m profit a year ago. Even after one-off charges, revenue was down as a result of lower sales of its films and videos. Its share price fell.</p>
<p>There was better news for <b>Euro Disney</b>, whose parent is Walt Disney. Its losses in the first half narrowed to FFr169m ($34m) from FFr241m a year earlier. The group predicted a big increase in revenues in the second half, its busier period.</p>
<p>A year after Canada's Seagram bought the giant <b>MCA</b> entertainment group, it found a big name for the big Hollywood job. It appointed Frank Biondi, recently fired as head of Viacom, another big media outfit, as <font size=-1>MCA</font>'s chief executive.</p>
<p><b>Conrad Black</b>'s Hollinger International is taking full control of the Telegraph group, which publishes the <i>Daily Telegraph</i>, Britain's top-selling broadsheet newspaper, and the <i>Sunday Telegraph</i>. It agreed to pay around &#163;300m ($454m) for the 36% it does not already own.</p>
<p><b>PepsiCo </b>pulled out of a joint venture in Myanmar (Burma), where it has 85% of the soft-drinks market, after pressure from American human-rights groups. It sold its 40% stake for an undisclosed sum to its partner, which can produce Pepsi products for another five years yet.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Annulled</h2>
<p>(See <a href="wtw3.gif">chart</a>)<br>The British government overruled the recommendation of its monopolies commission and blocked two controversial mergers that would have brought more vertical integration to the <b>electricity</b> industry. PowerGen's bid for</p>
<p>Midlands Electricity and National Power's for Southern Electric cannot now go ahead.</p>
<p>The European Commission blocked a bid by South Africa's Gencor and Britain's Lonrho to merge their <b>platinum</b> operations. The commission said the move would have left two companies in control of the world's platinum production. The other company is South Africa's Anglo American.</p>
<h2>In clover</h2>
<p>Japan's largest securities house, <b>Nomura</b>, recorded its biggest annual profit in five years. It made &#165;91.5 billion ($949m) in the year to end-March compared with &#165;6.8 billion in the previous year.</p>
<p>Salomon, parent of the <b>Salomon Brothers </b>investment bank, said net profits more than trebled in the first quarter, to $276m.</p>
<p>Mexico announced plans for an innovative deal in which it will exchange $2.5 billion of its <b>Brady bonds</b>, which are backed by American Treasury bonds, for debt which has no such collateral. If this swap succeeds, it would mark another important step in Mexico's return to relative financial respectability.</p>
<p><b>Swiss Bank Corporation </b>moved to strengthen its operations outside Switzerland. It has bought Standard Chartered's international private-banking operations with assets under management of $5 billion, mainly in South-East Asia, and a $1 billion private-client portfolio from America's Chase Manhattan Private Bank.</p>
<h2>Joy ride</h2>
<p>Group net profits at <b>Volkswagen</b> grew ninefold in the first quarter, to DM116m ($79m), as sales rose 15% and costs were contained. But the German car manufacturer, Europe's biggest, still reckoned full-year profits would be modest.</p>
<p><b>Fiat</b> plans to halve investment spending over the next five years but will continue to introduce three new car models a year, a strategy that has helped it gain market share.</p>
<p><p>First-quarter net profits at America's biggest car maker, <b>General Motors</b>, fell to $1.02 billion compared with $2.10 billion a year earlier. Some $900m of the fall was due to last month's 17-day strike.</p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
<p align=center><a href="wtw1.html">POLITICS THIS WEEK</a></p><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,iss">Search</a>
