<html><head><title>Gordian knots</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Constitutional reform</b></p>
<h1>Gordian knots</h1>
<p>
TONY BLAIR may have thought that he had picked an easy target. Surveying the Labour Party's ambitious plans for constitutional reform in a speech earlier this year, he highlighted the party's promise to remove hereditary peers from the House of Lords. After all, who could defend the old duffers, there only "because 300 years ago their ancestor was the mistress of a monarch"? In fact, as a new report makes clear, reform of the House of Lords, far from being an easy target, is more likely to prove a can of ermined worms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On April 25th, the Constitution Unit, a collection of academics, former civil servants and politicians backed by a group of charities, published its first two reports, on the reform of the Lords, and on how to deliver constitutional reforms in general (&#163;10 each from The Constitution Unit, 4 Tavistock Place, London <font size=-1>WC1H</font> <font size=-1>9RA</font>). Future reports on devolution, human rights, referendums, relations with Europe and other constitutional issues are due to be published later this year. The reports are meant to spell out in detail how reforms might be implemented, not just to bleat about their desirability.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first two reports are admirably lucid expositions of the options and obstacles facing reformers. Although the Constitution Unit is non-partisan, and its advisory committee includes members from all three main parties, its work seems squarely aimed at Labour, which not only promises wide-ranging constitutional change, like the Liberal Democrats, but also looks set to be in a position to fulfil such pledges as the next government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both reports make it clear that the task facing Labour is daunting. Even if voters are as favourably disposed towards change as they tell pollsters, overtly changing Britain's constitutional arrangements is going to be fraught with pitfalls. The basic problem of changing a system of government even while operating it faces reformers in any established democracy. But in Britain this problem is made far worse by the fact that there is no written constitution, and so no agreed and explicit mechanisms for amending it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most easily achieved constitutional reforms in Britain have been surreptitious, or gradual, such as the Tories' reduction in local-government powers in the 1980s. Explicit reforms announced as "constitutional" have always proved enormously time-consuming and controversial and, like Labour's devolution proposals of the 1970s, have often failed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Constitution Unit's report on reforming the House of Lords makes clear the complexities of even so simple a change as ushering out the anachronism of hereditary peers. Mr Blair's plan is to kick them out (except a few hardworking ones, who would be reappointed), and then to leave the House of Lords largely intact until a plan for an elected second chamber can be agreed, probably years later in a second Labour term. Of course the danger is that the move to an elected chamber may never happen. In any case, an all-appointed chamber would exist for some time. This prospect has already been dismissed by both the Lib Dems and the Tories as an "ermine-clad quango" . It does seem an awkward outcome to defend, even as a supposedly interim measure, for a party which has waged such a fierce campaign against the proliferation of appointed quangos under the Tories.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if Labour does achieve an appointee-only House of Lords, how will appointments be made? Will appointment be an honour, or a job? What will the party balance be? (Even without hereditary peers the Tories still have the most seats, though not a majority.) The report floats the intriguing idea that the main parties could agree to let the government of the day have a simple majority of one, or the largest contingent of peers. But reaching such an agreement would not be easy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Equally significant, changing the Lords' composition is likely to change its behaviour. The report rightly points out that an appointed chamber, shorn of hereditary peers, might well feel more legitimate, and so might exercise its limited powers more aggressively, frustrating the government and enraging the House of Commons. And the move to an appointed chamber will spark an immediate debate about the next step: the move to an elected chamber. How will peers be elected? For what term? What will be the role and powers of any new elected upper house? Will the devolved assemblies which Labour has promised Scotland, Wales and the English regions have a role in a new, elected chamber? Is rivalry between the Commons and a newly fashioned upper house a virtue, or to be avoided at all costs?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So far Labour is only just beginning to tackle such questions. Most other big constitutional issues, simple in principle, will prove just as complex and contentious in practice. If Mr Blair is serious about his party's sweeping and ambitious reform agenda, he had better get to grips with the detail soon.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
