<html><head><title>And this is competition?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Telecoms mergers</b></p>
<h1>And this is competition?</h1>

<font size=1>NEW YORK</font><p><b>The merger between Nynex and Bell Atlantic makes sense for the two firms concerned; regulators may beg to differ</b></p>

<p>LESS than three years ago Ray Smith, chairman and chief executive of Bell Atlantic, unveiled what was billed as "the Multimedia Deal of the Century": the merger of his regional telecoms group (or "Baby Bell") with Tele-Communications Inc (<font size=-1>TCI</font>), America's biggest cable operator, to create a new company worth about $60 billion. Four months later the deal was dead, killed in part by what Mr Smith called "the unsettled regulatory climate".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now, in the wake of a telecoms bill that has deregulated America's telephone market, Mr Smith is trying again, amidst a second flurry of superlatives. On April 22nd he unveiled "the Telecoms Deal of the Century": a merger with Nynex, another Baby Bell, to create the country's second-largest telecoms group, with a market value of $50 billion. But regulators may yet again leave Mr Smith on hold.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The deal, says Mr Smith, is "a merger of equals in every sense" . Each Baby Bell serves 13m customers in adjacent regions that, together, include 13 north-eastern and mid-Atlantic states, plus the District of Columbia. Last year each company generated $13.4 billion in revenues. And the pair are already engaged: two years ago they merged their cellular operations. Nynex, however, is the weaker firm. In the first quarter its operating-profit margin stood at 21.4%, compared with Bell Atlantic's 25.2%. Nynex's long-term debt is $9.1 billion; its new partner's is $6.2 billion. And Bell Atlantic has almost twice as much cash.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bickering over Nynex's value--its share price has been inflated by months of rumours--came close to scuppering the deal, just as squabbling over <font size=-1>TCI</font>'s valuation helped end Bell Atlantic's previous engagement. In the end, the merger values Nynex at a small discount to its market price, leaving Bell Atlantic shareholders with 56% of the new firm (which will also be known as Bell Atlantic). The question of who will run the group--another factor in the failure of the <font size=-1>TCI</font> deal--was settled more easily. A year after the merger is finalised, Ivan Seidenberg, Nynex's boss, will succeed Mr Smith as chief executive of the new firm. He will then take over from Mr Smith as chairman when the latter retires.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The union of Bell Atlantic and Nynex comes only three weeks after Pacific Telesis and <font size=-1>SBC</font> Communications, another two of America's seven (now five) Baby Bells, announced a merger that will create a $45 billion telecoms giant. Driving both deals is the appealing profitability of long-distance telephony. Each year, some $20 billion of long-distance calls originate in the two regions covered by Bell Atlantic and Nynex--and much of the profit from these is pocketed by <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, <font size=-1>MCI</font> and Sprint, America's three big long-distance carriers. Because 45% of those calls both start and finish on its territory, however, the new Bell Atlantic could carry them from end to end, instead of passing part of each call--and its profit--to the long-distance carriers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Around a third of America's international calls are made from the new Bell Atlantic's turf. This could be particularly valuable if, like <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, <font size=-1>MCI</font> and Sprint, the new company links up with an overseas telecoms firm. A global alliance would make sense. The new Bell Atlantic already has extensive overseas interests, especially in Europe and Asia, and gradual global telecoms deregulation should make these increasingly lucrative. Economies of scale will also boost the new firm's competitiveness. The merger will save $600m a year in operating expenses (helped by a 2.3% cut in the group's combined workforce, to 130,000) and up to $300m annually in capital spending.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this assumes that the merger is consummated. The whole point of the telecoms bill was to open up markets and foster competition. Mr Smith says these two aims will be promoted by the merger, because the new Bell Atlantic will be better able to compete with the likes of <font size=-1>AT&T</font>. This sidesteps a key objection. Because Bell Atlantic and Nynex operate in adjacent territories, they could easily have competed for each other's local calls.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By merging, however, each has eliminated its biggest potential local rival, a strategy that will hardly help consumers, as the Federal Communications Commission (<font size=-1>FCC</font>) has noted. The merger between PacTel and <font size=-1>SBC</font>, by contrast, is less likely to hurt local competition. With their home territories several states apart, they were unlikely to have invaded each other's regions.
<p><b>Jingled Bells
</b><br>The <font size=-1>FCC</font> and the Justice Department may yet accept Mr Smith's line that a merger between Bell Atlantic and Nynex is still in the public interest because of its positive effect on long-distance competition--an argument he backs up by noting that <font size=-1>AT&T</font> and <font size=-1>MCI</font> have already lodged their protests with Washington. (Sprint, however, has kept quiet: presumably because, on April 23rd, Nynex signed a deal to resell Sprint's long-distance services in six states outside the Baby Bell's home territory.)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Smith will have a tougher time with the numerous state and district regulators that have to approve the deal, and which have already been flooded with protests by consumer groups. Only one state has to turn nasty--and New York's regulators, as Nynex will testify, have a reputation for toughness--to kill the deal.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Had they bided their time, Bell Atlantic and Nynex might only have had federal regulators to worry about. On April 19th the <font size=-1>FCC</font> said it was mulling over the idea of establishing explicit national rules to govern competition in regional telephone markets. These would effectively circumvent the whims of state regulators--a move that might ease the passage of complex multi-state mergers such as that between Bell Atlantic and Nynex. Whether the Baby Bells' deal would actually comply with the <font size=-1>FCC</font>'s proposed rules--which will stress the need for more, rather than fewer, regional competitors--is another matter.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="wb2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
