<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>A leap forward</h2>
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>The latest <i>World Economic Outlook</i> from the <font size=-1>IMF</font> predicts continued <b>solid growth</b> for the main industrial economies, albeit at a slower pace than in 1995. On average, <font size=-1>GDP</font> is set to grow by 2.0% in 1996, compared with 2.1% in 1995, before rising again to 2.6% in 1997. The <font size=-1>IMF</font> expects a more robust recovery in Japan. After four years at a virtual standstill, its <font size=-1>GDP</font> is expected to grow by 2.5% in 1996 and 3.1% in 1997.</p>
<p>A fillip for Europe's economies: the <b>Bundesbank</b> cut Germany's discount rate from 3% to 2.5% and its Lombard rate from 5% to 4.5%.</p>
<p>Government shareholders in the <b>European Bank for Reconstruction and Development</b> agreed to double the bank's capital with an injection of 10 billion ecus ($12 billion), the first capital increase and, said shareholders, its last. They also discussed ways of defining "graduation": when ex-communist countries no longer need help. Earliest graduates are likely to include the Czech Republic and Poland.</p>
<p>America's <b>Apple Computer</b> announced a loss of $740m in the firm's second quarter, even bigger than had been expected. There was more mixed news from <b>IBM</b>. Its first-quarter revenues from services rose, but those from hardware were flat. Lou Gerstner, the firm's boss, asserted that <b>IBM</b> was on "the proper course" , but its share price fell.</p>
<p>The European Commission said that it would approve the Uniworld <b>telecoms alliance </b>between <font size=-1>AT&T</font> of America and four European operators only if the American firm allows <font size=-1>EU</font> telecoms companies access to its transatlantic network. The Commission said that <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s Euro-partners would in turn have to abide by the <font size=-1>EU</font> timetable for telecoms liberalisation.</p>
<p>It was a bad week for shareholder activists. Martin Ebner, who through <font size=-1>BK</font> Vision holds a big stake in <b>Union Bank of Switzerland</b>, failed to block the election of Robert Studer as chairman. In New York, two mutinous shareholders, Bennett LeBow and Carl Icahn, conceded defeat in a long battle to force <b>RJR Nabisco</b> to split apart its food and tobacco interests.</p>
<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Australia's venerable media group, <b>John Fairfax</b>, is ousting its latest chief executive, Bob Mansfield, after only four months, reportedly after clashes with the board and with Fairfax's main shareholder, Conrad Black, who holds a 25% stake. With two other media heavyweights involved--Kerry Packer holds 18%, Rupert Murdoch 5%--and chances of a government relaxation of media cross-ownership rules that will unleash all three, turbulence at Fairfax is likely to continue.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>American banks </b>had a strong first quarter. Only Chase Manhattan recorded a net loss after a one-off charge related to its recent merger with Chemical. That aside, its profits soared by 44% over the first quarter of 1995 to $937m.</p>
<p><b>Groupe des Assurances Nationales</b>, a state-owned French insurer, announced net losses of FFr1.8 billion ($360m) last year, compared with losses of FFr5.3 billion in 1994. But the firm predicted that it will be privatised in 1997, when it should be in profit again.</p>
<h2>Gaijin in charge</h2>
<p>A <b>foreigner </b>is to become president of a big Japanese company. America's second-biggest car maker, Ford, is spending &#165;52 billion ($480m) to raise its 25% stake in Mazda to a controlling 33.4%. Henry Wallace, a Ford man who is currently vice-president of Mazda, will become its president.</p>
<p>The plot in Japan's <b>housing-loan scandal</b> took a further twist, with police making their first arrest. Kenichi Sueno, head of a property company called Sueno Kosan, was held on suspicion of making false statements in documents.</p>
<p>An American electricity utility, Southern Company, said it might bid for <b>National Power</b>, one of Britain's two privatised electricity-generating giants, but is waiting to see whether the government will approve more vertical integration in the industry.</p>
<p>Talks between two Baby Bells have reopened. A merger of <b>Bell Atlantic </b>and <b>Nynex</b> would be worth more than $22 billion.</p>
<p>Creditors pushed <b>AIOC</b>, an American commodities trading company which used to be dominant in Russia's huge metals market, into filing for chapter 11 protection after the firm made heavy losses on futures trades.</p>
<p><b>Lonrho</b>, a British conglomerate with plans to demerge its mining interests, gave one of its shareholders, <b>Anglo American</b>, a South African mining giant, an option to raise its stake, prompting speculation Anglo may take control of Lonrho's mining assets after a demerger.</p>
<h2>Silly names!</h2>
<p>The share price of <b>Yahoo!</b> more than trebled in its debut on the Nasdaq stockmarket, valuing the year-old Internet search firm, which has yet to make a profit, at more than $1 billion.</p>
<p><p><b>France T&eacutel&eacutecom</b> is launching an Internet service for consumers called Wanadoo, which will also give access to Minitel, its own on-line service, and will include Youpi!, a French-user-friendly version of the Yahoo! system of searching the Internet. Netscape and Microsoft software will come with the service.</p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
