<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/20-04-96/sf1.html 199.173.162.110 19970215041032 text/html 20499
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 04:06:22 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:03:59 GMT
Content-length: 20311
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Two eyes for an eye</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif"  alt="Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Two eyes for an eye</h1>

<p><b>Why has violence flared between Israel and Lebanon? What does Israel really want? And what are the chances of a peaceful resolution? These three pages look at the events of the past week, at their immediate and longer-term backgrounds, and at the near future</b></p>


<p>A WEEK into Israel's ferocious bombardment of "Hizbullah targets" in Lebanon, there was no sign that the guerrilla movement had been broken. As thousand upon thousand of Israeli shells and bombs thump down on Lebanon, ancient Katyusha rockets continue to be plonked into Galilee's deserted fields. Operation Grapes of Wrath, a resonant clich&eacute from "The Battle Hymn of the Republic", was launched to protect the Israelis of northern Galilee. It has not, in that respect, been a demonstrable success. Yet it has still been a domestic triumph. And, at the start when casualties were low, it won international sympathy; the reproaches were muted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Strange that: Lebanon, though not Hizbullah, has been badly hurt, its land once again a battlefield, its people being killed and made homeless. Since the barrage began on April 11th, several hundred thousand Lebanese have been forced to flee their homes, trailing up the single road north, seeking temporary refuge in the streets, schools and mosques of Beirut. Their presence, plus Israel's surgical strikes at two of Beirut's power stations, have plunged the capital back into the disorder it thought it had escaped.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Close to 100 Lebanese, most of them civilians, had been killed in the first week of the bombardment, half of them on April 18th when Israel shelled a <font size=-1>UN</font> peacekeeping base near Tyre where hundreds of Lebanese refugees were sheltering. Earlier in the day, a family of nine, including small children, had been killed in a raid on a village near Nabatiyeh (see <a href="sf1.gif">map</a>). The casualty rate, at first relatively low because of Israel's policy of telling people to get out before it blasted their homes, was rising fast. The number of dead Lebanese civilians, in just a few days, was many times more than the 12 people in northern Israel killed by Hizbullah rockets in the 14 years since Israel invaded Lebanon in 1982.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Israel has struck houses in Beirut, supposedly belonging to Hizbullah but not inhabited by them. Helicopter gunships attacked a Palestinian refugee camp, wounding the small son of a radical commander, the object of the chase. One of the power stations hit was in Lebanon's Christian heartland where no Hizbullah guerrilla would show his face. Its destruction, Israel said, was in revenge for the rocket that broke a single power line in Galilee.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By mid-week diplomacy was stirring. How quickly it would take hold remained doubtful. Shimon Peres, Israel's prime minister, had earlier felt confident enough to tell the residents of northern Israel, escaping from the rockets, that they would soon be back in their homes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The diplomacy, it was plain from the start, would have to be American. A meeting of the United Nations Security Council, called by Lebanon on April 15th, failed under America's frown to utter even the most circumspect criticism of Israel's action. France's foreign minister, Herv&eacute de Charette, dispatched by President Jacques Chirac on a peace-making mission, was snubbed, on his arrival in Israel, by Mr Peres who said it was too early to talk about peace. He valiantly carried on, visiting Damascus and Beirut before returning to Israel. France is one of the few western countries to have suggested that Israel may have been in the wrong. In contrast, Britain's minister of defence, Michael Portillo, who happened to be visiting Israel at the time, went over the top in Israel's support.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Then Warren Christopher, America's secretary of state who was touring East Asia with Bill Clinton, reached for the telephone and the real bargaining began. There seem to be two alternatives. The first is to restore the rules of engagement that Mr Christopher worked out in 1993 in a peace deal after Israel's last big bombardment of Lebanon, though this time the curbs on Hizbullah would be much tighter and those on Israel much looser. The second is more ambitious. The Americans are proposing a plan under which all guerrilla action against Israel would stop, and be guaranteed by Syria not to resume, in return for Israel getting ready to withdraw from its "security zone" in Lebanon. The Arabs will not buy this in its present form; Israel is interested.
</p><p><b>The immediate background</b></b>
<br>Israel is punishing the Lebanese in the name of anti-terrorism. This stretches the term. Certainly, the Hizbullah guerrillas create terror--or at least fear, annoyance and pain--by firing their Katyusha rockets into northern Israel. But confusion has crept into the anti-terrorist argument.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Israel was hit by undisputed terrorism this February and March when, in four separate incidents, suicide-bombers sent by Hamas and Islamic Jihad, which are Palestinian Islamist groups, killed 59 people who had been going about their peaceful business in Israeli cities. In the wave of international outrage that followed--at its height during an anti-terrorism conference in Egypt--the interpretation of "terrorism" came to be spread thick and wide. It became tempting to lump Lebanon's Hizbullah with Palestine's Hamas: both, after all, were enemies of Israel, murky and militant.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;May they both be damned, said Israel's friends. Hamas and Islamic Jihad try to undo the current Israeli-Palestinian peace process by terrorising the Israeli public into an anti-peace mood. Hizbullah (the party of God) was born with Iranian help during Israel's invasion of Lebanon in 1982. It still depends on Iranian money. Its guerrillas, like their Palestinian colleagues, are a fanatic anti-Zionist bunch who have done foul deeds in the past and could do them again. The party does not accept Israel's right to exist and when Lebanon eventually reaches the stage of making peace with Israel, it could, like Hamas, try to destroy that peace.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps. But, on the other hand, Hizbullah's leaders could go in the opposite direction, dropping their guns and pursuing their political ambitions within Lebanon. With the savage civil-war years behind them, they have acquired an active political organisation; their social network of schools and institutions is much wider than Hizbullah's relatively small numbers would suggest. Hizbullah candidates competed in the 1992 elections, winning eight of the 128 seats in parliament. The party might well decide to try to challenge Amal, Lebanon's main Shia Muslim party, for the hearts and minds of Lebanon's 1.2m Shias, the country's biggest single group.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What Hizbullah might or might not do if there were peace is speculation. The facts are that the Hizbullah guerrillas nowadays, a band of a few hundred men, fight Israel's occupation of a slice of southern Lebanon, and their main targets have been Israeli soldiers not Israeli civilians. The party's secretary-general, Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah, defines Hizbullah's anti-Israeli ambitions in limited terms. If he is to be believed, the organisation wants only to drive Israelis out of Lebanon, not into the sea. Syria, with nearly 30,000 troops in Lebanon, is happy to let the guerrillas get on with their campaign. And the Lebanese government itself, however awkward it finds their presence, cannot openly oppose people struggling for the return of Lebanese territory.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hizbullah is not a straightforward terrorist group. Nor was the sequence of events leading to Israel's attack as simple a routine as terrorism answered by counter-terrorism. There were rules, albeit of a brutish sort, governing the war in southern Lebanon. Three years ago, when a week-long Israeli blasting of the land last made refugees out of several hundred thousand Lebanese, Mr Christopher worked out a truce between Israel on the one hand and Syria and Lebanon on the other, jointly representing Hizbullah. This informal arrangement laid down that it was all right for Hizbullah and the Israeli army to fight each other in Israel's occupation zone, but Hizbullah was not to slam rockets into northern Israel and Israel's soldiers were not to attack Lebanese villages.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The rules were generally observed, although broken from time to time by both sides. Israelis in Galilee could relax, though never completely. But Israeli soldiers found their job increasingly dangerous. At one time Israel's Lebanese military proxy, the South Lebanon Army (<font size=-1>SLA</font>), patrolled the zone. But the <font size=-1>SLA</font>, by now, barely counts as a military force; its demoralised members have their minds fixed on their own uncertain future after an Israeli-Lebanese peace. And Hizbullah, this year, has shown itself increasingly proficient at killing Israeli soldiers. Its intelligence has improved, it uses tricks to draw Israeli units into pursuit and then to ambush them, and, on March 20th, it returned to ancient ways (more recently borrowed by Hamas) by sending a suicide-bomber to kill a soldier.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That may have been the moment when Israel decided the rules would have to be revised. The suicide-bomber opened a vista of military funerals--and Israel has never allowed the death of its conscript soldiers to be an inevitable part of army life. The vicious tit-for-tat killing wound on for a time. The Israelis killed two Lebanese civilians; Hizbullah fired Katyusha rockets into Israel; a Lebanese youngster was killed by an unexplained explosion; Hizbullah fired more rockets injuring several Israeli civilians; another Israeli soldier was killed. Then, on April 11th, Israel struck, making that last Katyusha salvo its justification.
</p><p><b>The long-term explanation</b>
<br>Lebanon is the battleground on which Israel fights its wars, first with the Palestine Liberation Organisation (<font size=-1>PLO</font>), now with Hizbullah. Yet, for the first 20 years or so of Israel's independence, Israelis living near the Lebanese border were the safest of all the frontiersmen. The Lebanese got on with their own affairs; the Israelis, while keeping a wary eye on water resources, had no designs on Lebanese territory.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The event that changed this came in the early 1970s, when Jordan's King Hussein, with Israel breathing down his neck, forced the <font size=-1>PLO</font> out of his country. The <font size=-1>PLO</font> regrouped in Lebanon, taking control of part of the south, creating a state within a state from which it launched attacks on Israel. The border became a war zone.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1978 the Israelis, made bold by their breakthrough with Egypt (and by the havoc of Lebanon's own civil war), invaded southern Lebanon. After three months, and many Lebanese and Palestinian casualties, the Israelis went home but, on the way, ignoring <font size=-1>UN</font> instructions to withdraw completely, they handed over a chunk of the southernmost part of Lebanon to the <font size=-1>SLA</font>, an army that they financed, equipped and controlled. The <font size=-1>PLO</font>, despite this, continued its operations. In 1982, the decision was taken--whether by Israel's prime minister, the late Menahem Begin, or by his defence minister, Ariel Sharon, is still disputed--to send ground troops all the way to Beirut and crush the <font size=-1>PLO</font> once and for all. Lebanon would be freed of Palestinians, and of Syrians too, said the propaganda. And the Israelis could henceforth live at peace, with no <font size=-1>PLO</font> trying to drive them out of the occupied West Bank and Gaza.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It all went terribly wrong. It took Israel three bloody months to seize Beirut. The <font size=-1>PLO</font> and its fighters were indeed driven out of the country but survived to fight--and eventually to make peace--elsewhere. Hizbullah was formed in 1982, inspired by Iranian revolutionaries largely in response to Israel's invasion. At least 12,000 people were killed during that invasion, including 600 Israeli soldiers. Palestinian refugees were massacred in their camps in a Beirut district under Israeli military control. An American-led force tried to stop the fighting but limped home after a suicide-bomber killed 240 marines. Lebanon, when it had eventually fought itself to a standstill, ended up under Syrian control.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Israel withdrew from Lebanon in 1985, it established, formally if unilaterally, that a "security zone" in the south should remain under its control. This uneven buffer area, about nine miles (14km) wide, amounts to roughly one-twelfth of Lebanon. It does indeed protect northern Israel from armed incursions. But it cannot protect Israeli citizens from rockets that can be fired from outside the zone--and it provides Hizbullah with an excuse, and indeed support, for its continued resistance.
</p><p><b>The politics behind the operation</b></b>
<br>Israel has bad, sour memories from its 1982 invasion and no Israeli politician, if he has any choice at all, would again send ground troops into Lebanon's steely trap. But the current operation, Israelis think, is different. Israeli lives are barely at risk. Unseen foes are being satisfactorily thumped. Months of agonising are done with. Israel is demonstrating, as it so often used to do, that it is not a country to be trifled with. Dissenting voices are rare, dismissed as cranks, who question the value of a "security zone" that is causing so much pain.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Peres, the one-time thinker, is in a new element, a reassuring presence striding about in a battledress. Television footage of the prime minister, who is also defence minister, shows him debriefing helicopter pilots on sandy landing-strips, his grey hair tousled by the draught of the rotor blades. With Israel's election due on May 29th, it is all far more effective than anything the campaign professionals could possibly have contrived. While it would be too much to claim the offensive is a campaign gimmick--Israel, after all, has genuine security worries--the fact is that it has paid electoral dividends.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It puts a sheepish Likud opposition, and its leader Binyamin Netanyahu in particular, in the shade. The Likud had been about to unleash a blitz of media and billboard advertisements centring on the slogan "Defence is too big for Peres". That has now been shelved and the Likud is flailing about for a cogent new line.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Suspicions of Mr Peres's "weakness" have vanished. His campaign slogan, "A strong Israel with Peres", suddenly rings true. Israeli television news, like American television in the Gulf war and sometimes with as little relevance, shows missiles pinpointing targets that then explode. The whole affair is a tremendous electoral bonanza--though one that could go terribly wrong if, for instance, Hizbullah carries out its threat to send suicide recruits behind Israel's lines.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The prime minister and his men have been careful to keep expectations low. Unlike the heady months when the <font size=-1>PLO</font> was to disappear from the face of the earth, there is no talk of "destroying" Hizbullah and no great hopes of disarming it. Ehud Barak, Israel's foreign minister who was army chief in 1993, suggested on television that the operation could be considered a success if it provided Israel's townships with two Katyusha-free years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But if the Americans do succeed in restoring the rules of engagement that prevailed after 1993, the Israelis are bidding for a much tighter interpretation--at least of the rules that bind Hizbullah. They want a ban, under any circumstances, on rockets fired across the frontier. For themselves, they want the rules relaxed: their gunners, they say, should be permitted to target Katyusha launchers, even if these are in villages. Moreover, they want the right to hot pursuit of Hizbullah units out of the security zone--without such pursuit giving Hizbullah an equivalent right to fire its rockets into Israel.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Likud opposition is demanding even more. Mr Netanyahu says that he wants the infrastructure of Hizbullah in southern Lebanon to be dismantled (whatever that means) and Syria to be "deterred" from allowing the group to reconstruct itself. Two of his top lieutenants, Ariel Sharon and Rafael Eitan, both hawkish veterans of the 1982 war, go much further. They want Israel to expand its security zone to the Litani river (see <a href="sf1.gif">map</a>). This would mean either incorporating another 250,000 unfriendly residents--or forcibly preventing them from returning to their homes when the bombardment stops. Either scenario conjures up in Israeli minds the nightmare of a new Lebanese embroilment. So Mr Netanyahu, an expert in verbal casuistry, has rejected this advice, at least "at this stage".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Peres's government is looking beyond tactical gains on the frontier. After all, as he and his aides reiterate, the bombardment was ordered by leaders committed to a comprehensive peace process: that is, a process that must include both Syria and Lebanon (a lasting peace with Lebanon will not be possible without peace with Syria).
</p><p><b>What next?</b></b>
<br>An odd way to pursue a peace, perhaps. But Israel reckons that, when the punishment comes to an end, Syria may be more amenable about the terms for peace. In Mr Barak's words, "We are showing the Syrians that we are prepared to endanger their years of investment in Lebanon." Apart from Syria's military and political presence in Lebanon, some 1m Syrians are employed in Lebanon's reviving economy--and sustained bombardment is the surest means to scare off investors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Israel had been encouraged by the initially muted response of most Arab governments. The Tunisians went ahead and opened an Israeli interests office in Tunis. Iran's President Ali Akbar Rafsanjani even telephoned Libya's Colonel Muammar Qaddafi to complain about the feebleness of the reaction to Israel's adventure. Then, on April 18th, came both the shelling of the <font size=-1>UN</font> base and a terrorist outrage that may well be related to the events in Lebanon: Egyptian gunmen killed 18 tourists, most of them Greek, in a Cairo hotel.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lebanon's prime minister, Rafik Hariri, with a big stake in Beirut's reconstruction, is travelling around trying to drum up support. His foreign minister, Faris Bouez, told an emergency meeting of the Arab League that peace depends on an Israeli commitment to leave Lebanon. "When Israel promises, in a way that is definitive, unequivocal and final, to withdraw completely from Lebanese territory," said Mr Bouez, "only then will Lebanon say that this is a safe border."Is Mr Peres listening?
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,iss">Search</a>
