<html><head><title>Wage war</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>Wage war</h1>


BRITAIN'S financial markets wobbled on April 17th when new labour-market data revealed an unexpectedly sharp fall in unemployment, down by 25,700 in March, and a rise in average earnings by 3.5% in the year to February. The annual growth of earnings had been stuck at 3.25% since last July. These two surprises coming together prompted fears that the labour market may be starting to tighten, possibly pushing up inflation. The following day's announcement of a surprise 0.5% month-on-month jump in underlying inflation in March, pushing up the annual rate of inflation to 2.9%, did nothing to calm market nerves.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Recent earnings growth has been surprisingly weak. Indeed, as our <a href="br1.gif">chart</a> shows, unusually in the last four years it has lagged behind the growth of (nominal) labour productivity. This has contributed to a sharp decline in the share of wages in British national income, and a rise in the share of profits (a trend mirrored in other industrial economies). Adair Turner, the director-general of the <font size=-1>CBI</font>, has suggested that this switch from labour to capital may have gone far enough. But Douglas McWilliams, an economist at <font size=-1>CEBR</font>, a research firm, reckons the shift has barely begun, and that over the next 25 years the share of wages in national income will fall from today's 68% to less than 45%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This, he argues, is because British business earns a low rate of return on capital compared with rival economies and will have to raise this sharply if it is to continue to attract capital, let alone achieve the increase in investment he says will be needed early next century. Maybe. But this assumes a perfectly liquid, competitive global capital market. Although the world is moving in that direction, it is doing so very slowly.


</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,iss">Search</a>
