<html><head><title>It's a miracle</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Church of England</b></p>
<h1>It's a miracle</h1>


<p>WHEN the Church of England revealed that it had lost &#163;800m in the early 1990s due to lousy property investments, there was uproar from church members, much serious talk of dismantling the costly nationwide parish system, and unholy glee amongst the unwashed masses as they pondered the incompatibility of God and Mammon. So it was a relieved George Carey, the Archbishop of Canterbury, who announced that the church's investments were "bouncing back", up by &#163;300m in 1995 to the second highest level ever (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>). Hard decisions taken in 1992 are being proved right, he said. Really?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Church of England was not alone in losing heavily on property in the 1990s. But its results were so much worse than other investors because property comprised a hefty 60% of its portfolio. A typical conservative investment institution, such as a pension fund or insurance company, invested no more than 10-15% in property, often much less. The Church Commissioners, who manage the portfolio, now recognise the absurdity of investing so much in as risky an asset as property, and have cut its share of their portfolio to 36%, with a long-term target of less than 30%. Even that is a high figure, however, which would leave the church badly exposed to any future property crash.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Church Commissioners admit that their portfolio is not ideal for investment performance, but reckon it is the best they can do given their obligations to provide the church with cash. To stump up what is needed, an amount that has soared over the last 20 years, the Church Commissioners have to invest disproportionately in assets such as property which pay out plenty of cash but may produce little capital growth. Government rules stop them selling assets and handing over the proceeds, although they have partly got around this by "coupon stripping"--buying a share just before it pays a dividend then selling it, usually for less, as soon as the dividend is received. This practice, which generated &#163;12m in cash last year, is legal, if hardly in the spirit of the rules.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To ease the pressure on the commissioners to pursue a quirky investment strategy, the church has agreed to reduce the amount of income it expects from them--and required greater giving from pew-fillers to make good the difference. That has helped, but, as the commissioners still feel obliged to allocate a risky 30% of their portfolio to property, clearly not enough. To be sure of avoiding a future property debacle, Mr Carey would have to cut the commissioners' obligations further and send the collection plate round again.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br5.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
