<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><b>One to go</b> &nbsp;
The Conservatives suffered a crushing defeat at the hands of Labour in a parliamentary by-election at Staffordshire South East, reducing the government's Commons majority to one.</p>
<p><b>Blow from the right</b> &nbsp;
In a further threat to the Tories' electoral prospects, Sir James Goldsmith, a financier, said his anti-<font size=-1>EU</font> Referendum Party would put up 600 candidates at the next general election.</p>
<p><b>Social climber</b> &nbsp;
Labour's deputy leader, John Prescott, pleased Tony Blair but shocked other party colleagues and his father by admitting that he is now middle-class because of his parliamentary life-style.
<p><b>Short</b> <b>changed</b><br>
Clare Short, Labour's transport spokesman, said people like her should pay more tax, apparently contradicting the party leadership's promises not to increase taxes on middle-income families.</p>
<p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><b>On the rocks</b> &nbsp;

The day after John Major said the monarchy was "rock solid" , the Duke and Duchess of York announced that they were divorcing.</p>
<p><b>One that got away</b> &nbsp;
Scotland Yard's attempt to get an alleged <font size=-1>IRA</font> member extradited to Britain from the Irish Republic failed after a Dublin court ruled that the documents relating to the extradition were flawed.</p>
<p><b>Flick nixed</b> &nbsp;
Gert-Rudolf Flick, the grandson of a convicted Nazi war criminal, asked Oxford University for the return of his controversial &#163;350,000 donation.</p>
<p><b>Bitter pill</b> &nbsp;
The British Pregnancy Advisory Service said it carried out about 800 more abortions than usual in the months following last October's scare over the safety of some types of contraceptive pill.
</p>
<p><b>Bashful bunnies</b> &nbsp;
Rabbits are no longer breeding like rabbits. Pet shops reported that they were finding it hard to get supplies of rabbits, perhaps because of the effect of cold weather on reproduction.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
