<html><head><title>Something worth watching, at last</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Digital television in Europe</b></p>
<h1>Something worth watching, at last</h1>

<font size=1>PARIS, BERLIN AND LONDON</font><p><b>Digital television has thrown Europe's media groups into a frenzy. But will it make money?
</b><p>NOT since the days of Metternich has continental Europe seen such a web of conspiratorial, expensive alliances. In both France and Germany rival consortia of media moguls are forming and reforming. The reason: digital broadcasting, hailed by its fans as the short cut to interactive television. Digital broadcasting promises many more channels of television than analogue; it can also provide pay-per-view programmes (such as soccer matches) much more easily and it offers ways of transmitting software such as computer games.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Europe's first full-blown digital offering will be launched on April 27th by France's Canal+. Though Italy's Telepiu has already started digital satellite broadcasting in a modest way, Canal+ is offering a bouquet of 25 channels, including pay-per-view films and sports, thematic channels and an option to download software. In two landmark deals, the company has stitched up the pay-per-view rights to first-division French football and acquired rights to the Disney channel.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To receive the basic service subscribers have to pay FFr98 ($19) a month, plus FFr45 a month to rent the receiving equipment. That is still cheap, compared with FFr136 for the analogue pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> service which offers fewer channels. Bruno Delecour of Canal+ hopes subscribers will spend an average of FFr200 a month, rather than the FFr150 that analogue attracts. He thinks the project will cost at most FFr500m, and expects to break even after three years with 900,000 subscribers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Others mutter that the costs will be far higher. That is more likely if a rival group goes ahead with a plan to offer another digital service in September. The alliance, announced this week by Jacques Chirac's government, is enmeshed in French politics. It includes France T&eacutel&eacutevision, the French public broadcaster, <font size=-1>TF</font>1, the main commercial broadcaster, and Lyonnaise des Eaux, whose president, Jerome Monod, is a big noise in Mr Chirac's Gaullist party. Canal+ is close to France's Socialists. The alliance's most important catch, though, is <font size=-1>CLT</font>, a media group based in Luxembourg.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To many, the deal (still not formally signed) looks mad. Neither <font size=-1>TF</font>1 nor France T&eacutel&eacutevision appears to have the cash to finance such a venture; none of the partners has experience in pay-television, on which digital services will inevitably depend for their main revenue; and none seems to have a clear view of what programming the venture will offer.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, if the deal goes through, it will enrage Havas, a French media group which owns 24% of Canal+, and has a minority stake in <font size=-1>CLT</font>. Relations between Havas and Albert Fr&egravere, the boss of <font size=-1>CLT</font>, are already dire. <font size=-1>CLT</font>'s yearning to launch a digital venture in France and Germany led it into an agreement last August with Rupert Murdoch's <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>. In early March <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> abruptly defected to a digital alliance with Bertelsmann, a giant German group--and Canal+. Mr Fr&egravere blames Havas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But <font size=-1>CLT</font>'s French foray is not just irritating for Havas. At the beginning of April Bertelsmann agreed to merge <font size=-1>UFA</font>, its television and film subsidiary, with <font size=-1>CLT</font>, in a new company in which both groups would have equal shares. "That is not a very good or stable agreement," observes Gilles Fontaine of <font size=-1>IDATE</font>, a French media consultancy. Bertelsmann has for some time had an alliance with Canal+. This week, the Germans were blunt: <font size=-1>CLT</font> must choose between the French venture and <font size=-1>UFA</font>. Given Havas's weak position, the internal wrangling promises to be vicious.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>CLT</font> and Bertelsmann need to stay on good terms because in Germany they are allies in what could be an even fiercer war. Both are members of <font size=-1>MMBG</font>, an alliance that also includes Canal+ and Deutsche Telekom, and which on paper looks immensely strong. Fielded against them is an alliance put together by Leo Kirch, a shadowy Bavarian mogul, including his own Kirch group, Vebacom, the telecoms subsidiary of Veba, a large energy conglomerate, and Metro, Germany's biggest retailer. Crucially, Mr Kirch promises to get a decoder box on the market and up to 50 channels on the air in July. According to one of its shareholders, <font size=-1>MMBG</font> will be launched by Christmas "only if it is really lucky".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Germany, at least, the reasons for rivalry go beyond mere political and corporate pique. Each consortium has members who hope to sell services associated with its box. For instance, since the decoder box can deliver signals to computers as well as to televisions, Vebacom could use it to sell telecoms services. "It could be every house's link with the outside world for encrypted services," claims Vebacom.
<p><b>Give me a reason to pay<br></b>But will viewers really want to shell out, particularly if they have to decide between two competing technologies? In Britain, many viewers shunned (analogue) satellite broadcasting as long as there were two incompatible services; once Mr Murdoch's Sky won and took over its rival <font size=-1>BSB</font>, the service took off. The chances are that the same will happen when it comes to set-top boxes in France and Germany. In Germany the speedy Mr Kirch may have a slight edge. In France it is hard to imagine Canal+ losing. Indeed, it has already offered to carry other broadcasters' signals, at a price they claim is outrageously high.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But even if all digital channels were available on any box, would digital television pay? In Germany, whose viewers are offered more free television than anyone in Europe, the investment is steep. Martin Gruschka of Arthur D. Little, a consultancy, estimates that it costs DM1 billion ($660m) to launch a box, including the costs of developing and marketing, and of setting up a subscriber-management system. Programming costs extra: the Kirch Group is expected to spend up to DM700m to launch <font size=-1>DF</font>1, its digital subsidiary. By 2000, claims the group, it will have 2m subscribers and reach break-even in operating terms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With lots of public and advertising-financed channels, German viewers have been unenthusiastic about pay television. Premiere, Germany's only pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> channel, launched in 1991, is only now becoming profitable. Klaus Schrape, media analyst at Prognos, a Swiss consultancy, points out that Germans already pay about DM50 a month in cable subscriptions and television tax. Digital's promoters expect them to add DM20-30 a month to rent a box, and an average of DM40 a month for programming. He thinks only 7-8% of households will take digital television by 2000, well short of the 10% at which growth accelerates and unit costs start to fall rapidly. At best, break-even is five years off.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The strategy of <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, the world's biggest direct-to-home broadcaster, suggests the case for caution. Sky has already designed an elaborate digital package, which would offer some interactive services and rental capacity for corporate television, as well as showing the familiar mix of thematic channels, films and sport, and pay-per-view. It has booked ample transponder space, and been testing decoder boxes since the beginning of 1995. "If we wanted to launch this autumn, we could definitely do so," says David Chance, <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>'s deputy managing director.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But unlike its continental partners, <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> faces no immediate rival. It has therefore decided to wait until 1997 or even 1998. One reason is that the British government is still deciding how to regulate the terms on which other broadcasters have access to Sky's digital system. Another is the hope that the cost of decoder boxes will fall (unlike Canal+, Sky's customers will buy their own). More to the point, Sky's analogue business is still growing at a healthy pace, while Canal+ seems to be nearing a ceiling. So why risk cannibalising it, when nobody else is threatening to do so?


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,iss">Search</a>
