<html><head><title>Tomorrow's network, tomorrow</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<p><b>Information technology</b></p>
<h1>Tomorrow's network, tomorrow</h1>
<p><b>Asynchronous Transfer Mode switches are the latest mouthful to thrill Silicon Valley. But who will buy them?</b></p>

<p>JEAN-LOUIS GASSEE, who used to run Apple Computer's research labs, has called it "Silicon Valley sophism": the assumption among the wired elite that a new technology will take off "because it would be cool if it did." Examples include virtual reality, personal digital assistants, and practically everything dreamt up at the Media Lab of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. These innovations thrill boffins but make little impact on consumers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the early 1980s one such flop was a digital-networking technology called <font size=-1>ISDN</font>. Though telephone companies enthused about <font size=-1>ISDN</font>'s use for home videophones (a sure sign of a non-starter, as nearly 40 years of videophone demonstrations have proved), consumers just yawned. Now an even faster networking technology, called Asynchronous Transfer Mode (<font size=-1>ATM</font>), has got the geeks in a lather again.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>ATM</font> is already half a decade old. Its selling point is that it is tailor-made for multimedia. The Internet, plus the various "local" and "wide" area networks (<font size=-1>LAN</font>s and <font size=-1>WAN</font>s) used by companies chop data into "packets" of variable length. By dealing with packets, the network does not need to consider what sort of information is being transmitted; it just mixes all the packets together and pumps them through the network by the fastest route available at any time, allowing software on the receiving side to sort them out again.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nonetheless, packet-switching has its drawbacks. The sorting takes up valuable time; and the irregular nature of the packets creates bursts of frantic motion followed by frozen pauses. That wrecks "real-time" music or video, where the re-ordering process can make the best digital recording sound like short-wave radio.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>ATM</font> solves this problem by breaking the digital information into tiny "cells", or mini-packets, of exactly the same 53-bit size. These uniform cells travel faster and are easier to sort out when they arrive, raising transmission speeds to 155m bits per second, more than 15 times the speed of normal <font size=-1>LAN</font>s, and permitting a network to carry broadcast-quality video and sound.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this has brought dollar signs into the eyes of the technology's champions. <i>The Red Herring</i>, a Silicon Valley magazine, devoted much of its latest issue to the technology under such headlines as "<font size=-1>ATM</font> changes everything". And the market value of <font size=-1>FORE</font> Systems, a six-year-old company which is the leading supplier of <font size=-1>ATM</font> equipment, has doubled in the past year to more than $2 billion--even though the firm made net profits in the year to March 1995 of only $7.4m on revenues of $76m.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the same time, mainstream makers of networking equipment, such as Cisco Systems, 3Com and Bay Network, have been acquiring <font size=-1>ATM</font> technology rapidly. Small networking firms such as Cascade Communications, StrataCom and Newbridge Networks are jostling with established giants such as <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, <font size=-1>IBM</font> and Fujitsu in the scramble to claim a piece of what they all expect to be a huge market.
</p><p><b>Not so WANderful</b></b>
<br>But does <font size=-1>ATM</font> really change everything? It is undeniably smoother, faster, and, yes, cooler than today's standards. But nearly three years after manufacturers started to produce <font size=-1>ATM</font> switches, sales are still modest: about $270m in 1995, out of a total market for data-networking equipment of about $7 billion. Even by 1998, reckons the Vertical Systems Group, a consultancy in Dedham, Massachusetts, <font size=-1>ATM</font> revenues will be around $1.6 billion, less than those from frame relay, an older and less capable technology that has the advantage of being less trouble to install and use.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike the Internet, which uses existing telephone lines, networks and computers, <font size=-1>ATM</font> often requires new cabling and new software, along with network managers who can make it work its magic. A firm that embarks on this course will often need to hire new people, invest in training, and prepare for headaches of various sorts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That may be worthwhile for big communications companies, whose business is pumping data through wires. Long-distance telephone carriers prize <font size=-1>ATM</font>'s ability to handle voice, video-conferencing and computer data seamlessly. Some of those that carry Internet traffic have already installed <font size=-1>ATM</font> switches on their most congested links. Firms building new networks, such as the cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> companies that are preparing to offer high-speed Internet and other interactive services to the home, are increasingly choosing <font size=-1>ATM</font>, too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, most of the world's data networks are on internal company <font size=-1>LAN</font>s or <font size=-1>WAN</font>s. (A <font size=-1>LAN</font> tends to be within a single building or campus; a <font size=-1>WAN</font> is made up of the leased lines linking up various <font size=-1>LAN</font>s). This is the domain of hard-nosed systems managers who think more about monthly budgets than multimedia. And since most corporate <font size=-1>PC</font>s do not have sound cards or <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>s, they could not use <font size=-1>ATM</font> video and audio even if they could get it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the case of <font size=-1>WAN</font>s, moreover, <font size=-1>ATM</font> can sometimes be too fast. The technology generally runs at speeds of at least 51m bits per second, and leasing a telephone line capable of handling this can cost $100,000 a month. That is a lot to pay for a sharper picture in your video-conferences.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the case of <font size=-1>LAN</font>s, the problem is not so much the cost of transmission within a building or campus, but the cost of installation. An <font size=-1>ATM</font> card and switch for a <font size=-1>PC</font> costs around $800, and might not be compatible with the existing software. It costs half as much to buy a turbocharged version of the old Ethernet standard that most <font size=-1>PC</font>s already use, and which will transmit data at a speed of up to 100m bits per second, fast enough for most current multimedia products. Forrester Research, a Massachusetts consultancy, reckons that by 1998, only 10% of <font size=-1>LAN</font> traffic will have moved to <font size=-1>ATM</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>ATM</font>'s backers hope that two changes will make systems managers readier to accept the new technology. One is its falling price. Several firms make 25m-bits-per-second gear that is expected soon to cost as little as $400 per <font size=-1>PC</font>, and which should work with existing Ethernet networks (though they will need new software to make the most of their features).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In addition, the technology may benefit from the current management fad for turning groups of workers, even in different offices, into teams. Unlike a conventional <font size=-1>LAN</font>, <font size=-1>ATM</font> is flexible enough for a network manager to connect teams at will, regardless of where they are. With such "virtual <font size=-1>LAN</font>s" , managers can reconfigure network connections between employees as often, and as easily, as they redraw their organisational charts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the meantime, many <font size=-1>ATM</font> makers are hedging their bets. In February, for example, <font size=-1>FORE</font> agreed to pay $684m for Alantec, a San Jose firm which makes fast versions of the old Ethernet standard. <font size=-1>ATM</font>'s day will undoubtedly come, but maybe not quite yet. Too little demand and too much hassle: many a promising technology has foundered on these rocks before.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
