<html><head><title>Asia's flagging alliance</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p><h1><center>Asia's flagging alliance</center></h1>THE handshake will be demonstrably firm, the declaration--issued jointly--will be deliberately reassuring, the timing could scarcely be bettered. On April 16th, less than a month after China ended its menacing military manoeuvres off Taiwan, and amid troubling new tensions on the Korean peninsula, Bill Clinton will travel to Tokyo to reaffirm America's security treaty with Japan. And since the America-Japan alliance is the cornerstone of security in East Asia, next week's summit should help calm rattled nerves around the region. But, alas, not for long. Fashioned for a bygone era, the America-Japan alliance is itself under strain. If it is to survive and to go on underpinning a wider stability, it needs to be radically redesigned. In future, Japan needs to be able to do more to help America meet East Asia's fast-changing security needs.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The alliance's great weakness is its lop-sidedness: America is committed by treaty to help defend Japan against attack, but the treaty's vague wording about upholding "peace and security in the Far East" has enabled Japan to avoid making a military contribution beyond its own shores. When the Soviet Union posed a global threat, the bargain made sense: Japan could busy itself building democracy and a wealthy economy behind America's broad military shield, while America could base its planes and warships deterringly close to the potential hot spots in Asia's version of the cold war. But, since the cold war ended, dissatisfaction has been growing. Trade tensions have obsessed America. Some Japanese now ask why they should pay huge sums to support the 47,000 or so American troops (out of about 100,000 in the region) still on their soil. Some Americans argue that Japan, one of the world's richest countries in an increasingly wealthy region, should be able to defend itself (see <a href="sf1.html">pages</a>).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet, as recent events have shown, with the end of the cold war East Asia's troubles have not disappeared, they have grown more diverse. First came suspicions that prickly North Korea may have been building nuclear weapons. Then a more powerful and militarily assertive China started pressing territorial claims against its neighbours, from Japan in the north to the Philippines and Indonesia in the south, as well as bullying Taiwan. With Russia on the sidelines, and China playing awkwardly by its own rules, the natural balancer in East Asia's changing power game ought to be Japan. But continued suspicions of a Japan striking out alone, and the absence of any other reassuring multilateral alliances, make America's continued presence essential. Without it, the region's rivals could swiftly end up in a brawl.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Americans, however, are increasingly reluctant to take on East Asia's military burdens alone. With fewer friendly bases in the region (those in the Philippines went in 1992, Hong Kong's will go next year), America will need to rely more heavily on Japan simply to keep its ships and aircraft on patrol. Acknowledging this, at next week's summit Japan will agree to help out more with peacetime supplies, spare parts and the like. And diplomats on both sides are quietly preening themselves for getting a public mention of wider security co-operation into the joint declaration. Yet the co-operation envisaged falls far short of the militarily useful sort. Come the next crisis, the America-Japan alliance will still be found wanting--and both sides will share the blame.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Japan fends off accusations of freeloading on America's defence budget by pointing, not just to its contribution (some 70%) to America's troop costs in Japan, but to its growing share of "soft" security tasks, within the region and beyond: using its aid and diplomacy to ease tensions, contributing some (mostly unarmed) peacekeepers, not just cash, to United Nations missions, from Cambodia to the Golan Heights. Yet it still balks at the "hard" military jobs on which stability in East Asia depends. In the confrontation over North Korea's nuclear ambitions, Japan pointed to its constitution and refused to contemplate even minimal military support for America--even though Japan's own security was at risk. Had either side miscalculated, bringing China and America to blows last month over Taiwan, Japan's warships would have stayed in port, its top-of-the-range aircraft grounded.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Clearly, if push ever does come to shove in East Asia, that sort of you're-on-your-own attitude will shatter the America-Japan alliance. So while toasting their increasingly insecure security treaty in Tokyo next week, America's president and Japan's prime minister could usefully start discussing new ways to strengthen it.</p><p><b>Broke, if you don't fix it</b><br>Japan's constitution did not stop it building up its own Self-Defence Forces, or, despite opposition, contributing to <font size=-1>UN</font> peacekeeping operations. It is only a bar to offering more robust military assistance to the <font size=-1>UN</font> or to joining in collective military action with America if politicians choose to read it that way. Though reinterpreting the constitution to allow Japan to play a more grown-up security role is no longer taboo in Japan, it would take strong political will to push it through. The sooner it is done, however, the safer will be the alliance on which Japan's wider security depends.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet a rebalanced alliance would make demands of America, too. Just as Japan has been content to hide securely behind America, so America has found it convenient to have an ally that asks few questions. Scarcely any Japanese officials, even the most senior ones, know what goes on at America's Japanese bases: though one of the aircraft-carriers that America recently sent to help protect Taiwan came from Japan, America did not think to let the Japanese government in on its plans. But if Japan is to stand closer to America's shoulder in future crises, America needs to acquire unaccustomed habits of consultation about threats to peace well before they explode, not just expect Japan to help pick up the messy pieces.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;None of this will come easily. But, as the secure foundation for East Asia's growing prosperity, a restored America-Japan alliance is irreplaceable. Best to fix it, therefore, before the damage becomes irreparable.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829350000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
