<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p><p align=center><img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p><hr size=6 align=center width=65%><center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><h2>A Yeltsin surge</h2><p>Opinion polls which have previously shown the Communist Party's candidate, Gennady Zyuganov, to be well in the lead in the race for <b>Russia's presidency</b>, suggest that President Boris Yeltsin is now rapidly closing the gap. The first round of the election takes place on June 16th.<p>Fighting in Chechnya between Russian forces and rebel <b>Chechen guerrillas</b> continued, despite Mr Yeltsin's declaration of a ceasefire on March 31st and his new willingness to negotiate with the Chechen leader, Jokar Dudaev, through intermediaries. Mr Dudaev still officially demands outright independence, but unofficially hints at flexibility.</p><p>China's prime minister, <b>Li Peng</b>, visited France and signed $2 billion-worth of trade deals, the biggest with Airbus Industrie. But his visit was marred by a diplomatic wrangle with Alain Jupp&eacute, the French prime minister, over human rights in China. The two men dropped the normal exchange of banquet toasts, after objecting to references to human rights in each other's draft remarks.</p><p>Fighting between <b>Kurdish guerrillas</b> and Turkish government forces intensified in eastern Turkey. The government said that more than 100 guerrillas and 30 Turkish soldiers had died in less than a week. An early peace settlement seems unlikely.</p><p>Barely five weeks after Spain's general election was won by Jose Maria Aznar and his conservative People's Party (<font size=-1>PP</font>), the leader of the main Catalan nationalist party, <b>Jordi Pujol</b>, has threatened to provoke another general election. The <font size=-1>PP</font>, which lacks a majority of seats in the new parliament, needs to make a deal with the Catalans, but Mr Pujol is playing hard to get.</p><p>The French president, Jacques Chirac, on a visit to Egypt, proposed a <b>Euro-Mediterranean summit</b>, which could, he said, lead to a "stability pact" to promote peace all round the Mediterranean.</p><h2>A terrorist hermit</h2><p>Theodore Kaczynski, suspected by the <font size=-1>FBI</font> of being the <b>Unabomber</b>, an anti-technology terrorist who has killed three people and injured many others in mail bombings over the past 18 years, was arrested in Montana and charged with possession of bomb-making materials. Agents say they found a live bomb ready for mailing and the names of some of the victims in his cabin.</p><p>Hearings began in Denver in the trial of Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols, charged in connection with the bombing in <b>Oklahoma City </b>a year ago which killed 169 people.</p><p>President Bill Clinton signed bills giving him the power to <b>veto </b>single items in budget bills, and reforming <b>farm subsidies </b>for the first time in 60 years. Both were favoured goals of the Republican majority in Congress.</p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><p>After a 15-month investigation, the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission filed suit against Mitsubishi Motor for "continued physical and verbal <b>abuse against women</b>" at its plant in Normal, Illinois.</p><p>The Children's Defence Fund reported that in 1993 gunfire was the second-biggest cause of death among <b>American children </b>aged 10 to 19 (accidents were the first), and that a child died from gunfire in America every 92 minutes.</p><h2>Beirut attacked</h2><p>The tacit agreement between <b>Israel and Hizbullah</b> not to attack civilian targets collapsed after a Lebanese boy was killed in an explosion, and the Hizbullah rocketed a northern Israeli town. Israeli aircraft blasted Lebanon, including Hizbullah's offices in Beirut's densely populated suburbs.</p><p>After several days of factional fighting and hostage-taking in Liberia's capital,<b> Monrovia</b>, America evacuated its nationals and some other foreigners by helicopter. The fighting leaves last year's peace accord and prospects for disarmament and elections in ruins.</p><p>A Saudi-owned company pulled the plug on an<b> Arabic television service</b> that it had been providing jointly with the <font size=-1>BBC</font> after the service transmitted a documentary critical of the Saudi regime. The programme was not only shown in Britain but transmitted in Arabic to the Middle East and North Africa.</p><p><b>Jordan </b>agreed to let American military aircraft use its main air base for surveillance flights over southern Iraq.</p><h2>Cocking a snook</h2><p>For three nights up to 300 <b>North Korean soldiers </b>breached the armistice agreement on the Korean peninsula by moving into the demilitarised zone separating North and South Korea. The North is thought to be weary of the truce agreed in 1953 and wants to negotiate a peace treaty with America, which keeps a large defence force in the South.</p><p>A report prepared for the <b>Vietnamese Communist Party </b>congress in June envisages a lively private sector over the next five years, but says the state should be the main engine for growth.</p><p>The number of British nationals in <b>Hong Kong </b>increased by 39% to 34,500 in the eight months to February. Many more British companies are said to be moving to the territory to concentrate on the Chinese market. The British population is the third largest there, after those of the United States and the Philippines.</p><p></p></td></tr></table></center><p align=center><a href="wtw2.html">BUSINESS THIS WEEK</a></p><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829350000,iss">Search</a>