<html><head><title>Crisis, again</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width=67 height=26  alt="Asia"><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><p><b>The Korean peninsula</b></p><h1>Crisis, again</h1><font size=1>SEOUL</font><p>THE ruling elite in North Korea certainly knows how to stir up a crisis. So it should; it has had plenty of practice.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The latest confrontation on the Korean peninsula bears all the hallmarks of well orchestrated political theatre. In sending up to 300 heavily armed soldiers into the demilitarised buffer zone at Panmunjom on three separate occasions, from April 5th to April 7th, North Korea's communist dictatorship certainly caught the world's attention. Bellicose declarations that war between North and South Korea is inevitable, and that the North would no longer abide by the terms of the armistice that ended the Korean war more than 40 years ago, have garnered the desired headlines.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But despite all the war-like rhetoric, neither the Americans--who have over 30,000 troops in South Korea--nor the South Koreans believe that a conflict is imminent. They have detected no signs of a build-up of North Korean troops or other threatening manoeuvres that might indicate preparations for an attack. The only sign of a change visible to recent visitors to the frontier was that the North Koreans were not wearing armbands, which are required under the military armistice.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Privately, the American and South Korean analysis of the situation may be similar. But the two governments' public reactions have been different. The Americans, who have no desire for another security crisis in Asia, have played down the North Korean actions. They continued to escort tourists through the public areas at Panmunjom as North Korea conducted its manoeuvres, an ostentatious sign that they were not alarmed.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By contrast, South Korean officials have been talking the crisis up. State television showed South Korean forces crouching in combat positions, and running along the south side of the demilitarised zone with blackened faces.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But, when pressed at a news conference, a senior defence-ministry official conceded that the armed forces as a whole were still on the same general level of alert as they had been before the latest crisis. American and South Korean officials say the "watch" grade has been increased one point, which means that intelligence readings are analysed more frequently.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many South Koreans take a cynical view. Parliamentary elections were held on April 11th. In the past, war scares have created a bit of a bounce in the vote for the government. It seems that history may have repeated itself. Early projections by state television, after the polls had closed, predicted that Mr Kim's New Korea Party would increase its majority--contrary to most expectations. "I don't understand why North Korea helps the ruling party at every election," bemoaned one member of the opposition.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not understanding the North Koreans is a fairly common complaint. But the best guess is that the North probably has two aims. Meddling in the South Korean elections is always tempting. And with President Clinton heading for Seoul next week, on his way to Tokyo, the opportunity to engage the Americans' attention was clearly too good to miss.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since <font size=-1>KEDO</font>, an American-led consortium, offered to supply two 1,000-megawatt nuclear reactors costing $4.5 billion in exchange for North Korea's agreeing to shut its plutonium-making reactors, the communist regime has realised that by far its best chance for survival is to extract more concessions from America. It has made no secret of its long-term aim to replace the armistice signed in 1955 by North Korea, China and the United States with a peace treaty solely with the Americans. The United States has strongly resisted this idea. In the meantime, the North's aim is probably to get the Clinton administration to supply more aid and diplomatic recognition. South Korea, meanwhile, wants to convince the North that only by making peace with the South will it get economic help. So the South is keen to block northern overtures to America and to Japan.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although the situation is not yet a crisis, it could become one. North Korea knows that brinkmanship and threats worked during the nuclear crisis. Its capacity for making mischief is its only asset. Its armed forces are more numerous than those in the South; but are reckoned to be far weaker. If the North does not get what it wants now, it is sure to up the ante. And with their survival at stake, North Korea's rulers may be prone to reckless miscalculation.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829350000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
