<html><head><title>Uphill struggle</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business"><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><p><b>Olivetti</b></p><h1>Uphill struggle</h1><font size=1>ROME<font><p>EXACTLY how much Olivetti lost last year will be announced on April 16th. But it is certain that the 1995 accounts of Italy's leading information-technology group will be splattered with crimson ink. A loss will in itself hardly surprise the group's shareholders, who have become accustomed to increasingly bad news ever since 1991 (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>). All the same, its dimensions should worry even the most ardent fans of Carlo De Benedetti, Olivetti's chairman: the figure for 1995 is likely to be around 1.5 trillion lire ($920m).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Olivetti's annual reports used to be stylish affairs, filled with dazzling diagrams showing the company's progress. More recently, such gimmicks have disappeared. The price of an Olivetti share has tumbled to just over 800 lire from 9,000 lire in 1987. As Olivetti's largest shareholder (his family owns, indirectly, a 15% stake) Mr De Benedetti has suffered too. Yet the biggest blow may be to his prestige: gone are the days when his international image was as sleek as his company's computers.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Olivetti has already announced losses for the first half of 1995 of almost 1.1 trillion lire on revenues of 4.7 trillion lire. The chief culprit was a 900 billion lire restructuring charge: as well as laying off staff and closing factories, Olivetti also reorganised itself, spinning off two of its businesses--personal computers and office products--into two new companies, Olivetti Personal Computers (<font size=-1>OPC</font>) and Lexikon, both of which came into being in January 1996.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The biggest problem is <font size=-1>OPC</font>, whose antecedents lost more than 200 billion lire last year--before various reorganisation and financial charges. Olivetti sold only 720,000 <font size=-1>PC</font>s last year (about the same number as in 1992); and even this figure may have been artificially boosted by what looks like a year-end clearance sale (around 40% of its <font size=-1>PC</font>s were sold in the last quarter). <font size=-1>OPC</font>'s target is to break even this year. To this end, it has concentrated <font size=-1>PC</font> production in one factory, in the process cutting its staff from about 4,000 to 1,800.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But is it too late? Even if <font size=-1>OPC</font> reaches its ambitious target of selling 900,000 <font size=-1>PC</font>s this year, it will still clearly be a second-division firm. With no obvious edge (its <font size=-1>PC</font>s, though quite stylish, are neither cheaper nor technically better than its rivals'), <font size=-1>OPC</font>'s only niche is geographic: it relies heavily on European sales, and on its home market in particular--both of which are now being attacked by more powerful computer makers such as America's Compaq.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even insiders now concede that if <font size=-1>OPC</font> fails to make money this year, the group will have to quit the business altogether. There has been some speculation, dismissed by Olivetti, that <font size=-1>OPC</font> might be sold to Bull, a troubled French computer company. The harsher truth is that a buyer for <font size=-1>OPC</font> may be hard to find. Cynics note that its establishment as a separate company has made the <font size=-1>PC</font> business easier to close as well as to sell.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of Olivetti's current profits come from two areas: Lexikon, which makes office equipment such as fax machines, photocopiers and printers, and its systems-and-services division, which is still controlled by the main company and enjoys particularly strong custom from financial and public-sector institutions. Here at least Olivetti possesses a few clear advantages (for instance, it is a leader in bank-automation products). On the other hand, it is facing increasing competition, particularly in Italy, and its profit margins are under pressure in both areas.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most of Olivetti's hopes for growth are pinned on two areas which currently yield little revenue (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>): Telemedia, its embryonic multimedia-technology subsidiary, and, particularly, Omnitel Pronto Italia, a new cellular-telephone company in which Olivetti has a 41.3% stake. Omnitel looks like a winner: it has at last navigated around a series of obstructions created by Italy's state telephone company (which, curiously enough, owns the first national cellular service) and it is recruiting subscribers fast. However, profits are two years off, and the firm is currently eating up cash. By June, Olivetti has to stump up 145 billion lire as its part of a 350 billion lire capital injection.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In December, Olivetti raised a massive 2.3 trillion lire of fresh capital to pay for its reorganisation and to finance its investment plans. The group's "net financial indebtedness" (ie, excluding cash and intra-company debt) at the end of the year was still around 800 billion lire. This year it plans to sell 400 billion lire-worth of non-strategic assets, of which it has already raised 200 billion lire (half of that through the sale of Zincocelere, a circuit-board maker). Olivetti is now looking for a purchaser of Eurofly, its executive-jet subsidiary that looks out of place in the company's current reduced circumstances.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some bearish analysts are privately forecasting another cash crunch later this year. In that event, Olivetti might have to sell more assets, or perhaps float off Lexikon. Pointing to the 903 billion lire raised in 1993, as well as to the December rights issue, Paola Toschi of Milla &amp; Co, a Milanese securities house, argues that investors will not support yet another rights issue.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, one of Mr De Benedetti's problems is that his shareholders, most of whom are now non-Italians, have become increasingly mutinous. In retrospect, the rights issue last year was badly handled. There was confusion about the sort of profits the firm was promising to deliver. Investors subscribed for shares at 1,000 lire, only to see them drop to just over 700 at one point (the subsequent partial recovery in the share price has been largely due to a bullish market rather than new faith in Olivetti).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This matters. In the past, one of Olivetti's intangible assets has been the goodwill felt towards the company, which was a pioneer not only in design but also in areas such as employee relations. Mr De Benedetti too had a powerful personal following, based on his reputation in the 1980s as one of the clean brooms that would sweep out the Augean stables of Italian industry. This goodwill now appears to be very nearly exhausted. Olivetti will survive next Tuesday's results; the real test will be 1996's half-year figures in September.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829350000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="ob1.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
