<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p>


<h2>Connecting</h2>
<p>In a deal valued at nearly $17 billion, two of America's <b>Baby Bell</b> telecoms companies are to merge for the first time to create one of the world's biggest telecoms groups, with a market value of $45 billion. For Texas-based <font size=-1>SBC</font> Communications (formerly Southwestern Bell) the main attraction of subsuming Pacific Telesis under the <font size=-1>SBC</font> name is Pacific's huge Californian market.<p>
(see <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>
The reopening of merger talks between Britain's two largest telecoms operators, <b>British Telecom</b> and <b>Cable and Wireless</b>, pushed their share prices up sharply. Any deal would value <font size=-1>C&W</font> at &#163;12.5 billion ($19 billion); market capitalisation of the two would be close to that of the two Baby Bells. <font size=-1>BT</font> wants <font size=-1>C&W</font>'s desirable 57.5% stake in Hongkong Telecom to create a launchpad for its ambitions in Asia.<p>
With the $8.9 billion purchase of <b>U.S. Healthcare</b>, a leading operator of health-maintenance organisations known for keeping a tight grip on medical expenses, cash-rich <b>Aetna </b>will become America's biggest medical-benefits group.<p>
<b>General Motors</b> agreed on terms to spin off its <font size=-1>EDS</font> computer-consultancy unit. They include a tax-free exchange of shares and a $500m pay-out from <font size=-1>EDS</font> to its car-making parent. <font size=-1>EDS</font> expects to benefit from its freedom; meanwhile, it announced a restructuring that will cut jobs and result in a charge in the second quarter of $500m-750m.<p>
Luxembourg-based <b>CLT</b> and the television subsidiary of <b>Bertelsmann</b>, Germany's biggest media company, are to create Europe's biggest <font size=-1>TV</font> broadcaster through a merger worth $6.6 billion. Provided regulators approve, the new company will try to extend its dominance to Europe's fledgling pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> market with help from Rupert Murdoch and Canal Plus of France.<p>
Germany's biggest industrial firm, <b>Daimler-Benz</b>, reported a DM5.7 billion ($3.9 billion) loss for 1995. The company said it would not pay a dividend for the year, but forecast a profit in 1996.

<h2>Soaring</h2>
<p>(see <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>
The <b>French franc</b> had its best run against the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark for nearly two years, buoyed by optimism about the French economy and a corresponding weakness in Germany's. The combination gives the French hope of some sort of monetary union being achieved on schedule. The dollar also hit a two-year high, against the yen.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Despite another bank collapse, the <b>Tokyo stockmarket</b> soared to a four-year high at the beginning of a new financial year. This reflected hopes of better corporate earnings growth and an improving economy. On April 3rd the bond market wobbled after Japan's central-bank governor hinted that interest rates could soon rise.

<h2>Not very Swiss</h2>
<p>Martin Ebner, whose <font size=-1>BK</font> Vision is <b>Union Bank of Switzerland</b>'s largest shareholder and a thorn in its side, said he would oppose the election of Robert Studer, currently chief executive, as chairman at the bank's <font size=-1>AGM</font> later this month.<p>
Two huge <b>bank mergers </b>came into force. Bank of Tokyo and Mitsubishi Bank united to form Tokyo Mitsubishi Bank, the world's biggest, with &#165;75 trillion ($700 billion) of assets; and the merger of Chase Manhattan with Chemical Banking creates America's biggest bank (Chase Manhattan) with assets of $304 billion.<p>
Days after the Italian government promised a rescue, <b>Banco di Napoli</b> recorded the worst results ever run up by an Italian bank--a loss of 3.16 trillion lire ($1.94 billion) for 1995, compared with a 1.15 trillion lire loss a year earlier. The bank also said its capital base had shrunk from 3.58 trillion lire to 522 billion lire.<p>
<p>
Japan's finance ministry set up a panel to review its operations and ordered a wide-ranging review of its banking policy. Its action comes after more embarrassing incidents. Reminiscent of the $1.1 billion Daiwa fiasco, Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan admitted false reporting of bond-trading at its American unit, though no losses were incurred. And the continuing financial crisis in Japan led to the collapse of Taiheiyo Bank--only the second listed bank to go bust in 50 years.

<h2>Floating</h2>
<p>In one of the biggest public share offerings ever, Sweden's <b>Scania</b>, one of the world's largest lorry and bus makers, was valued at SKr36 billion ($5.4 billion) when 50% of it was launched by Investor, Wallenberg's investment unit, on the Stockholm and New York stock exchanges.<p>
Less than two years after the <font size=-1>QE2</font> set off on a cruise before a &#163;30m ($46m) refit was complete, resulting in &#163;7.5m paid out to passengers in compensation, <b>Cunard </b>is planning another overhaul. Peter Ward, Cunard's new head, reckons its flagship liner is worth the work.<p>
Japan's top car maker, cash-rich <b>Toyota</b>, plans to spend &#165;100 billion ($930m) on buying back 1.2% of its shares. It would be Japan's biggest-ever share buyback.<p>
<b>Car prices </b>in Europe need to be cut by at least 20% if consumers are to buy more cars, said a team of British car dealers. They reckon better distribution, fewer dealers and fewer models would help cut prices.<p>
<p></p>
