<html><head><title>Manufacturing growth</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Manufacturing growth</h1>


BRITISH manufacturing output has increased by a modest 21% since 1980. But the productivity of manufacturers (how many units of output they produce from given inputs of labour and capital) has soared. Labour productivity (output per employee) has more than doubled (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). In the 1980s, this was dubbed the "productivity miracle". Today, economists are finding less metaphysical reasons for the improvement.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In "Productivity Growth," a paper presented at the Royal Economic Society conference on April 2nd, Gavin Cameron, an economist at Oxford University, explores the causes of higher productivity in each of the 19 industries that make up the manufacturing sector. Every industry has enjoyed dramatically faster productivity growth since 1980 than it did in the 1970s. Falling employment was a common factor. But beyond that, the reasons for the change varied from one industry to the next.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;De-unionisation, which has been rapid since the early 1980s, was crucial in engineering, one of the most heavily unionised industries. But in chemicals, where union membership was lower, further decline had little effect on productivity. Intriguingly, in electronics, greater unionisation appeared to raise productivity. This may have been due to the spread of single union deals with benefits linked to higher productivity, reckons Mr Cameron.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Increased spending on research and development was influential in metals and minerals, chemicals and electronics. However, many of the industries enjoyed no significant productivity boost from higher <font size=-1>R&D</font>--although these were mostly the ones that spent relatively little on it. Higher average skills and qualifications were particularly important in boosting productivity in electronics.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour-productivity growth has slowed during the past year: manufacturing output has been flat and employment in manufacturing has increased for the first time in many years. Will the improvement seen in the 1980s prove a one-off? Only time will tell.


</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828745200,iss">Search</a>
