<html><head><title>Up the Tories</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Up the Tories</h1>

<p>THE Conservatives face a setback in local elections on May 2nd. But they are at least making some headway in local by-elections, which occur when a councillor quits or dies. The latest of <i>The Economist</i>'s quarterly surveys of such by-elections shows that the Tories polled 32% of the vote in Jan-March 1996 (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>), putting them just three percentage points behind Labour.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Tories have been trumpeting their gains in local by-elections recently. Some commentators doubt whether they are significant. By-elections are not held where a seat falls vacant which would be filled within six months at a regular council election. This means that in local by-elections the Tories are not now having to defend seats which they won at their high point in May 1992, because these seats are due to be contested again on May 2nd. This has automatically cut Tory losses in by-elections.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor should too much weight be placed on the increase in their share of the vote. This depends on which particular seats fall vacant in a given quarter, which is subject to random variation. The sample is also small.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even so, Downing Street should be encouraged by the latest results. The Tories have not won as big a slice of the votes since the fourth quarter of 1992. With the Liberal Democrat vote solid, Labour, with 35% of the total, is down sharply on its 1995 average of nearly 43%.


</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828745200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
