<html><head><title>Howard's way</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Sentencing</b></p>
<h1>Howard's way</h1>


<p>THE much-trailed white paper on sentencing policy, published on April 3rd by Michael Howard, the home secretary, has more to do with politics than crime.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The white paper proposes minimum prison sentences of three years for persistent burglars, seven years for drug dealers and mandatory life sentences for violent and sex offenders on a second conviction. These might deter some criminals, if such sentences ever become law, but that is unlikely. The white paper is aimed more at public opinion than parliamentary draughtsmen. Mr Howard's bill would be bitterly opposed by a broad coalition of the judiciary, prison governors and penal reformers. Even if this Parliament runs its full course until May next year there will be little time to get the bill passed, especially because it will face considerable obstacles, not least in the House of Lords.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Howard knows this. But he is less concerned with getting his ideas on to the statute books than in getting them into his party's next election manifesto. The government's record on crime allows for no complacency. Although falling recently, since 1980, recorded crime has doubled while the number of those convicted or cautioned fell by 6%. None of this is much to crow about, especially for a party which prides itself on its reputation for law and order. Nor for a home secretary on the right of his party with leadership ambitions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tougher sentences will do nothing to improve conviction rates. In fact, they could reduce them further by discouraging accused people from confessing or plea bargaining. And there must be a question over whether wild swings in penal policy achieve anything other than to undermine public confidence in the entire criminal justice system. As Lord Taylor, the Lord Chief Justice, noted recently, Britain has had more Criminal Justice Acts in the past six years than in the previous 60 years. Only five years ago, the 1991 Criminal Justice Act aimed to reduce the numbers of those given custodial sentences on the grounds that prison simply did not work.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Howard has now set off on precisely the opposite course, with no evidence that it will do anything to reduce crime. Incarcerating thousands of young men for longer and longer periods would be expensive. The white paper admits that the prison population, already at a record 52,000, would increase by a quarter over the next decade if Mr Howard gets his way on sentences. At least 20 more prisons would also be needed to house maybe 13,000 new prisoners at a cost to the taxpayer in the peak years around 2010 of about &#163;500m a year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Howard does have a legitimate point when it comes to the lack of progression in sentencing for crimes such as burglary and drug dealing. Home Office statistics show that the average length of sentence for a persistent burglar (seven or more convictions) in Crown Courts in 1993-94 was 19.4 months, barely three months more than that handed down for a first offence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the white paper's proposal for a minimum three-year sentence combined with no automatic early release is a crude way to deal with this. Sentencing guidelines set by the Court of Appeal, as Labour has proposed, make more sense. Faced with a drug addict who needs treatment, rather than a three-year incarceration for burglary, a judge would still have the discretion to impose a non-custodial sentence combined with a treatment order. Mr Howard has brushed aside such arguments. He is after headlines, not justice.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828745200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br6.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
