<html><head><title>Labour shunt</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Railtrack</b></p>
<h1>Labour shunt</h1>

<p>AFTER months of internal agonising, Labour's committment to "a publicly owned, publicly accountable railway" has vanished in a puff of political smoke. The gritty realities of New Labour were revealed on March 29th by Clare Short, the party's transport spokesperson, in a speech which skirted around the merits of public ownership in favour of more regulation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The decision is a victory for Gordon Brown and his shadow Treasury team over John Prescott, the party's deputy leader, who had championed ways of regaining public control over the rail network. Several devices had been proposed, among them forcing Railtrack's investors to accept non-voting preference shares or redirecting public subsidy to increase control over Railtrack. But they were all rejected by the party's leadership as either dangerously confiscatory or hugely expensive.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The tacit acceptance of privatisation has gone down badly with Labour's left wing. "To back away from our commitment to a publicly owned railway in this way is very worrying," said one disgruntled shadow cabinet member. The rail unions, enraged by Labour's backtracking, will continue to campaign for the publicly owned railway promised with enthusiasm by successive party conferences.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Instead of renationalisation, the party is now promising high levels of public subsidy and more regulation to achieve an integrated railway system. Public ownership was dismissed by Ms Short as a second-order issue dependent on "the availability of resources, and as priorities allow." For the moment, Labour is placing its hopes on widening the powers of the rail regulator to enable him to direct Railtrack's investment spending, to clawback profits from its disposal of surplus property and to control track-access charges.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This sounds draconian, but in reality it is not much different from the Tories' approach. The rail regulator already has extensive powers to control charges, fares and investment levels. If Labour had really wanted to keep the rail network in the public sector, it could have done so. A threat to impose an annual levy on Railtrack, equivalent to any profit it proposed to distribute to shareholders in dividends, would have brought privatisation to an abrupt halt. Even the party's initial plan to reduce Railtrack's access charges in order to maximise track usage would have given investors real cause for worry. As it is, Labour's current plans will merely depress Railtrack's launch share price without adding much to investors' long-term risks.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828745200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br7.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
