<html><head><title>A match made in heaven</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>




<h1>A match made in heaven</h1>
<p>BRITISH TELECOM, or <font size=-1>BT</font> as it now likes to be known, is a big fish in a small pond. With a market capitalisation of &#163;24 billion ($37 billion), it is far and away Britain's biggest telephone company. But it is not quite big enough to become the all-embracing, global telephone company it has long wanted to be. A merger with Cable and Wireless (<font size=-1>C&W</font>), a British telephone company operating in around 50 countries, and worth around &#163;12 billion, would change all that. But will it go ahead?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They seem to make a perfect match. <font size=-1>BT</font> dominates Britain and is strong in America and Europe. <font size=-1>C&W</font> has a lucrative 57.5% stake in Hongkong Telecom, and a string of operations in emerging markets in the Caribbean and Asia. Analysys, a British consultancy, reckons that by 2005 developing countries will make up 30% of the projected $900 billion worldwide telecoms market, up from 16% of around $520 billion in revenues today.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, romances that everybody wants to happen have a habit of either not coming off or taking a long time to totter to the altar. The first problem is price. At least twice before, discussions foundered over <font size=-1>BT</font>'s valuation of the smaller company. With <font size=-1>C&W</font> worth less than &#163;10 billion before talks began, <font size=-1>BT</font> is unlikely to offer more than &#163;11.5 billion; <font size=-1>C&W</font> is rumoured to want &#163;13 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The deal also requires some complicated financial engineering. The rules of Hong Kong's stock exchange force anyone acquiring <font size=-1>C&W</font> to buy the remaining 42.5% of Hongkong Telecom--thus adding an intimidating &#163;6 billion to the final price. That means that the deal will probably have to be structured so that <font size=-1>C&W</font> actually ends up buying <font size=-1>BT</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The next problem is Britain's antitrust regulators. <font size=-1>C&W</font> owns 80% of Mercury, Britain's second-largest telephone operator; this must now be sold--probably for around &#163;2.5 billion or so. The list of potential suitors includes <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, America's biggest long-distance company which is moving into Europe quickly, and a consortia of American companies which own British cable-television operators. <font size=-1>BT</font>'s favourite appears to be Deutsche Telekom--for three reasons. First, it does not want to help <font size=-1>AT&T</font>. Second, there is a chance that favouring Germany's state-owned telecoms operator might ease <font size=-1>BT</font>'s own entry into the German market. And, lastly, Deutsche Telekom is unlikely to be a particularly fierce competitor.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are other, smaller, complications. <font size=-1>C&W</font> Inc, a small but profitable long-distance carrier based in Virginia, will probably need to be sold to satisfy local regulators. And <font size=-1>BT</font> and <font size=-1>C&W</font> may have to choose between the various alliances they have formed with rival utilities in Germany. Here the survivor is likely to be <font size=-1>C&W</font>'s partner, Veba, which has a 10.5% stake in <font size=-1>C&W</font>; that will not please <font size=-1>BT</font>'s partners, <font size=-1>RWE</font> and Viag, both of which are building networks of their own. It will be a long way to the altar.</td></tr></table>
