<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Shedding the load</h2><p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">table</a>)<br><b>Japan's banks </b>vied with each other to announce the biggest write-offs, in a concerted effort to clear the worst of their bad debts. Almost all the country's top commercial and trust banks will declare losses for the year to end-March; in the process they will write off around &#165;8.8 trillion ($92 billion), nearly a quarter of the latest government estimates of the system's total bad loans.
<p>Another consolidation in the British financial-services industry: the <b>Halifax Building Society</b>, the country's largest, is to pay &#163;800m ($1.2 billion) for <b>Clerical Medical</b>, an insurer. The Halifax will become one of Britain's biggest retail banks when it goes public next year.</p>
<p>In an effort to speed up a return to health of state-owned <b>Banco di Napoli</b>, the Italian government imposed new conditions on a loan of 2.4 trillion lire ($1.5 billion) that the treasury and a group of banks had granted the stricken bank in November. The bank must make a new restructuring plan and cut its labour costs. The treasury is taking over its management in an effort to prepare it for full privatisation next year.</p>
<p>Werner Rey, wanted in Switzerland on fraud charges, was arrested in the Bahamas and now faces extradition proceedings. His <b>Omni Holding Co </b>collapsed with debts of some SFr3 billion ($1.7 billion) in 1991, owing huge sums to Swiss Bank Corp and nearly bringing down a smaller Swiss bank.
<h2>Trade-offs</h2>
<b>France </b>and<b> America </b>reached agreement over one of their many airline disputes. Air France will be allowed to make 500 extra flights this summer to four American cities in exchange for France withdrawing a threat to cut landing rights for American airlines. But the chances of the two countries renewing their more wide-ranging air pact that lapsed in 1992 look slim.</p>
<p>The World Trade Organisation warned 50 countries that there was little time left to reach agreement on global <b>telecoms liberalisation</b>. With an end-April deadline, America has yet to see the " critical mass" of sensible offers from other countries that it says it must have before it will open its own markets to more foreign competition.
<h2>Come together</h2>
In a deal that brings together the two largest owners of shopping centres in America, <b>Simon Property Group</b> of Indiana and <b>DeBartolo Realty </b>of next-door Ohio are to merge to form America's largest property company, with 10m square metres of retail space and a total market value of $7.5 billion.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>A British shipping, construction and property group, <b>P&O</b>, is to sell assets worth &#163;1 billion ($1.52 billion) over the next three years to try to boost its share price, the worst performing in the <font size=-1>FT-SE 100</font> last year. Disposals will include the flotation of one of Britain's biggest house builders, Bovis Homes, the sale of &#163;500m-worth of property and a reduction in its bulk-shipping interests. <font size=-1>P&O</font> said pre-tax profits fell 8% to &#163;320m last year.</p>
<p>A proposed merger to create America's biggest railway company suffered a serious setback when the Texas Railroad Commission voted to oppose <b>Union Pacific</b>'s proposed $5.4 billion purchase of <b>Southern Pacific Rail</b>. Union Pacific said the decision was "parochial"; a more senior regulator will have the final say later in the year.
<h2>Taking stock</h2><p>(See <a href="wtw3.gif">chart</a>)<br>Pre-tax profits at <b>Inchcape</b>, a British distribution and services group, plunged in 1995 by 92% to &#163;17.4m ($27.5m) after exceptional items of &#163;129.4m, hurt by a strong yen and weak demand in its Japanese-car distribution business. Amid a shake-up that will refocus group activities, the company cut its dividend and announced it was replacing its chief executive, Charles Mackay, with Philip Cushing, Inchcape's managing director. Its share price rose.</p>
<p><b>Alcatel</b> <b>Alsthom</b>, a French telecoms and industrial group, reported a loss of FFr25.6 billion ($5.1 billion) in 1995, the biggest loss in French corporate history. The loss arose from heavy charges for reorganisation and asset write-downs.</p>
<p>Desperate to get a foot in China's door, Rupert Murdoch's News Corp unveiled a joint venture between its own loss-making <b>Star TV </b>(45%), and two Hong Kong firms with good contacts in China, Today's China (45%) and China Wise International (10%). The ambition is to use the new broadcasting network, called Phoenix Satellite Television, to break into China's restricted cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> market.</p>
<p>Heavily traded shares in <b>Orange</b> closed at a 16% premium to their offer price after the &#163;2.45 billion ($3.75 billion) flotation of the British mobile-phone group, jointly owned by Hong Kong's Hutchison Whampoa and by British Aerospace. The offering was some ten times oversubscribed.</p>
<p><b>Apple Computer</b> said it expects to report a net quarterly loss of $700m, its largest-ever, in the three months to end-March. Most of the loss stemmed from inventory write-downs and restructuring charges. Moody's had already downgraded Apple's credit rating. Gilbert Amelio, Apple's newish chief executive, said the firm's problems were "fixable" .</p>
<p>Manfred Schmitt, chairman and founder of <b>Escom</b>, Germany's biggest <font size=-1>PC</font> maker, resigned after the company ran up losses of DM125m ($87m) in 1995.</p>
