</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Cash for cows</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>

</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<h1>Cash for cows</h1>
<p><b>Predictions that Britain's economy will be seriously damaged by the scare over mad-cow disease are exaggerated</b></p>

<p>THE health panic triggered by the government's admission that the fatal Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (<font size=-1>CJD</font>) might be caused by eating beef has fast become an economic scare. Share and bond prices suffered as speculation mounted that a worldwide ban on exports of British beef and related products (from soup to jelly babies), plus a cull of the cattle herd, might lower growth, raise inflation and unemployment, and cost the taxpayer up to &#163;20 billion ($30 billion).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is certainly a grim time for cattle farmers, who have still not recovered the market share they lost in the previous big scare about <font size=-1>BSE</font> in 1989. But will their problems really have much impact on the economy as a whole?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Consider, for instance, the most extreme policy response, the slaughter of all of Britain's 11.8m cattle--something that is not yet a serious proposal, not least because it would mean killing cows now producing milk, currently unaffected by the scare. Farmers now get compensation of up to &#163;865 per slaughtered infected cow. At that rate the total bill would be &#163;10.2 billion. On top of this there would be the cost of killing and burning each cow, currently &#163;120. Allowing for some extra expenditure on new incineration capacity, that cost might come to &#163;2 billion. Some are suggesting that as well as compensating farmers for their lost cattle, they should be bought new cows. But compensating them twice in this way is unreasonably generous.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Welfare payments to workers made redundant would also have to be met. The British Meat and Livestock Commission calculates that around 400,000 people are employed in beef and dairy farming. The Treasury reckons that every 100,000 rise in unemployment puts up the social-security bill by &#163;275m. So, even on the assumption that the entire workforce were fired and unable to find other work, the cost would be &#163;1.1 billion a year. That would be bearable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Payments might be made to workers sacked in other beef-related industries. But most firms using beef products will simply switch to foreign suppliers, and so be affected only to the extent that world prices rise as British beef disappears. Besides, new jobs would be created slaughtering cattle, and in farming livestock such as poultry, pork and lamb, for which demand has risen as consumers have shunned beef.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The maximum bill facing the taxpayer would thus be something less than &#163;15 billion, with continuing costs of up to &#163;1 billion a year. Some help has now been promised by the <font size=-1>EU</font>. The government would have no difficulty borrowing the rest. It would largely be a one-off cost, so financial markets would not regard the resulting rise in the public-sector borrowing requirement as a permanent deterioration of the public finances. So there need be little extra pressure to raise interest rates or abandon planned tax cuts.
</p><p><b>Mad cows and sterling</b></b>
<br>Slaughtering the national herd would affect the balance of payments. Alex Gerrard, an economist at the securities wing of Union Bank of Switzerland, says a complete cessation of beef and dairy production, plus imports of live cattle to replace the current herd, would increase the current-account deficit by up to &#163;6.5 billion a year for several years. (The 1995 deficit was &#163;6.7 billion.) Deficits tend to damage an economy only if they persist for many years--although there is a chance that a bigger deficit would weaken sterling, pushing up import costs and thus inflation. In the short run, the fall in beef prices might lower inflation, depending on how much prices rise for other foods. But if the entire herd were slaughtered, beef prices would almost certainly rise. The absolute maximum by which <font size=-1>GDP</font> would fall is 1.2%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Less drastic options, such as those being considered by the cabinet when it met on March 28th, would have a smaller impact. Doing nothing might kill exports of British beef, for a while anyway, but dairy exports would continue. The increase in the current-account deficit would be only one-third as big as in the worst case.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What happens to domestic beef sales will depend on two factors: first, how far consumers keep buying beef because of government assurances and lower prices; and second, how successful producers are in differentiating beef produced from diseased herds from beef produced from unaffected herds. Some 85% of beef herds and 40% of dairy herds remain unaffected. Lower sales and prices would certainly hurt farmers and cost jobs. But it is unlikely that sales would plummet to zero, so the fall in <font size=-1>GDP</font> would be less than the 0.3% accounted for by beef production.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The National Farmers Union argues that limited culling is better than none if consumer confidence in British beef is to be restored and the export ban lifted. It wants the government to kill and burn dairy cattle, and bulls and cows used to produce beef calves, at the end of their working lives. As they are older, these are the ones most likely to have <font size=-1>BSE</font>. At present, they are slaughtered and sold for human consumption; 850,000 such cows are killed every year. As these elderly cattle fetch only around &#163;500 a head, compensation should not be much more than &#163;400m. The only other cost would be a 20% fall in domestic beef output, reducing <font size=-1>GDP</font> by a minuscule 0.05%. Few jobs should be lost.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this assumes that the worst fears about eating beef turn out to be wrong. In the unlikely event that such fears prove well-founded, and projected deaths rise into the hundreds of thousands, the economic implications of the <font size=-1>BSE</font> scare would take on a different complexion. (Imagine the analysts' reports: "People expecting to die may switch from saving to spending, fuelling an unsustainable consumer boom.") In such a case, however, the economic implications are unlikely to be of much concern. At last, a scenario in which Britain stops worrying about the economy.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828136800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
