<html><head><title>All parties great and small</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Northern Ireland</b></p>
<h1>All parties great and small</h1>

<font size=1>BELFAST</font>
<p>GERRYMANDERING is traditionally designed to preserve the power of the haves against the have-nots. An exception, however, is the way that the British government has fixed the elections to be held in Northern Ireland on May 30th. It will give two seats each to the biggest ten parties in the province, whether or not they win seats in any individual constituency.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The idea is to ensure that there will be a wide spectrum of opinion in the pool from which representatives for all-party talks, beginning on June 10th, will be drawn. Sinn Fein will be allowed to stand, since the government knows that preventing it would be counter-productive. But Sinn Fein will be at the talks only if the <font size=-1>IRA</font> meanwhile restores its ceasefire.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Northern Ireland's four big parties--the Ulster Unionist Party, the Social Democratic &amp; Labour Party, the Democratic Unionist Party and Sinn Fein--are well known. But the six parties most likely to join them are not.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The largest, with around 9% of the vote, is the<b> Alliance</b> <b>Party.</b> Formed in 1970, it offers a middle road between anti-Catholic unionism and anti-British nationalism. It upholds the union as the choice of the majority, but argues for devolution from London to Belfast, for power-sharing between nationalists and unionists, and for closer co-operation with the Irish republic. Led by John Alderdice, who is (appropriately) a psychiatrist, the Alliance is largely a party of middle-class Protestants.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The<b> Workers' Party</b>, led by John Lowry, and the<b> Democratic Left</b>, led by Proinsias de Rossa--who is a member of the Irish government--together seem likely to draw less than 1% of the vote. They are descended from the Official Republicans, nicknamed the "Stickies", Marxists who split from the Provisionals (ie, the current <font size=-1>IRA</font>) in 1970. The "Stickies" progressively shed the doctrines and symbols of violent nationalism, and then nationalism itself. Both groups would like parties in Northern Ireland to agree on a system of government without involving the government in Dublin. The shadow of the gun has been slow to fade and other parties scoff at their avowed support for law and order.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The<b> Ulster Democratic Party</b> (<font size=-1>UDP</font>), in the party's own words, "emanated from the Ulster Defence Association" (<font size=-1>UDA</font>), the largest loyalist paramilitary group. As with Sinn Fein and the <font size=-1>IRA</font>, the <font size=-1>UDP</font> says it is separate from the <font size=-1>UDA</font> but has "an insight into <font size=-1>UDA</font> thinking." It claims the large unionist parties are unrepresentative of working-class Protestants, and suggests a form of power-sharing with nationalists. Strongest in Belfast and nearby Lisburn, it has three elected representatives on local councils: Gary McMichael, the party leader, and two former <font size=-1>DUP</font> councillors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The<b> Progressive Unionist Party</b> (<font size=-1>PUP</font>) calls itself the "political confidant" of the Ulster Volunteer Force (<font size=-1>UVF</font>), another group of loyalist paramilitaries. Formed in 1979, but scarcely noticed until the loyalist ceasefire, the <font size=-1>PUP</font> has only one councillor: Hugh Smyth, who was nevertheless Lord Mayor of Belfast in 1994. It prefers to be described as "socialist" rather than unionist, and has two articulate spokesmen in David Ervine and Billy Hutchinson, who is a reformed lifer.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last of the ten is likely to be the <b>UK Unionist </b>Robert McCartney, who won a by-election to the British parliament in prosperous North Down in 1995. Mr McCartney maintains that if all British parties organised in Northern Ireland, sectarianism would gradually end. Ironically, the Tories, who do organise in Northern Ireland and win about 6% of the vote, have just been ordered by their bosses in London not to stand in the elections, on the absurd grounds that ministers will represent their voters at the talks.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828136800,iss">Search</a>
