<html><head><title>A mighty jam</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>A mighty jam</h1>

<p>THE government's plan to charge motorists for the use of motorways--a central part of its transport policy--is facing serious delay at best, at worst total collapse. Less than a year ago, ministers announced, amid much publicity, that tests of electronic-payment systems would start on the <font size=-1>M3</font> motorway this summer. But within the next few days Sir George Young, the transport secretary, is expected to announce an indefinite postponement of the &#163;20m trial. Officials hope to save something from the wreck by announcing that limited trials of tolling equipment will take place later this year on test tracks at the Transport Research Laboratory at Crowthorne in Berkshire.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The abandonment of the <font size=-1>M3</font> trial has been forced on the government by the withdrawal of four of the eight consortia chosen by the Department of Transport to compete to provide a national tolling system. Three of the eight--Siemens, Tollway and Autolink--have already said that they will not take part in the <font size=-1>M3</font> trials. A fourth, Tollstar, is expected to announce shortly that it too is pulling out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All eight of the consortia, selected from 29 applicants, have become increasingly disillusioned by the lack of a clear government commitment to road pricing. The trial was already running 18 months behind schedule, partly because ministers were wary of taking difficult decisions in the run-up to a general election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One factor raising doubts about the future of motorway charging is the outcome of last year's tolling trial on the Bonn-to-Cologne motorway in Germany. Although some systems achieved accuracy rates of 99.9%, the German government has decided against introducing motorway tolls for cars. Instead, it plans to proceed first with a scheme to charge only heavy-goods vehicles.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The British government is even more terrified of motorists' reactions to charging. Although Department of Transport forecasts suggest that traffic might double between now and 2025, ministers believe that tolls are politically unsellable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As a result, the so-called "great transport debate" started by Brian Mawhinney, the previous transport minister, has dissolved into incoherence. The road-building programme has been cut, but no alternative method of dealing with traffic growth has been put in its place. A German transport economist, Carmen Hass-Klau, unkindly rubbed this in when she told a recent European transport conference that the only activity in the field in which Britain led the world was talking. In every other area, she said, Britain was at least a decade behind the rest of Europe.

</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828136800,iss">Search</a>
