<html><head><title>Split decision</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Divorce and pensions</b></p>
<h1>Split decision</h1>

<p>MINISTERS may squirm when forced to confront questions of marriage, divorce and the fabric of society. But these are nothing compared with the shudders produced when the public coffers are at risk. This was evident during the Commons debate this week on the new Family Law Bill, already passed by the House of Lords. Although heated words were exchanged about no-fault divorce and cooling-off periods, the government's big worry is what the legislation might cost.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The bill, as amended in the Lords, would allow judges to divide the pension assets of divorcing couples. Although Roger Freeman, the minister responsible for the bill, has in principle accepted the new rule, it is unlikely to take effect before the next election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At present, judges often consider a spouse's pension when ruling on divorce settlements. But since pensions cannot be carved up, any settlement must instead rearrange other assets to balance things out. She gets the house, he keeps the pension.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The House of Lords tried to simplify things in the 1995 Pensions Act, by allowing couples to split their pensions upon divorcing. This proposal was watered down in the Commons. As passed, the act lets judges divide up future pension payments explicitly in a divorce settlement. The pension is not split now, but the pensioner can be required to turn over a share of it to his spouse when either partner retires.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This will help, but problems remain. The biggest is that the pension rights still nominally belong to the pensioner. When he or she dies, the spouse is no longer entitled to further payments. Hence a House of Lords' amendment to the new bill allowing judges to split the fund at the time of the divorce. Many Tories in the Commons support this, which has forced the government to concede the point. But the government has also said it will not implement the new rule until it has issued a consultative green paper on the proposal.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Allowing pension-splitting will be a legislative nightmare. The social-security department reckons that at least 30 laws will have to be rewritten to accommodate the new rule. But even worse is the cost.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tax revenue will be lost because each spouse would receive separate pension payments, on which each would be entitled to a tax allowance. Fortunately, this cost is likely to be modest, perhaps no more than &#163;80m a year, and would be largely offset by a fall in means-tested benefits.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The bigger worry is public-sector pension funds, which the new rule would clobber. Whereas most private plans set assets aside to cover future payments, those for many public employees are financed on a pay-as-you-go basis. If divorcees suddenly demand their share of the loot, they would have to pay out sooner than they planned, which could cost them around &#163;500m a year. The choice is stark: either public employees will have to be excluded from the new rules, or the taxpayer will face a big bill.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828136800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br5.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
