<html><head><title>Blockbusters</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Housing</b></p>
<h1>Blockbusters</h1>


<p>"FIVE, four, three, two, one," a pregnant pause, and then Rowan Court, a 20-storey tower block on the Holly Street estate in Hackney, east London, is transformed into a tidy pyramid of rubble. "Rowan Court has never looked better," David Thompson, the administrator of the project, told a cheering crowd.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thanks to the Comprehensive Estates Initiative, a local plan that has set out to improve five council-owned estates, blowing up tower blocks has become a regular event in Hackney. Eight have hit the dust in the past year. Two of Rowan Court's neighbours are doomed, and at least four more will go before the campaign is completed in 2001. Residents will be rehoused in attractive, though smaller, low-rise homes that they helped to design.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Local enthusiasm is understandable. Tower blocks, fashionable among town planners in the 1960s, have proved unacceptable to most British families. On March 25th, Westminster council in London was criticised by an independent inquiry for putting homeless families into a tower block riddled with asbestos. The block has since been demolished.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But surprisingly, as the demolishers step up their work, some housing experts fear that too many tower blocks could be removed from the scene. A high-rise block is no place to raise a family. But many boast fine views from their quiet upper floors. Adults often like them. Birmingham, for example, has turned over several dozen high-rises to childless or elderly adults. Grange Court, a twin to Rowan Court in Hackney, is being refurbished to provide homes for people over 50.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This makes sense. There is an increasing demand for housing for people living alone, such as students, struggling artists, young adults just out of care, and the newly divorced. The population of single-person households is increasing by 200,000 a year, faster than any other group.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But local authorities cannot afford to sit on unpopular housing stock and wait for the number of suitable tenants to grow. They also find it hard to allocate homes to single people when many families on their books are in even greater need of housing. So many tower blocks are half-empty, inviting the attentions of the wrecking ball--even though, in a few years' time, they could be providing just the kind of homes then most in demand.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828136800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br7.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
